<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS AND CLEMENS APPEAR TO GET A JUMP ON THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Roger Clemens has said that he wants to finish his
career with the New York Yankees, and two baseball officials
contend that there is an understanding that the team will give him
a two-year extension after his current contract expires in the
fall. That would mean Clemens would be tied to the Yankees through
the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, 37, will be paid $8.1 million this season; he is in the
last year of a contract he signed with the Toronto Blue Jays before
the 1997 season. One official indicated that Clemens would receive
an extension in the range of $13 million to $14 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Yankees have informed the Detroit Tigers of their
interest in outfielder Bobby Higginson, and Gene Michael, the
club's top scout, has watched Higginson the last two days. But the
New York Mets appear to be the front-runners to get Higginson,
offering a package that could include outfielder Rickey Henderson
and the left-hander Rich Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' two-year understanding has not been completed, and
specific terms within the deal are undetermined. The agreement may
have taken place as much as a year ago, when Clemens joined the
Yankees in a trade from Toronto. At that time, Clemens' leverage
was at its highest: he had won consecutive Cy Young Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trade, his agents, Alan and Randy Hendricks, had
asked the Houston Astros in contentious negotiations for an
extension worth about $27 million, a figure that is close to the
value of the understanding reached with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens went 14-10 with a 4.60 earned run average for the
Yankees during the regular season while battling injuries, but he
pitched well in two of his three postseason starts, including a
victory in the final World Series game against the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have long had a similar two-year, $18 million
understanding with second baseman Chuck Knoblauch. Under his
existing contract, the Yankees will pay Knoblauch $6 million a
season for 2000 and 2001. At some point the two-year understanding
will become a two-year extension, tying Knoblauch to the team for
the 2002 and 2003 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have never made the Knoblauch extension official,
for reasons that may be related to the luxury tax and issues
personal to Knoblauch. It may be that the Yankees will not announce
Clemens' extension until after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Yankees, who never got that close to pulling off
a trade for outfielder Jim Edmonds before he was traded from
Anaheim to St. Louis on Thursday, are monitoring Higginson, just in
case they feel the need to acquire another hitter. Higginson, 29,
has a .366 career average in Yankee Stadium, but he is coming off a
season in which his average plummeted to .239, and he has continued
to struggle this spring, batting around .200 with only two
extra-base hits in 43 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson is scheduled to earn $4.3 million this year and $5.2
million next year, a heavy price to pay for a questionable talent
at a time when the Yankees are already facing massive salary
increases for players like Derek Jeter and Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets might not be so daunted by the idea of acquiring
Higginson's contract, because they have been desperate to unload
Henderson all winter, shopping him to teams in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson would give the Mets better left-handed balance in
their lineup. Currently, they have six right-handed hitters and
only two left-handed hitters among their regular position players,
with Henderson scheduled to be the left fielder. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
