<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-FLORIDA-DUKE-HNS &LR;      03-25 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FLORIDA-DUKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Another top seed has been planted. This time, it
was the No. 1 team in the nation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Florida Gators used a deeper bench and an aggressive press
to upset top-ranked Duke 87-78 in an East Regional semifinal Friday
night at the Carrier Dome, making the Blue Devils the third No. 1
seed to exit the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Florida (27-7) scored the final 13 points of the game after
trailing 78-74 with 4:01 to go. The Gators' bench outscored the
Duke reserves 35-4. Florida forced 22 turnovers by the Blue Devils,
who made only three of 19 shots from the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman guard Brett Nelson came off the bench to lead Florida
with 15 points. He was one of five Gators to score in double
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a great win for us because Duke has been the
model of excellence over the last 20 years,'' said Florida coach
Billy Donovan, whose team advances to the Elite Eight for the first
time since 1994. ``People said we couldn't press them and we
shouldn't dare try, but that's the way we play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys did an excellent job of executing our
system, and I thought our zone helped us in the last three minutes
of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's victory snapped Duke's 26-game East Regional winning
streak going back to 1986. Duke also lost for just the fourth time
as a top seed.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators played man defense most of the night until switching
to a 2-3 zone that Duke could not score against down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the shots we usually make,'' said Duke forward Chris
Carrawell, who finished with 16 points in his final college game.
``We took our shots and went out firing all our bullets. That's all
you can ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Shane Battier led the Blue Devils with 20 points, nine
rebounds and four blocks, but Duke used only seven players and
seemed to tire at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Duke ends the season 29-5 after starting the year 0-2 with a
team that lost four key players from last season's team, which fell
to Connecticut in the NCAA championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you guys expect me to feel bad about this, you're crazy,''
said Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski. ``This may have been the most
gratifying year I've ever had as a coach. These guys fought like
crazy, and it's been an amazing year with a special group of young
men.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear early in the game the Florida press was going to be
a problem for the Blue Devils, who had 12 turnovers in the first
half. The Gators managed to hold a 40-33 lead at the half despite
the fact Duke went to the free-throw line 16 times (making 11)
while the Gators shot only five free throws and made four.
</P>
<P>
   Duke came out strong to start the second half. A 7-0 Blue Devils
run tied it 40-40 in the first minute before Florida guard Justin
Hamilton sank a 3-pointer to stop the spurt. A baseline jumper by
Nelson put the Gators ahead 45-40.
</P>
<P>
   Things were starting to get rough when Florida forward Kenyan
Weaks was whistled for a technical foul after he elbowed Duke guard
Jason Williams under the chin while both players were scrambling
for a ball on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The game continued to seesaw, and Duke took a 60-58 lead when
Matt Christensen made a layup off a fast break, which was the first
basket of the game by the Duke bench.
</P>
<P>
   Williams finally started finding the range in the last eight
minutes of the game. After going 1-for-10, Williams made four
consecutive shots to help the Blue Devils take their biggest lead
at 72-66.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gators battled back and tied it at 74 when Teddy Dupay
converted a 3-point play as Duke center Carlos Boozer fouled out
with five minutes remaining. Boozer left with 11 points and nine
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was big to get Boozer out of the game,'' Dupay
said. ``He is a real anchor for them inside, and it hurt them not
having him out there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   A 3-point basket by Dupay made it 78-77 Duke before Florida took
the lead for good on a fast-break layup by Udonis Haslem.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators were ecstatic with the win, but they calmed down
quickly in the locker room, realizing there was more work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come here just to beat Duke,'' Weaks said. ``We came
here to win two games and get to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
