<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CLEAVES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S NOT ELICITING ONLY COMPLIMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ The way Mateen Cleaves handles a
basketball, he could pass for Harry Potter. It turns out, the
marvelous Michigan State senior is going to be the lead character
in a book. Only it's not going to be a fanciful piece of fiction
like the best-selling works of J.K. Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves' mother, Frances, is writing a nonfiction book (the
working title is ``Player Haters'') about the scurrilous side of
college basketball. For four years, she has been keeping copious
notes on verbal batteries hurled at her son from hecklers in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   The reader can expect an eyeful because Frances Cleaves has
gotten an earful over the seasons, this despite the fact her fifth
and youngest child has developed into arguably the best collegiate
point guard in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves can deliver the No.1-seeded Spartans to their second
straight Final Four with a victory today over a No.2-seeded Iowa
State squad that has a proficient point guard of its own in Jamaal
Tinsley.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old from Flint is glad for the competition, but he
wasn't going to let a pesky press trap him into turning the contest
into a backcourt duel between himself and Tinsley.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to run my team and that's what I'm going to do,''
Cleaves said Friday during a media session at The Palace, site of
today's Midwest Regional Final. ``I don't really go out to put on a
show or impress people. I just go out and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates don't always show the same fire. In the first half
of their third-round game against Syracuse on Thursday, the
Spartans got lax and appeared on the verge of getting waxed.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen took a 10-point lead into the intermission, during
which time Cleaves lit into his teammates so severely it's a small
wonder they didn't return to the court sporting burn marks.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans scalded Syracuse in the final 20 minutes to notch a
17-point victory. Cleaves contributed all 10 of his points in the
second half and finished with seven assists. He had silenced the
naysayers for yet another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be some doubters,'' said Cleaves, the
Big Ten all-time leader in assists. ``It's funny to me. When I was
growing up, I was always trying to go out and prove people wrong. I
don't get caught up in that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves has been written off because he's not a slick shooter,
because his past includes two alcohol-related scrapes with the law
and because he suffered a stress fracture in his right foot last
fall and missed the first 13 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The writing is on all the offensive signs his mother has
confiscated and kept over the years. They provided the fodder for
her book, which she is doing with Cleaves' equivocal blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no choice but to back her,'' Cleaves said with a laugh
that let everybody in the room know that, hey, moms can do the
darndest things. ``I guess she just wants to tell about all the
negative stuff you hear people say and how people will try to tear
you apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves felt as if his soul had been shredded when his right
sole first shelved him. He could have taken his game to the NBA
after his junior year and suddenly he wasn't going anywhere it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid,'' Cleaves said. ``It was very tough for me. At
first, the main thing I kept saying is, `Why me?' The thing that
helped me out is I had a lot of positive people around me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them was Spartans coach Tom Izzo. ``If he looked at
me and it looked like I was having a bad day, he'd call me into his
office and talk to me,'' Cleaves said of Izzo. ``Coach was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo returned the compliment. ``If you want to be really honest
about it,'' he said, ``about 90 percent of the players in Mateen's
situation would cheer for their team but secretly hope they didn't
do !ital!too!off! well without them. But I never saw an inkling of
that with Mateen.''
</P>
<P>
   What strangers see when they watch Cleaves play is magic (and
Magic Johnson, too, the former MSU guard whose assists record
Cleaves surpassed).
</P>
<P>
   ``That Cleaves is unbelievable,'' one onlooker said to another
after the Syracuse game. ``He's fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cleaves, ``That's really a good feeling to hear people talk
about you like that. I'm just out there being myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
