</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-EDMONDS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL WISHES AND A FEW TEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Jim Edmonds showed up at the Angels
spring-training complex on Friday morning to tie up some loose ends
and say his goodbyes. But he couldn't do it without letting out
some emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds walked into the clubhouse at 10 a.m., peeked out the
clubhouse door to look at his former teammates on the field and
then sat down to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a few players came in, one at a time, and wished him well.
When Garret Anderson came in, the two hugged, and Edmonds began to
cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like moving away from your family,'' said Edmonds, traded
Thursday to the St. Louis Cardinals for pitcher Kent Bottenfield
and second baseman Adam Kennedy. ``How do you react? It's hard to
talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that Gary DiSarcina and Tim Salmon had reminisced
about playing with him in the minors, Edmonds' eyes welled up with
tears. He has spent 12 years in the Angels organization, and grew
up in Diamond Bar, only a few miles up the road from Edison
International Field.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the hometown-boy-makes-good potential of Edmonds'
career, his name has been mentioned in trade rumors for four years.
When it finally happened, Edmonds was floored.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bill Stoneman had told him only a few days
earlier that he expected Edmonds to play the season with the
Angels. But the deal with the Cardinals came up and just like that,
it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia pulled Edmonds from the game after
the sixth inning and sent him to the clubhouse. Edmonds was
supposed to play the entire game, but he didn't think anything
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any idea something was going on,'' he said. ''I
just thought I was coming out of the game. I learned anything can
happen in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds said he has no hard feelings for Stoneman, saying he
didn't feel betrayed by the sudden turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just doing his job,'' Edmonds said. ''The reason he
reassured me the other day was so I could focus on baseball and do
my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds was hitting .390 with the Angels this spring and will
get to play in a place many consider one of the best baseball
cities in the country. He'll get to hit in the same lineup as
Damien High grad Mark McGwire. The Cardinals are so loaded with
talent, Edmonds will probably hit fifth or sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy about being able to go to an atmosphere that's
pretty exciting,'' Edmonds said. ''But right now, I don't know.
It's just taking a while to sink in. I'm tired and exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was Edmonds' best friend on the team, and possibly his
only friend at times. And it is Anderson who will take over
Edmonds' spot in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `Goodbye, and keep in touch,' '' Anderson said.
``I really respect him and he's a good friend. I want it to stay
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds has been maligned over the years for his approach to the
game. He is so athletic and his style is so free and easy, other
players fumed, perceiving that he didn't care. But those who know
him best, know better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the flair,'' right fielder Tim Salmon said. ``He banged
into walls a ton of times and made great plays, and somehow it
worked against him. He was so valuable over there. He'd give me
cues right before the pitch. He'd say, `Timmy . . . changeup'
because he'd read the catcher's sign and know what pitch was coming
and where it was going. He made my job a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds flew from Arizona to Florida Friday night and will join
his new club today. It's also a new league and a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a little bit sad for him to leave home,'' said
Paul Cohen, Edmonds' agent. ``He'll miss the guys and miss the
fans. But once he gets past the emotion of it, he'll be pretty
excited about the future. To be able to play with Big Mac in the
same lineup is going to be an incredible experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
