A7666 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHR     03-25 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS MOVE LITTLE AS BONDS CLAIM THE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add S&AMP;P in 2nd graf and to adjust closing numbers in final
graf.)  
(mk) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks go up, and stocks go down, but on Friday
stocks mainly went sideways.
</P>
<P>
   A volatile week on Wall Street ended with a whimper, as the Dow
Jones industrial average fell slightly and the technology-fattened
Nasdaq composite index crept closer to the record it set earlier in
March. The Dow was down 7.14 points at 11,112.72, while the Nasdaq
rose 22.42 to close at 4,963.03. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index rose slightly, 0.11 point, to 1,527.46.
</P>
<P>
   The real action Friday was in the bond market, with the price of
the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond falling 1 7/32 to 103 19/32.
That drove the the yield, which moves in the opposite direction as
its price, up to 5.99 percent from 5.91 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that bond investors were worried by the report
that some members of the Federal Reserve, which sets short-term
interest rates, had argued for a half-percentage-point increase in
rates at the Fed's February meeting, whose minutes were just
released. The Fed has raised rates five times since June, most
recently on Tuesday when it pushed up a rate on overnight loans
between banks to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But each increase has been only one-quarter of a percentage
point. A larger increase would indicate that the Fed is
increasingly concerned about inflation, which is bad for bonds,
because they pay a fixed return.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, stocks and bonds move in tandem, with higher interest
rates considered bad for stocks because they drive up corporate
borrowing costs and make bonds more attractive as an alternative to
stocks. But stock investors shrugged off the latest rate increase,
confident that higher short-term rates would not slow the economy
enough to hurt corporate profits and that the Fed was almost
finished raising rates in any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every increase that occurs, people feel that we're closer to
the ultimate time where the Fed's going to see the light at the end
of the tunnel,'' said Vernon Winters, chief investment officer of
Mellon Private Asset Management, which has $58 billion in assets.
``Maybe a half-point rise gets it over with even sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters said that this week's action had been very positive for
stock investors because it marked the first time this year that
stocks had risen across the board. He noted that the Wilshire 5000
index, which represents almost the entire U.S. stock market, broke
out of a narrow trading range and set all-time highs for the last
four days. Friday, the Wilshire closed at 14,751.64, up 17.39
points. For the week, the index was up more than 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there's been a thrust in the last week that has a
positive tone,'' Winters said. ``The values of all stocks went up
across the board, rather than just taking from one and giving to
the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Big individual gainers Friday included IBM, which rose $6.125 to
$121.375, and Wal-Mart, up $1.50 to $55.50. The day's biggest loser
was Johnson &AMP; Johnson, which fell $7.50 to $72.50 after halting
marketing of Propulsid, a heartburn drug that has been linked to
heart problems and as many as 80 deaths. Propulsid sales, which
were almost $1 billion in 1999, could be just over $250 million
this year, analysts said. The drop wiped out more than $10 billion
in market value from Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
