<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITS-TEENS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR CALLS FOR SUPPORT OF POSITIVE LATINO FILMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   North Hollywood, Calif. _ The price of cinematic glory for
Latinos runs about $8, preferably for a new film starring Jimmy
Smits and a San Fernando High School calculus whiz, Smits told
secondary students Friday in North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Smits plays a washed-up prizefighter seeking the fame he was
denied in the jabs and uppercuts of his three sons in New Line
Cinema's ``Price of Glory.'' Friday, he urged more than 500
students from San Fernando High and 14 other Southland schools to
support the film and others that realistically portray Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta go those first couple of weeks that it opens,
because that really helps the next one that comes down the line,''
he said of the film, which also features San Fernando High senior
Ernesto Hernandez, who plays one of the sons.
</P>
<P>
   Smits called on Hollywood to produce more movies with
nonstereotypical portrayals of Latinos, such as his own ``My
Family, Mi Familia'' in 1995, and 1997's ``Selena.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Between each of those films passed time, time where we were
not represented on the big screen,'' said Smits, who sported a
fisherman's cap and a gray textured sweater. ``Considering how many
of us there are in this country, in this city, in this state,
that's not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was organized by the 20-month-old Premiere Weekend
Club, a downtown-based nonprofit group that aims to promote films
with Latino themes and characters. Director Carlos Avila told the
students he collaborated with the group in making ``Price of
Glory,'' his first film, and even invited the club's president, Gil
Botello, to view a rough cut before he finished editing.
</P>
<P>
   Botello told the students that Latinos spent more than $1.5
billion at the box office last year, and urged them to bring some
of that economic clout to bear on the film industry's reluctance to
do Latino-inspired works.
</P>
<P>
   But the group also wants to work on studios from the inside,
Botello said, by encouraging young Latinos to work in the film
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the academy before the event, Smits grinned
when asked about Hernandez, who missed the movie's introduction
because his mother was ill.
</P>
<P>
   He recounted the persistence of Hernandez, who was plucked from
more than 1,000 young men who auditioned for the part of Johnny
Ortega, the youngest son of Smits' character. On each callback,
Smits recalled, Hernandez gave a sharper performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just very proud of the work that he did,'' Smits said,
adding that he's also proud that success hasn't disillusioned
Hernandez, who is taking Advanced Placement calculus and other
rigorous courses at San Fernando High.
</P>
<P>
   The young actor already has turned down two roles, Smits said,
``one time because he was taking tests in school and he was
conflicted, and the other time he didn't really like the particular
script and what it said about Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, he's got all this going on, and he's got a nice little
conscience, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Perez, a 19-year-old senior and cultural arts commissioner
for San Fernando High's student government, said Hernandez's
success as an actor inspired him to seek work behind the scenes as
an editor.
</P>
<P>
   Perez recently produced a video about the life of Cesar Chavez
that will be shown at a school observance of the farm labor
leader's birthday Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that he's not the exception,'' Perez said of
Hernandez. ``He's a kid just like us.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
