<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCFOOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL STAR COMMITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Birmingham High (of Van Nuys) defensive back/wide
receiver John Walker has become the second player to give USC an
oral commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Walker (6-feet, 170 pounds) is projected as a cornerback in
college. He follows Upland defensive end Jason Wardlow, who
committed earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Walker could be the latest recruit to also run track for the
Trojans, since he excels in the 110-meter hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   __ New role: USC coach Paul Hackett believes the lines of
communication are better in spring practices, because offensive
coordinator Hue Jackson is also working as the quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jackson handled the running backs while Ken O'Brien
was the quarterbacks coach. O'Brien quit last December after being
asked to work with the tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I was concerned about was that the guy
putting the offense together (Jackson) was not having a direct link
to (quarterback) Carson Palmer,'' Hackett said. ``It wasn't Ken
O'Brien's fault, he was fine, but Hue had to be with the running
backs all the time, so it was difficult for us last year.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Controlled scrimmage: USC will scrimmage for about a
half-hour near the end of today's practice, which runs from 11:30
a.m.-2 p.m. at Howard Jones Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be real simple,'' Hackett said. ``A lot of first-and-10
situations. It's a chance to get some snaps.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Busy schedule: The player with the most hectic schedule could
be wide receiver Marcell Allmond, who is also a prominent hurdler
and decathlete on the track team.
</P>
<P>
   Allmond is trying to juggle both sports and will miss next
weekend's scrimmage, along with the April 8 scrimmage at the
Coliseum to participate in track meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to track practice every day before football,'' Allmond
said. ``I'm doing both.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Lucais MacKay, who is also a top discus
thrower, will miss today's scrimmage to go to a track meet.
</P>
<P>
   __ Outside linebacker battle: The most-competitive position on
the team could be strongside linebacker, where senior-to-be Sultan
Abdul-Malik started last season before moving to defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Kori Dickerson, freshman Chris Prosser, junior college
transfer John Cousins and converted tight end Scott Huber are all
competing for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping at the end of each scrimmage, we'll get closer to a
decision,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   While weakside linebacker Markus Steele recovers from shoulder
surgery, reserves Henry Wallace and Darryl Knight are fighting for
the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   Another position that needs to be filled is the holder for field
goals and extra points. Last year, senior John Fox handled those
duties. Cornerback Kevin Arbet, quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst and
free safety Ife Ohalete are all working at the position.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are also searching for a long-snapper. Linebacker
Zeke Moreno did it last year, but USC would prefer to have a
reserve handle the role. One of the candidates is former Westlake
High tight end Joe Boskovich.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shotgun debut: For the first time this spring, the Trojans
showed their shotgun formation Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the debut,'' Hackett said. ``We broke it out a bit.
I don't know where we'll go, but we'll take a look at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0011 </DOCNO>
