<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-YOSEMITE-RESTORATION-     03-25 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-RESTORATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIOR SECRETARY BABBITT TO ANNOUNCE YOSEMITE
ENVIRONMENTAL  PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL NOLTE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt will
announce details of an ambitious new plan for cutting car traffic
and restoring natural habitat in Yosemite Valley at a San Francisco
speech on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to those familiar with the plan, Babbitt will endorse
major reductions in parking spaces in the valley, turning Yosemite
National Park's headquarters building into a museum, ripping up
some roads, removing three bridges and a dam along the Merced
River, and building three satellite parking lots outside the valley
and encouraging day visitors to take buses.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new plan would make major changes in the ways
visitors can enjoy Yosemite, it does not go as far as a proposal
announced two years ago that would have banned most private cars in
the valley.
</P>
<P>
   That idea envisioned a fleet of shuttle buses carrying visitors
from outlying locations or some kind of parking facility near El
Capitan in an area called Taft Toe.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle bus idea has been greatly scaled back in the new
blueprint and the parking facility has apparently been dropped.
Both ideas ran into considerable opposition, and the 1997 plan was
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The new National Park Service document that Babbitt will outline
in Monday's speech at the Commonwealth Club instead hopes to reduce
summertime traffic jams in Yosemite Valley through a major cutback
in parking spots.
</P>
<P>
   Parking will be concentrated in the Yosemite Village area and
many parking lots in the eastern end of the valley will be torn out
along with roads through the Stoneman and Ahwahnee Meadows, two of
the most beautiful areas of the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the park service hopes to slash car traffic by opening
three new lots with a total of 1,600 spaces. One would be on the
Highway 120 entrance to the park, near Crane Flat, the second would
be off Highway 41 near the Badger Pass ski area and the third is
planned for El Portal, on Highway 140.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors would be encouraged to park their cars at these
locations and ride shuttle buses into Yosemite Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The new blueprint _ technically called a preferred alternative
to the Draft Yosemite Valley Plan _ also reportedly calls for
tearing up parking lots near Yosemite Falls, removing a large and
homely toilet facility near the falls, tearing down the old
superintendent's residence, eliminating the old horse stables,
taking out some units of the Housekeeping Camp, and removing other
park service and concession facilities.
</P>
<P>
   However, the major effort is to strike a blow against
overcrowding. Eighty percent of the visitors to Yosemite come for a
single day only and 90 percent of them drive cars. On some summer
weekends, the valley that John Muir called ``incomparable'' has
been the scene of horn-honking traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service has been trying to solve this problem
for over 20 years with a series of plans that were announced with
speeches and fanfare, but never implemented.
</P>
<P>
   The last valley plan, unveiled at a news conference in Yosemite
on a glorious autumn day two years ago, had to be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, the Park Service was sued by the Sierra Club and
forced to redo yet another of its plans. By then Babbitt himself
had become involved. He replaced park service veteran Stanley
Albright as Yosemite's superintendent and installed David Mihalic,
a manager with a reputation for action.
</P>
<P>
   Now Babbitt is taking the highly unusual step of introducing a
draft plan himself. The secretary ``has been interested in Yosemite
since he first took office,'' said Department of the Interior
spokesman Tim Ahern. ``Yosemite is one of the four or five most
beautiful places in the world, and he has fallen under its spell.''
</P>
<P>
   Others feel that the Clinton administration is attempting to
leave a legacy of environmental actions that are popular with its
core constituency, including the creation of roadless areas in
national forests and new national monuments in the southwest and
west together with new ways to enhance the visitor experience in
the national parks.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the Park Service's Yosemite ideas have the
enthusiastic support of some environmental groups like the
Wilderness Society. Jay Watson, the society's regional director,
said he thought the new Yosemite plan would be ``a very big deal''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is clear that the Park Service will make an effort
to substantially reduce car traffic in Yosemite.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Watson said he had not seen the plan, he was ``very
encouraged'' by what he had heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a big change, a dramatic improvement,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other environmentalists may not be so enthusiastic. The draft
plan also contains some proposals dealing with expansion of
Yosemite Lodge, which has drawn fire from the Sierra Club and rock
climbers. The new plan is reportedly a massive document _ five
volumes, including one thick book of maps. The Park Service will
hold public hearings on the plan, some of them as far from Yosemite
as Seattle, Chicago and Washington, D.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
