r a BC-CITYHALL-BUDGET-LADN     03-25 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITYHALL-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY HALL MAKEOVER COST TRIPLES TO $299.8 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles _ The cost to renovate Los Angeles City Hall has
jumped an additional 10 percent, to $299.8 million _ nearly three
times the original price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Legislative Analyst Ron Deaton on Friday blamed the latest
escalation on a combination of factors, mainly that bids came in at
nearly $14 million more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lag in time on when we prepared our bids and when
they went on the street,'' Deaton said. ``They came in much higher
than expected.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, officials decided to put in a new
communication system using fiber optics, at a cost of $4.5 million,
as well as a $9 million contingency fund to cover other costs.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Vosburgh, a spokesman for the Howard Jarvis Taxpayer's
Association, said he was not surprised by the increases for a
project originally estimated at $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of an `Oh, God, what else is new?' type of thing,''
Vosburgh said. ``It strikes me they have already invested so much
in it that they can't get out now. It's like being in quicksand.''
</P>
<P>
   The project, started nearly two years ago because of damage from
the Northridge Earthquake, is scheduled for completion next year
with a planned move-in date of July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   There will be some changes from the way offices were laid out in
the past, an effort to bring some sense to a building whose
interior can be as confusing to navigate as some City Council
ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office will return to the third floor just off the
Rotunda, as it had been in the past, and mayoral staffers will have
offices on the second, third and mezzanine levels rather.
Previously they were scattered about the building on floors that
sometimes required two elevators to reach.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council chambers will retain its site but with a new
look, so the council horseshoe will face out to the audience. Work
also is planned to improve the acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think if you stand in the back of the room, people will
actually be able to hear what is said,'' Deaton said.
</P>
<P>
   All council offices will be located on the fourth floor of the
building, rather than on various floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is make it easier for the public to
find the council offices rather than (be) wandering around,''
Deaton said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for making use of the entire building instead of
an earlier proposal that closed off floors above the 10th level.
This would allow the city to bring back some key departments such
as Planning and Public Works, which now are in office space six
blocks from City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In regard to City Hall's plan to consolidate offices, Joel
Loomer, who is part of a group that owns property on Spring Street
and has the city as a tenant, said he was concerned about the
historic downtown area being abandoned by the city or its workers
and the impact it would have on the historic core area of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city convinced the state to build the Ronald Reagan State
Office Building in the historic core with the promise it would
support the area,'' Loomer said. ``I wouldn't want to see a change
in policy.'
</P>
<P>
   Deaton said the city remained committed to the area but also
needed to consolidate its services at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the extra costs of fixing City Hall, the Ad Hoc
City Hall Seismic Committee recommended that an additional $170,000
be provided to repair an elevator at Van Nuys City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
