<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUCHANAN-ANTIWAR-SFCH     03-25 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-ANTIWAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN, IDEOLOGICAL OPPOSITES GATHER AGAINST WAR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MATEO, Calif. _ Conservative presidential candidate Pat
Buchanan and leftist author Alexander Cockburn are the strangest of
bedfellows in a unique anti-war conference this weekend in San
Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for tie-dye T-shirt-wearing protesters chanting
``Give peace a chance'' are going to be disappointed. The
conference, sponsored by Antiwar.com and the Center for Libertarian
Studies, is expected to attract about 200 people to the Villa Hotel
in San Mateo, where speakers will slam the United States for
``acting the part of a global bully,'' said Burt Blumert, a
spokesman for the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the deep American tradition of anti-intervention,''
Blumert said. ``Just like in Vietnam, the opposition comes from the
extremes of the political spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   For Harry Browne, the Libertarian Party's presidential candidate
in 1996, the conference is a chance to talk about his party's
opposition to foreign intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does war add to the size of government, but big
government leads to war, since war provides a way to enhance its
size and power,'' said Browne, who's seeking his party's nomination
again this year. ``To stop war-making, we need to reduce government
to a tiny fraction of its current size.''
</P>
<P>
   While ideological opposites like Cockburn, a columnist for The
Nation, and Buchanan, a former Republican seeking the Reform Party
nomination for president, travel very different political paths,
they have ended up at the same point when issues like last year's
bombing of Serbia are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``How the Left sold out to Imperialism,'' is the title of
Cockburn's lunchtime talk Saturday, while in a speech last night,
Buchanan made his own position clear.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Republicans and Democrats a trying to foist a
``neo-imperialist'' foreign policy on the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is best for America and the West, they tell us, is that
the United States should remain a superpower sheriff ... possessed
of the sole right to deputize posses ... to discipline evildoers
wherever our `values' are threatened,'' Buchanan said. ``I submit
that this foreign policy poses a great and growing danger to the
peace and security of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   While Buchanan called himself ``a proud ex-Cold Warrior who
supported every great anti-Communist initiative from JFK to Ronald
Reagan,'' he pledged that if elected he would pull all U.S. troops
out of Bosnia and Kosovo by year's end and bring all American
troops home from Europe by the end of his first term. That promise
drew loud applause from the standing-room-only audience last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not wish to isolate America from the world, only to
isolate America from wars _ the religious, ethnic and territorial
wars of less fortunate lands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today's anti-war movement is anything but politically correct,
Blumert admitted. The semi-isolationist doctrines of Buchanan and a
number of other conservative scholars carry plenty of baggage
dating from the original ``American First'' movement before World
War II, an effort to keep the United States out of the war in
Europe that left its members branded anti-Semites and Nazi dupes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the body bags start coming home is the only time it's
easy to be anti-war,'' Blumert said.
</P>
<P>
   While Cockburn represents the political left at the conference,
most of the speakers are from the conservative edge of the
landscape and the crowd there reflected that. While Buchanan's
jibes at Democratic Vice President Al Gore drew laughs from the
audience, his suggestion that the Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
GOP nominee for president has shown ``neither an absorbing interest
nor an extraordinary aptitude for foreign policy'' brought a
similar response.
</P>
<P>
   The third party theme of the convention ran through the other
scheduled speakers. Lenora Fulani, a Reform Party member and
Buchanan backer who ran for president on the New Alliance Party
ticket in 1988, is a speaker, as is Browne, the Libertarian leader.
Ron Paul, a Republican congressman from Texas who was the
Libertarian presidential candidate in 1988, also is on the
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The conference begins at 8:30 Saturday morning and continues
Sunday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
