<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DODGERS-STADIUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL TO BUILD SCHOOL STRIKES OUT WITH DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles _ The Los Angeles Dodgers threw a curve Friday to
the Los Angeles Unified School District's ``ideal'' site for a new
high school near downtown: the team's parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Since the $200 million Belmont Learning Center was abandoned,
LAUSD officials have been looking for new sites nearby. But Dodgers
President Bob Graziano has informed the district that the team does
not believe the use of 16 acres of Parking Lot 23 would be
appropriate for a school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district's suggestion to build a 2,000-person high school
... is fraught with extraordinary hurdles that make the concept
impractical,'' Graziano wrote in a letter to school officials
obtained by the Los Angeles Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building a high school at the main entrance to Dodger Stadium
would create significant safety issues for our neighbors, our fans
and the prospective students. In addition, there are concerns over
traffic, construction and parking needs, freeway access,
environmental issues and scheduling conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziano said the Dodgers would be willing to help the district
with alternative sites, but it was unclear whether that would
include other parts of their property.
</P>
<P>
   The school board voted this year to abandon Belmont, the
nation's costliest school, which was built on a site oozing toxic
and explosive gases from abandoned oil wells. To replace the 4,000
student seats lost by that decision, the LAUSD is considering
replacement sites nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials said Friday that they could not comment on the
letter as part of an agreement with the school district not to
discuss the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Miller, chief operating officer for the district, said
school officials believe the parking lot remains the ideal
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need high school seats and we think Lot 23 is the best
site,'' Miller said. ``We will just have to continue our
discussions with the Dodgers on this or other sites they have
control of. We don't know what alternatives they are talking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The school district has the power of eminent domain to take over
property for schools, although the Dodgers could slow down that
process in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get to that point,'' Miller said. ``We think
there is room for more discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   School board member Caprice Young said she was not surprised by
the baseball organization's position, adding that she welcomes
their help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take any 16 acres they can come up with,'' Young said.
``We are totally open to their suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg, whose district is adjacent to
Dodger Stadium, said she believes the school district is wrong to
look at other locations until it resolves all the questions over
the Belmont Learning Center site.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it isn't safe and can't be made safe, that's one thing,''
she said. ``No one would want to build there. But if it was a
political decision to stop construction, that's something else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles City Council entered the Belmont debate this
month, passing a motion that called for the city to withhold key
funding and building permits for new school construction in the
Belmont attendance area if the council is dissatisfied with the
district's plans to replace Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7679 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ABSINTHE-RETURNS-SFCH     03-25 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABSINTHE-RETURNS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENDSETTERS BRING BACK A DILUTED ABSINTHE, ONCE TOUTED BY VAN 
 GOGH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Absinthe, the emerald-green liqueur that was popular in
fin-de-siecle Paris and is now enjoying a watered-down comeback,
contains a neurotoxin that may account for some of the addled
behavior of Vincent Van Gogh, scientists said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Using lab mice to solve a century-old riddle, researchers
reported that a substance called alpha-thujone _ the active
ingredient in what some cognescenti call ``La Fee Verte,'' or ``the
green fairy'' _ can lead to the out-of-control firing of brain
cells.
</P>
<P>
   A similar misfiring is found in some forms of epilepsy. Other
symptoms long linked to absinthe consumption include addiction,
hallucinations and delirium.
</P>
<P>
   Many late 19th century and early 20th century creative geniuses
had a strong taste for absinthe, and became well-practiced in its
elaborate mystique and rituals _ typically involving perforated
spoons, water and sugar in a sidewalk-cafe setting.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Van Gogh, other famous imbibers included Baudelaire,
Rimbaud, Verlaine, Toulouse-Lautrec and Picasso. Many immortalized
the beverage in paintings, notably Toulouse-Lautrec, who favored
diluting his in cognac rather than water, forming a deathly
concoction he called an ``earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears some of their more curious, if not
self-destructive, psychiatric symptoms may be explained by
absinthe's activity on a special type of receptor responsible for
controlling the excitation of brain signals.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the GABA receptor, it is a key component in the brain's
delicate system of self-control.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy consumption of the high-potency liqueurs common in Van
Gogh's day ``would have greatly disrupted the nervous system,''
said John Casida, a professor of toxicology and environmental
chemistry at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Casida and colleagues at UC Berkeley and the Northwestern
University Medical School summarized their findings in the latest
issue of the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   A separate report on the same material is scheduled for Monday
during the national meeting of the American Chemical Society, which
convenes this weekend in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the latest findings explain Van Gogh's psychiatric
symptoms and more extreme behavior _ which ultimately led to his
infamous ear-slicing and suicide _ is a matter of conjecture.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gogh experts said Friday the new biochemical evidence
certainly sheds some important light on one of history's most
intensely creative periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old absinthe was bad stuff,'' said Dr. Wilf Arnold at the
University of Kansas Medical Center, author of the book ``Vincent
Van Gogh: Chemicals, Crises and Creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is finally a good scientific reason to explain the
toxicity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Van Gogh appears to have suffered a congenital
condition called acute intermittent porphyria, whose psychiatric
conditions can be drug induced.
</P>
<P>
   Others who lacked such predispositions, including Van Gogh's
onetime roommate Paul Gauguin, may have been able to drink more
absinthe than Van Gogh with much less severe results, Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Absinthe's active ingredient, which comes from an extract of the
wormwood plant, has been linked to psychiatric illness, convulsions
and even death since the 1850s.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could determine just how the drug affected the brain. As
a result of health concerns, the drink was banned shortly after the
turn of the century in France and many other countries, including
the United States, where it is still outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   But today, green-colored absinthe beverages, some containing 55
percent alcohol, are sold legally in parts of Europe and Canada.
Their potency, however, is much reduced: less than 10 parts per
million of the active ingredient versus 260 parts per million in
``old absinthe,'' according to some recent studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite trendy in the U.K. at the moment,'' said Sue Hill,
office manager at a British absinthe dealer called Sebor Absinthe,
which advertises on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the company's Web site gets a steady stream of
orders, perhaps 20 or so daily, from would-be absinthe drinkers in
the United States _ part of an apparent worldwide surge in
retro-European-style tippling.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, herbal concoctions containing the same active
ingredient, including extracts of wormwood oil and cedarleaf oil,
are sold to control various digestive and liver symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Dosages are supposed to be too low for any brain effects, but at
least one accidental poisoning has been reported recently in a
31-year-old man who eventually recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Casida noted that many of the herbal medicines have not been
rigorously tested. The National Institutes of Health plans further
studies of products with alpha-thujone next year.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates argue against outright prohibition, maintaining that
people who want the stuff will find it anyway, or can make their
own homemade versions with unpredictable results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 0103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
