<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7680 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-TULSA-MIAMI-HNS &LR;      03-25 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TULSA-MIAMI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ By nature of its location, Central Texas doesn't often
feel the brunt of a hurricane. At the Erwin Center on Friday night,
however, one was going to make landfall one way or another.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only question was singular or plural.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle of the breeze, the Tulsa Golden Hurricane blew
away the Miami Hurricanes 80-71 to advance to the South Regional
final Sunday afternoon as one of the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   With one more NCAA Tournament victory, Tulsa would go on to the
Final Four, quite an achievement for a small, private school that
plays in the lightly regarded Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what you call us, but in a lot of ways we are a
Cinderella,'' said Tulsa coach Bill Self. ``We got like two votes
in the AP preseason poll. But as the season's gone on, our players
have shown they can play with anybody. I don't mind being the
underdog. We play better when we think we're the underdog. We have
a little chip on our shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Hurricane, seeded No. 7 in the South despite what is
now a 32-4 record, used speed and defense to take down No. 6 Miami
(23-11) of the Big East Conference. Tulsa center Brandon Kurtz,
shut out in the first half, scored 17 points in the second half and
keyed a 20-4 run that put the game out of reach. Kurtz and Eric
Coley led Tulsa with 17 points each, and Kurtz had 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   As usually is the case, five players scored in double figures
for Tulsa. Greg Harrington added 14 points, Marcus Hill 13 and Tony
Heard 11.
</P>
<P>
   Miami put up a valiant fight after falling behind by 17 points
in the first half. The Hurricanes closed to 31-25 at the half and
took a 46-43 lead when Vernon Jennings hit a 3-pointer with 10:30
left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings and Mario Bland led Miami with 17 points each. Johnny
Hemsley, the Hurricanes' leading scorer all season, was held to 13
points by Tulsa's tenacious defense.
</P>
<P>
   As it did in a second-round win last weekend against Cincinnati,
Tulsa took a big early lead, let it slip away in the second half
and then raced away in the final 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they'd make a run,'' said Kurtz. ``It reminded me of
the Cincinnati game in that we felt that we had worn Cincinnati
down with about six minutes left. Tonight, we took Miami's punch
and kept plugging away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa used its quickness and ball-hawking talent to force 13
Miami turnovers in the first half and 20 in the game. The teams
traded baskets in the early going, but Tulsa went on a 16-0 run
over a nine-minute span to go ahead 25-8.
</P>
<P>
   With 6:40 left in the first half, Miami had committed nine
turnovers and scored eight points _ numbers that add up to no good.
</P>
<P>
   During that run, Harrington scored five points, while Coley and
David Shelton added four each. In addition, Harrington and Coley
took turns holding down Hemsley, who had to work for every shot.
</P>
<P>
   But as was the case in its second-round win over Cincinnati,
Tulsa couldn't stand prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   When Miami's John Salmons scored on a short jumper with 6:10
left, Tulsa was ahead 25-10. However, Miami's Jennings and Hemsley
heated up, and Tulsa cooled off. Jennings scored eight points
before halftime, and James Jones hit a 3-pointer to trim the Tulsa
lead to 31-25.
</P>
<P>
   Except for 4-of-5 shooting from 3-point range, Miami would have
been further behind. The Hurricanes were only 4-of-14 on two-point
field goals and were outrebounded 20-14 by a shorter Tulsa team.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had no answer in the second half for Kurtz, a 6-11 senior
who scored eight points during Tulsa's 20-4 game-deciding run.
After a slam dunk put Tulsa back ahead 47-46 with 9:45 left, Kurtz
gestured toward the Tulsa fans and exhorted them to make more
noise.
</P>
<P>
   The fans responded, and so did Kurtz. He scored six of Tulsa's
next eight points as the Golden Hurricane lead grew to 63-50 with
4:45 left in the game. Tulsa hit its free throws down the stretch
to hang on for the win, its first in a Sweet 16 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with the way they keep fighting and
scratching,'' said Miami coach Leonard Hamilton. ``They were a step
quicker than us at the end. If they play that way, there's no
telling how far they can go in this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
