<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-25 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ This 2000 NCAA Tournament certainly will be remembered for
being so upside down, so backward, so inside out.
</P>
<P>
   Up has been down. High seeds have felt low. Big has been little.
And Friday night at the Erwin Center, there were a few strange
moments cropping up here and there.
</P>
<P>
   A giddy chant of ``TU, TU'' went up in the middle of the South
Regional, and the Aggies were nowhere to be found. Later, UT was in
the house, but nobody was flashing the Hook 'em Horns.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as you might feel the urge to lump all the goings-on
Friday with the other shocking developments of the 2000 Tourney,
don't.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa 80, Miami 71 was no surprise and no upset.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Tulsa team that has been redefining the term
``Self-ish'' all year and now might even have thrust itself into
the role of the favorite to make it not just to the Final Four but
to the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Two big pieces of clutter sitting between Tulsa and Indy were
dusted away Friday night, in much the same fashion as so many other
obstacles have been booted on their big Tournament run. With
defense. With speed. And with a bit of good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrific exhibition of defense and hustle that jammed
Miami into submission.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Syracuse, N.Y., the Florida Gators _ a team that
Tulsa can beat _ ousted No. 1-seeded Duke, which was a team no one
figured to beat.
</P>
<P>
   The path to a remarkable 2000 story is clearing. What other
teams don't sweep away, the Golden Hurricane seems more than
capable of doing itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could care less what tag people put on us,'' Tulsa coach
Bill Self said. ``Cinderella? I just know we're still playing.
These players have shown they can play with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   They showed it with remarkable conviction Friday, scratching
past a team that shared the Big East title only one outing after
booting the former No. 1 team in the country, Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   If you're counting, the Golden Hurricane is now 32-4, with the
four losses coming by a total of seven points.
</P>
<P>
   Self has been selling this all-out scrambling,
fingernails-to-the-floor style of his all season. The Hurricane has
bought it and has swarmed opponent after opponent into submission
with an endless stream of fresh bodies and athletic moves.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Miami Hurricanes sold, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember ever saying that the other team had more
energy than we had,'' Miami coach Leonard Hamilton said. ``But
Tulsa did. There's no other way to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hurricanes regular-season leading scorer Johnny Hemsley,
whose 13 points Friday were five below his average and who hit just
four of 10 shots: ``I've seen pressure before. But I have never
seen a group of guys play together as well as they do or as hard as
they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably not since 1985, when Villanova won it all as a No. 5
seed, has a team seemed so in sync with the X's and O's come
Tournament time. Probably not since then has the whole bunch of
starters fallen into such a groove and looked so fluid,
particularly defensively.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's game, Miami had four turnovers in the first three
minutes and 20 for the game and hit just 39 percent of its shots
against a team that features only one player taller than 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration was written all over the faces of the Miami players,
even when they briefly took the edge 46-43 before the Hurricane
stripped away the game with its defense and a 22-5 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went pretty much as scripted,'' Self said. ``We got tired,
but I think we wore them out more.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of scripts, probably not since the 1988 Kansas Jayhawks
(a No. 6 seed) has a Tourney team seen so many things fall
perfectly in place for a big run.
</P>
<P>
   After taking out UNLV in its Tournament opener, Tulsa faced
Cincy, which had lost Kenyon Martin for the season. On Friday, the
Golden Hurricane was simply better than Miami, but Tulsa still
caught a break when Miami big man James Jones left early with a
knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Now standing before the Hurricane and a trip to the Final Four
is No. 8 North Carolina, a young team that beat Tennessee on Friday
but, with 13 losses, isn't your classic Tar Heels powerhouse. And
if the Hurricane wants to dream beyond a Final Four appearance, the
road to the championship game also got easier with Duke's loss to
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Villanova? Remember Kansas? Say hello to Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
