<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-25 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ He stands around the side of the court in his
old gray sweatshirt and matching worn pants and looks like anything
but the next great thing.
</P>
<P>
   And to hear Larry Eustachy tell it, he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the message being delivered by his Iowa State
team.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, when Eustachy's Cyclones take on top-seeded Michigan
State and its green-and-white wave of a home-court advantage at the
Palace, at stake will be a spot in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   And anybody who says they saw that one coming back in November
probably has a nose longer than Pinocchio's.
</P>
<P>
   In most of the preseason polls, Iowa State was picked to finish
last or near the bottom of the Big 12 Conference. Now, the most
improved and most surprising team in the country stands 31-4 after
turning out the lights on UCLA's high-wire act Thursday night in
the Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones come at you with a truckload of defense and with an
offense that is as tough to stop as an advancing army. The tank is
Marcus Fizer, the 6-7, 265-pound junior who is a sure NBA lottery
pick. The trigger man is point guard Jamaal Tinsley, who slices and
dices better than anything advertised on late-night television.
</P>
<P>
   But Eustachy is the man drawing up the plays and employing the
strategies that have enabled Iowa State to make the assault. TV
portrays the coaches in college basketball these days as sideline
generals, the main event to watch as the players come and go so
quickly through the programs in such a constant hurry to strike
professional riches.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Knight is nothing less than the General at Indiana, even
going so far overboard with some of his antics to be described as
czar, dictator, king for life.
</P>
<P>
   Not Eustachy. To say he and Knight are cut from the same mold is
to say Rembrandt and the guy who put a fresh coat on your living
room are both painters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Eustachy recently took a big step toward Knight and the rest
of the big names in terms of salary, receiving a bump from $500,000
annually to nearly $1 million per season in a 10-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been happier,'' Eustachy said. ``Never, ever.
That's what happens when you get to a place you finally know is
where you're going to be. When I signed that deal, I was signing a
lifetime contract at a place I love, a place with tremendous
potential. I'll tell you, that is something that is very, very
reassuring.''
</P>
<P>
   Those should, of course, be reassuring words to the fans and
administration of Iowa State, hearing that the man who has them on
the verge of their first Final Four appearance since 1944 never
wants to call the moving van again. There is every reason to
believe Eustachy believes those words and says them with honesty
and conviction. Today.
</P>
<P>
   However, the truth of the matter is that in these days of
salaries spiraling up like financial cyclones, it is hard to
envision a coach of his caliber staying at such an out-of-the-way
place like Ames, Iowa, for the rest of his career. Sure, it could
happen. Jim Boeheim arrived on campus to enroll and play ball at
Syracuse in 1963 and has never left. But Boeheim is an anachronism,
and besides, Eustachy doesn't have the old school ties to Iowa
State.
</P>
<P>
   The previous coach who had the Cyclones fighting for a time for
national recognition was Tim Floyd, and he jumped when he could to
the post-Michael Jordan Chicago Bulls, even if it meant losing
every night. Because the money was huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me,'' said Eustachy, pointing to his sartorial
inelegance. ``How much money do I need? This is who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   But it becomes a question not of need but of what is offered and
how big a spotlight is shined in a man's face and whether he is
attracted to the warmth.
</P>
<P>
   No one would blame Eustachy _ or any other coach _ for listening
to another offer if the athletic directors of Division I-A schools
want to dangle a sheik's riches. The ADs say they are just trying
to keep pace with the market, and yet they send the market higher
and higher all the time. Kansas State just hired Jim Wooldridge and
gave him $600,000 a year, even though his resume is limited.
</P>
<P>
   So what if someday a bigger name like Louisville comes along
looking for a replacement for Denny Crum, who is near the end of
the line and may have been nudged closer by a first-round NCAA
Tournament loss to Gonzaga? It so happens the Louisville AD is Tom
Jurich, who just happens to be an old high school pal of Eustachy's
from Arcadia, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The two also share a past in the Big Sky Conference. Jurich ran
the program at Northern Arizona while Eustachy was the coach at
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   This is what some schools do when they want to give their
programs a shot in the arm _ bring in a coach with solid
credentials and a track record, rather than the glory of mere name
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm flattered that anybody would even think of me
in terms of a program like that,'' said Eustachy. ``But it's not my
kind of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it here. The only place I'm interested in going is
Indianapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy, content, full of everything he needs in Ames. But if
Eustachy gets to the Final Four, don't bet on it being where he
winds up. Other schools have gray sweatshirts.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
