<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA TO FACE TULSA FOR FINAL FOUR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hang around and let the other team hang itself.
Pick up the pieces. That is what North Carolina did Friday night
against Tennessee, winning in stunning style, 74-69, before 16,731
fans at the Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier game here, Tulsa beat Miami, 80-71. The Golden
Hurricane (32-4) now plays North Carolina (21-13) on Sunday for the
South Regional title and a trip to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee led at halftime, 39-33, and the lead would have been
more if Carolina's Jason Capel had not scored a 3-pointer 3 seconds
before the buzzer sounded. Carolina picked up from there in the
second half despite losing its 7-foot center, Brendan Haywood. He
fouled out with 8 minutes 3 seconds left and Carolina trailing,
55-53.
</P>
<P>
   But Carolina guard Ed Cota provided all of the leadership the
team needed, controlling the game, driving for critical baskets,
including the one that tied the score, 64-64, with 3 minutes left,
and one that put Carolina ahead for good, 66-64, with 1:58 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tremendous win for us,'' said Bill Guthridge, North
Carolina's coach. ``I'm proud of the way my team hung in there. We
gambled with Brandon in there and that backfired, the then the team
bailed us out with tremendous play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cota, who finished with 11 points and five assists, said:
``Coach told us we were probably going to be behind a lot in this
game and to keep our poise. He was right and soon enough the game
turned our way and was ours.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is seeking the 15th Final Four appearance in the
school's history.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Tar Heels were outplayed. They won despite
failing to score any points off fast breaks. They won despite being
outrebounded, 38-34. They won despite being beaten at the free
throw line, 21-12. And they won despite making making only four
3-pointers, two fewer than Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very good team, very athletic and I had a feeling we
would play this game from behind,'' Guthridge said. ``The teams
that have beaten them have mostly come from behind. We just wanted
to keep it close and have a chance to win at the end. And one of
the ways we managed that was our team was the most fired up that I
have ever seen from this bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first game, Tulsa, unlike Tennessee, was able to finish
what it started. Tulsa, the champion of the Western Athletic
Conference, raced to a 17-point lead late in the first half. The
Golden Hurricane lost the momentum midway through the second half
but finished strong, using a late 14-0 spurt to ensure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa featured balance _ four of its players scored in double
figures, led by forward Eric Coley and center Brandon Kurtz with 17
points each. Kurtz added 10 rebounds, helping Tulsa outrebound
Miami, 41-37.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa led in nearly every key category: it shot 56 percent in
the second half; it won in points in the paint, 40-22; points off
turnovers, 23-15; second-chance points, 10-6; and fast-break
points, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hats off to Miami,'' Kurtz said. ``They played great defense
in the first half. But then we spread the floor, and things sort of
opened up.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley added: ``We got the loose balls and we blocked shots. We
were able to win the little battles. We didn't get stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miami did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was probably faster than Miami wanted,'' Tulsa coach
Bill Self said. ``At the end, we were tired, but Miami was more
tired. Our four losses this season are all on the last possession
of the game. We've proven ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
