<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-EAST-NYT &LR;      03-25 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA STATE TOPPLES SETON HALL, WILL FACE FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE _ With its best player sitting on the bench in street
clothes, Seton Hall's improbable tournament run ended in dramatic
fashion Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen Holloway, a senior guard and co-captain who suffered a
severe sprain of his left ankle last Sunday against Temple, could
only watch the final excruciating minutes of the Pirates' 68-66
loss to Oklahoma State in the semifinals of the East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (27-6), seeded third in the region, will face
Florida, which upset top-seeded Duke, 87-78, in the other semifinal
Friday night. Seton Hall, seeded 10th, finished its season at
22-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates, who defeated Oregon and Temple in overtime in the
first two rounds, led by a point at halftime, and the game was tied
at 53-53 with 8 minutes 7 seconds remaining. The teams traded
basket after basket, and with 2:23 left, Seton Hall trailed by
60-57 despite hitting only 7 of 34 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The final moments were filled with timeouts, fouls and strategy.
Two free throws by Seton Hall's Al Harris cut Oklahoma State's lead
to 60-59 with 1:09 left. But the Cowboys got the next two points on
a layup off an inbounds pass and Seton Hall's next shot fell short.
Two free throws by Joe Adkins gave Oklahoma State a 64-59 lead.
Seton Hall called timeout with 27.5 seconds remaining. On the
inbounds play, Ty Shine, Holloway's replacement, set up Greg
Morton's layup to cut the Oklahoma State lead to 64-61 with 17.4
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   A foul by Shine resulted in two free throws by Glendon
Alexander, both good, to increase the Cowboys' lead to 66-61. With
16 seconds left, Shine missed a 3-pointer, but Darius Lane put in
the follow shot to cut the deficit to 66-63 with 7.6 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys came out of a timeout, Shine fouled Alexander
before the inbounds pass. After Alexander made one free throw of
two, Kaukenas dribbled downcourt and hit a 3-point field goal to
cut the lead to 67-66. But Alexander was fouled again and sank his
first free throw to make it 68-66 for the Cowboys. After a timeout,
he went back to the line with half a second showing on the clock.
He missed the second shot and Seton Hall took the ball off the
rebound. But the buzzer sounded to end the game before the Pirates
could get off a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Rimas Kaukenas led Seton Hall with 17 points. Lane had 16 and
Shine 11. For Oklahoma State, Desmond Mason had 16, Fredrik Jonzen
had 15 and Brian Montonati also had 15. Lane was 2 for 18 from long
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it really hasn't hit me,'' Holloway said of the end
of his career. ``It will hit tomorrow. I feel worse for my
teammates than I do for myself. We put forth a tremendous effort.
What a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tommy Amaker said: ``You can see it, smell it, almost feel
it. But we ran into a really good basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hitting our bodies, wearing us down,'' Lane said.
``We just got tired at the end. I thought we just ran out of time.
There wasn't enough time to get a miracle shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway sat on the bench, his left foot encased in wrappings.
He had cried on the bench Sunday after returning from the X-ray
room of the hospital in Buffalo during the second game against
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Shine came out cold Friday night, missing his first from outside
the arc in the first half. He did many other things well, including
grabbing rebounds and bringing the ball upcourt as the point guard
against the man-to-man defense of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gottlieb, the Cowboys' guard who finished with 12 assists
said he and coach Eddie Sutton were discussing the game afterward.
``Coach said, `Boy that was a struggle,''' Gottlieb said. ``It was
a war. Every team has to show up for a war like that. They were
undermanned. They are well coached.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
