<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-OKLAST-SETONHALL-     03-25 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLAST-SETONHALL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Seton Hall's string of upsets came to an end
Friday night when Oklahoma State held off the Pirates down the
stretch and advanced to the East Regional final with a 68-66
victory in front of 31,681 spectators at the Carrier Dome.
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSU (27-6) will play Florida on Sunday at 4 p.m. to see which
team will advance to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys led the final eight minutes of the game, but the two
teams never were more than five points apart in the second half.
OSU starts four seniors while Seton Hall had only one senior on the
floor Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience is big down the stretch,'' said Oklahoma State
forward Desmond Mason, who led the Cowboys with 16 points. ``When
you get this far, everybody is playing their tails off, but
experience can make a difference in the final minutes, and I think
that was true tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall, the No. 10 seed, ends the season 22-10 after pulling
off two overtime upsets to reach the regional semifinal. But the
Pirates were playing against OSU without senior starting point
guard Shaheen Holloway, the team's leading scorer this season. He
tore a ligament in his left ankle in the second-round victory over
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaheen is a heck of a player,'' said Oklahoma State coach
Eddie Sutton. ``They lost a lot when they lost him.''
</P>
<P>
   Backup point guard Ty Shine scored 26 points last weekend
against Temple, but he was 4-of-16 from the field Friday and
finished with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys point guard Doug Gottlieb had a big night with 12
assists and only two turnovers, along with seven rebounds. OSU
center Fredrik Jonzen scored 15 points and grabbed seven boards.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys led 60-57 when forward Brian Montonati went to the
line with 1:38 to go but missed two free throws. The big surprise
came on the other end when Seton Hall freshman Al Harris, a 46
percent free-throw shooter, made two attempts from the line to cut
it to 60-59.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were right there,'' said Seton Hall coach Tommy Amaker.
``We could see it, smell it and almost feel it, but we didn't
capitalize. Oklahoma State is a seasoned team, and they made huge
plays at the crucial moments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys built their lead back to 64-59 on a layup by
Montonati and two free throws by Joe Adkins with 27.5 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   It was 67-63 and appeared to be over when Seton Hall guard Rimas
Kaukenas, who led the team with 17 points, banked in a 3-pointer to
make it 67-66 with 1.8 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates quickly fouled Glendon Alexander on the inbounds
play with only five-tenths of a second left on the clock. Alexander
made the first free throw and missed the second, but Seton Hall
could not get a shot off before the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The first half had a bizarre ending when the Cowboys thought
they had taken a two-point lead as Mason took two steps across
midcourt and shot a 40-foot jumper that went through the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   But the shot came after the buzzer, even though the scoreboard
clock had not expired. The clock on the stadium scoreboard was not
in sync with the clocks above the baskets by six-tenths of a second
because of a cable connection problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton argued the shot should count, but OSU went to the locker
room trailing 36-35. Maybe that anger helped inspire the Cowboys at
the start of the second half, because OSU scored the first six
points after the break to take a 41-36 lead on three baskets by
Montonati.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
