<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAGIC-HNS     03-25 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAGIC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ORLANDO, Fla. _ Apparently, Hall of Fame-bound superstars are not a
requirement to succeed. Young, athletic players can, it seems, play
consistently hard and with hunger. A team built to be rebuilt can
win.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Rockets had any doubt _ and they did _ the Orlando Magic
rolled easily past them 112-96 on Friday to prove how much can be
gained through effort and intensity, athleticism and exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rockets worked to improve their draft lottery
position, the Magic just plain worked, increasing its lead for the
last Eastern Conference playoff spot to 1{ games over the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Shandon Anderson's career-high 35 points, the Rockets
lost for the ninth time in 10 games and are 5-19 since the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just played harder than us,'' said Rockets center Kelvin
Cato, who was scoreless in 22 minutes. ``They just played harder
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had the usual reasons to be relatively impassive,
and a few new ones.
</P>
<P>
   They did have to play Thursday night and then travel. They were
limited by more injuries. With Hakeem Olajuwon making his second
visit to the injured list, Walt Williams was ordered to skip the
game with a bruised thigh. And Matt Bullard, activated Thursday,
was not ready to return from back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic displayed its usual high-intensity, scrambling
defense. And the Rockets found themselves a few shooters short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are forced to go with a small lineup, missing Walt and
Matt,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``The way they play, they are
going to double-team everything, give you spot shots. We didn't
have a bunch of those guys. We made a couple of minute runs at them
and just didn't have enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important game (for the Magic). They're really
focused on the playoffs. We have a built-in excuse with all our
guys out. We have to get over all that stuff and start playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Magic, having supposedly razed the roster to save up for a
free-agent spending spree, instead has gone on a playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic's John Wallace played with a bone spur bulging on top
of his foot; he takes the cast off only for games. But he still
pounded the boards for 14 rebounds in 25 minutes and set the tone
as the Magic outrebounded the Rockets 10-1 on the offensive boards
in the opening half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely hurting,'' Wallace said. ``I want to be out
there with my teammates. When you're not out there on the floor _
that's when the team has the most fun _ and I want to be a part of
that. I don't want to miss anything.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Rockets playing much of the game with at least three of
their fleet guards on the court, the Magic consistently beat the
remaining big men up the court, outscoring them 31-15 in fast-break
points. Orlando had a 24-11 edge in second-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   With the likes of John Amaechi, Bo Outlaw, Monty Williams and
Wallace working inside, the Magic outscored the Rockets 52-34 in
the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were undermanned at almost every position,'' Tomjanovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets might have been hurt and tired. But the only way in
which they could not match up was effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we need,'' Rockets guard Steve Francis said. ``We
need to be like that. We have to have it instilled in our heads and
have that be the mentality of our players once we decide that's how
we're going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Magic came at the depleted Rockets in waves,
getting double-figure scoring from four players off the bench, more
than the Rockets had total. And if depth wore the Rockets down, it
was not just because of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played harder than us,'' the Rockets' Cuttino Mobley
said. ``They played hard as a team, real hard. The guys know their
roles, and it makes it easier for all of them. They just played
harder than us, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   But after trailing by 20 points in the third quarter, the
Rockets went with every guard they could find _ and Carlos Rogers
in the middle _ and made a run.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson picked up the open shots left by the Magic's traps.
When he nailed a free throw and a trey, the Rockets were within 11
with seven minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets stayed that close for another minute, then Pat
Garrity nailed back-to-back 3-pointers to push the lead back to 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have some shooters out there, it changes the whole
scheme of defense on pick-and-rolls and all that stuff,''
Tomjanovich said. ``We didn't have any way to get anything off the
plays we run 70 percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a day after they combined for 64 points, Mobley and
Francis faced constant double-team pressure and had to force shots
to shoot at all. They combined for 31 points on 9-of-31 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Rockets made just 39 percent of their shots. And
other than Anderson's 11-of-21, they connected on just 18 of 54
shots.
</P>
<P>
   But more than lament what they failed to do, the Rockets were
impressed by the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great what (Magic coach) Doc Rivers and those guys have
done with all the trades and things of that sort,'' Anderson said.
``They're in the playoff hunt with guys from all over. They're just
really playing and working hard. That's what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
