<HEADER>
A7689 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLAN     03-25 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TRY TO MAKE IT INTERESTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whether toying with their opponent or just toying
with the idea of a suspenseful game, the Lakers played Friday like
a team that could get away with a little too much relaxation. And,
hey, they can.
</P>
<P>
   They let the injury-depleted Phoenix Suns nearly erase a 12-
point, fourth-quarter lead, let them crawl within three points in
the last minute, let everyone believe a careless collapse was
possible.
</P>
<P>
   They let it go no further. Kobe Bryant scored 28 points,
including three free throws down the stretch, and the Lakers held
off the gritty Suns 109-101 at Staples Center, to extend their
latest winning streak to five and improve to 3-0 against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was their 12th in a row at Staples and improved
their home record to 31-4, matching the Indiana Pacers for best in
the league. They haven't lost at Staples since Jan. 22, to
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have won 24 of their last 25 and haven't lost to a
Western Conference opponent since Feb. 1, at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal led the Lakers with a game-high 40 points and
14 rebounds. Bryant struggled in his defensive assignment against
Penny Hardaway and was burdened by foul trouble throughout but hit
9 of 15 shots and added seven assists and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shaw scored 11 points to play the role of third scorer on
a night when Glen Rice made just 1 of 6 shots for two points.
</P>
<P>
   After leading by as many as 12 points early in the fourth
quarter, the Lakers let the Suns whittle it down to 89-84. But they
put a stop to that run, as O'Neal scored six quick points, and Shaw
_ subbing for the foul-troubled Bryant _ hit a 3-pointer to push
the lead to double digits again.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Robinson scored five quick points to bring Phoenix
within seven points, 98-91, but the Lakers pulled away again, on
another Shaw 3-pointer and an O'Neal layup that made it 104-93 with
2:59 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson scored 22 points for the Suns. Hardaway finished with
25.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix arrived minus injured starters Jason Kidd and Tom
Gugliotta, but Lakers coach Phil Jackson wasn't worried about
anyone underestimating the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the way I prepared for them,'' he said before tipoff. ``I
told them, I think they're a better team right now, which happens a
lot of times. They came out of a two-point deficit on Wednesday
night (at Sacramento, when Kidd broke his ankle in the first half),
and beat them by 18 going away.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they turned it up a notch. They will, they've got the
talent. They can replace players. They still have a bench. (Oliver)
Miller's back, and (Shawn) Marion's back and Penny (Hardaway)'s
back. And they didn't play us last time with these three players.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even though Jason's gone, they've got guys that can step
in at least initially in a role like this and probably play very
well. In that regard, I think they will be well prepared. I
consider this a very difficult opponent and a good game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns hardly looked like an outmanned team in the first half,
scrapping again and again to stay within striking range and
settling for a respectable 51-45 deficit at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, the Lakers pushed their lead to seven or eight
points but never into double digits as the Suns kept plugging away
behind the offense of Penny Hardaway (12 points) and Clifford
Robinson (10 points).
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers, who led from the opening tip, never let the lead
slip below two points either, as O'Neal scored 15 points in the
half and Bryant overcame early foul trouble to score 17 points on
7-of-10 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Lakers had their way, with the exception of Ron
Harper, who was blocked by the front of the rim on a first-quarter
dunk attempt that had the entire Lakers bench doubled over in
hysterics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
