<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAROLINA-TENNESS     03-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAROLINA-TENNESSEE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ This time, it looked as if North Carolina's personal
version of March magic was at an end.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead, the Tar Heels continued their surprising run in the
NCAA Tournament on Friday night at the Erwin Center, outscoring
Tennessee 17-5 down the stretch to claim a 74-69 win in the South
Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Ed Cota, held scoreless in the first 17 minutes of
the second half, scored six points in the final three minutes. Cota
finished with 11 points, but he took over with the game on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out there trying to control the game, trying to have
patience,'' Cota said. ``I knew my time was going to come. My
teammates had faith in me, and I made some big plays down the
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, the No. 8 seed in the South, will play No. 7
Tulsa for the right to go the Final Four. With a win Sunday, the
Tar Heels would play in the Final Four for the sixth time in the
last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   None of those Carolina teams was anywhere near as surprising as
this year's, however. The Tar Heels were 18-13 before the NCAA
Tournament but have turned things around in the last 10 days. They
beat Missouri and Stanford last weekend and overcame a huge deficit
to beat Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tremendous win for us,'' said North Carolina coach
Bill Guthridge. ``The team bailed us out. Ed Cota, as he's done so
many times for four years, made some big plays. It was a thrill for
this team to advance this far.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee had a 62-55 lead with just more than six minutes left,
and 7-0 North Carolina center Brendan Haywood was on the bench with
five fouls. Freshman Joseph Forte, who led the Tar Heels with 22
points, scored five quick points to make it 64-60 with 4:25.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee froze up in the final minutes, getting only a
3-pointer by Tony Harris and a meaningless last-second layup by
C.J. Black, who led the Vols with 17 points. Harris was 1-of-10
from the field and 1-of-6 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for 35 minutes we played a very good game,'' said
Tennessee coach Jerry Green. ``But in the last four, five minutes
we started trying to make the hard play. While we were making the
hard play, they were making baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   As strange as it seems, North Carolina is the only team
remaining from the Atlantic Coast Conference. Duke, the ACC
regular-season champion and No. 1 seed in the East, was eliminated
Friday night by Florida.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina (21-13) jumped ahead early behind Forte, who
scored 13 first-half points and helped the Tar Heels to a 20-15
lead eight minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Isiah Victor and freshman Ron Slay keyed a 15-3 run by the
Vols that made it 30-23 with just more than seven minutes left in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee threatened to run away with the game when Victor and
Slay combined for the Vols' final nine points of the half to make
it 39-31, but Jason Capel scored five quick points for North
Carolina. Capel's 3-pointer with three seconds left in the half cut
the Tennessee lead to 39-36.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is four inches shorter than North Carolina's Haywood,
Black scored the first six points of the second half to help the
Vols to a 47-40 lead. Black had to sit down with three fouls at
17:05, but the Tar Heels not only couldn't cut into the lead, they
fell behind 51-42 with 12 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Haywood did slam one home and converted a standard three-point
play to pull the Tar Heels to 51-45. With that, Black came back
into the game, but North Carolina went inside to pull within 57-53
with 7:55 left.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Tar Heels were forced to play the rest of the way
without Haywood, who picked up foul No. 4 at 9:30 and fouled out 90
seconds later. Black, playing with four fouls, scored on a rebound
to make it 59-53 Tennessee, but the Tar Heels wouldn't go down
easily.
</P>
<P>
   With the game on the line, Cota took over. And once they had the
lead, the Tar Heels knew what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so proud and happy for our team to accomplish that,''
said Guthridge. ``Things didn't look very good for us tonight, but
the players did something I thought they were capable of doing all
season.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened earlier this season, when Carolina went 10-11
after starting the season 8-2?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to set everything (for the Tournament),'' said
Guthridge, smiling but perhaps knowing something more than the rest
of the college basketball world.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
