<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTENFIELD HOPES TO FIND HIS SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ The Angels acquired Kent Bottenfield and Adam
Kennedy from the Cardinals in Thursday's trade for Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   In Kennedy, they are getting a young second baseman who is
average defensively but has great potential offensively. In
Bottenfield, they are getting a pitcher who (a) won 18 games last
season, and (b) won four games in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Angels must be asking themselves, which Bottenfield did
they get?
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield is confident he will be the pitcher that went to the
All-Star game last year, simply because he says he has learned how
to pitch. Gone is the blazing fastball. Say hello to Mr. Location.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an opportunity to work with (Cardinals pitching coach)
Dave Duncan,'' Bottenfield said during a conference call Friday
afternoon. ``He taught me the mental aspects of the game. Pitching
is more than throwing hard. He taught me how to set hitters up, how
to prepare for each pitch, each hitter, each game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to say I'm on his level, but I'm a Greg Maddux-
type pitcher. Guys will walk away and wonder how I got them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield said his transformation as a pitcher was one of
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to understand the type of pitcher I was,'' said
Bottenfield, 31. ``I couldn't try to throw the ball by guys like I
did in the past. For a few years, I was banging my head against the
wall. I had to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield said he talked with Angels reliever Mark Petkovsek,
a former Cardinal, on Thursday night and was encouraged about his
new situation. However, Bottenfield said it was difficult to leave
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a little bit of time to get over the shock,'' he said.
''I was quite happy there. I didn't expect it. I was told it wasn't
going to happen. Maybe that was my first clue. . . . I turned my
career around in St. Louis. It's no secret St. Louis is a great
place to play.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Greene happy: Possibly the happiest Angel is Todd Greene, who
was in danger of being cut and losing a job. Instead, he'll make
the team as the primary DH and serve as a third-string catcher.
Scott Spiezio also will get some time at DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it in the past,'' Greene said. ``If I get consistent
at-bats, I think I can be successful. I know I can hit.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hill struggles:Starter Ken Hill gave up seven runs and 10
hits in 4 innings Friday in the Angels' 8-4 loss to the San Diego
Padres. That was the bad news for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for them was that Ramon Ortiz (small tear in
shoulder tissue) pitched one inning and felt fine. He gave up a
home run to Carlos Hernandez on his second pitch but retired the
next three hitters on ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like home runs,'' Ortiz said. ``But I felt great. I
threw only fastballs and changeups. I'm a happy man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz is likely to get a start Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
