<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUMPEL HEATING UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jozef Stumpel doesn't look back now that his future is
bright once again.
</P>
<P>
   After injuries threatened to ruin another season with the Kings,
Stumpel has emerged as one of the club's hottest scorers heading
into tonight's matchup with his former team, the Boston Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's 3-2 victory over Philadelphia, Stumpel tied the
game on a goal with 2:15 remaining and won it 1:20 into overtime
with a second goal. He also assisted on Luc Robitaille's power-play
goal midway through the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Kings move on to the Bruins, who selected Stumpel 40th
overall in the 1991 draft as an 18-year-old center from Slovakia.
They traded him with Sandy Moger on Aug. 29, 1997 for goaltender
Byron Defoe and defenseman Dimitri Kristich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Boston for five years and I enjoyed it very much,''
said Stumpel, who now has 17 goals and 50 points in just 49 games.
``It is a great city to walk around in. But it seems so long ago
now, my life is in Los Angeles. You always remember the team you
came up with, but we are headed to the playoffs and that is the
greatest feeling of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, 27, has five game-winning goals this season, including
three in OT this month. Yet, for much of this season, Stumpel
seemed to be carrying the same tag he wore in Boston _ a soft
player who was injury-prone. He missed seven weeks after undergoing
abdominal surgery and another month with a muscle tear in his right
knee. Without him, the Kings went 9-12-1. The rest of the time,
they were 26-18-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question he has stepped up his game,'' Kings coach
Andy Murray said after Thursday's game. ``He was in a bit of a
scoreless streak (four games), but there is no doubt how valuable
he is to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he mixes it up inside and adds a different dimension to
our offense. That's what we've been seeing more of.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Stumpel missed 18 games and the Kings finished out of
the playoffs. During his time with Boston, Stumpel was sidelined
with a bruised kidney, fractured cheekbone, sprained knee and a
separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   When he was healthy, Stumpel scored, leading Boston with 55
assists and 76 points during the 1996-97 season. The Bruins, like
the Kings this season, were trying to get grittier and believed
Stumpel was expendable.
</P>
<P>
   In his first season with the Kings, he led the team with 58
assists and 79 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons he has gotten hurt is because he is so
active around the net,'' said Dave Taylor, who made Stumpel one of
his first acquisitions after becoming GM in April 1997. But when he
is healthy, you can see what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Emerson out: Winger Nelson Emerson, acquired with Kelly
Buchberger from Atlanta at the trade deadline, is expected to miss
at least the rest of the regular season with a broken right index
finger.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, 32, returned to Los Angeles after suffering the injury
in the first minute of the third period during Thursday's 3-2
overtime win in Philadelphia. He was examined by hand specialist
Harold Zemel on Friday and his hand was placed in a cast.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, who scored one goal in four games after the trade, will
be replaced by Craig Johnson on the Kings' makeshift first line.
Johnson had assists on both Stumpel goals after Emerson left the
game on a slash by the Flyers' Daymond Langkow.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson moved into the top unit after Ziggy Palffy went down
last week with a sprained right shoulder. Robitaille, the third
member of the line, now is playing more with Bryan Smolinski and
Glen Murray. Robitaille scored his 34th goal Thursday, his first in
10 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
