<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-76ERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS FALL TO 76ERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Chins slumped on chests. Voices disappeared in
throats. Tears were seemingly the blink of an eye away.
</P>
<P>
   This could have been an interment, but it wasn't. It was worse.
The Celtics are still alive, and it's killing them.
</P>
<P>
   It's a foregone conclusion that they are trying desperately to
make the playoffs _ and probably won't. The mystery is why they'd
want to in the first place. How much agony can a team take?
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's dagger may be tougher to remove than all the
others combined. Turning abundant opportunities to prevail into
sawdust, the Celtics dropped a 117-115 double-overtime decision to
the resilient Philadelphia 76ers at the First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big heartbreaker,'' said coach Rick Pitino, looking as
if he'd just swallowed rotten calamari at his favorite North End
eatery. ``It's difficult, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is difficult, Pitino can only hope he never has to
experience intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' third straight loss was their second straight
crusher. But it made Wednesday's last-second, 109-106 demise at the
hands of Anthony Peeler and the Minnesota Timberwolves look like a
sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   This one plunged the Celtics to the depths of despair _ and the
brink of playoff mortality. Shoved deeper into 10th place in the
Eastern Conference, they now trail the victorious Orlando Magic by
3 1/2 games and the Celtics have only 13 games to play.
</P>
<P>
   If they can bear to take the court again, which they're
scheduled to do Sunday at ninth-place Milwaukee and Tuesday at
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't seem to be going our way,'' said Paul Pierce,
who led Boston with 31 points. ``We fight and fight down to the
end, but we just can't finish it off. It's like we've got a curse
on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, you know demons are on the loose when Matt Geiger beats
you. Or when you let Matt Geiger beat you.
</P>
<P>
   The journeyman center was the 76ers' unlikely savior, dissolving
the last of the game's 26 ties when he grabbed and converted Kevin
Ollie's missed layup with 39.9 seconds left in OT, Part II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good rebound,'' said Geiger. ``I went to the hole in
case Kevin missed. He did and I was there. It was just a routine
play.''
</P>
<P>
   What was galling was that it exploited a routine lapse by the
Celtics, who squandered 5-point leads in the last 1 1/2 minutes of
both regulation (95-90) and the first OT (104-99) because they
couldn't protect the ball. Even more than crucial missed free
throws (five in the two extra sessions) it was their failure to
break serve that did them in.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Ollie was allowed to run free after Adrian
Griffin's layup off a feed by Antoine Walker (24 points, 14
rebounds) was typical. And fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one to blame missed free throws and I'm not one to
blame missed shots,'' said Pitino. ``Transition defense has been
our Achilles' heel the whole year after we score. Kevin Ollie
should not be open on a breakaway in crucial situations.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was, and thus came undone the efforts of Pierce, Walker,
Kenny Anderson (18 points, 4-for-7 3-point accuracy), and Vitaly
Potapenko (18 rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with great courage,'' said Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   They also played with an alarming lack of purpose in the crunch.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Eric Snow (21 points, 8 assists, 5 rebounds) was able
to inbound the ball with 15 seconds left in regulation to Allen
Iverson (21 points on 7-for-25 shooting), who ignored the chip
fracture of his left big toe to set up Theo Ratliff (11 points, 14
rebounds) for the stuff that tied it, 97-97, and extended the
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   And that was why Aaron McKie countered Pierce's chest-thumping
19-foot jumper with 1.7 seconds left in the first OT and drilled an
18-footer that tied it, 107-107, and added another chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Just before that exchange, Anderson had missed his only free
throw of the night. ``If I make that,'' he said, ``then it doesn't
matter what McKie does. I could stay up thinking about that all
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Better he should dwell on this admonition from his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never over,'' said Pitino, harkening back to his college
days at Kentucky when Duke beat his Wildcats in the Elite Eight as
Grant Hill and Christian Laettner combined on a last-second
court-length conversion. ``I can tell you that, just like with
Christian Laettner, it's never over. You have to play defense.
Can't give them shots. It's never over.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Anderson could try the valiant philosophical approach of
Walker: ``It was just a good game. All those excuses _ we just came
up short. That's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny. He didn't look as if he'd particularly enjoyed himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
