<HEADLINE>
JORDAN: BRYANT'S D PUTS HIM OVER CARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Kobe Bryant's rapid growth as a defensive force
needed a stamp of validation, he got it Thursday from one of the
top authorities on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, comparing two of his supposed heirs _ Bryant and
Toronto's Vince Carter _ singled out Bryant as the better
all-around player. Defense was the reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince doesn't play defense,'' Jordan told the Chicago
Sun-Times. ``Kobe can play both ends. Right now he's a better
all-around player. And he's only 21? The kid hasn't even touched on
his greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant _ who has dominated at times against the likes of
Philadelphia's Allen Iverson, New York's Latrell Sprewell and
Milwaukee's Ray Allen _ took the comments as a sign that he's
getting recognition for his hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of it, I take pride in it. It pushes me even
more,'' he said. ``It tells me that I'm improving. (Jordan) is
observing the game, he's watching the game as everybody else is. .
. . It's cool, I guess, to get recognition like that. It just shows
I'm heading toward the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Jordan's evaluation of Bryant vis-a-vis Carter, Bryant
was nonchalant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter to me. It's a compliment, I guess,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said making the NBA All-Defensive Team is a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell yes,'' he said. ``Hell yes. Like now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Defensive Player of the Year, an award Jordan won?
``Eventually,''Bryant said, ``I'll get it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I've been here, I think you guys know, when a
player lights me up, whether it was Allen or whoever it was, that
gets under my skin, you know what I mean?'' Bryant said. ``You
don't like that feeling too much. So you want to get better at it
and that was my mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson has also lauded Bryant's defense but was
careful in responding to Jordan's assessment of the two young
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're different players for sure,'' he said. ``Kobe's more
of a playmaker right now than probably Vince is, and he's called
upon to do that role. I think it's too early to tell (who the
better player is). . . . They're young men that are still
developing their game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ KJ like MJ?: Jackson said it will be difficult for Kevin
Johnson, who rejoined the Phoenix Suns but skipped the trip to
L.A., to come back after two seasons in retirement. Jordan once did
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-four is really a tough age for guards,'' he said.
``Defensively, getting his legs underneath him and then the speed
of the game. To jump in at this time of the year, players are
playing at such a high level, the intensity and the quickness is
just really difficult to activate your nervous system and get up to
speed with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Rookie swingman Devean George missed Friday's
game because of the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 0215EST &QL; 
