<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANUCKS ROAST DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER _ For a team with playoff aspirations it was
embarrassing _ even pitiful. With two crucial points on the line,
the Mighty Ducks were simply sitting ducks for the Vancouver
Canucks who routed Anaheim 8-1 before 18,422 at GM Place on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of all but ending any playoff hopes the upstart Canucks
might have had, and maintaining or bettering their position in the
Western Conference standings, the Ducks went belly up _ much to the
delight of Vancouver's second sellout crowd of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The eight goals allowed equaled a season high and the Ducks, who
had given up only 14 in the previous seven games, managed to
accomplish that feat even though the Canucks had just one power
play _ on which they scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a hockey game,'' Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said.
``It was a total team breakdown . . . it shocks me.''
</P>
<P>
   And well it should. After a tenacious effort in a 2-1 loss at
Edmonton, the Ducks, played like a team playing out the string, not
a group desperate to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest game of the year and we didn't show up,''
said defenseman Oleg Tverdosvky. ``We got outbattled on every inch
and I have no answers why.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim may have Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne, but they were no
match for Vancouver's Peter Schaeffer. No joke. Schaefer was a
one-man wrecking crew against a Ducks team that was really only
competitive for the first 10 minutes of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year winger was on the ice for the Canucks' first
four goals, scoring the first two and assisting on the third. He
wasn't credited with an assist on the fourth, but made a long pass
that helped start a play that was converted by Matt Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya's power-play goal 27 seconds into the second had offset
Schaefer's first-period goal, and the Ducks actually had some good
chances to take the lead, including Antti Aalto hitting the post.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 good minutes out of 60 doesn't get it done in these
desperate days and Anaheim, which finishes the season 0-2-2 against
the Canucks, rolled over and played dead the final 10 minutes of
the second.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer gave Vancouver the lead at 11:07 when he beat
Tverdosvky around the net and put a wraparound past Guy Hebert. It
was the first of four goals in 8:11 for the Canucks, who seemed to
be the more desperate of the two supposedly desperate teams.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Messier all but finished off the Ducks at 14:09 when
Schaefer easily won a race to a loose puck behind the Anaheim net
and centered to the Vancouver captain in the high slot. The goal
came just nine seconds after the Ducks had squandered a chance to
tie the game on a power play.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was window dressing as Cooke and Andrew Cassels scored
56 seconds apart in the final 1 minutes of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg mercifully pulled Hebert after Cassels' goal with 41.3
seconds left in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved our butts in the first period,'' said Hartsburg. ``I
took him out to give him a rest. Todd Bertuzzi added two more
Vancouver goals in the final three minutes of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks arrived in Edmonton early Wednesday morning sharing
eighth place with the San Jose Sharks. They returned to Southern
California tied for ninth with the Canucks. They trail the
eighth-place Phoenix Coyotes, who they play Sunday, by three points
and Edmonton and San Jose by four with only six games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try to forget this and bring our best game
Sunday,'' said Tverdovsky, who realizes despite the embarrassing
nature of the loss that the Ducks' hopes remain alive, but
realistically only if they beat Phoenix at the Pond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
