<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE HOOP BY MALONE SENDS SONICS TO THIRD HOME LOSS IN ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When Karl Malone sauntered to the Utah Jazz bench late
in the fourth quarter, he threw a few jabs in the direction of
Olden Polynice. Malone's punches barely grazed his teammate's
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Figuratively, the Sonics felt every blow.
</P>
<P>
   When they wake up this morning, the ache of a painful 98-95 loss
to the Jazz Friday night at KeyArena will be real.
</P>
<P>
   Utah led 95-94 before Malone's 16-foot baseline jumper with 6.2
seconds left knocked the wind out of the Sonics' comeback attempt.
And when Vernon Maxwell's 3-point attempt to tie the score at the
buzzer bounced off the front of the rim, the loss inflicted a
couple of wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics dropped their third in a row in KeyArena. They also
fell to eighth in the Western Conference playoff standings.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's victory put the Sonics a half-game behind the
seventh seed. Sixth-seeded Minnesota won to move 2{ games in front
of the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my team that the NBA has a way of dealing you funny
challenges, and this is one of them,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sonics are in little danger of missing the playoffs _
they are 10 games ahead of the ninth-place team _ they are
staggering toward the postseason, which is about a month away.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz provided a taste of the week to come for the Sonics.
They were the first of five consecutive playoff-bound teams that
Seattle will face during the next nine days.
</P>
<P>
   After San Antonio on Monday, the Sonics host New York and
Sacramento before traveling to Portland. Each game now becomes
critical if the Sonics are to improve their playoff seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, though, was more about the team's psyche,
considering their recent struggles at home. They have dropped four
of five games at KeyArena _ all to teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's giving the effort and playing hard,'' said Sonics
forward Vin Baker, who did not appear inhibited by a bothersome
left hamstring. ``We've been losing some tough games. The one thing
we understand is we're not going to feel sorry for ourselves. A
couple of breaks here or there or a call or two here or there, and
we could have won these games.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's basket epitomized the Sonics' recent struggles at home.
</P>
<P>
   They can't seem to do enough to pull out a close game in their
building. Malone made the winning shot fading away because Sonics
center Horace Grant was so close the two could have been married.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way that shot was going in,'' Grant said
afterward. ``But, wow, you have to give him credit. He wanted to
take the last shot, and I knew he was going to take it because you
could see he wanted it. If I had to do it all over again, I think I
would have put him on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   That probably would not have mattered. Malone made 9 of 10 free
throws en route to a team-high 21 points to go with 12 rebounds. He
led five Jazz players who reached double figures in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton's 28 points and nine assists led the Sonics. Baker
added 25 points and Maxwell chipped in 18 points. Maxwell was
4-for-7 on 3-pointers before missing the game's final shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expects the Jazz to be in this situation,'' said
Malone, whose team won for the 12th time in 13 games. ``You know,
we're old and things like that. That's what they say. ... But it
says a lot about our team by going out and executing down the
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied 83-83 and the score seesawed until Utah took
the lead for good after Baker split a pair of free throws with the
Sonics down 92-90 with 1:26 left.
</P>
<P>
   After a Malone jumper, Baker scored to get the Sonics within
94-93. But then Jeff Hornacek answered quickly when he lost Maxwell
and scored a backdoor layup with 35 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-point Sonics cushion to start the final frame was
hardly enough. Utah went on a 10-1 run to start the fourth and
stormed in front 75-74.
</P>
<P>
   After a 45-42 halftime lead, the Sonics led by as many as 10
points in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The game was played with playoff intensity, evident by the
emotion and antagonism on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Several Sonics complained that Malone recklessly threw elbows to
the face after he grabbed rebounds. Maxwell received a flagrant
foul in the first half, and Westphal picked up a technical foul in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell even threw a forearm toward Hornacek after the final
buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking over where (Dennis) Rodman left off, maybe,'' Utah
coach Jerry Sloan said of Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   As imitations go, the Sonics would settle for just playing with
the results they had the first half of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we've got to find ways to win here,'' Grant said. ``But
I believe if we keep playing hard like this, we're going to get
those wins.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
