<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PAKISTAN (Islamabad, Pakistan) _ Facing the most
challenging task of his trip to South Asia, President Clinton
arrived here Saturday to warn the military leader of Pakistan that
he must defuse tensions with India over the disputed territory of
Kashmir. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SCENE (Islamabad, Pakistan) _ At a men's store here in
Pakistan's capital, the owner keeps a small TV on a shelf. Saturday
the featured show was Bill Clinton, who had come to Islamabad for a
quick five-hour stop after five days in India. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   POPE (Nazareth, Israel) _ Cheered by a mixed local crowd of
Muslims and Christians, Pope John Paul II appeared for one
sun-dappled moment to have erased the religious rifts in this
ancient city as he came to celebrate Mass here Saturday. By William
A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-NOTEBOOK (Jerusalem) _ 16 minutes for Barak; Trying to find
the words; Some wistful words; Angry words and curses; A chorus of
critics. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VOICES (Moscow) _ What does Russia want in its president?
Does it want a strongman or a man of the people? Does it want to be
led back to imperial glory, or simply, as Russians will say without
a hint of irony, to join the club of civilized nations? Do they
want a democrat, or has 10 years of democracy induced nostalgia for
Soviet-style transfers of power? By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-WOMEN (Osaka, Japan) _ In one of her first public acts as
Japan's first woman governor, Fusae Ota was to enter the ring at
the Spring Grand Sumo Tournament this weekend and bestow prizes.
But there has never been a woman governor before. So, just a month
after taking office, Ota found herself battling not just the sumo
wrestlers' ban on women in their hallowed ring, but the centuries
of tradition that have accorded her sex a distinctly second-class
place in Japanese politics. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   With map
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-SOONG (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Ask people here who is the most
intriguing political figure to emerge from Taiwan's momentous
presidential election last weekend, and few name Chen Shui-bian,
the earnest opposition leader who ousted the Nationalist Party
after half a century of rule. Hands down, that distinction goes to
James Soong, a former Nationalist official whose independent
candidacy for the presidency drew 37 percent of the vote, just 2
points behind Chen. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MADRID-AIRPORT (Madrid, Spain) _ Sixteen Madrid suburbs filed
suit on Feb. 16 against a planned expansion of Madrid's Barajas
Airport, built in 1931, arguing that it presented health and safety
dangers and would inhibit urban planning. But Spain's prime
minister, Jose Maria Aznar, has so far stood resolutely against
building a new airport, instead favoring extension of the existing
airport, which is just seven and a half miles northeast of the city
center. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-IRAN (Baghdad, Iraq) _ Even in a city that has weathered
countless barrages of missiles and bombs in recent years, the
mortar attack in a residential neighborhood of Baghdad this week
that killed four people and wounded 38 was unusual. The strike on
Tuesday, carried out by Iran, appeared to be in retaliation for
recent mortar attacks in Tehran that were attributed to an Iranian
opposition group, the Mujahedeen Khalq, many of whose guerrilla
camps are just a few hours from Baghdad, along the border with
Iran. By Hadani Ditmars.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-STRIFE (Aba, Nigeria) _ Nigeria's recent politically
driven religious conflicts have claimed hundreds, perhaps
thousands, of lives and destroyed countless churches, mosques and
houses. President Olusegun Obasanjo has described these clashes as
attempts to undermine the nation's 10-month-old democracy, and many
Nigerians from different parts of the country agree that several
states' attempts to introduce sharia, the Islamic penal and social
code, have more to do with politics than religion. But the
conflicts are rooted in all-too-real hatreds and divisions. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-MEETING (Vienna, Austria) _ The OPEC oil ministers will
meet Monday. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TRIMBLE (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ David Trimble
Saturday held off a surprisingly strong challenge to his leadership
of the Ulster Unionist Party but emerged with his authority and his
room for maneuver in conducting peace negotiations diminished. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-RECRUIT (Kansas, Mo.) _ As the labor pool shrinks,
employers are increasingly recruiting from among the 36 million
people in the United States between the ages of 16 and 64 who had
not sought a job, or even thought about taking one. Among those
American corporations are trying to attract are students, retirees,
housewives and the urban poor. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-LAPTOPS (Winston-Salem, N.C.) _ More than 100 colleges
and universities across the country where a computer is now
required to matriculate. Not only has this created new forms of
in-class distraction and revolutionized campus communication, but
it has begun to transform teaching itself. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBE-MISCARRIAGES (Shoalwater Bay Indian Reservation, Wash.) _
The tiny tribe that lives here on a wind-battered, rain-swept spit
of land hard by the Pacific Ocean knows something about fighting
for survival. But the most difficult battle is for the women who
live here, who are up against an unseen foe, a killer that seems to
come and go over the years, though no one can even prove it exists.
For some reason, it is frighteningly difficult to give birth to a
living child here. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-HUNTERS (Joelton, Tenn.) _ The purpose of The
Christian Sportsmen's Fellowship, an evangelistic organization
based in Atlanta, is to reach out to Christian hunters. Richard
Jordan, the president of the fellowship, said the organization was
trying to reach men who go hunting and fishing on Sunday morning
instead of going to church. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   USAIRWAYS-ACCORD (Dateline TK) _ US Airways and its flight
attendants' union reached agreement on a tentative contract
Saturday, averting a threatened shutdown, officials said. (Summary
from wires.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTERS (Washington) _ Behind much of the political debate
in recent weeks, on issues from gun control to education, is an
intensifying struggle for the hearts of women, particularly
suburban mothers. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ROGICH (Las Vegas) _ The chatter among Gov. George W.
Bush's advisers is that the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee might turn to Sig Rogich, an advertising and public
relations executive with a reputation for buffing the images of
big-name Republicans, for a political reconditioning job. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Republicans facing an abortion
battle; At the DNC, upheaval as usual; Poll suggests Bush has the
right issues; Gas prices the talk of state campaigns; What's in a
name? Secret Service knows. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   D-DAY-MUSEUM (Washington) _ On June 6, the anniversary of the
Normandy invasion, the National D-Day Museum will open, telling the
story of the war with special attention to the major amphibious
assaults undertaken by Americans in the war, including Pacific
engagements like Iwo Jima, Guadalcanal and Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Alpha male's e-mail. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _  &UR; Deficit attention disorder &LR; .  &UR; By
Paul Krugman &LR; .
</P>
