<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7710 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-REVIEW-2     03-25 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE BATTLES ARE OVER, REAL TESTS BEGIN FOR PUTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ During Russia's abbreviated presidential campaign,
Acting President Vladimir Putin was on television practicing judo
throws and skiing down a mountain slope. Last week he flew top-gun
style in an Su-27 jet fighter to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But now the ``acting'' is nearly over, and the hard work of
governing Russia will, everyone presumes, soon begin for him. In
the three months since Putin was catapulted into power by Boris
Yeltsin's resignation, his most serious campaigning has been in the
prosecution of a brutal military operation in Chechnya, intended to
prove to Russians that he is the firm hand that can rebuild a
strong Russian state.
</P>
<P>
   But far more complex tests await him, assuming he wins election
either in the first or second round of the balloting that starts
Sunday. In either case, the real test will be his appointments,
policies and economic reforms. ``Everybody understands that we are
on the brink of disintegration if we fail this time with reforms,''
said Sergei Karaganov, a Russian political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding the economy to make Russia a strong state and laying
the groundwork for full-fledged democracy could still take decades,
but the signature of Putin's rule _ as another tough authoritarian
or as an enlightened democrat _ is likely to emerge in the opening
months of his presidency. Until now it has been impossible to
determine just what Putin means when he talks about a strong state.
So here are nine important tests, distilled from the views of a
number of experts, that may help with that definition.
</P>
<P>
   1. CORRUPTION _ Putin has said he seeks a ``dictatorship of
law.'' If he is to attain it, he will have to attack the corruption
that pervades the Russian economy from top to bottom. Millions of
Russians are waiting to see whether Putin makes sure that police
and prosecutors get the support to go after corrupt politicians,
governors and oligarchs as well as the Mafia-like gangs entrenched
in so many cities. Putin said he is prepared to recruit former
associates from the KGB to help root out corruption. One sign of
whether he is serious could be if a top oligarch like Boris
Berezovsky faced a thorough investigative scrubbing by an
independent prosecutor or anti-corruption commission.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE ECONOMY _ Russia's economy will not get back on its feet
without money. Today, Russians refuse to put their money in the
bank and banks refuse to lend to most businesses, fearing loans
will not be repaid. Pouring more international aid into a
dysfunctional market system is not the answer, experts say. So
Putin must instill trust in Russia's financial sector. To do that,
he must construct a national banking system that works, and the
business community is looking to him to act, as Franklin D.
Roosevelt did 67 years ago, to close and merge banks and to
inaugurate a new banking system under federal regulation and with
guarantees for depositors.
</P>
<P>
   3. ACCOUNTABILITY _ The cornerstone of any democracy is
accountability. In Russia, the institutions of accountability _ the
courts, the legislature and a free press _ are either corrupt,
desperately weak or overwhelmed by the power of the presidency. The
question now is whether Putin will try to invigorate them or weaken
them further. Newspapers and television networks are largely in the
hands of oligarchs, autocratic governors and other local bosses.
Putin could clearly break this ownership chain, but many
journalists fear that he may make matters worse by asserting more
central control and political influence over them.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the absence of rational legal codes and a
well-developed legal profession, the work of judges and courts is
politicized or just for sale. So business executives and investors
are looking to Putin to initiate legal and judicial reform. He
could start by advocating a truly independent judiciary _ to show a
commitment to the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   4. CRONYISM _ Cracking down on corruption will not be possible
without cleaning house with the many Yeltsin-era cronies associated
with graft, foreign bank accounts, money laundering and kickbacks.
In other words, Putin will be judged by the company he keeps as
president.
</P>
<P>
   5. TAX COLLECTION _ Billions of dollars in capital flee Russia
every year, mostly to avoid taxes, since Russian tax laws are often
more confiscatory than progressive. And Russians who make money
horde it in dollars at home and report as little of their income as
they can. So there is an enormous potential for taxation and for
investment in rebuilding the country. But Russians will not
repatriate their fortunes until a rational tax code that is fair,
just and predictable is implemented. One test: major tax
legislation could be introduced early.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
