   Similarly, in the absence of rational legal codes and a
well-developed legal profession, the work of judges and courts is
politicized or just for sale. So business executives and investors
are looking to Putin to initiate legal and judicial reform. He
could start by advocating a truly independent judiciary _ to show a
commitment to the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   4. CRONYISM _ Cracking down on corruption will not be possible
without cleaning house with the many Yeltsin-era cronies associated
with graft, foreign bank accounts, money laundering and kickbacks.
In other words, Putin will be judged by the company he keeps as
president.
</P>
<P>
   5. TAX COLLECTION _ Billions of dollars in capital flee Russia
every year, mostly to avoid taxes, since Russian tax laws are often
more confiscatory than progressive. And Russians who make money
horde it in dollars at home and report as little of their income as
they can. So there is an enormous potential for taxation and for
investment in rebuilding the country. But Russians will not
repatriate their fortunes until a rational tax code that is fair,
just and predictable is implemented. One test: major tax
legislation could be introduced early.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   6. PUBLIC HEALTH _ Russia is a sick country, its social safety
net in tatters. A million more Russians are dying every year than
are being born. Rates of illness, reflecting poor nutrition and
reduced immunity to disease, are rising alarmingly. Prostitution,
alcoholism, drug addiction, HIV infection and tuberculosis prey on
hopelessness.Doctors and nurses are abandoning their profession to
earn more money as taxi drivers and store clerks. With an
impoverished national treasury, finding some way to rescue of
Russia's health establishment may be among the hardest tests for
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   7. CHECHNYA _ Probably the most familiar test before Putin is in
Chechnya. How Putin makes peace there will inform the world about
Russia's commitment to human rights and autonomy for Russia's
ethnic populations. Will he be a compassionate healer or a
punishing victor? He could give a signal by airing the results of
investigations into human rights abuses by the army and by Chechen
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   8. MILITARY STRENGTH _ The military that delivered ``victory''
in Chechnya will make demands on the new president to modernize the
Russian army _ if not to its former strength in the Soviet era, at
least into a competent and well-equipped fighting force. Putin is
already talking about pumping money into Russia's vast
military-industrial complex, but he will have to decide where the
limits are or he will fall into the same trap as his Soviet
predecessors, endangering Russia's economy. One test will be how
much he is willing to invest in new hardware _ missiles, tanks and
submarines.
</P>
<P>
   9. CENTRAL CONTROL _ Russia's regional powers have been pulling
away from Moscow's control for a decade. Governors and regional
economic czars, who control huge industries and resources, have
established trade and political relations with neighboring
countries and each other in survival strategies that put regional
interests first and national interests second. To keep Russia from
pulling apart, Putin will have to assert national authority in the
regions without appearing as a dictator, as he did recently when he
flirted with the idea of having governors appointed from Moscow. He
will have no choice but to work with the parliament to clearly
define local and national interests and the boundaries between
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
