</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS' OFF-FIELD VIOLENCE AN ISSUE FOR NFL AND UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the topic of off-field violence was raised during the
recent National Football League union meetings, it sparked a heated
debate that lasted hours. Eventually one player was able to shout
above the chaos, making a simple statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``One violent act _ you're gone,'' he said, ``that should be the
NFL's new motto.''
</P>
<P>
   The passionate arguments led to an unusual proposal. Currently,
if a player is convicted of a violent crime, he is subject to fines
and suspensions by the league. But there were a number of players
who wanted to go beyond that and proposed that the union add
additional fines and suspensions on top of any imposed by the
league. Thus, players convicted of committing violent crimes would
be punished twice, once by the NFL, a second time by the union.
After much debate, the resolution was voted down.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate shows how the NFL is considering how to deal with
off-field violence, an issue that came to the forefront after Ray
Lewis of the Baltimore Ravens and Rae Carruth of the Carolina
Panthers were both charged with murder within a four-month span.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone agrees we have to do something,'' Gene Upshaw, the
executive director of the players association, said. ``What we
can't seem to agree on is what.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue will be introducing several
initiatives, and the topic is expected to be discussed at the
owners' meetings that begin Sunday in Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue's ideas _ which range from sterner punishment to
bringing in military leaders as advisers _ are sure to be debated,
even criticized, by the owners and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do not know if there is anything the league office can
truly do to help with this problem,'' the Ravens' owner, Art
Modell, said.
</P>
<P>
   The point man for Tagliabue, Harold Henderson, the NFL's
executive vice president, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the policies we have in place now are excellent,''
Henderson said, ``but we can always improve upon and better what we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent series of high-profile crimes has led to nationwide
criticism of the league and made it the butt of late-night comics'
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   And the problem has continued in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the police arrested Solomon Page, the Dallas
Cowboys' guard, on a charge of disorderly conduct and resisting
arrest after they said he was involved in a fight outside a bar in
Morgantown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Mario Bates, the Arizona Cardinals' running
back, was arrested on charges of slapping his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 8, the Miami Dolphins kicked running back Cecil Collins
off the team after a woman accused him of breaking into her
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 3, Panthers running back Fred Lane was arrested in
Tennessee on drugs and weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   In late November, Indianapolis Colts' defensive back Steve
Muhammad was charged with beating his pregnant wife, who died days
later of labor complications.
</P>
<P>
   Before last season began, three players were involved in a bar
fight.
</P>
<P>
   The most highly publicized incidents were the two murder cases.
</P>
<P>
   Last Dec. 14, Carruth was charged with murder after his pregnant
girlfriend, Cherica Adams, died of wounds from a Nov. 16 shooting
that Carruth is accused of masterminding and two friends with
criminal records are accused of carrying it out.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 31, Lewis and two friends _ both with criminal records _
were indicted for murder after two men were stabbed to death
outside an Atlanta nightclub hours after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue first took on the issue when his violent-crime policy
was initiated in 1997. While the policy was hailed as proactive,
punishment often resulted only in counseling or fines. Recently,
Tagliabue has gotten tougher, suspending three players for the
first time in the policy's three-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Denard Walker was suspended for two games next
season after pleading guilty to assault on the mother of his son.
Two other players, offensive linemen Matt O'Dwyer of the Cincinnati
Bengals and Jumbo Elliott of the Jets, were suspended for two games
for their roles in a fight in a Long Island bar. Elliott has filed
an appeal. Tagliabue fined the Jets lineman Jason Fabini $14,000
for his role.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Tagliabue seems to be taking a harder stance, executives
close to him maintain he wants to do more. Tagliabue has sought
suggestions from high-profile players such as Michael Strahan of
the Giants, Cris Carter and Robert Smith of the Minnesota Vikings,
Tony Gonzalez of the Kansas City Chiefs and Robert Porcher of the
Detroit Lions. The commissioner has also spoken extensively with
Upshaw and established an in-house panel to come up with a plan.
The result has been more than a dozen proposals, including:
</P>
<P>
   _Establishing a waiting period before players that were arrested
for violent crimes in college could play in the league. The
specifics of this are not known, but a player with a history of
violence might be forced to endure a probationary period of a year
or longer before being allowed to enter the draft.
</P>
<P>
   _Standardizing the interview process of college prospects at the
Indianapolis Combine. Teams use interviews as one way of finding
out about a player's personal history. Some teams are better at
mining information than others, and anything deemed significant is
rarely shared. The NFL is considering having a standard interview
and making it mandatory that teams share all information.
</P>
<P>
   _Increasing the presence of team security officials in the
locker room and informing players if they have made bad choices of
friends or hangouts.
</P>
<P>
   _Requiring all teams to hire coordinators who would be
responsible for addressing all off-field matters and keeping
players informed about places that they should steer clear of.
Currently some teams, like the Jets, have full-time people filling
these positions. Other teams do not.
</P>
<P>
   _Creating an escrow fine system in which a small percentage of
each player's paycheck would periodically be put aside until he
leaves the game. If he stayed out of trouble, the player would then
get the money back.
</P>
<P>
   _Extending and enlarging a pilot program in which professional
players speak to college players about staying away from ills like
drugs, gambling and violence. The program, the NFL believes, has
dual benefits. College players who may later play professionally
are already hearing the right message, and professional players,
playing the role of mentor, are more likely to remain out of
trouble themselves.
</P>
<P>
   _Asking military leaders to speak to head coaches. ``The
military is adept at incorporating people from disadvantaged
backgrounds into an environment,'' Henderson said. ``They may be
able to teach us a few things about how to better do that.''
</P>
<P>
   _Starting a news media campaign that emphasizes the positive
deeds players do in the community, and encourage wives and
girlfriends to participate more in the various programs designed to
help players stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   One recent union survey of the league's 1,600 players showed
that 90 percent could identify at least one at-risk teammate. That
is one reason why Tagliabue is considering the formation of team
committees. The idea is to compose a small group that would consist
of several players, security officials, and the club coordinator,
which would function as a an advisory board if an at-risk player is
identified. Then if a player starts exhibiting questionable
behavior, the board would address the player.
</P>
<P>
   This idea addresses what is being called in N.F.L. circles the
``entourage problem.'' Some players believe if Lewis had chosen his
friends more wisely, he would not be in trouble now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to surround yourself with people who want to
accomplish what you're looking to do,'' Jamal Anderson, the Atlanta
Falcons' running back, said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more important changes could be strengthening the
violent-crime policy. Currently, a player who is arrested for
committing a violent act receives mandatory counseling and a
subsequent conviction or guilty plea would result in a possible
suspension and fine.
</P>
<P>
   The league is acknowledging that some players who may be guilty
of a crime slip through the cracks _ maybe a judge looks the other
way or a player is able to use his celebrity to get out of an
arrest. Tagliabue is considering suspending a player who may not
have been legally found guilty, but the league, through its
investigation, discovers the player may have committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcing such a rule would be difficult because it could
violate a player's civil rights. But these are the kinds of drastic
moves the league is beginning to think might be necessary to curb
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said: ``Paul is going to tell the owners: `We need to
take serious steps. You need to be involved. Character is as
important as talent.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some owners may already be getting that message. The Denver
Broncos' owner, Pat Bowlen, said the recent trade of the talented
young pass rusher David Bowens to Green Bay and the release of
starting strong safety Darius Johnson were due to character issues.
Bowlen declined to specify what the issues were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have a good, solid player who is a good person than
a superstar who is a bad person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
