<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OF STICKS, SLASHES AND THE CULTURE OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Worrell of the Florida Panthers sure shook up the National
Hockey League last week, when he failed to do what one normally
does when zonked on the head with a hockey stick. As opposed to
crumpling to the ice, semi-conscious, oozing blood, he remained
upright, alert and enraged.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell responded to being attacked by the Devils' Scott
Niedermayer with the infamous throat slash gesture _ not once,
twice, but three times. This infuriated the Devils and seemed to
set off some kind of demographics alarm, as if the NHL had for a
few mortal moments wandered into a neighborhood it did not wish to
be in. It did not punish Worrell, but was quick to make clear that
such imagery had no place and would not be tolerated in a clean,
wholesome sport like hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him get sticked across the head and see how he reacts,''
Worrell said of Niedermayer.
</P>
<P>
   Not to condone the slash as a matter of practice and principle,
but Worrell had a point. Had he really been out of control, he
might have just started whacking back.
</P>
<P>
   When Worrell, a French Canadian who is black (as was Marty
McSorley's Feb. 21st victim, Donald Brashear), responded after the
ensuing brawl by borrowing from the so-called culture of disrespect
that is more commonly ascribed to the African-American athlete, it
was as if a window opened and we had a clear look into the
dichotomy that exists in the sporting court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guy gets cracked across the helmet with a stick, three New
Jersey guys jump on him and he's the guy the officials grab,'' said
Bryan Murray, the Panthers' general manager. ``The slash on the
throat is not acceptable but everyone's focused on Worrell's
gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the truth if not the whole truth. Niedermayer was
promptly and correctly suspended by the NHL for 10 games. Yet once
again, a barbaric and criminal assault (according to the
authorities in Vancouver, in the McSorley case) was treated by
hockey advocates and the general public as an isolated act of
extremist behavior, an unfortunate crossing of the line, outside
the bounds of acceptable violence.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, when Latrell Sprewell committed his indefensible
attack on P.J. Carlesimo, he became the great American pariah, the
human metaphor for an entire sport gone sour. His past was
dissected. His scowling visage was plastered everywhere but the
post office. He was the uncontrollable product of Generation X, of
black rage, a threat to our very athletic culture.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey's ongoing violence, though legislatively reduced in the
past few years, is still tolerated as a culture all its own and
therefore exempt from the standards loosely applied elsewhere.
Players employed strictly as brawlers, whose very existence in
sports dominated by blacks would be the cause of national
convulsion, have been more than tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, I asked a major executive who has had access to
both sports why hockey players have by and large been left alone in
their own violent vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting, dropping the gloves, has always been part of that
game,'' he said. ``Maybe we've just become conditioned to it.''
</P>
<P>
   And more. In the way the country celebrates its professional
wrestlers and make-believe mobsters, hockey goons have been
immortalized in film (``Slap Shot''), and have even been commended
by no less a mainstream authority than Sports Illustrated two years
ago for being ``a surprisingly honest and amiable bunch'' and for
abiding by the ``unwritten code of the NHL tough guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, that they are part of a white, violent culture
of respect.
</P>
<P>
   How the hate mail flowed when I wrote that exact phrase two
years ago, after taking my sons to Madison Square Garden for a
Rangers-Devils game. The older one, after weeks of paying close
attention to the Sprewell condemnations, had the good sense to ask
why in the world all the adults in the business suits were standing
and cheering as soon as the gloves were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those same people who can't wait to see a good hockey
fight would tell you they can't watch professional basketball
because of all the posturing and trash talking. Hockey, you hear,
is a fast, physical game, as if one played above the rim by huge,
superbly conditioned athletes is not.
</P>
<P>
   So if I explained that the NHL has preferred to keep a
manageable level of violence as it expanded to the American
sunbelt, it still begged the question of why people who condemn
every violent act or image in one sport will embrace it in another.
Why in hockey, the throat slash would be considered a graver
marketing threat than the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   It is pretty obvious why.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
