<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7734 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-LAWSUITS-TOBACCO-REVI     03-25 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWSUITS-TOBACCO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING LAWSUITS TO DO WHAT CONGRESS WON'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact arl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than three decades, gun-control advocates have pressed
lawmakers for stiffer measures, but the gun lobby ensured that they
got nowhere in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Then about two years ago, two dozen cities and counties
nationwide began suing gun producers to recover the costs of
treating gun shot victims.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Faced with the lawsuits and the costs of litigating
them, Smith &AMP; Wesson, the nation's largest firearms maker, recently
agreed to make changes in the way it makes and markets handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, cigarette makers had long frustrated public health
activists who sought national legislation aimed at restricting how
tobacco is sold, especially to children. Congress proved unwilling
to buck the tremendous lobbying power of the industry, and nothing
happened. But four years after state attorneys general nationwide
and wealthy plaintiffs' lawyers joined forces to sue the tobacco
companies, the companies reversed field and sued for peace.
</P>
<P>
   These two cases are emblematic of a shift taking place in how
Americans attempt to govern their own society. Over the last few
years, the legal system has begun to overtake the legislative
process as the vehicle to resolve contentious debates, particularly
over unpopular products, when Congress is unwilling to act. Both
the tobacco and firearms litigation, for example, were highly
organized assaults on specific industries.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, lawsuits had been brought by individuals against
both industries with little financial success or effect on company
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were always cases out there, and they were going
nowhere,'' said Susan Koniak, a law professor at Boston University.
``But the law is moving the way it is because of the huge
consolidation of cases that are taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of concentrated legal firepower to set social policy has
stirred sharp debate. Some legal experts have decried such lawsuits
as abusive. Others view them as a problematic but necessary
counterbalance to the powerful control that companies and interest
groups can exert over Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Schuck, a law professor at Yale University, said that in
assessing whether to go to court or settle, ``a lot of time a
company has to make a judgment regardless of whether it thinks it
is right on the law.'' But in the case of Smith &AMP; Wesson, which
Schuck doubts would have lost a court case, legal right or wrong
was not the relevant calculation. The problem for the company was
simply that it didn't have the money to roll the dice. And that was
a reality its lobbyists were powerless to change.
</P>
<P>
   Some see this as fundamentally unfair. Walter Olson, a senior
fellow at the Manhattan Institute, a conservative research group,
described the type of lawsuits brought against cigarette companies
and gun makers as ``end runs'' around the legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not what litigation is supposed to be,'' said Olson.
``It gathers too much power in the legal system to litigate
everything we used to vote over.''
</P>
<P>
   But others disagree, calling the new legal activism an important
counterweight to the power and resources of corporations. ``We have
a political system that is shaped in a significant fashion by
powerful interest groups that spend their resources,'' said Deborah
Hensler, a law professor at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   She added that private litigation, because of the resources
wielded by wealthy plaintiffs' lawyers, now represents another
arena where political power resides.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the courts have long been used to shape social
policy. In the 1960s and 1970s, so-called impact litigation was
brought by civil rights groups and other activists to bring about
changes in public policies that legislatures were unwilling to
effect, like reforms in prison conditions.
</P>
<P>
   And major litigation against products like asbestos, breast
implants and defective birth-control devices like the Dalkon Shield
also traces back decades. In many of those cases, too,
manufacturers withdrew products from the marketplace even though
regulators had not ordered such actions.
</P>
<P>
   But this latest wave of litigation is fundamentally different,
legal experts said. First, its purpose was to change how cigarettes
and guns are sold, and thus consumed, rather than to eliminate
their use. Legal action, initiated largely by private individuals,
was being used as a tool of social engineering. But these suits
also mark a growing alliance between state and city officials on
one hand and private plaintiffs on the other.
</P>
<P>
   That merger confers on the lawyers political credibility and
quasi-public authority, while endowing the states and cities
frustrated by logjams at the federal level with the entrepreneurial
energies of the legal marketplace. The result is a two-track system
where issues stuck in Congress can now jump off that track into the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Hensler, the Stanford University professor, said she believed
that the development was a mixed blessing. While it does provide
for an increased form of legal activism, the private lawyers who
may end up steering such actions are not answerable to the public
they supposedly represent.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has to ask the question, `Are these the right people to be
leading the charge on the private side,''' she said. ``In the end,
I do get to vote on my congressman, but I don't have any direct
power on the deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Few expect the recent wave of large-scale litigation to end.
Recently, for instance, some of the lawyers involved in state cases
against the tobacco industry filed lawsuits against health
maintenance organizations for failing to disclose that they gave
financial incentives to doctors who restricted medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jack Weinstein of the U.S. District Court in Brooklyn has
overseen much of the recent wave of product litigation, including
major cases involving firearms and tobacco. Known as a judicial
activist, Weinstein said that he believed the courts would always
probably play a pivotal role in resolving social problems. ``We are
going to have government that takes responsibility or have the
private bar back them up where they are not doing a good job,''
Weinstein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
