   Eight agreed, and off they went, not only to the opera but to
the pre-opera workshop. The reviews, predictably, were mixed. ``Two
of them absolutely loved it,'' Peters said. ``Four thought it was
just OK, and two said they'd rather pick up trash. They fell asleep
and said it was really tough to sit through it.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 60 students have taken the opera option, Peters
said. About 30 have turned it down. Most of the offenders are men
charged with alcohol-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not apologizing at all,'' Peters said. ``I feel a college
has a responsibility for raising standards.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE FRITSCH
</P>
<P>
   Pope Speaks of Holocaust During Visit to Israel
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish to remember,'' Pope John Paul II said at Jerusalem's
Holocaust memorial, ``to ensure that never again will evil
prevail'' as it did for the Nazis' victims.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is on his first visit to Israel, which the Vatican did
not even officially recognize until 1994, and his plea of ``never
again'' _ coming on top of his recent broad apology for past church
sins _ struck a distinct chord.
</P>
<P>
   While some Holocaust survivors faulted the pope for not going
even further in condemning the church's wartime silence, his visit,
one survivor said, ``marks a turning point for Jews and
Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on Cuban Boy
</P>
<P>
   The international custody battle over 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez
seems to be nearing a conclusion. After a federal judge in Miami
concluded that only Attorney General Janet Reno can grant the boy
asylum, Reno said Elian should be reunited with his father in Cuba
in a prompt, orderly fashion. Lawyers for both sides wrangled over
just how, and if, that would be accomplished. The government wants
lawyers for Elian's relatives in Miami to agree to a speedy
timetable for any appeal of the ruling, but the lawyers have
balked.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK BRAGG
</P>
<P>
   '60s Militant Arrested
</P>
<P>
   H. Rap Brown spent the last 25 years effacing his reputation as
one of the most militant black radicals of the 1960s. He changed
his name to Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, became the imam of his mosque
in Atlanta and helped clean up his impoverished neighborhood. But
his peaceful obscurity was shattered when he was accused of the
shooting of two Atlanta sheriff's deputies, one of whom died.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was captured after a shootout in Lowndes County, Ala.,
and he claimed to be the victim of a ``governmental conspiracy.''
His trial is likely to be a death penalty case.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID FIRESTONE
</P>
<P>
   Decoding the Fruit Fly
</P>
<P>
   At their annual meeting, biologists who study the Drosophila
fruit fly got a gift: a CD-ROM, courtesy of Celera Corp.,
containing the DNA code for the fly's 13,601 genes. The decoding of
the fly's genome validates a bold strategy that Celera is confident
will work on the human genome. The understanding of the fly's
genome will be of major help in interpreting the human genome.
Wings aside, the organisms have a surprising amount of genetic
equipment in common.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   Court Rules on Student Fees
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment protects the right to speak _ and sometimes
the right not to speak. No one can be forced to salute the flag,
for example. Conservative college students have argued that they
should not have to support causes they disagree with through
mandatory student activity fees.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting that argument, the Supreme Court said the overall
quantity of speech at universities mattered more. Unbounded debate
is central to a university's mission, the court said, and mandatory
fees are constitutional as long as the money collected is
distributed without regard to viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Record Sex-Bias Award
</P>
<P>
   The Voice of America, the government-run radio service that
broadcasts news about the United States abroad, and its parent
agency agreed to pay a record $508 million to 1,100 women to settle
a sex discrimination case. If the settlement is approved by the
judge overseeing the case, each woman will get at least $450,000.
The suit, which was filed 23 years ago, charges that the women were
denied jobs and promotions with the service.
</P>
<P>
   _ By IRVIN MOLOTSKY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Grisly Discoveries in Uganda
</P>
<P>
   The corpses of more than 150 people were found by the Ugandan
police buried under a building used by a doomsday cult involved in
a fire on March 17 in which 500 of its members died.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were found about 40 miles from the church at Kanungu
where the 500 members of the cult perished when their church was
set ablaze, the police said. The police said the discovery shed new
light on the Kanungu blaze, which they said they were treating as a
mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   Conviction in Subway Murder
</P>
<P>
   A New York jury convicted Andrew Goldstein, a schizophrenic man
who threw a woman to her death in front of a subway train last
year, of intentional murder and rejected his insanity defense. The
case has prompted scrutiny of how the mentally ill are cared for in
New York. A law named for the victim, Kendra Webdale, allows courts
to compel the mentally ill to submit to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JULIAN E. BARNES
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes Drug Withdrawn
</P>
<P>
   Two widely used drugs, blamed for deaths among patients, are
being taken off the market. The diabetes drug Rezulin, linked to 63
deaths from liver failure since 1997, was withdrawn by Parke-Davis.
The 500,000 Americans taking the drug were urged not to stop until
they get other treatment. Janssen Pharmaceutica, the maker of the
heartburn drug Propulsid, which has caused 80 deaths from heart
problems, said the drug would also be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Gay Bias in Military
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon report found that anti-homosexual harassment in the
U.S. military remains widespread, especially in the form of
offensive remarks and gestures. The survey, ordered after a gay
soldier was beaten to death last July at Fort Campbell, Ky., also
found that an overwhelming majority of service members believe
their superiors and colleagues tolerate harassment ``to some
extent.'' The survey suggested that despite repeated efforts to
prohibit such behavior, negative attitudes toward gays remain a
pervasive part of military culture.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
<P>
   Good News for the Elderly
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted unanimously to repeal a Depression-era
provision that forced Social Security recipients to give up all or
part of their retirement benefit if they earned more than $17,000 a
year. The House passed the same measure this month, and President
Clinton said he would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was intended to discourage older people from
remaining in the work force. But with employers complaining about a
shortage of workers, the political case for abolishing the earnings
limit became overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Move on Internet Drug Sales
</P>
<P>
   In its first action against foreign Internet sites selling
prescription drugs to American consumers, the U.S. Customs Service
joined Thai authorities in raiding online pharmacies in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jane E. Henney, the commissioner of food and drugs, has sent
warnings to 13 Web sites in other countries, saying they could be
violating federal law by selling prescription drugs to U.S.
citizens without valid prescriptions. Such drugs may be dangerous,
she said, because there is no assurance they were properly
manufactured or stored.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
