<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-POPE-ART-925(2TAKES)-     03-25 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ART-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE VISITS ANNUNCIATION SHRINE AS RELIGION RIFTS ARE SET ASIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Israel _ Cheered by a mixed local crowd of Muslims and
Christians, Pope John Paul II appeared for one sun-dappled moment
to have erased the religious rifts in this ancient city as he came
to celebrate Mass here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As the gold-hubcapped popemobile passed through the streets
where Jesus is believed to have spent his childhood, the Israeli
Arabs who are today's Nazarenes waved yellow Vatican flags, hoisted
tots in commemorative papal baseball caps, and held up placards
welcoming the pope, ``Benvenuto Papa Carissimo.'' The pope, tightly
gripping the white handrail in his bulletproof encasement, blessed
the crowd to roars of approval.
</P>
<P>
   The pope proceeded on this Catholic holy day of the Annunciation
to the huge modernist Basilica of the Annunciation, built to
commemorate the moment here 2,000 years ago when Catholics believe
that the Archangel Gabriel told the Virgin Mary that she was to be
the mother of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The fortress-like structure, the largest Roman Catholic church
in the Middle East, is a 1950s creation of Italian architects and
Israeli civil engineers. It sits atop the sequential ruins of a
fourth-century Byzantine oratory, a grander 12th-century Crusader
church and an 18th-century Franciscan chapel. Deep below its
ancient foundations is a cave believed in Christian tradition to
have been Mary's family home.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims have received approval from the Israeli government to
build a mosque in the plaza adjacent to the basilica, causing
tension in the town, which has seen its Christian population shrink
drastically.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Muslims joined enthusiastically in the festivities
Saturday, though the crowd outside was dominated by Nazareth's
Christian minority. ``This is an expression of our joy at the visit
of his holiness the pope,'' said Saman Arslen, the director of a
40-member Islamic Scouts drum corps, as it pounded out a deafening
welcome to the pope.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit was seen here primarily as a gesture toward
Israel's dwindling number of Christians, who once dominated
Nazareth and the Galilee region. Local Christians worry that they
have become a minority within a minority, now barely 10 percent of
an otherwise Islamic Arab population in a state that is five-sixths
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christians greeting the pope glared at the small group of
Muslims who had camped on a plaza where they plan to erect a mosque
next to the tomb of a nephew of Saladin, the warrior hero who
expelled the Crusaders in 1187. The Vatican strongly objected to
the project as an Islamic attempt to overshadow a traditional
Catholic pilgrimage site, and to remind the Muslim faithful of the
atrocities committed against their ancestors by the Crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Christians were not placated by the Islamists' handwritten
signs in English, Italian, Hebrew and Arabic welcoming the pope and
calling their planned mosque ``a symbol of harmony and
neighborliness.'' But the Muslims adhered to an agreement with the
police to keep a low profile, and they were silent and virtually
invisible as the papal motorcade cruised passed.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli security was taking no chances. All roads to the town
center were blocked from dawn. Sharpshooters patrolled rooftops.
The blue-uniformed riot squads and olive-green army platoons along
the pope's route often outnumbered the families crowding the
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   But inside this heavily policed bubble, the mood was genuinely
celebratory and free of visible religious strains. Even the lapel
stickers worn for the papal visit by Israeli security forces _
``Mivtza Yedid Vatik,'' Hebrew for ``Operation Old Friend'' _
seemed to reflect the remarkably congenial atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to many stops on the pope's carefully scripted Holy
Land itinerary, the Nazareth visit was a genuinely indigenous
affair, with lots of hometown pride mixed with straightforward
religious fervor. There were no overt politics, no delicate
interfaith initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In his homily to an invited congregation of area church leaders
and lay dignitaries, the pope delivered a traditional holy day
message venerating the memory of the Virgin Mary and avoiding even
indirect allusions to religious divisions here.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this day the eyes of the whole church turn to Nazareth,''
he said. ``I have longed to come back to the town of Jesus, to feel
once again, in contact with this place, the presence of the woman
of whom St. Augustine wrote: `He chose the mother he had created;
he created the mother he had chosen.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The pope spent 10 minutes praying alone in the sacred grotto
near the basilica Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his carefully apolitical sermon _ his only public
remarks here _ many Christians here saw his visit as an intentional
reminder to both the Muslim majority locally and the Jewish
majority nationally of the symbolic importance of Nazareth to the
Christian world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel with this visit that now there is someone who is
looking after us, when we felt that we had been forgotten,'' said
Robert Dirawi, a 37-year-old Nazareth-born Roman Catholic. When
Pope Paul VI visited Nazareth in 1964, Dirawi recalled, about
two-thirds of the town was Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Today it is two-thirds Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Even Orthodox Christians, who often resent what they see as the
Vatican's attempt to claim primacy among the Christian churches,
said Saturday that they welcomed the pope's pilgrimage. ``It is a
visit to say that we are here, and that we have an identity,'' said
Rafleh Ghanadreh, a Greek Orthodox Christian from Nazareth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The senior Catholic clerics accompanying the pope were acutely
aware of the importance of the visit for the Christian minority.
``It is a source of great hope for them, and it will be a source of
strength for them to carry on their wonderful Christian
traditions,'' Cardinal Adam Joseph Maida, the archbishop of
Detroit, said as he waited to be escorted through an Israeli police
phalanx outside the basilica Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Even inside the basilica the issue was raised. Antoine Shaheen,
an Arab Christian and retired Israeli tourism official who took
communion from the pope Saturday, criticized the government for
``playing political games'' and rewarding the Muslims, who he said
had ``unilaterally occupied'' what was formerly a public square.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Christians are not against the building of a mosque in
principle, but we are against the way it is being done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nazareth has for centuries been the Christian Arab center of
what is now northern Israel. But Muslim leaders note that from the
collapse of the 12-century Crusader kingdom until the early
20th-century British mandate, Nazareth, like the rest of the Holy
Land, was under uninterrupted Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This land does not belong to the Christians,'' says Ahmed
Zoebi, a leader of the ``mosque defense committee'' here.
</P>
<P>
   If there was one concern uniting Muslims and Christians here, it
was the lack of any visible economic benefits to their town from
the pope's long-awaited visit. Mayor Ramiz Jaraisy, who is
Christian, complained that the Israeli government had spent just
$250,000 sprucing up his old city center, in contrast to the
millions spent on the Old City district of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   And few tourists have arrived in the pope's wake, complained
Marwan Maharu, a Muslim pastry-shop proprietor, displaying a cash
register ticker from Friday with just $95 in total sales. ``They
come for five minutes, see the basilica, and then go to Tiberias or
Tel Aviv to drink their coffee,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
