<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7755 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-HAIRDRESSERS-WIFEBEAT     03-25 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRDRESSERS-WIFEBEATING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE WHO COIF MIGHT ALSO PROTECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JEFF STRYKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember Clairol's catchy slogan from the 1950s, ``Hair color so
natural, only her hairdresser knows for sure''?
</P>
<P>
   In recognition that hair stylists may know more secrets about
their clients than merely cosmetic ones, new programs are being
established by community-based organizations and state agencies to
help hairdressers identify signs of domestic violence. These
programs are trying to take advantage of the bond that often exists
between hairdressers and their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Each year 3 to 4 million women are beaten in their homes,
according to the Justice Department. In 1998, the latest year for
which data are available, homicide figures gathered by the FBI
showed that 32 percent of the women slain in this country are
killed by their husbands, former husbands, boyfriends or former
boyfriends. If stylists can spot the signs early, they could refer
abused women to social service agencies and support groups.
</P>
<P>
   The New London Rotary Foundation in Connecticut awarded Susan
O'Toole of the Women's Center of Southeastern Connecticut a $1,000
grant last summer to teach hairdressers how to recognize domestic
violence and sexual assault. Participating salons post hot line
numbers, display brochures and make referrals to social service
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Boyd-Frenkel, domestic violence ombudsman for the
attorney general of Nevada, is working with the state board of
cosmetology to develop a training program for cosmetology teachers
and school administrators, who would earn continuing education
credits.
</P>
<P>
   But Nevada's program does not turn stylists into crisis workers.
Instead, according to its training brochure, it teaches them how to
ask the right questions. The brochure warns the hairdresser when
dealing with her client: ``Don't offer advice. Especially, do not
advise her to leave, without knowing how dangerous such a choice
might be for her.'' The brochure also emphasizes the importance of
confidentiality, saying, ``A slip to another client or to another
stylist can result in increased danger to the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Torn-out hair or a bruised eye may signal abuse, but more subtle
warning signs may come out in conversation. One Nevada hairdresser,
Boyd-Frenkel said, told of a client who said: ``My husband doesn't
want me to see my friend anymore. He says she is putting bad ideas
in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotional abuse, intimidation, control, jealousy,
overpossessiveness and constant monitoring,'' she said, can be as
sure signs of domestic violence as physical injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Psychotherapists are not particularly thrilled to cede any
ground to hairdressers. ``Hairdressers are being placed in a role
that they have little training for,'' said John Reid, a clinical
psychologist practicing in San Antonio. ``They may get in over
their heads in terms of the therapeutic relationship and issues
like transference and countertransference. Plus, taking on this
role could get them smack dab into the family dynamics if the
husband finds out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other skeptics note that confidentiality _ a legal duty for
physicians and therapists _ is merely professional etiquette for
hairdressers. They might be too neutral and nonjudgmental in the
interest of maintaining a business relationship.
</P>
<P>
   These misgivings are not confined to therapists. An editorial in
the Las Vegas Review-Journal in February blasted the Nevada
program, invoking the notion of the slippery slope, asking whether
bartenders will be the next group required ``to take government
courses on how to snitch out their customers'' to enforce laws on
domestic violence or child support.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one person's slippery slope is another's vista of
opportunity. The Women's Center of Southeastern Connecticut hopes
to extend its training to bartenders, as well as taxi drivers and
veterinarians.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, hairdressers have been taught to advise their
clients of the importance of mammography and breast
self-examinations. In Los Angeles, city administrators have held
luncheons with hairdressers to hear what their clients think about
city life. In Nashville, Shears United, a program of a local AIDS
organization, uses beauty parlors to discuss HIV prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Although the phenomenon of the hairdresser, bartender or
personal trainer who acts as a ``paid friend'' may be the result of
today's social isolation and the anomie that arises with far-flung
families, television and the Internet, it is hardly new. A number
of articles on the subject were published in the 1970s. In
``Hairdressers as Caregivers'' (American Journal of Community
Psychology, 1979), the psychologist Emory L. Cowen and his
colleagues wrote that the jobs of ``informal agents'' like
bartenders, barbers, beauticians and cab drivers ``bring them into
contact with interpersonally distressed people.'' Interviews with
90 hairdressers defined the atmosphere of what the authors called
the ``beauty parlor surround'' and revealed that most hairdressers
enjoyed dealing with their clients' personal problems, gratified at
the trust placed in them. One of the survey respondents even
claimed he could infer the emotional state of his client from the
condition of her hair. The psychologists were skeptical,
dismissively so, noting the hairdresser ``offered no dandruff
counts, oil density or sheen measures _ no `objective data'
whatsoever'' to bolster his claim.
</P>
<P>
   But the insight that comes from pounds of journal articles can
be gleaned from a wisp of fiction. Dorothy Allison got it right in
her novel ``The Cavedweller'' (Dutton, 1998), when she described
hairdressers as ``priestesses of appreciation and encouragement.''
It is an apt phrase for the beauticians many Americans bare their
souls to year in, year out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-HAIRDRESSERS-WIFEBEAT     03-25 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRDRESSERS-WIFEBEATING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE WHO COIF MIGHT ALSO PROTECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
