<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, March 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous jet-stream winds over the northern tier of states and
southern Canada will promote rapid weather changes over the next
few days. A broken area of showers will move quickly off the New
England coast Sunday morning. In its wake, breezy and cooler
weather will sweep into the Northeast. Clouds and a few wet snow
showers will linger from the Adirondacks to southeastern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will erupt in a sultry air mass from eastern Texas
and Oklahoma to the interior Gulf Coast states. High-level winds
from the northwest will deliver colder air at 15,000 feet above the
southern Plains later Sunday. The strong vertical temperature
difference will set the stage for potent thunderstorms and a few
tornadoes Sunday afternoon and Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   A few showers will precede a cold front in the northern
Mississippi Valley on Sunday. The front will cause deteriorating
conditions in the interior Northeast on Monday and Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Seeds of Drought
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of summer drought are often planted early in the year. The
winter had the least rainfall on record in Jackson, Miss., a
reflection of exceptional dryness in much of the Southeast.
Reliable predictions for those areas of the nation that will have
drought this year are difficult because patterns of spring rainfall
can markedly alter the drought probabilities. But in many past
years, unusually dry areas at the start of the growing season have
a greater risk of summer drought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
