<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Brothers Martinez
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hargrove will not soon forget the Pedro Performance. In a
season filled with memorable Pedro performances, the one against
the Cleveland Indians last October was the piece de resistance. It
was Pedro Martinez at his most resourceful and absolute finest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely amazing'' was how Hargrove described it, five
months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that Pedro Martinez showed me last year was not so
much that he put it on the line for his team,'' Hargrove said. ``It
was that Pedro went out and threw the ball 86, 87 miles an hour and
was just as dominant a pitcher as he was throwing 95 miles an hour.
Not a lot of power pitchers can do that, but Pedro did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' presence in the playoffs and, as it turned out,
Hargrove's job, were on the line when Martinez entered the fifth
game of the division series as a relief pitcher in the fourth
inning. Martinez would ordinarily have started that final game of
the playoff series or the previous one for Boston, but he pulled a
muscle in his back in his opening-game start and was not available.
</P>
<P>
   But with the score tied, 8-8, after three and a half innings,
Martinez became available. He pitched the final six innings,
allowing no hits or runs, walking three and striking out eight as
the Red Sox won, 12-8.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is the leader of a starting rotation that has the
potential to be very good and very deep this season. Not many teams
can boast of such a unit. But this staff comes with a caveat:
Except for Martinez, the rotation offers no guaranteed winners.
Each of Pedro's pitching pals has a question mark attached to his
arm. If the pitchers come through, the Yankees could find a huge
Red Sox roadblock between themselves and another World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our players,'' Jimy Williams, Boston's low-key manager,
said when asked about his pitchers. ``How well we're going to do I
don't know. We got some kids who like to compete. We got some good
arms, guys who know how to pitch. Can Ramon sustain what he did at
the end of last year? He's shown good arm strength here so far. He
feels good about himself. When you have those injury situations,
you take one start at a time and build on it hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, Pedro's older brother, returned to the major
leagues late last season, 14 months after rotator cuff surgery.
Gambling that he could return, the Red Sox signed him last year as
a future performer. He started four times for them in September
(two victories, one loss, a 3.05 earned run average), then twice in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   His big brother, a winner with Los Angeles, who just turned 32,
has the prospect of an open-ended victory total _ if his arm
remains strong and he remains healthy. Consider where the Red Sox
could go if the Martinez brothers were to match the 49 victories
the Dean brothers (Dizzy and Paul) gained for the St. Louis
Cardinals in 1934, or the 47 they had the next season or even the
38 the Perry brothers (Gaylord and Jim) earned for Cleveland in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fassero has not been injured, but Joe Kerrigan is trying to
nurse him back to good pitching health nevertheless. Kerrigan is
the Red Sox pitching coach who held the same job with Montreal when
Fassero was building an attractive career there.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox signed Fassero as a free agent, believing his 4-14
record and 7.38 ERA with Seattle last year were an aberration,
coming only two seasons after a 16-9, 3.61 season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was any secret to a turnaround, Williams said:
``Oh, I don't know any secrets. A change of uniform, change of
ideas. Joe Kerrigan was with him before. John Cumberland is in the
bullpen. If they can help this kid, he could be a big plus for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as they don't know which Fassero they will get, the Red Sox
can't be certain about Tim Wakefield. If his knuckleball flutters
the way he wants it to and his fielders catch the ball behind him,
he could approach the 16-8 record he had in 1995 or the 17-8 he
produced two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the No. 5 spot in the rotation. It will go to one of
two youngsters, both of whom made good impressions last season.
Brian Rose, a 24-year-old right-hander, beat the Yankees in his
first two starts six days apart. Juan Pena, a 22-year-old
right-hander, made only two starts before suffering a shoulder
ailment, but in those games he allowed only one run in 13 innings
and won them both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rose and Pena are trying to establish themselves as major
leaguers,'' General Manager Dan Duquette said. ``Rose has a little
more experience. But they both look like they're capable of
helping.''
</P>
<P>
   The one who doesn't make the rotation for the start of the
season will be a short ride away in Pawtucket, R.I. A far more
veteran pitcher will be waiting in the on-deck circle, too. Bret
Saberhagen, who has vast experience at coming back from injuries,
is working his way back from a torn rotator cuff. He has been
throwing on the side and hopes to be ready around June 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courage that kid showed with a torn muscle in his shoulder
trying to play the game is about as good as it gets,'' Williams
said. ``Shows a lot of heart. A lot of kids who had this injury, it
would be monumental. But because of what he's already gone through
it ain't quite so big. The guy knows how to pitch. He knows what
he's doing in a game, what he means to our team as a pitcher. He
helps the rest of our staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Genius of Maddux
</P>
<P>
   Before there was Pedro Martinez, Atlanta's Greg Maddux dazzled
everyone who faced him or watched him pitch. He still does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what he does better than anyone I've seen since
Catfish Hunter,'' said Phil Garner, the Detroit Tigers' manager,
who saw Maddux pitching for the Braves when he was managing the
Milwaukee Brewers. ``He watches everything. He can see what hitters
are doing. He knows when to throw it in and he knows when to throw
it away. That's his genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``His skill is that he can do that when he wants to, but his
genius is that when he throws the ball he can see what the hitter
is doing. He knows absolutely where to go with it. He's a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Astros Need Their Rest
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell has played every one of the Houston Astros' 162
games in three of the past four seasons. Craig Biggio has missed a
total of four games in the past four seasons. Larry Dierker, their
manager, said he would like them to take a few more days off this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about it,'' Biggio said. ``Last year we didn't
have that luxury to take off days, because we had everybody hurt. I
told him I'd take some more off days this year. It depends on when
you get them. You don't want an off day in the middle of a week,
like a Wednesday night game. You want one like on a travel day and
a day game. The older you get, you don't bounce back as quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell said the amount of rest he gets will be up to Dierker.
``That was his intention last year, but we lost so many guys to
injuries I didn't have time to take off,'' the first baseman said.
``I was tired in August a little bit. I think everybody's tired in
August.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Biggio said he would not want to take 20 days off
in any season. ``That's not going to happen unless I have an
injury,'' he said. ``I'll take a couple more days off this year.
I'm not down on that. In the long run you will feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell was one of five players who played 162 games last
season. The others were John Olerud with the Mets, Sammy Sosa with
the Chicago Cubs, Andruw Jones with Atlanta and B.J. Surhoff with
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   A Million-Dollar Memory
</P>
<P>
   His career highs in home runs (38) and runs batted in (112)
certainly pleased Jay Bell, but the Arizona Diamondbacks' second
baseman was most impressed with the career-high 132 runs he scored
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the one place that I really put emphasis on my game
is runs scored,'' Bell said. ``From the two hole, that is one thing
I have to do. Driving in runs is a bonus; scoring runs is
mandatory. With everything that happened last year, the home runs,
the RBI's, those things are great. But if those go down a little
bit, no big deal. With runs scored I want to maintain what I did
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 33, in his 12th year in the major leagues, Bell had the
season of his life. He had never hit more than 21 home runs, driven
in more than 92 runs (and that total was his only one exceeding 71)
and scored more than 102. But he was an offensive force in the
Diamondbacks' 100-victory, division-championship season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take a long look at what happened last year,'' Bell
said. ``What was fun for me was the one at-bat where I won the lady
a million dollars. That's probably the thing I looked at more often
than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell referred to the grand slam he hit July 11 against Jimmy
Haynes of Oakland in an inning that was used for a promotion. If an
Arizona batter hit a grand slam, a designated fan would win $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ironic how everything happened,'' Bell said. ``Going up
there, knowing the situation, bases loaded, two outs, pretty good
hitter's count and hitting a home run. It was exciting. The
individual stuff was fantastic, but I didn't think about it much.
The grand slam and the team success we had, when I did think about
the season, that was the focus.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1311EST &QL; 
