<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7774 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-VOICES-ART-900     03-25 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VOICES-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS VOTE UNDER THE SPELL OF PUTIN'S MANY PROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ They don't make them much tougher than Siberian
bulldozer operators, so it follows that Roman Khasanov, a
30-year-old excavator from the flat, treeless permafrost of
Yakutia, has little use for politicians who feel people's pain. By
his way of thinking, it was Mikhail Gorbachev and his squishy
notions of perestroika and glasnost _ restructuring and openness _
that brought Russia to ruination in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he took off the handcuffs, he should have done so
slowly,'' Khasanov said as he sat, nursing a vodka hangover with
ulcer medicine, on a train bound to a Mongolia construction job.
``Because now people don't know what to do with their freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he believes Russia needs Vladimir Putin, the acting
president and the man who slapped the cuffs back on Chechnya's
rebels. Putin has the muscle to reimpose order on a chaotic nation,
and come the presidential election Sunday, Khasanov declared
earlier this month, ``I will vote for him with three hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But almost a continent westward, in the Volga River town of
Samara, Boris Fursov says Putin's muscular submission of Chechnya
is reason enough by itself to deny him the presidency. In Soviet
times, he said, maybe one man could impose order. In a democracy,
it is an entire nation's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you the truth about Putin,'' Fursov said over a
snack of bread and apple-and-currant preserves in his two-room
apartment. ``There is an element in his behavior that to my mind
pushes us back in time. And for my son and for my grandson, I would
prefer that they have an open and democratic road to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Fursov, a retired Soviet army officer who devoted much of his
career to the Cold War, says he will vote for Grigory Yavlinsky, a
member of Parliament who is, by most measures, the most
Western-oriented of Russia's presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   What does Russia want in its president? Does it want a strongman
or a man of the people? Does it want to be led back to imperial
glory, or simply, as Russians will say without a hint of irony, to
join the club of civilized nations? Do Russians want a president
who will bind them to Europe and the West, or do they want a
nationalist? Do they want a democrat, or has 10 years of democracy
induced nostalgia for Soviet-style transfers of power?
</P>
<P>
   What pollsters say Russians clearly want is Putin, although his
intentions remain, so far, largely a blank slate. The last
pre-election samples (polling here ended, as the law requires, a
week before the vote) gave Putin as much as 57 percent of the
backing among people who said they planned to vote in the election
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The closest of his 10 rivals, the Communist Party leader Gennady
Zyuganov, drew only about 25 percent; Yavlinsky, the Yabloko party
leader, was third with about 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Putin needs only 50 percent of the vote to escape a two-man
runoff, which would take place on April 16. With an additional
expected flood of pro-Putin ballots from the military and some
prisoners, who already have voted, he seems likely to avoid a
second election with room to spare.
</P>
<P>
   But saying the Russians want Putin as their president says
precious little about how or where they want him to lead. For
Putin's brief campaign has cast him as all things to all people: a
brutal warrior against Chechens; a dog lover who cries at funerals;
a supporter of basic rights; a supporter of a crackdown on
politically unruly journalists; an architect of a new rapprochement
with the West; an architect of an anti-Western alliance with China.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the war in Chechnya, a gamble that paid off royally among
voters thirsting for some symbol of national strength, Putin's
actual policies _ as opposed to promises _ have been few and
uncontroversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters are in a situation where they know all the other
candidates, and they know the others aren't suitable,'' said Otto
Latsis, a political analyst and deputy editor of the newspaper
Noviye Izvestiya. ``Putin they don't know. But they also don't know
many things which would push them away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, pollsters and analysts say, Putin, a 47-year-old
former KGB agent who took over as acting president last New Year's
Eve after just four months as prime minister, has managed to remain
remarkably popular precisely because he has religiously shunned any
one ideology. In a nation that, ideologically speaking, has been
exhausted by the brand of Wild East capitalism allowed under
Yeltsin, and before that by the brutal excesses of communism, Putin
has captured the none-of-the-above vote. And it is huge.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years after the fall of the Soviet Union, the Communist
Party is doomed to lose at the polls, at least in its present
incarnation. Its base of support is about 25 percent of the
electorate. The Communists are more popular than Putin only among
voters over 60; below that, their support dwindles almost in lock
step with age.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Western democrats of Yavlinsky's stripe are even worse off,
topping out at perhaps 15 percent of voters, by and large the
young, experts say. Ultranationalists like the flamboyant
legislator Vladimir Zhirinovsky claim perhaps 5 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the voters, like Khasanov, the bulldozer
driver, are united less by strong political beliefs than by the
lack of them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They are like Valery Khubalov, the general manager of a candy
factory in Kazan, the Tatarstan capital a night's train ride due
east of Moscow. Urbane and fluent in English, an occasional
presence at Harvard seminars, he says he backs Putin in the hope
that he will make both federal and regional officials stop abusing
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy is ``in my bones,'' Khubalov said. But ``I have
finally come to the conclusion that we have to go more slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Or like Georgi Vasilevsky, a 59-year-old architect at Terminal,
a St. Petersburg engineering company that was a top-secret Soviet
military complex and has now shrunk from 1,200 workers to 100,
making roughly $35 a month each.
</P>
<P>
   Putin ``is a decisive leader,'' he said. ``I'm sick of the
lawlessness and chaos that plagues Russia. He's the man who can
take on the oligarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Or like Inna Kremert, a 32-year-old St. Petersburger:
unemployed; mother of two; foster mother to the infant daughter of
a cousin who recently died.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, Kremert worked at a bank in neighboring
Latvia, where persecution of Russians is persistent; now she
subsists, barely, with pay from odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
   She wants one thing, and one thing only, from the next Russian
president: a better life. And she thinks Putin, a native of St.
Petersburg, stands the best chance of delivering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to worry about the time in 10 years when my children
will be adults,'' she said this week. ``Where will they live? How
will they buy apartments?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To make life better in Russia, first and foremost it must be
made safe and secure so people can live without fear from crime, so
they will be able to find work and feed their children,'' she said.
``Putin has shown himself to be a man of action; just look at
Chechnya. Maybe he's used too much force. But he's decisive in
tackling problems.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their differences, Russia's voters do broadly share some
desires. One is that they are democrats _ a word with a sprawling
definition, but one still rooted in a comfortably Western demand
for the right to think and do as they please.
</P>
<P>
   ``The percentage of people who do not rely on the government but
only on their own abilities is growing constantly,'' Georgi
Satarov, president of the Information Science for Democracy
Foundation, said in an interview. ``People don't want to part with
freedoms they have already gained. But they also do not want the
style of power they have already witnessed for the last decade, the
past four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Another common desire is, quite naturally, the longing for a
better life _ by which is meant, for the most part, the sort they
see on ever-present television imports or in their increasingly
frequent trips to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   True, Russian nationalism has rocketed since last year's clash
with NATO over Yugoslavia put the nation's shrunken role in world
affairs on exquisitely painful display. And Russian disdain for
Western protests against brutality in Chechnya is a direct reaction
to that snub.
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, said Igor Bunin, who directs the Moscow-based
Center for Political Technologies Foundation, ``the deep-seated
orientation of Russian society is completely different. It is to
enter European civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the majority of the population,'' he said, ``the Western
model is a kind of paradise in the future, a star in the distance.
We want to be just as civilized as them, the same kind of
civilization as in Europe. All the sociological polls show that
this is the main goal.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Russia's third presidential election, it is those
conflicting desires on which Putin seems to have gained a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   If voters have a question, it is whether Putin can keep it after
he becomes a democratically elected president, and has to begin
making the tough decisions that seem destined to fragment the vast,
motley collection of interests that has invested in him so far.
</P>
<P>
   Nonna Oznobikhina, 61, a professor at a Vladivostok teachers
college, is trying to wring Marxist ideology out of an education
system that still uses Soviet-era textbooks. She says that she and
her husband, Yuri Sibirtsev, a biologist, are supporting Putin
``with great hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He does inspire trust,'' she said. ``I like how he behaves in
public. There is a certain quiet dignity in him, especially in the
way he talks to foreign politicians. But who knows? This is Russia,
and he might turn into something unexpected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
