<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-25 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COACHES CORNER, OLD AND NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Just before Friday's regional semifinal game
between Oklahoma State and Seton Hall, Eddie Sutton and Tommy
Amaker made the customary walk to midcourt to shake hands. Sutton,
the 64-year-old Oklahoma State head coach, smiled at the
34-year-old Amaker and said, ``I've been coaching longer than you
are old.''
</P>
<P>
   Amaker admitted that Sutton's quip caught him off guard. ``He
was trying to intimidate me,'' Amaker laughed. ``Trying to rattle
me, but I didn't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State squeaked out a 68-66 victory to advance to the
regional championship game. But the victory had less to do with
Sutton's age and experience, than with the swollen left ankle of
Shaheen Holloway, Seton Hall's senior point guard,
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Sutton faces the University of Florida coached by the
34-year-old Billy Donovan. On Friday, Donovan defeated Duke coached
by the 53-year-old Mike Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about playing against teams coached by Amaker
and Donovan, Sutton smiled. ``It makes me feel a little older than
I want to feel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan played for Rick Pitino at Providence. Donovan remembered
his own NCAA tournament odyssey in 1987 when Providence reached the
Final Four. He didn't savor the moment then but is relishing every
moment this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy every game a lot,'' he said. ``Because, you know what?
I don't know the next time I'm getting back here. That's the thing
you realize its so fragile; it's so fragile that you'd better enjoy
it while you're here''
</P>
<P>
   Amaker made the same point after his team lost to Oklahoma
State. Players, he said, young people in general, always feels
there's a tomorrow. That's what makes the NCAA tournament so
devastating to the losers: there is no tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a chance, you better get it while you're there
because you may never get back,'' Amaker said. ``It's very
difficult to advance and survive in this tournament _ no matter how
good you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan and Amaker are now the sages. They preach and lecture,
tell their players to savor the experience of reaching the Round of
16, playing in the NCAA tournament. With so many players leaving
school earlier the value of the experience is missed altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys when they are here for a year don't really
understand, `` Donovan said. ``They get a little taste, but they
don't realize what its all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Battier, and Carrawell,'' he said, referring to the Duke
seniors Shane Battier and Chris Carrawell, ``understand what it's
all about because they've been through it for so many years and
they understand what the preparation's like to get there. Sometimes
you have guys that are young, they stay for a year or two and
they're gone. They never understand what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Amaker and Donovan entered college the same year _ Amaker at
Duke and Donavon at Providence. Amaker was Krzyzewski's assistant
for nine seasons, Donovan was on Pitino's coaching staff at
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino's staff replaced Eddie Sutton's in 1988 in the aftermath
of a recruiting scandal that wound up with Kentucky being placed on
probation. The old pillars of the college coaching industry are
being reinforced and replaced by new pillars. Donovan and Amaker
are part of a transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's changing; when I say its changing, I think the
profession is changing,'' Donovan said. ``I look at myself 11 years
ago being with Coach Pitino. College basketball has changed because
Dean Smith has retired, John Thompson has retired, you have a lot
big, big figures who, when you look at institutions the coach comes
to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's changed. With players leaving and going pro, with all
the recruiting and how crazy everything is, I think a lot of
athletic directors are going with young, energetic, vibrant guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said he wondered how the Suttons and Krzyzewskis have
carried on season after season and doubted that he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell you right now: There's no way in my mind I
ever think I could ever coach as long as Dean Smith,'' Donovan
said. ``I may not have the opportunity to do that _ they may get
rid of me. But there no way I could physically handle at this
level, coaching until I'm 55, 60 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton said he doesn't think the new crop of young coaches will
stay in the business for lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be surprised if they coach that long; they should be able
to make enough money to where they don't have to,'' he said. ``When
I started out, I made $4,500 the first year I coached, teaching
five U.S. history classes, assistant football coach, head
basketball coach in high school _ $500 a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Amaker said he can't see being a lifer, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I marvel at the people who have been in this business that
long,'' he said. ``You look around guys have been doing it 20, 25,
30 years, 40 years. This is the end of my third year and I feel I'm
wiped out.''
</P>
<P>
   But every coach feels that way at the end of a long season. Then
they look up and five years have passed, then 10, then 20 years.
Finally, one day Amaker will walk to mid-court to shake hands with
an opposing head coach and playfully remind him that he has been
coaching longer than his rival is old.
</P>
<P>
   Amaker laughed at the thought of it but conceded the
possibility. Once the game is in your blood, getting it out is next
to impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a loss your feelings are different,'' he said. ``If we
had won this game tonight I would have said `I want to do this
until I'm a hundred.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
