<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-USAIRWAYS-ACCORD-ART-     03-25 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAIRWAYS-ACCORD-ART-785(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENDANTS UNION IN TENTATIVE DEAL WITH US AIRWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   US Airways and its flight attendants union reached a tentative
agreement Saturday morning, more than three hours past a strike
deadline, preventing a shutdown of the United States' sixth-largest
airline that would have snarled tens of thousands of travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached shortly before 3:30 a.m. after a marathon
eight-day round of negotiations, was announced at a Washington
hotel, and when word went out to attendants gathered at vigils in
cities like Pittsburgh and Charlotte, N.C., the workers whooped
with joy.
</P>
<P>
   The accord gives the airline's 10,000 flight attendants a
substantial raise, which was one of the main demands of the
Association of Flight Attendants, while US Airways said the deal
helped advance its primary goal, to keep its costs competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the deal, Lynn Lenosky, the union's chief negotiator,
said, ``The contract is a five-year agreement flight attendants can
be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelers with US Airways reservations expressed relief that
their trips would not be turned topsy-turvy by a shutdown during an
especially busy season, when many schools and colleges are on
spring break.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Lotstein, who was at La Guardia Airport in New York at 8
a.m. Saturday to fly to Fort Lauderdale, Fla., for a golfing trip,
said: ``I am thrilled to be down here. We have been up all night
trying to find out what's happening. It's been a long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the agreement would give the attendants a 5
percent cash bonus when the agreement is ratified and a 5 percent
raise when the contract is signed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the attendants will receive 2 percent raises 18
months into the contract, and additional 2 percent raises after 30
months and 42 months.
</P>
<P>
   Several flight attendants interviewed said they were pleased
that for the first time they would get special holiday pay. Under
the agreement, the attendants are to receive time and a half for
working New Year's Day, Memorial Day and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zack, a union spokesman, acknowledged that the agreement
contained some work-rule changes on complex issues like scheduling,
which the airline sought to increase efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airline says it's cost-competitive,'' Zack said. ``That's
what we wanted to help them achieve. The flight attendants I've
spoken with say it's a very fair, very good agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual pay for the flight attendants ranges from $17,145 for
new attendants to a maximum of $36,918 for those with 14 or more
years of experience.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, US Airways said: ``The AFA leadership and the
company's management worked extremely hard to put in place an
agreement that works for our flight attendants and allows the
company to compete in the marketplace. We are very pleased that we
were able to do so and that there will be no interruption in
service or inconvenience for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to discuss details of the agreement
or what the company gained in the accord. In the days immediately
after a tentative agreement is reached, company officials often
hesitate to talk about what they gained for fear of angering union
members and thus making it harder to obtain ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The union's executive council now has to review the agreement
and decide whether to recommend it to the rank and file. If it
does, the flight attendants will be asked to vote on the accord,
with the entire ratification process expected to last up to 45
days.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening an unconventional strategy, the flight attendants
had said that if there was no agreement by 12:01 a.m. Saturday,
they would wreak havoc on the airline by disrupting 49 of the
airline's busiest routes. The airline has 2,200 flights a day
carrying 150,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of this strategy, called CHAOS, for Create Havoc
Around Our System, was to maximize disruption, while allowing most
flight attendants to continue working and drawing salaries. The
union said it would not disrupt every flight on those 49 routes but
would pick its spots, shutting them down on some days and letting
them fly on others.
</P>
<P>
   But airline officials responded with an unorthodox strategy of
their own, saying that if no agreement was reached by the strike
deadline, the airline would shut down its operations instead of
being whipsawed by the union's planned partial strike.
</P>
<P>
   A strike or a shutdown would have hurt the eastern third of the
nation most, because the airline has 36 percent of the region's
market and has hubs in Pittsburgh, Charlotte and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   David Castelveter, an airline spokesman, said operations had
returned to normal Saturday. ``Operations are going well,'' he
said. ``It's business as usual. We're operating a full schedule.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers holding reservations for Saturday's flights said
they had stayed up into the middle of the night to learn whether
their flights would depart.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Driver of Albany, N.Y., said she had called the airline's
800 telephone number every half-hour until 3:30 a.m., when the
recording informed her of the settlement. She was in a joyous mood
when she flew Saturday from Albany to Greensboro, N.C., to visit
friends.
</P>
<P>
   During a stopover in Charlotte, she said: ``I feel great. All my
plans were on schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Galbreath, who was worried about her plans to fly
Saturday from Charlotte to her home in Little Rock, Ark., said she
was delighted that there was a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know if we'd be able to get back,'' she said
Saturday morning at Charlotte/Douglas International Airport. ``I
got up at 4 o'clock, and the news was on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants' last contract expired in 1996, and the
two sides have held sporadic negotiations since. But on March 17,
negotiators, led by Lenosky and the airline's chief executive,
Rakesh Gangwol, began meeting for intense negotiations at the
Wyndham Washington Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest W. Dubester, chairman of the National Mediation Board,
joined the talks to prod the two sides to resolve their dispute.
His board had ordered a 30-day cooling-off period that barred the
union from walking out until 12:01 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the middle of the week, we were pretty much going around
the clock,'' he said in an interview Saturday. ``We had different
folks together at different times. It's analogous to shuttle
diplomacy. Sometimes have a full negotiating committee, sometimes
just the top two people.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law gives President Clinton the power to order the
airline or the union to continue normal operations for 60 days, but
labor experts said he was not considering such an order, for fear
of angering the AFL-CIO in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said on Friday that they were briefing the
president on the talks, and on Friday night the White House issued
a statement saying that Clinton ``urges the two sides to stay at
the table and redouble their efforts to reach an agreement as soon
as possible. They owe that to each other and to the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The company had pressured the union to accept a formula, known
as ``parity plus one,'' that had been agreed to by the company's 10
other unions, including the pilots, mechanics and ticket agents.
That formula would link the attendants' pay to that of their
counterparts at the nation's four largest airlines, plus 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lenosky, the union negotiator, criticized that formula and
rallied attendants against it, insisting that it would reduce their
wages and benefits. After the agreement was reached, neither side
was calling the agreement a ``parity plus one'' formula; instead
the two sides were calling it a ``cost-competitive formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Pask, a flight attendant for two years, said Saturday at
the airport in Rochester, N.Y., that she was pleased by the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very proud to stand behind the people who had been doing
this for 30 and 40 years,'' Pask said. ``I'm glad we didn't have to
walk out, for the customers' sake, but it was important to keep
this a professional and serious career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
