<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-SCENE-NYT &LR;      03-25 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE SHOP IN PAKISTAN TUNES INTO CLINTON ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Cotton Terminal is a men's store here in
Pakistan's capital. The owner keeps a small TV on a shelf, wedged
between a stack of khaki trousers and another of blue jeans.
Usually, the set comes on only for a big cricket match.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday the featured show was Bill Clinton, who had come to
Islamabad for a quick five-hour stop after five days in India. He
was to address the nation on state television.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very painful thing for us, five hours in Pakistan
and only five days in India,'' said Wasi Nayib, one of the
employees at the small shop. ``India is our adversary, and Bill
Clinton should have been fair to both sides. But we will watch him
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   In itself, this was unusual. Most Pakistanis did not tune in. It
was presumed that Clinton would be speaking in English in a nation
where people are far more likely to speak Urdu, Punjabi and Pushto.
Many believed the speech would merely be an opportunity to see an
important man moving his lips.
</P>
<P>
   But Cotton Terminal is an upscale store in the Jinnah Super
Market. And most workers and customers felt they knew enough
English to catch about half of what was being said. At noon, they
began viewing the Pakistani state television station, PTV, which
had cameras at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans prefer the Indians because the Indians have more
money,'' Nayib said seriously, a remark that drew the approval of
the 10 other people around him.
</P>
<P>
   But the PTV announcers were upbeat. If Pakistanis felt slighted
about the brevity of Clinton's visit, the state newscasters gushed
with praise for the American president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a musician as well as a politician, you know,'' Naveed
Shahzad, one of the announcers, said as the television screen
showed a still-empty runway.
</P>
<P>
   Her co-host agreed, ``Yes, he is a very versatile man.''
</P>
<P>
   The people at the Cotton Terminal considered most of this patter
to be nonsense, but there was not much competition for their
attention. The main roads had been shut down by soldiers with
automatic weapons. The key security force was the army's 10th
corps, the same outfit that had been central in the Oct. 12 coup
that brought Pakistan military rule.
</P>
<P>
   Most civilians stayed home, unable to get to their jobs or
schools. The streets were eerily quiet, as if it was a holiday:
Bill Clinton Day. Some storekeepers at the usually busy shopping
plaza had begun their own game of cricket on the walkway outside
their shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when is he coming already?'' Nayib said glumly to his
friends in the store.
</P>
<P>
   But then the announcers began getting excited. A plane had
landed, which they dubbed Air Force One, and they began talking in
awe about how the aircraft is a fully equipped flying office.
</P>
<P>
   ``And here he is!'' proclaimed Shahzad, a well-known
commentator, as people began exiting the big jet. ``President
Clinton is distinguished by his height and the shock of gray in his
hair,'' she said. ``One can see him moving leisurely toward us.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this was merely the press plane and the announcers had
mistaken a tall reporter for Clinton. Ten minutes later, a smaller
plane set down, lowered its staircase and men in dark suits began
slowly stepping down to the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time it's no mistake,'' Shahzad said enthusiastically.
``He's here! There's so much energy in the air, it's almost
crackling.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this was merely a decoy plane transporting a few
low-level officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's not coming,'' said Usman Ghani, one of the people
watching at the store. ``Maybe he's afraid Osama bin Laden is
waiting on the runway.''
</P>
<P>
   But at 12:39 p.m. the president did arrive, traveling in an
executive jet as part of elaborate security precautions. ``Here's
our hero,'' Nayib said sarcastically to his friends, who then broke
away from their chores.
</P>
<P>
   Then, inevitably, just as one would expect in the United States,
some wise guy raised his palms toward the television and feigned
puzzlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's Monica?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Some moments later, a wrinkled, bent-over man came into the
store, a long white beard flowing from his face and a set of prayer
beads moving through his fingers. His name is Haji Shaukat Ali, 70,
and he was a friend of the store's deceased owner. He is regarded
as an elder, and the younger people wanted to know what he thought
of the president's visit.
</P>
<P>
   He considered this question carefully. ``As Muslims, it is
mandatory for us to show him hospitality,'' he said. ``But he is
not here to help us. He is here for his own agenda. And we do not
need him. Americans are not the superpower. The only superpower is
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the people in the store nodded with approval.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the visit, a poll by Gallup Pakistan had measured
opinions about the visit. Only 24 percent thought anything fruitful
would emerge from Clinton's meetings with the nation's military
rulers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Americans had now tilted to India over Pakistan, 25
percent said yes; 57 percent said America is not really a friend of
either. Of those sampled, 71 percent thought there was a chance of
war with India; 47 percent expected the war to go nuclear.
</P>
<P>
   The wait for the Clinton speech seemed interminable. He was
supposed to talk at 4 p.m., but that hour came and went and even
the PTV punditry _ journalists and scholars _ ran out of things to
say. As people waited for the American president, the television
station ran a documentary about wood carving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very late,'' one of the store clerks complained. ``Maybe
he did bring Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 5:30, the speech was broadcast. To people's
surprise, PTV provided a simultaneous translation in Urdu. The shop
became very quiet. There were no more Monica jokes. A foreigner was
telling their nation some difficult things about the threat of
nuclear war and the loss of democracy and the awful consequences of
economic stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   The speech lasted less than 15 minutes, and when it was over, no
one said anything for a long while until the silence became
awkward.
</P>
<P>
   At last, a man named Tariq Hameed spoke up. ``Clinton is
right,'' he said simply.
</P>
<P>
   And again everyone nodded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
