<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-UGANDA-CULT-NYT &LR;      03-25 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-CULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE SHOWS UGANDA CULT HELD AN EERIE PRELUDE TO FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUTOMA, Uganda _ At least some of the 153 people killed at a
secluded cult compound in southwestern Uganda died several weeks
before hundreds of followers of the doomsday cult died in a raging
inferno in their church eight days ago, police said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The compound, set at the end of a narrow dirt path, was set on
fire just hours before the church inferno on March 17 in which at
least 330 people died. The fire at the compound gutted the five
small dwellings on the site and scorched much of the surrounding
earth in an eerie prelude to the catastrophe that then unfolded in
the village of Kanungu, where the cult, known as the Movement for
the Restoration of the Ten Commandments of God, made its home.
</P>
<P>
   The fire here, and the discovery of the bodies of people who
were killed apparently weeks or even months ago, have bolstered the
growing sense among investigators that what happened in the Kanungu
church was, on some level, a carefully orchestrated act by the
cult's leader, Joseph Kibwetere, and some of his lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we prove that they are dead, we want them to answer
charges of murder,'' Assuman Mugenyi, the chief spokesman for the
National Police Service, said Saturday in a telephone interview
from Kampala, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly overwhelmed by their grisly discoveries, police
officials said that international help for the underequipped
Ugandan police force would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find clues about the cult and about what happened at
Kanungu, investigators have been combing other sites where the cult
operated. When they arrived here on Thursday, an investigator
spotted unnatural depressions in the ground in three places.
</P>
<P>
   When diggers began excavating the ditches on Friday, the toll
was staggering: 153 bodies _ 20 in one grave, 45 in another, and 88
in the third, Mugenyi said. Of the dead, 59 were children, and
everyone, it appeared, had been killed, he said. Some of them had
been strangled and others had been slashed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the massacre at Kanungu, in which everyone died at once,
the killings here appear to have occurred at the very least over a
period of weeks, Mugenyi said. ``Some of them looked a bit fresh,
with blood and hair still on them, but others had been decaying for
some time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The site here, set at the end of a narrow dirt path, was used by
the cult for inducting new members and introducing them to its
ways, a senior police investigator said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a place for indoctrination,'' Terense Kinyera, the
regional head of criminal investigations for the Ugandan police,
said Saturday after meeting with other investigators here. ``People
were brought here for a few days before being moved to Kanungu.''
</P>
<P>
   The bodies found here were examined by medical investigators and
then buried en masse in a grave dug on the edge of one the
buildings, not far from their original resting places. Saturday,
empty boxes of surgical gloves used in the grizzly recovery
littered the site.
</P>
<P>
   With staffing limited and rough terrain making travel to the
scenes difficult, investigators have been slowed in their search
for evidence and limited in what avenues of inquiry they can
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   More than a week after the Kanungu fire, investigators were only
beginning to search another of the cult's sites, in the neighboring
village of Bushenyi. And investigators will never have the type of
forensic evidence that could have been gleaned from examination in
a laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   But removing the bodies would have been an enormous logistical
challenge, even for a police force with far more staff and
resources than the Ugandans can muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big problem for us because our police force is not
fully equipped,'' Mugenyi said. ``If we could get some
international assistance, we would welcome it. We need some
experts, especially on homicide, to help reinforce our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty to 30 investigators are assigned to the case, he said,
and ``even those resources are not enough for them to do thorough
work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
