<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE _ It is one of the most venerated of Aggie traditions:
the annual burning of the Texas A&AMP;M bonfire. But even as it has
evolved into a mainstay of A&AMP;M life, university officials have
always insisted that it is a student endeavor. But documents over
four decades highlight nagging safety problems that the bonfire
posed _ and that never seemed to be resolved. Texas A&AMP;M University
officials have insisted they had no reason to believe that the
bonfire would ever collapse. But more than 10,000 pages of
documents released after the deadly 1999 collapse show that chronic
safety risks went uncorrected for at least four decades, partly
because of ineffective oversight by university officials. (Gamboa,
Austin American-Statesman). 80. MOVED. WITH PHOTOS OF BONFIRE AND
KEY DOCUMENTS AND A TIMELINE GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-MAIN _ BETHEL, N.C. _ A look at the changing way of life
on tobacco farms. (Schulken, Greenville Daily Reflector). 60. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SIDE _ BETHEL, N.C. _ In their infancy tobacco plants
look like tiny shamrocks. As many as a million plants have taken
root in the warmth of Moore's greenhouse, snug in Styrofoam seed
crates, resting on a bed of water. They were sowed in mid-March,
and in April, when the threat of a hard freeze is past, they will
be transplanted in the field, the first crop of a new century.
(Schulken, Greenville Daily Reflector). 10. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLE-ADDICTS _ SHREVEPORT, La. _ Louisiana has opened the
first gambling addiction in-patient center in the nation that is
paid for by a state government _ the other such centers around the
US are all private. Wasn't gambling only supposed to be a good
thing for the state? So why is the state, which by the way is
strapped for cash at the moment, now forking over more than
$400,000 to treat the addicts the state itself created?
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PRESTON-KING _ ALBANY, Ga. _ Preston King's return home to
Albany, Ga., last month was chronicled by local, national and
international media as an extraordinary journey. After all, the
63-year-old college professor had to wait 39 years to make the
transatlantic trip from England, all because of his long-ago
insistence on being treated with respect. Yet, for the Kings of
Albany, Preston King's homecoming was the latest in a long line of
journeys _ both literal and metaphorical _ in search of dignity for
themselves and others. These travels are a theme of a rich family
history. They have taken generations of Kings along country roads,
across the continent, over oceans and beyond racial barriers. The
first steps were taken when Clennon Washington King, who would
become the patriarch of a remarkable family, set off on foot from a
Florida Panhandle hamlet called Two Egg determined to reach
Tuskegee, Ala., some 180 miles to the north. (Head, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 67. WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-CITY _ SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ A stay-at-home mom, Kathy
Verschoor sits down daily at the family computer to stay in touch
with her toddler's playgroup, scan upcoming events at the nearby
community center and keep up on neighborhood concerns. But
Verschoor is no nerd. She kew little about computers and the
Internet until she and her husband, Scott, moved last year to DC
Ranch, a high-tech housing development taking shape in the desert
foothills on the northern fringes of Phoenix's urban sprawl. Amid
the personal-computing boom, real-estate developers and architects
across the country are collaborating on new neighborhoods that
feature high-speed connections marrying the Internet, television
and telephone services. But DC Ranch is not intended as an
exclusive haven for the pocket protector crowd. The Arizona
developers, DMB Associates, have taken their technology a step
further by encouraging the use of computers to build personal
relationships among the suburbanites. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-FEATURES _ How DC Ranch technology helps residents
organize their lives.
</P>
<P>
   (Scratched) _ WIRED-NOT.
