<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   EMAN SERIES/PART TWO
</P>
<P>
   EMAN-PART2 _ Alexander Graham Bell, the inventor of the
telephone, would be astounded by today's portable wireless cell
phone. And early radio aficionados never envisioned their
grandchildren walking down the street with a Sony Walkman perched
on their heads. Today, computers are making that same transition.
Once heavy and place-bound, they are becoming so lightweight and
portable that they will soon be wearable, part of the clothing and
accessories that people don each morning. (Bookman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 60
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EMAN-WIRED _ ``For two years I had 30,000 people inside my head,
watching what I did everyday, altering my reality, offering
suggestions on what I should do next,'' recalls Steve Mann, a
professor at the University of Toronto. ``I finally had to shut it
down, though. My head space got a little too crowded.'' Mann is not
crazy. From 1994 to 1996, while a grad student at MIT in Boston, he
streamed live video directly onto the Internet from a device that
was mounted on his head. Everything Mann saw and heard, visitors on
his website could see and hear as well.
</P>
<P>
   EMAN-MILITARY26 _ Thanks to speech recognition software in their
computers, soldiers will be able to fire weapons and take other
combat actions by voice command alone in military exercises this
summer. (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAXES _ DALLAS _ Last week's chaotic final meeting of
the Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce didn't settle the
question of how to tax Internet sales, but it may have put to rest
the idea of banning them permanently. Instead, Congress seems
likely to explore ways to makes sure that all retailers everywhere
have a ``level playing field'' for taxes. (Geewax, Cox News
Service).
</P>
