<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-MAIN0326-COX     03-25 2218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-MAIN0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Editor's note: A Season on the Land will take readers through a
year with a farm family in this rural region, and report on a way
of life that is vanishing.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A changing way of life for tobacco farmers
 &HT;    By Mary Schulken
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.C. Spring comes to the farm in rows as neat as
pigtails.
</P>
<P>
   Red and green tractors slice fallow ground with sharp blades,
turning up a promise repeated every year.
</P>
<P>
   Another beginning. Another season on the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell what kind of tractor grandpa has,'' W.C. Moore tells his
two grandsons, who are bouncing around an easy chair in the living
room of a white farmhouse set back off highway 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red'' one 4-year-old offers in a string of words that are not
quite clear to adult ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Deere'' says the other tow-headed 4-year-old, a fact the
first boy loudly disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa and Grandmama smile from opposite ends of a long blue
couch, legs crossed toward each other. Their faces tell it plainly:
They would rather be having this conversation than doing anything
else on an unseasonable March morning.
</P>
<P>
   It is an everyday scene in this pleasant room, banter between
grandchild and grandparent, repeated as their lives play out within
easy reach of each other on this farm that is the center of their
universe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is a rare scene, too. And becoming more rare with every
day that passes.
</P>
<P>
   More flue-cured tobacco is grown in Pitt County, North Carolina,
than anywhere else in the nation. The culture and the economy are
rooted in tending the leaf, and in the self-reliant way of life
such labor demands. Yet as court rulings, public opinion and
pressure from Washington alter the fortunes of tobacco, change has
made its way into the fields.
</P>
<P>
   There will be fewer and fewer lives like the ones Betty and W.C.
Moore of Bethel live, shaped and bound by the rituals of passing
seasons on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   A GOOD LIVING
</P>
<P>
   Sunny week-day mornings with kids are nothing new in the
150-year-old house the Moores share near Bethel. They've spent
almost all the days of their 40-year marriage here, near each
other. He has worked the fields and the tractors. She has worked
beside him, and balanced the books. Both have tended the family.
Their three grown offspring live barely out of sight: one up the
road, another across the field, a third beyond the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Grandchildren come and go nearly every day in this house where
peanut butter and jelly and peaches are shared at lunchtime and
grandpa tests the biceps of growing boys between bites. A framed
picture over the kitchen counter says ``Farming is everybody's
bread and butter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has made us a good living so we don't have to
penny-pinch,'' Betty says. ``In that time he and I have been able
to spend a lot of time together, a lot of quality time, because we
were here on the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Family is the focus of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to get up and go off in the morning to a job
and then we'd have to wait for daddy to come home in the
afternoon,'' she said. ``That, I thought, was something worth no
amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   You can feel the measure of that closeness in the Moore's easy
give and take with their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collin, where did you get that name?'' William Collin Moore
asks his namesake.
</P>
<P>
   Collin, blue-eyed and impish, shrugs his shoulders, says
nothing, grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did you get it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don' know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody obviously didn't teach you very well,'' says Betty,
giving Grandpa a look.
</P>
<P>
   Like most farmers in this rural region or North Carolina,
tobacco is the Moore's cash crop. It has paid most of the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of them smoke. But they do not believe the federal
government should keep people from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our choice,'' says W.C. ``It's anybody's choice.''
</P>
<P>
   And they do not think growing tobacco is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing out of all this that bothers me is that we're doing
the same thing as our fathers and grandfathers did and it's always
been a hard, decent living,'' says Betty. ``All of a sudden it
becomes corrupt and you have a stigma on you.''
</P>
<P>
   TENDING THE LAND
</P>
<P>
   W.C. Moore has a place he calls an office in the metal building
that houses the farm operation. And he has a place in his home
where he studies maps of the land he tends, and does planning.
</P>
<P>
   But the cab of his white and blue Ford F250 diesel pick-up truck
is where he manages what goes on in the fields, connected by a cell
phone and a business band radio. On a spring day the radio crackles
with questions from his five full-time employees. After a winter of
maintaining equipment inside the farm's metal building, his workers
are out in the sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got two tractors discin' land and one guy rippin' tobacco
land,'' he says. ``And we're cutting ditchbanks, clearing brush,
getting ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore rides uneven dirt paths through fields, stopping to
inspect damage from beavers and progress with the plow.
</P>
<P>
   He is tall and lean, and slightly stooped when he stands.
Wrap-around shades protect his vision from constant sun. When the
shades come off, the eyes behind them are brown, and more than a
little merry. His uniform is standard, depending on the weather:
Blue work pants and a plaid short-sleeve shirt on warm days, blue
corduroys and a long-sleeve flannel shirt when it's cool. There's a
tractor on his belt buckle, and a boast that ``Agriculture feeds
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unit one,'' the radio spits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead four'' Moore says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you want me next?'' asks a man on a tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That field up by North Pitt (high school)'' Moore replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``10-four.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers vary from year to year, but Moore plants close to
100 acres of tobacco, 90 acres of cotton, 300 acres of corn and
wheat, along with soybeans and peanuts. Some of it is on land he
owns, some on the farms of others he tends. The Wainwright farm,
where W.C. and Betty live. The Brown farm. The Ward farm. The Vann
Taylor land.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up on a farm near Falkland, and worked off the land only
briefly, at a supply store, as a new husband in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmin' has been good to me,'' he says. ``But, now, I mean I
had to work for it. It wasn't give to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He likes what he does. He sticks to careful decisions. And at a
time when many others are being forced to turn in the plow, he
makes adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard at times,'' he said. ``But you do have your freedom,
you're kind of your own boss to a certain extent.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore tells about his wife Betty's two sisters, and how they
swore as young girls they would not marry a farmer, or farm.
Neither did. One lives in Chicago. The other married a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't done any better, I thought, than I have,'' he
said. ``I'm not saying I'm on cloud nine, but we have done some
things we wanted to do. We've never been in debt for a lot of
things we didn't have to have, other than debt for the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's routine takes him by crossroad stores like the one at
Whitehurst Station, where he kids with men he sees almost every
day. His usual is a short Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates he owns about a thousand acres, but isn't sure. Yet
he readily knows the details of how each scrap of land came to be
under his care.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly widow who needed the money for her increasingly
costly care. An heir who had no use for the family farm. A neighbor
who stepped down from the tractor. One deal sealed the
old-fashioned way, with a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many folks will take a handshake these days,'' Moore says.
He is pleased to be someone whose word is honored in the circles he
keeps.
</P>
<P>
   And he takes pains to see to the needs of the people whose
property he farms. Keeping strangers away from a fishing pond, and
cleaning up pecan trees blown over by hurricanes. For Moore,
tending land is a trust that requires such things.
</P>
<P>
   TENDING THE BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   The sign on the sliding door to Betty Moore's back stoop warns
visitors. But it doesn't prepare them for what's inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me about my grandchildren,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, almost every conversation in this house turns to
family.
</P>
<P>
   Grandchildren skitter through the house and yard, part of the
scenery. They go to grandmama for snacks and hugs, and to have a
kindling-size splinter removed from a small palm. Betty knows what
they do every day, even when they are not at her house. And her
children, too are close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Reginia every day, and Randall most every day.'' she
says. ``He comes in for breakfast. ``I don't see Myra every day
because she works in Greenville, but we do a lot of talking.''
</P>
<P>
   On the farm, Betty worked the fields until a few years ago. She
still works the finances and is a certified public accountant. That
means keeping up with a cash flow of as much as a half-million
dollars and balancing the crucial timing of loans, supply purchases
and payments due.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does the bookkeeping. She tries to pay the bills. And keep
up with the government,'' W.C. says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And be grandmama,'' Betty replies.
</P>
<P>
   She is short and trim, but round in places. She frets about
clutter in her house, but does not pass up conversation with a
visitor _ or a grandchild _ in honor of straightening up. Smoky, a
well-fed 15-year-old cat with silver hair, ghosts her steps.
</P>
<P>
   Betty's voice and manner are easy. But she speaks her mind,
particularly about the county's efforts to zone part of the farm
they live on and about plummeting regard for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many people that ride around, they have no idea
that peanuts grow in the ground,'' she says, ``they think they're
supposed to grow on trees like pecans.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty grew up on a farm. Her father ran a country store near the
crossroad of Penny Hill. The land has offered her a good living and
nurtured deep roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know of any other life that could give that much
coverage for a family,'' she says. ``And that's what I had seen in
my growing-up time.''
</P>
<P>
   `A DYING BREED'
</P>
<P>
   It's getting harder and harder for the farm to sustain a family
in the way it has the Moores.
</P>
<P>
   In Pitt County, where more flue-cured tobacco for cigarettes
grows than anywhere else in the nation, the decline of the leaf has
hit especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   Unprecedented cuts in federal tobacco quotas, disastrous
flooding in 1999 and depressed export markets have imposed unusual
hardship. This season will be a make-or-break year for a greater
number of farmers than normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique season I think because of the fact that
usually there would be some aspect of agriculture which would lift
up the others,'' says Mitch Smith, Pitt County director of the
state Cooperative Extension Service. ``Well, we don't have that
now, we've lost half our (tobacco) quota since 1997, all of our
grain prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Each December U.S. tobacco manufacturers announce how much leaf
they expect to buy the next year. The federal government then sets
quotas that determine how much leaf farmers will be allowed to sell
at auction. For the last two years, quotas have dropped _ 28
percent for 1999, and another 18 percent for 2000. The cuts came
alongside a multi-billion dollar settlement of a lawsuit states
like North Carolina filed against tobacco companies to recoup the
cost of smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Other forces, too, have pressed farmers in the county that
tobacco built.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, floodwaters from Hurricane Floyd covered 58 percent
of the county. The fields still bear the scars. So do farmers'
pocketbooks. Many, like the Moores, carried over debt from
operating loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Moores lost 175 acres of cotton to floodwaters, and some
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even harvest half the peanuts; it was wet we
couldn't get 'em,'' W.C. said. ``We lost right smart corn, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You tighten your belt,'' Betty said. ``The lending institution
makes it better, and right now they will work with you, but now if
it gets any tighter I don't know what they'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, there were some full-time 550 farmers in Pitt
County. Now, only 450 hands-on operators remain. Most of them are
like the Moores. They have made it through a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got your 55-60 year-olds who have been in it and who
continue to borrow money and make decisions,'' Smith said. ``Then
you've got a small group of 15-20 producers in their late 30s and
early 40s who agonize over their future but nevertheless have
agreed to stay in it until something goes defunct.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects those numbers to dwindle even more.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported in November 1999 that North
Carolina could lose 15-20 percent of its tobacco farmers this year.
Smith's forecast is similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten to 15 percent in Pitt County are in the situation where
they could easily liquidate this year and not farm any more,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever comes, we will farm,'' Betty says. Yet the Moores
know the life they have enjoyed on the land will be more elusive
for the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   W.C. recalls a recent conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day a truck driver came out to the shop for some
stuff and he said 'let me touch you. I'm gonna go home and tell my
boy I touched a dyin' breed.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
