</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SIDE0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Innovations in farming tobacco
 &HT;    By Mary Schulken
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.C. _ In their infancy tobacco plants look like tiny
shamrocks.
</P>
<P>
   As many as a million plants have taken root in the warmth of
W.C. Moore's greenhouse, snug in Styrofoam seed crates, resting on
a bed of water. They were sowed in mid-March, and in April, when
the threat of a hard freeze is past, they will be transplanted in
the field, the first crop of a new century.
</P>
<P>
   The green fuzz sprouting in the seed crates doesn't look like
much. But with an average price, the half-million pounds of leaf it
will grow into could net $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhouses like Moore's 30- by-300-foot structure are big
innovations in farming tobacco. Yet like most breakthroughs, they
are expensive. Today it costs around $30,000 to set up a
greenhouse, said Mitch Smith, county director of the Cooperative
Extension Service. In 1991, Moore was one of the first growers
around to make that investment.
</P>
<P>
   It has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Tending seedlings in a hothouse is nothing like working
old-fashioned tobacco beds, where seeds were sowed in the ground
under plastic. It takes fewer people and makes setting out tobacco
_ one of the most back-breaking parts of raising leaf _ much
easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to say to Betty this is the only thing I spent money on
she never complained about,'' W.C. says. ``With beds it took 28
people to set out (tobacco in the field.) Now it takes eight. And
you don't have that mental thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the big changes that we made that worked very
well,'' Betty says.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the mercury has barely reached 60, the thermometer
inside reads 95 degrees. Plastic curtains around the bottom of the
house are open, letting cooler air drift over the 10-day-old
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Managing a greenhouse is a precise business. The seedlings are
watered by sprinklers and the temperature carefully regulated. At
night, the cold requires heaters. In the daytime sunshine demands
ventilation. And the young plants must be mowed with a lawn mower
adapted to a mechanical mount overhead. That forces them to grow to
a uniform size, and that is best for transplanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you mow 'em about twice you come in here and it looks
like a yard,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco seeds have changed, too.
</P>
<P>
   They used to be little brown specks. Now the pod is inside a
tiny ball of clay that is green and round, resembling the balls of
sugar used to decorate cakes and cookies. Crush one, and you find
white powdery stuff. The germ of North Carolina's cash crop is all
but invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
