<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trail Blazers Have Time to Heal
</P>
<P>
   In Joe Kleine's 15-year career, he could not remember a
regular-season game more hyped and anticipated than the one between
the Portland Trail Blazers and the Los Angeles Lakers on Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Vying for home-court advantage throughout the playoffs, the
teams came into the game tied with the National Basketball
Association's best mark at 45-11. ``The greatest regular-season
game in the history of the NBA,'' bellowed Bill Walton, the NBC
analyst and the former Blazer center, before the matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen anything like it,'' Kleine, Portland's reserve
center, said of the buildup. ``I don't want to blame that game on
everything that happened, but obviously it had something to do with
it. It was like everything just came to a standstill for one
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Including the beleaguered Blazers. They have not been the same
since, going 5-5 since that defeat. Portland has lost four of six
at the Rose Garden after winning 16 straight. They blew
fourth-quarter leads to Minnesota and Detroit. Toronto recently
beat the Blazers on their home floor by 19 points, their worst loss
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   As the Blazers prepared to entertain the Knicks on Sunday, the
question was: could they find their rhythm and heart before the
Lakers run away with the Western Conference championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``With the 82 games, it's inevitable that no matter how good you
are, sooner or later you're going to hit a funk during the year,''
said Kleine, who has played on six teams, including a championship
team in Chicago. ``Very rarely does a team not go through one. You
lose your way and eventually you find it again. But sometimes to
find it, you need a good slap in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Dunleavy added: ``Certainly when you have a big loss,
there is a residue to it. But more than that, we've really missed
Brian Grant. Especially his toughness and rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant, a power forward, was activated last Friday after missing
most of March with an injury in his foot. He also had off-season
knee surgery. Instead of Rasheed Wallace being the anchor off the
bench, Grant has been forced into a starting role.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers also lost Arvydas Sabonis last week after the center
severely sprained his right foot. He is expected to miss two to
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, the Blazers were unanimously tagged as
favorites to succeed the San Antonio Spurs as champions. In some
quarters, the Spurs were picked to repeat, and the Lakers were seen
as a greater long-shot than any Eastern Conference team. But
mostly, Portland was the team spoken of most highly.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had the talent, experience and, most of all, the
depth. Acquiring Scottie Pippen, Steve Smith and Detlef Schrempf
during the off-season not only took oodles of Paul Allen's money
but also the maneuverability of Bob Whitsitt, the team president.
</P>
<P>
   After ridding themselves of Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson, the
Blazers' $50 million starting lineup was not as much about cash as
it was cachet. And for the first four months, the Blazers seemed
polished and poised, on the cusp of distinguishing themselves from
the pack.
</P>
<P>
   But gradually the problems began to surface. If it was not
Wallace blowing a gasket and leading the league in technical fouls,
it was poor decision-making on offense. Portland's lack of a
genuine go-to player at the end of a game has also been raised.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the biggest reason for their shortcomings is clear to see on
the court: at the moment, the Blazers are not mentally or
physically strong enough to compete for a title. It's not just
Wallace; many Portland players think all of humanity is out to get
them after a questionable call. They do not play through the
whistles. Instead of saving their nasty disposition for their
opponents, they direct it at the referees.
</P>
<P>
   Having already won 50 games, the Blazers are the second-best
team in the league. They are not in grave danger and have a few
weeks to fix the leaks. But less than two months ago, Portland was
considered a lock to wind up in the conference finals and dispatch
the Lakers. Now, they are just another slumping NBA team struggling
to find its identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely still have a chance to get there and win it,''
Kleine said. ``You can't say that about a lot of teams. But it's
not going to be easy. The problems we have are fixable. We, as a
team, complain too much. We've got to be a lot tougher, mentally
and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy said: ``My wish was to have us healthy by now. That
didn't happen. So we just have to find a way to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Carter Conspiracy
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month ago, Vincesanity was the catch phrase used to
describe the sweeping popularity of Vince Carter, and how the
All-Star forward of the Toronto Raptors had made the casual fan to
again pay attention to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But then Butch Carter invoked a number of conspiracy theories
that could thwart Toronto from keeping his star player under
contract. At one point this week, the Raptors coach accused both
the Toronto Maple Leafs of the National Hockey League of tampering
and the NBA of possibly trying to steer Carter toward an American
city after he become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Sun actually spoke with a highly placed league
official who essentially told the newspaper that the NBA would be
better off if Carter ended up on a team in the United States. It
was an anonymous quote that a league spokesman referred to as
``moronic'' and ``stupid'' and not at all indicative of the
league's stance.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Carter apologized for his comments after he was chastised
by general manager Glen Grunwald. But he added, ``I think there are
forces out there that have been and will be destructive to our
situation in Toronto. I don't think it will be anyone in the league
office.''
</P>
<P>
   For simple economic reasons, the league needs high-profile
players in its major markets. Yet the notion the NBA wants Carter
anywhere else than Toronto is a bit shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors, regardless of their locale, are currently helping
resuscitate NBC's sagging NBA ratings. If Toronto could somehow
negotiate its way through the Eastern Conference finals and into a
championship showdown with the Lakers, neither the network nor
commissioner David Stern would fret. They would be overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   The immediacy of the Internet and television almost negate
modern, big-market hyperbole. Witness the phenomenon of the
Sacramento Kings over the past two seasons. In the old days, Vince
would have had to go to Hollywood or Madison Avenue for maximum
exposure. Now, they go to him.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the NBA is so concerned about its Canadian presence that
the team owners recently unanimously rejected the ownership
application of Bill Lurie, the St. Louis billionaire. After all the
efforts that went into North American expansion, they did not want
Lurie transplanting the Vancouver Grizzlies to the Midwest until
that NBA market was deemed a failure over a longer period of time.
</P>
<P>
   If Carter's appeal could truly cut into the consciousness of a
hockey nation over the long haul, would not investors in Ottawa or
Montreal eventually give credence to NBA teams in their own cities?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one of the main issues fought for and won by owners in
the last round of bargaining was more restrictions on player
movement. They want people to stay with their teams. Continuity _
Michael in Chicago, Larry in Boston, Magic in L.A. _ is still a
valued asset in the NBA. Unless Vince Carter _ and only Vince
Carter _ wants to play somewhere else, he will remain a Raptor.
</P>
<P>
   The Children of 76ers
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dunleavy has been watching his son, Michael, play for Duke
in the NCAA tournament. Harvey Catchings has been watching his
daughters, Tamika and Tauja, play for Tennessee and Illinois in the
women's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 25 years ago, the two fathers were teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take all the players' kids off that team, you'd have a
pretty good team right there,'' Dunleavy said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 1976-77 Philadelphia 76ers fell to Bill Walton's
Portland Trail Blazers in the finals, but they should also be an
All-Genetic Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Catchings and Dunleavy, that 76ers team featured Henry
Bibby, whose son, Mike, starts at point guard for the Vancouver
Grizzlies, and a reserve forward with a decent vertical leap, Joe
(Jellybean) Bryant, father of Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   There was also Doug Collins, whose son, Chris, starred at Duke,
and Steve Mix, who has a daughter playing college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those amazing coincidences,'' said Pat Williams,
the general manager of that Sixers team. ``I can't remember a team
of players whose children turned out to be so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens Like Knick Trio
</P>
<P>
   And you thought it was just fed-up adults who wanted Patrick
Ewing to stop shooting so much and make way for the new generation.
According to Inside Stuff, the teen magazine of the NBA, Latrell
Sprewell, Allan Houston and Marcus Camby were named the league's
top trio _ the three teammates who work the best together on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The three Knicks edged out Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and
Glen Rice; Ray Allen, Glenn Robinson and Sam Cassell; Chris Webber,
Jason Williams and Vlade Divac; and Alonzo Mourning, Tim Hardaway
and Jamal Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   The voting actually was not done by kids. Rather, the magazine's
editorial board made the selections.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
