<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-STRIFE-ART-2T     03-25 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-STRIFE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEP POLITICAL AND RELIGIOUS RIFTS DISRUPT THE HARMONY OF NIGERIAN
TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABA, Nigeria _ In a corner of this city in Nigeria's Christian
heartland, where every other car seems to affirm the driver's love
for Jesus, Muslim migrants from the north had managed to become
landowners.
</P>
<P>
   The corner was known as Ama Hausa, or gathering place of the
Hausas, who make up one of the country's three main ethnic groups,
along with the Ibo and Yoruba. But after Ibo rioters destroyed this
street corner in Nigeria's recent religious conflicts, graffiti
scrawled on a wall of the gutted mosque reclaimed the land: Ama
Ibo.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Hausa have since packed up their belongings and
left for the north. Many headed to Sokoto, at the country's
geographic and cultural opposite end, where a similar exodus was
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   In Sokoto, the historic site from which a Muslim holy war
succeeded in spreading the religion through West Africa two
centuries ago, many Ibo were seen at the main bus station
scrambling to buy the $15 tickets that would take them back to Aba
and other cities in southeastern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's recent politically driven religious conflicts have
claimed hundreds, perhaps thousands, of lives and destroyed
countless churches, mosques and houses. President Olusegun Obasanjo
has described these clashes as attempts to undermine the nation's
10-month-old democracy, and many Nigerians from different parts of
the country agree that several states' attempts to introduce
sharia, the Islamic penal and social code, have more to do with
politics than religion.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflicts are rooted in all-too-real hatreds and
divisions, like the abyss between Sokoto and Aba. These hatreds and
divisions are staggeringly complex, fueled by the misrule and
corruption that have left most residents of one of the world's top
oil producers in poverty. What is more, these rifts have been
encouraged and exploited by the country's rulers, from the British
to the military governments to the European and American oil
companies that pump crude in the Niger delta, an area largely
abandoned by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Heaps of garbage, some of it on fire, littered the main road in
Aba on a recent day. The garbage contractor had been dismissed for
corruption, and a new contract had yet to be awarded. Nationwide,
the unreliable national electricity system collapsed recently,
plunging the Nigerians who could not afford generators into
darkness and forcing Obasanjo to declare an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   As Ibo were killed in the north and thousands returned here, the
events recalled those leading up to the Biafran Civil War. Three
decades ago, following massacres of Ibos in the north, the ethnic
group tried to secede from the rest of Nigeria. The war was one of
the most brutal in Africa's postindependence history _ a million
died _ but a successful postwar reunification policy knitted
greater ties among Nigerians. With the recent surge in hatreds, it
is unclear whether those ties are stronger than the divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried when I heard what had happened to my people,'' the
Rev. Prince Benny James, 29, an Ibo and associate pastor at the
Living Church here in Aba, said of the recent killings of Ibo in
the north.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of reprisal attacks against Muslim Hausa in Aba,
James sheltered 10 Hausa who escaped eventually. But on the first
morning, James said he was present at an attack against some Hausa.
He did not participate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But somehow I was happy these things were being done to
them,'' he said. ``In my heart, I was saying, `Yes, do that to
them! Go ahead! Go ahead! Right!' I gave my support by being there.
If I had not enjoyed it, I would have returned to my house.''
</P>
<P>
   The locals began attacking the Hausa after corpses of Ibo killed
in the north were brought back to Aba. But what began as a battle
between Muslims and Christians in the north became an ethnic witch
hunt here, as Ibo searched for anyone who might be a northerner.
</P>
<P>
   At James' Living Church, the security guard, Andy Petei, 25, hid
in a hole under the altar for three days after some youths came
looking for him. Neither Muslim nor Hausa, Petei is a member of an
ethnic minority from a north central state. He had nevertheless
become a target because he was from the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people said I may be Hausa,'' said Petei, a Christian.
Religion is one of the great fault lines in Nigeria, an ambitious
creation of British colonialists. Ethnicity is another. But
Nigeria's divisions are so treacherous because the cleavages can
shift from one region to another, from one day to another.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all Ibo are Christian; almost all Hausa are Muslim. The
Yoruba, on the other hand, are divided almost evenly between Muslim
and Christian. And the Islam practiced by the Yoruba is a much more
easygoing variety than that practiced by the Hausa.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Hausa, Islam is a total way of living,'' said Julius
Okolo, an Ibo and professor of political science at Usman dan Fodio
University in Sokoto. ``For the Yoruba, it's not a total way of
living. The cultural aspects of the Yoruba are stronger than
religion, whether it's Christianity or Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Yoruba Christians and Muslims marry each other without a
second thought. It is not unusual for Yoruba to have members of
both faiths in their families; some even practice both religions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But among northerners, being a Christian Hausa is considered a
contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seen as people who have sold out,'' said Emman Usman
Shehu, who heads an organization for Christians in Sokoto. ``In the
north, once we have left Islam, where the political, social and
economic aspects are all tied up, we become classless citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lagos, the commercial capital in the Yoruba southwest, deadly
clashes between Yoruba and Hausa have occurred in recent months.
But in the recent riots in the northern city of Kaduna, some Yoruba
seemed to have escaped injury because of their religion or
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Suraj Najimu, an 18-year-old student and a Yoruba Muslim, said
he was surrounded by a group of Hausa youths ready to assault him.
``But after I recited some Koranic passages, they let me go,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On a Muslim street in the predominantly Christian slum of
Kaduna, Christians destroyed all the houses except a few belonging
to Yoruba. Most of the Yoruba were Christian. But even one who is
Muslim, Shehu Garba, was spared, apparently because in this
particular instance, ethnicity was more important than religion.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo has said that he wants to avoid taking the issue of
sharia to the Supreme Court, which would rule clearly on the
matter. A political solution, he said, ``will end up without any
victor or vanquished.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No victor, no vanquished'' was the slogan adopted to reunite
Nigerians after the Biafran Civil War _ a policy regarded by many
historians as one of the most successful reconciliation attempts in
recent history. And indeed, over the years, despite all of
Nigeria's fissures, the country has grown more interdependent.
</P>
<P>
   The building of more roads, increasing urbanization and economic
exchanges have all pushed ever more Nigerians to leave their
historic home regions for other parts. Many of these Nigerians fell
victim to the recent violence.
</P>
<P>
   James, the associate pastor here, said he personally knew a
Hausa man who was killed here. ``He was married to an Ibo woman,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
