u i BC-NIRELAND-TRIMBLE-720&AMP;     03-25 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TRIMBLE-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER LEADER HOLDS ON, BUT POWER DIMINISHED IN UNIONIST PARTY
VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ David Trimble Saturday held off a
surprisingly strong challenge to his leadership of the Ulster
Unionist Party but emerged with his authority and his room for
maneuver in conducting peace negotiations diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, the province's most prominent Protestant politician,
defeated the Rev. Martin Smyth with 57 percent of the vote of the
ruling Ulster Party Council. Although the result ensured his spot
at the top of the province's largest party for another year, it
also indicated deepening division among members over going forward
with the steps aimed at sharing power with the Catholic minority
outlined in the Northern Ireland peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth, a 68-year-old former grand master of the traditionally
hard-line Orange Order, had only sprung his insurgency on Thursday,
yet still managed to attract the support of 43 percent of the
voters for his move to oust Trimble, 55, a Nobel Peace Prize
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Shouts of ``resign'' were heard inside the Royal Ulster
Society's Kings' Hall when the result of the secret ballot of the
805 delegates was announced, and a group of Smyth's backers charged
out the front door punching the air in jubilation. But Trimble's
supporters said afterward that he had no intention of stepping
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we would have liked the margin to have been much
more comfortable,'' Michael McGimpsey, a Trimble ally, said grimly,
``but this is a period of extreme tension, nerves and worry for the
party, and there would have been an element of protest votes in
there. I don't believe he would consider resignation having just
been endorsed by almost 60 percent of his ruling council.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry McDonald, author of a new biography of the Ulster Unionist
leader, said he believed Saturday's vote left Trimble ``completely
restricted'' at a time when Britain and Ireland, the sponsors of
the peace plan, and the United States, the principal foreign
backer, are urging flexibility in trying to get back up and running
a power-sharing home rule government that was put on hold last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland Assembly, with Trimble as first minister
and members of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, in executive positions, was suspended on Feb. 11
by Britain when the IRA refused to make expected moves on
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates said Saturday they were particularly angered by
Trimble's suggestion in Washington March 17 that he would be
willing to take the party back into a government with Sinn Fein
without prior disarmament. Smyth told a news conference on Friday
that the statement had prompted his sudden bid for the leadership
and showed that Trimble had strayed too far from the party's
principles.
</P>
<P>
   Although Trimble had not expected Smyth's move, he seized upon
it as a way of trying to unite the notoriously quarrelsome party
behind him and to end internal carping over his moves to reform the
party and make it a force for change. ``I want an end to the
campaign which undermines our positions,'' he said on the eve of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But those hopes were dashed today as opponents also forced
through a motion binding Trimble to a fixed bargaining position on
the highly charged issue of policing. The motion linked any return
to power-sharing government by the Ulster Unionists with the
retention of the name Royal Ulster Constabulary for the province's
force.
</P>
<P>
   This is a potentially huge setback for Trimble, since the
British and Irish governments accepted a principal conclusion of an
international commission last year headed by former Hong Kong Gov.
Chris Patten that the name must be changed if the force is ever to
attract Catholic recruits. The force is presently 90 percent
Protestant, and the British and Irish governments believe it must
gain the support of Ulster's Catholics if any peace agreement is to
stick and home rule to function.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Johnston, a delegate who supported Smyth, said Trimble's
opponents would stage another leadership challenge with a more
formidable candidate if he made any more concessions to Sinn Fein.
``I think he's finished,'' he said, adding that strategists who had
been doing telephone canvassing for Smyth had not anticipated
getting more than 35 percent of the vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Six of the ten other Ulster Unionists in the British Parliament
with Trimble voted against him Saturday, including Jeffrey
Donaldson, 37, a man who has long had his eye on the leadership and
who poses a more serious threat to Trimble than Smyth. Trimble was
also opposed by the 120 members of the Orange Order on the council.
</P>
<P>
   All of them are declared opponents of the April 1998 peace
settlement that was hailed at the time for its promise in resolving
a Catholic and Protestant conflict that has accounted for 3,600
deaths in the past three decades. What progress there has been
since then has repeatedly come to a halt over the issue of
disarming the IRA and paramilitary Protestant groups.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have maintained cease-fires for more than two years,
but the Ulster Unionists argue that a surrender of weaponry is a
necessary condition for any resumption of a power-sharing
government. Sinn Fein says it cannot satisfy that condition, and
the talks are stuck there.
</P>
<P>
   In a daring move last November, Trimble persuaded his party to
enter a government with Sinn Fein, even though there had been no
weapons turnover. One consequence of Saturday's vote is that he
almost certainly will not be able to be so bold in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
