u i BC-MADRID-AIRPORT-520&AMP;AD     03-25 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADRID-AIRPORT-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT AIRPORT IN MADRID, PROTESTERS IN PAJAMAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ The victory of Jose Maria Aznar and his
conservative party in Spain's elections this month could be bad
news for Jesus Coca and other residents of the upscale subdivision
of Ciudad de Santo Domingo, who say life in their neighborhood is
increasingly sullied by the noise of airliners overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen Madrid suburbs with a combined population of 350,000
people filed suit on Feb. 16 against a planned expansion of
Madrid's Barajas Airport, built in 1931, arguing that it presented
health and safety dangers and would inhibit urban planning.
</P>
<P>
   But Aznar, who won re-election on March 12, has so far stood
resolutely against building a new airport, instead favoring
extension of the existing airport, which is just seven and a half
miles northeast of the city center. The Spanish government ranks it
as the fifth-busiest airport in western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Neither continuous media complaints about airport delays nor
colorful protests against the noise have so far persuaded the
conservatives to heed calls for a new airport farther from the city
center and an immediate ban on flights to Barajas between 11 p.m.
and 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Aznar's government has added a third runway and a
new control tower. Plans call for two more runways and an
additional terminal by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Gracia, chairman of the state-run engineering company
that is helping to plan the expansion, defends it as economical,
saying it will cost $3.5 billion, or just a third of the projected
cost of a new airport.
</P>
<P>
   That is small comfort for the bands of protesters who started
monthly demonstrations at the airport last May to highlight what
they say is their plight.
</P>
<P>
   One recent Monday, nearly 40 adults and three children marched
through Barajas at around 10 p.m., dressed in blue and yellow
pajamas and red bathrobes, but not because of the frequent flight
delays that induce some passengers to sleep in the terminals.
</P>
<P>
   The group, called Pajamas in Action, lighted on the nighttime
attire as a way to plead their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``No noise!'' they chanted. ``Enough already!'' And they waved a
large banner that proclaimed: ``Dreams are for everyone. Don't
steal them from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dark-suited airline employees in the nearly deserted
terminals chuckled at the spectacle. But those who favor expansion
seem unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not do anything for them, because what they say is not
true,'' Gracia said. ``I live in the center of Madrid and have more
noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, the European Union will require its members,
including Spain, to permit only flights by the quieter latest
generation of jets by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Coca, who said he had lost sleep and suffered stress since the
airport's third runway began service in late 1998, is skeptical.
Passenger jets flying low over his $600,000 eight-bedroom home on
their landing approach to the airport 11 miles away have changed
his life for the worse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife wants to sell the house,'' said Coca, 42, lamenting
that they would take a loss because of the airplane noise. ``I feel
like I've been stepped on, as if I had no rights.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Coca, computer systems manager for a Spanish insurance company,
and some of his neighbors in Ciudad de Santo Domingo, which has 800
homes, have fought the airport expansion for a year. Lately they
have joined residents from other neighborhoods in the pajama
protests.
</P>
<P>
   The delayed flights and airport noise, regularly reported by the
Spanish news media, were not big issues in the recent election
campaign, although all sides _ the opposition Socialists, and
Aznar's conservatives _ want to reduce the congestion at Barajas
Airport, which was used last year by 27 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Madrid's passenger load is due to increase to 42 million in
2007, although government officials admit that the airport has been
at saturation point for several years. According to the Association
of European Airlines, 48 percent of flights last year were delayed
at least 15 minutes, and sometimes for hours, the second worst
record in Europe after the much smaller Malpensa Airport in Milan,
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish government insisted that only a third of the flights
were delayed in 1999 and it mainly blamed the airlines, Europe's
saturated air traffic control system and poor planning by the
former Socialist government.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's state-run carrier, Iberia, and other airlines put much
of the blame on the state-run airport authority. Aznar's government
apparently has a plan to fix that too: Two national newspapers that
are considered close to the government reported last week that the
administration intends to begin privatizing management of Spain's
43 airports, including Madrid's, as early as this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
