<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-SOONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNER-UP IN TAIWAN NOW HOLDS MOST CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Ask people here who is the most intriguing
political figure to emerge from Taiwan's momentous presidential
election last weekend, and few name Chen Shui-bian, the earnest
opposition leader who ousted the Nationalist Party after half a
century of rule.
</P>
<P>
   Hands down, that distinction goes to James Soong, a former
Nationalist official whose independent candidacy for the presidency
drew 37 percent of the vote, just 2 points behind Chen. With no
party organization to speak of _ and the full weight of the
Nationalist machine against him _ Soong won 4.6 million votes,
carrying Taipei and most of northern Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Soong's remarkable insurgency hastened the downfall of President
Lee Teng-hui, who was forced to resign as chairman of the
Nationalists. With Lee's departure, Soong has emerged as a man with
a multitude of options. He could try to win control of his old
party. He could lead a new party that was formed last week in his
name. Or he could play the field for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very strong voices within the KMT asking me to come
back,'' said Soong, 58, using the initials for the Chinese name of
the Nationalist Party, Kuomintang. ``But I don't think I should
take advantage of the situation for my personal interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts suppress grins at such declarations of
sincerity. They recall that before Soong was a political renegade,
he played the role of hard-nosed party operative _ including a
stint as government information director, during which he clamped
down on the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Soong was a party hack from the moment he joined the KMT
until the moment he was thrown out,'' said Shelley Rigger, an
expert on Taiwanese politics at Davidson College in North Carolina.
``But he has assembled an enormous base of popular support.''
</P>
<P>
   Soong's support has the potential to transform politics on this
island. Historically, Taiwan's top leaders, from Chiang Kai-shek to
President Lee Teng-hui, have ruled with sweeping powers. Although
Lee helped introduce democracy over the past decade, he also built
the Nationalist Party into a juggernaut that was all but impossible
to stop in a national election.
</P>
<P>
   While Chen Shui-bian finally defeated it, he did so only because
Soong split the traditional Nationalist vote. Soong noted that
together, he and the Nationalist candidate, Lien Chan, drew more
than 60 percent. That, he says, makes him a force for Chen to
reckon with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be the supervisor and watchdog,'' Soong
declared in an interview in the dining room of a gracious house
that he said belonged to his mother. ``The KMT was humiliated; they
have no credible person to do it. So I have to play that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Soong made his name as a retail politician. As the provincial
governor of Taiwan, he boasted of visiting nearly every village on
the island. Since the election ended, Soong has kept up a
dawn-to-dusk travel schedule that looks suspiciously like a
campaign. He says he is merely thanking his supporters. But he
notes, ``People are greeting me like a hero, not like someone who
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Soong's maneuvering has other implications for Chen. The
Nationalists still control Taiwan's legislature, with 117 of the
225 seats. If Soong were to throw his weight behind the just-formed
New Taiwanese People's Party, analysts believe he could lure 50 to
70 seats from the Nationalists. That would vault Chen's Democratic
Progressive Party into the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If James Soong joins this new party, it will be very solid and
powerful,'' said Lo Cheng-tien, the deputy secretary general of the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Soong was able to rejoin the Nationalists,
he could bring most of his supporters back under the party's
banner. That would enable the Nationalist Party to retain its
majority in the Legislature, where it could thwart much of Chen's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts predict that despite his popularity,
Soong will not be invited back. ``There is still strong opposition
to him right now, because the election was so bitter,'' said Ma
Ying-jeou, the mayor of Taipei, who is regarded as one of the
Nationalist Party's rising stars.
</P>
<P>
   It did not help that a mob of angry Soong supporters massed in
front of the Nationalist Party headquarters every day last week to
howl for Lee's resignation. Soong denied he was behind the
protests. But the image of his partisans hurling rocks and eggs at
the building may stick.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Soong could not resist a jab at the demoralized
Nationalists. ``I told them if I was behind it, it would not be
such a small demonstration,'' he said with a grin. ``Why should I
have 20 or 100 people? I can mobilize half a million people in
Taipei.''
</P>
</TEXT>
