<SLUG> BC-POPE-NOTEBOOK-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES AND PROTESTS SURROUND POPE'S VISIT TO ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ There with the pope, in a red-tiled Italian
convent's guesthouse overlooking the misty Sea of Galilee as dusk
approached, the worldly realities of nasty Israeli politics seemed
delightfully far away.
</P>
<P>
   But ``chik-chak,'' as the Israelis say for right away, it was
over for Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Inclement weather had delayed the start of the pope's day, so
Barak ended up with but 16 minutes in his compassionate company _
albeit 16 minutes likely to give a leader of any religious
background some faith.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the pope walked slowly down to the Church of
Beatitudes, to pray and read from the Sermon on the Mount, at the
very site where Jesus supposedly blessed the poor in spirit. Barak
had no time for such contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   An open microphone caught him confiding to the pope as he
prepared to hurry away. He apologized for cutting short their time
together. But the sirens were about to sound for the start of the
Jewish Sabbath, a time when all work stops in the religious Jewish
world, and all public evidence of it for those politicians who
depend on religious parties' support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go now, we can't break the laws of Shabbat. We have
to keep our government together,'' Barak told the pope. He rushed
to a waiting helicopter. When it landed in Tiberias, where he was
to spend the night, a security agent sent a relieved message over a
walkie-talkie: ``The parcel has arrived _ three minutes before the
Sabbath!''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to Find the Words
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the long red carpet sat two rows of strictly
Orthodox rabbis, most of them elderly men in black frock coats,
black hats and long white beards. On the other, facing them, were
two rows of Catholic prelates in cassocks, red sashes and red
skullcaps, with crucifixes dangling from their necks.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 minutes they waited together as the pope met privately
with Israel's two chief rabbis. Eyes were averted, throats cleared.
It was probably the largest high-level meeting of Catholic and
ultra-Orthodox Jewish leaders ever, many said.
</P>
<P>
   How to make small talk after 2,000 years?
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Etchegaray tried. ``You know the tailor who made
my very first cassock was Jewish,'' he said. ``And I have Jewish
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope finally emerged and walked down the carpet.
Surprisingly, the rabbis mobbed him. Some, as Etchegaray had done
with them, sought a common bond, however awkwardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him in Polish that I am one of the few Jewish children
who survived the Holocaust from Poland,'' said Rabbi Yosef
Glicksberg, chief rabbi of the city of Givatayim.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't exactly interfaith dialogue, but it was a start.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wistful Words
</P>
<P>
   Two elderly Palestinian woman, wearing traditional embroidered
dresses and head scarves, stood patiently for hours on Wednesday to
catch a glimpse of the pope's visit to their refugee camp. Even
after he left, they remained in the streets despite the chill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that was it,'' said one, Um Moussa. ``We barely
saw him. Maybe he will take tea with Abu Amar and then come back,''
she said, using the nom de guerre of Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, we were happy to receive him,'' said the other,
Um Bader. ``We do not know what will happen as a result of this
visit, but maybe he will help us. He pities the poor Palestinian
people, that is clear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can he help us in returning to our homes?'' said Um
Moussa. ``Mine is a mall now. The big Malha mall, where the movie
theaters are and the fancy shops. That's where I used to live. So
it's hopeless for me, the dream of return. Not even the pope can
take down such a mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Um Bader put her hand on her friend's arm, interrupting. ``We
have seen him passing by. It is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Um Moussa nodded in agreement. ``There is no joy in our hearts,
no delight in our days. So it was an opportunity, a break in the
routine.''
</P>
<P>
   They continued to wait, arm in arm, as night descended.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Angry Words and Curses
</P>
<P>
   Before the pope's visit, much attention was paid to posters in
an ultra-Orthodox Jerusalem neighborhood that called the pope
wicked.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the religious Jewish community, however, insisted
that such neighborhoods were indifferent, not hostile, to the
visit. The posters, they said, were the work of a fringe group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many secular Israeli journalists thought the sentiment
existed and wanted to illustrate it. Channel Two television, on the
night of the pope's arrival, showed chilling footage of a midnight
rite in a cemetery in the northern town of Sfad, a home to
Kabbalist Jewish mysticism.
</P>
<P>
   In the eerie ceremony, a man identified as a Kabbalist placed a
mortal curse on the pope as others blew a ram's horn. He called the
pope a ``hater of Jews'' and put him in the company of Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and Hafez Assad, the Syrian
president, who were also cursed.
</P>
<P>
   The scene alarmed Israelis, since it recalled curses on Yitzhak
Rabin, the former prime minister who was assassinated by an
extremist Jew in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the police detained the man, Meir Baranes. Concerned
spokesmen for the religious community sent urgent messages to the
foreign media: The man is considered ``a mentally unbalanced
individual'' and unrepresentative of the Orthodox community, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the police placed a researcher for the television
program under house arrest. He was suspected of staging the
ceremony, and paying the participants.
</P>
<P>
   And a Chorus of Critics
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit did not magically erase millennia-old religious
tensions in the Holy Land. But it did create some strange
bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   An extremist right-wing Jewish group called Kach, Christian
biblical scholars such as the Rev. Jerome Murphy O'Connor, and
environmentalists all protested what the Israelis did to the Mount
of Beatitudes in preparation for the pope's huge outdoor Mass on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They paved paradise _ or at least relatively virgin terrain _
and put up a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   After much prodding and the threat of lawsuits, Israel promised
to return the site to its unspoiled condition. All it would take,
officials said, was some planting and maybe a couple of
springtimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did we know?'' Moshe Fogel, the government's spokesman,
said. ``This is the first time the state of Israel ever put on a
Mass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
