<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-IRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGHDAD CALLS ATTACK RETALIATION BY TEHRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By HADANI DITMARS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ Even in a city that has weathered countless
barrages of missiles and bombs in recent years, most aimed by
American or British forces, the mortar attack in a residential
neighborhood of Baghdad last week that killed four people and
wounded 38 was unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The strike on Tuesday appeared to be carried out in retaliation
for recent mortar attacks in Tehran that were attributed to an
Iranian opposition group, the Mujahedeen Khalq, many of whose
guerrilla camps are just a few hours from Baghdad, along the border
with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Although Iran has struck at the group's bases outside Baghdad in
the past, the attack last week was the first on a civilian area of
the capital in many years.
</P>
<P>
   Since a cease-fire in 1988 ended a brutal eight-year war between
Iran and Iraq, relations between the two have remained tense and
each country harbors dissident groups fighting to topple the
other's government.
</P>
<P>
   As in Iran, where civilians in Tehran have twice been hit in the
past three months in mortar attacks claimed by the Mujahedeen
Khalq, ordinary people last week took the brunt of the tit-for-tat
violence that still plagues the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The official Iraqi news agency said the government held Iran
responsible for the mortar attack and reserved ``the right to
retaliate.'' Iraq said it had shot down a pilotless Iranian
reconnaissance plane over the southern part of the country, the
second in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, too, has said it holds Iraq responsible for attacks by the
Mujahedeen Khalq, which claimed responsibility for a mortar strike
on March 13 on a residential complex in Tehran that injured four
people. The group has also been blamed by Iran for a similar attack
in residential Tehran near the president's office in early
February.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the United States, which lifted some sanctions
against Iran this month, made public a satellite photograph of what
it said was a sprawling complex intended as a base for the
Mujahedeen Khalq 40 miles outside Baghdad. The photo was
declassified, it said, to prove that Iraq was supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   At Kindi Hospital in Baghdad, the details of who carried out the
attack last week and why were of little interest to the victims'
being treated there, or to their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tuesday's bombs fell, my children thought it was the
Americans,'' said the hospital director, Dr. Sarmad al-Kassar. ``I
tried to explain, but they have been so traumatized that they now
think every explosion is a bomb from America.''
</P>
<P>
   Kassar, who was trained in Glasgow, said he was concerned about
his children's psychological health, as much as anything. ``If I
have to leave for the hospital at night, they start screaming and
worry that the Americans are attacking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the recovery ward, the wounded residents of the apartment
building, many of whom are Palestinian immigrants, took the attack
as another in a series of life's hardships.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, who said she was 30, lay serenely in a hospital bed,
the bone in her left leg shattered by the shelling. Her 9-year-old
daughter, Sarah, lay in a bed next to hers, with a broken arm.
</P>
<P>
   The woman said she was born in a Palestinian refugee camp in
Jordan, but moved to Iraq with her husband, a construction worker,
in 1990, when Iraq had one of the region's most developed
economies. Their plans for a better life were thwarted, however,
with the Persian Gulf War and the decade of American and U.N.
sanctions, clamped on Iraq that year for its invasion of its
southern neighbor, Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she said, she thought the blast that injured her on
Tuesday was caused by a gas heater. After a second missile hit,
however, when she saw friends and family lying wounded on the
ground, she thought it must be an American attack. When taken to
the hospital, she was told it was Iranian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iranian, American,'' she shrugged, ``What can we do?''
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite bed, Afifa Muhammad, 60, who was also wounded in
the shelling, was recovering from surgery on a shattered fibula.
Seven of her relatives were also wounded. The ones who were not
hovered near the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister explained that Muhammad was born in Haifa in 1940 and
came to Baghdad in 1948. A few seconds later, Muhammad herself,
still groggy from the surgery, interrupted. ``But this is my
home,'' she said. ``Iraq is my country now.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added that her sincere hope was that there would be
``peace in Iraq, peace in Palestine and in the whole region,'' and
emphasized her point with a sweeping gesture that, even in her
weakened state, seemed intended to encompass the entire room and
even the world beyond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
