<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-1STL     03-25 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1210(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS PAKISTAN TO TREAD LIGHTLY IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Inserts new graf beginning ``Administration officials ...''
Deletes graf that began ``Pressed on ...'' Inserts 2 new grafs
beginning ``There were, however.'' Deletes 2 grafs that began
``Instead of 45 ...'') 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ In an effort to defuse tensions in a
region that he has described as the most volatile in the world,
President Clinton on Saturday asked the military leader of Pakistan
to show restraint in Kashmir, where Pakistan and India most
recently battled last summer, and to reopen a dialogue with his
Indian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But after more than an hour and a half with Gen. Pervaiz
Musharraf, Clinton received no assurances, said a senior
administration official who participated in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We broke no new ground on Kashmir,'' the official said after
the session. ``We heard no new assurances from the general.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had expected little if any immediate
progress from the talks with Musharraf, and the White House
official made clear that none was made beyond the mere dialogue
itself. Pressed on terrorism, the spread of nuclear weapons and
when he would return Pakistan to democracy at the national level,
the general offered nothing new, the official indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and India, the world's two newest nuclear powers,
regularly skirmish in Kashmir, which has been the main issue
between overwhelmingly Muslim Pakistan and Hindu India since the
two nations were created from the British Raj in 1947, and the
status of the Himalayan territory was left perilously unresolved.
The Clinton administration believes that incursions by
Pakistani-backed militants into Indian-held Kashmir have the
potential to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, battles in the mountainous Kargil region of Kashmir
were regarded as the first direct combat between two nuclear powers
_ fighting that was halted after Clinton persuaded Pakistan's then
civilian prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, to back down. Three months
later, Sharif was ousted by Musharraf.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who decided to come to Pakistan after intense
disagreement within the administration, spent barely six hours in
this country, arriving from an extensive five-day tour of India
under some of the most elaborate security precautions ever devised
for his travels.
</P>
<P>
   After his apparently grim meeting with Musharraf, Clinton made a
direct appeal to the Pakistani people in a live television
broadcast in which he addressed them as friends of the United
States. Instead of looking toward a future of economic collapse and
potential war, the people should choose the path of economic
security and peace, the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the right vision rooted in tomorrow's promise, not in
yesterday's pain, with a new dialogue, not destruction, Pakistan
can fulfill its destiny as a beacon of democracy in the Muslim
world,'' Clinton said. If Pakistanis choose this path, he promised,
``The United States will walk with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration official said the president had stressed to
Musharraf that there could be no military solution in Kashmir by
incursions across the Line of Control, as the border between
Pakistani- and Indian-held territory is known.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had asked specifically for ``restraint, respect for the
Line of Control, rejection of violence and return to dialogue,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   There was not much movement on other issues, either.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked the general to take action against terrorist
groups operating in Pakistan and to help pressure the Taliban
government in Afghanistan to bring to justice Osama bin Laden, the
terrorist who the United States believes is responsible for the
bombings of two U.S. embassies in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The general, as he has in the past, said he would work with the
Taliban leadership on the Osama bin Laden case, the official said.
But so far, the general has failed to fulfill his pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters as Clinton was leaving Islamabad,
Musharraf said he and the American president got along very well.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, no photographs of the two leaders together,
and the general _ as planned _ held a news conference alone.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he had given Clinton assurances that
Pakistani-backed infiltration into Indian-held Kashmir would cease,
the general replied: ``There were no assurances, because there was
no question. We are not involved in sending any kind of people
across the Line of Control.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Taliban, the general said he assured Clinton ``that I
would like to engage the Taliban in Afghanistan and take up the
issue of any sanctuaries for any terrorists or training that might
be going on in that country.''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of nonproliferation, the general pledged that
Pakistan would not be a source for the export of nuclear
technology, the administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   As the official ticked off the list of items on the president's
agenda with the general, it was clear there was a recitation of
long-held views on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said the official: ``We've made an effort to make our
position clear at the highest level. We didn't expect to come in an
hour and persuade the leadership of the wisdom of our position.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one point of the hotly debated stop in Pakistan, White
House officials said, was to try to keep the lines of communication
open. Should the situation deteriorate sharply in Kashmir _ as the
administration fears _ Clinton is now in a better position to deal
directly with Musharraf, they maintain.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the administration will be able to argue that Clinton
tried his best, by coming here, to avert a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also brought up the trial of the former prime minister,
Sharif, who is accused of hijacking, treason and attempted murder.
If convicted, Sharif could face the death penalty, and Clinton on
Saturday asked the general not to execute him. In reply, the
general explained that he was not a vindictive man but that the
matter was up to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   As he had in New Delhi, India, Clinton made clear to the general
that the United States would not mediate in the Kashmir crisis, the
White House official said. This was also a message that Musharraf
did not want to hear: Unlike the Indians, the Pakistani leader
would like the Kashmir dispute to be settled by international
mediation.
</P>
<P>
   The signals from Musharraf in the days before Clinton's arrival
were not promising. The Pakistani leader missed an opportunity to
send a positive message on his national day on Thursday when he
made a major speech.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of announcing that local elections would be held this
year, as he had indicated earlier, the general pushed the date back
to next year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the general has consistently talked in recent weeks about
the Islamic militants in Kashmir, who the administration says are
backed by the Pakistani regime, as freedom fighters committed to a
jihad, or holy war. The administration regards several of these
groups as terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan asserts that Kashmir, with a large Muslim majority,
should have the right to vote on whether to join India or Pakistan.
Secular India claims Kashmir as one of its states.
</P>
<P>
   The emotions behind the issue were vividly on display in some of
the banners along the route taken by Clinton's motorcade. ``You
were fair in Kosovo,'' said one, referring to NATO's bombing
campaign to deter Serbian repression against Kosovo's largely
Muslim Albanian majority. ``Why not in Kashmir?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is politically untenable for a Pakistani leader to appear as
though he is bending to an American diktat. Sharif's decision to
pull back from the Indian side of the Line of Control last summer
is thought to have been one factor behind his ouster in October by
Musharraf.
</P>
<P>
   And behind the general stands another, perhaps even tougher,
commander, Gen. Mohammad Aziz, the chief of general staff of the
Pakistani army, who Clinton administration officials assert was the
brains behind the fighting in Kargil last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived from Bombay, India, under elaborate security
precautions. At the Bombay airport, he walked to the door of a
military C-17 aircraft, shook hands with dignitaries as though he
were going to board that aircraft, and then slipped around the
front of the plane to board an unmarked, smaller white jet that was
parked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   This aircraft, an Air Force version of a Gulfstream, known as a
C-20, flew Clinton, his national security adviser, Sandy Berger,
the secretary of state, Madeleine Albright, and several other
advisers to Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   From the Islamabad airport, Clinton drove in a motorcade through
deserted streets to the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's unmarked plane was accompanied by another Air Force
Gulfstream, which was painted with the familiar blue and white of
Air Force 1 and marked ``United States of America.'' This was the
decoy plane with Secret Service agents on board and it arrived
first, followed soon after by the president's plane. Many of
Clinton's staff and reporters covering his trip were flown in on a
military C-17 aircraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1507EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
