<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHRISTIAN-HUNTERS-ART     03-25 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-HUNTERS-ART-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EVANGELICAL GROUP FOR HUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ga.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOELTON, Tenn. _ It was taking a while for Ralph Wilkerson to
get around to eating all the squirrel meat that had been in his
freezer since he and his son brought it home from their hunting
jaunts last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot about two dozen squirrels in the woods behind our
house back in August and September,'' said Wilkerson, 62, a
projects manager at Odom's Tennessee Pride Sausage.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday night, Wilkerson and his 24-year-old son, Jason,
were able to use the last of their bounty to help support an
organization for men just like the Wilkersons, men with a deep
Christian faith who also enjoy hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilkersons brought two casserole dishes full of squirrel
dumplings to Thursday night's fund-raising dinner in the gymnasium
of the Joelton First Baptist Church. The buffet meal, called a Wild
Game Tasting, benefited the local chapter of the Christian
Sportsmen's Fellowship, an evangelistic organization based in
Atlanta that reaches out to Christian hunters.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 men, women and children in this small town about
30 miles north of Nashville came to the gathering, which featured
such concoctions as elk chili, doves in brown gravy, deer sausage
and barbecued black bear.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Jordan, the president of the fellowship, said the
organization was trying to reach men who go hunting and fishing on
Sunday morning instead of going to church. The group uses hunting
and fishing, Jordan said, to ``connect with men through activities
they like to pursue as hobbies.''
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1994, the fellowship, with the motto ``On Target to
Catch Men for Christ,'' has nearly 300 local affiliates in the
United States, Jordan said. It publishes a magazine called ``The
Christian Sportsman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not put on hunting and fishing events,'' Jordan said.
``We put on events, such as the wild-game banquets, that have
hunting and fishing themes, where men can share their passions for
hunting and fishing with each other and with their families. But
the real point of all we do is to build relationships and to
present the gospel of Jesus Christ. It's a way of building a bridge
with outdoorsmen. We use hunting and fishing illustrations to
convey the love of God in terms many men can relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   At most of the fellowship-sponsored events there are keynote
speakers. At Thursday night's dinner, Steve Chapman, author of ``A
Look at Life From a Deer Stand,'' spoke and sang about balancing
the time a man spends fishing and hunting with the time he spends
with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman tours the country with his wife, speaking and singing to
groups about Christianity and hunting and honoring family. ``Men
mentoring men was a lost art in this country for many years,'' he
said. ``So I'm just reminding them of things they already know.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he spoke at a wild-game dinner in Pennsylvania a few
weeks ago with 1,000 pounds of wild game and 1,600 people attending
over two nights. ``I've been noticing,'' he said, ``that churches
are using game dinners as outreach tools to men more and more in
the past four or five years. It started in the South, but now it is
all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall Balmer, a professor of American Religion at Barnard
College, said the Christian Sportsmen's Fellowship was part of the
``pattern of what is called muscular Christianity, various
initiatives that have been launched to attempt to make Christianity
more palatable to men.''
</P>
<P>
   Balmer said the group was similar to better-known organizations
like Promise Keepers or the Fellowship of Christian Athletes.
``Usually these organizations draw on two themes,'' he said. ``One
is the militaristic rhetoric of `We're engaged in a battle against
dark forces.' Another theme is athleticism as an evangelistic
strategy. The rhetoric is about running the race, and often sports
figures are used to endorse their activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the group emphasizes both of those themes. In his talk
at the Wild Game Tasting, Chapman said, ``There is a moral battle
that needs to be fought and won through Christ. Too many young men
in our culture do not know that.'' And in its magazine and other
official literature, Steve Bartkowski, a former quarterback for the
Atlanta Falcons, is showcased as the fellowship's national
spokesman.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the fellowship purports not to have a political agenda,
every year the group sponsors a Sportsmen's Prayer Breakfast at the
National Rifle Association's annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart and soul of the fellowship is expressed at events
such as Thursday night's dinner. The evening ended with an auction
of hunting-related paraphernalia, including one of the most popular
items that the group offers: the Camouflaged Bible. The New
International Version is a pocket-size edition of the New
Testament, along with Psalms and Proverbs, bound in a durable
green, tan, black and brown camouflage-design cover.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time Michael Boble, 29, had attended one of
the group's events. ``I enjoyed the fellowship with the other men
here,'' he said. ``In some other hunting organizations you'll hear
foul language and there will be lots of drinking, but this was much
better, more Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Cruise, 27, a fellowship member, said, ``People may see
this as redneck or Bubba. But you've got very educated people who
are hunters. I'm working on my doctorate in ministry. I hunt for
the solitude of it, more than I hunt for the deer.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those who think that eating squirrel and bear is exotic,
Cruise answered: ``To me it's no stranger than eating raw fish. I
like my food cooked. You're not ever going to see me at a sushi
bar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
