u s BC-TEN-RODDICK-NYT &LR;      03-25 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-RODDICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE A GANGLY KID, RODDICK IS A MUSCULAR PROSPECT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb.)  (jt) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla., _ As a Lilliputian youth tennis player, Andy
Roddick learned how to win matches by scrappiness and guile. Then
he began to grow _ a foot in two and a half years, to 6 feet 2
inches. Soon, with the help of a weight-lifting program, he was
blasting serves and forehands past opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he was a complete player, able to blend power with
textbook resilience and craftiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's been kind of a blessing that I was small my whole
life until recently,'' said Roddick, now 17 and on the threshold of
a pro career. ``I was a scrapper, pusher, everything. I'd do
anything to win a match. You learn that if your game is not on,
you've still got to find ways to pull out matches.''
</P>
<P>
   His rapid emergence in the tennis world has almost mirrored his
growth in stature. Ranked 27th nationally in the 16-and-under group
in 1997, he became No. 1 in '98. He felt ``gangly'' the next year
during his main growth spurt, but since then he has more than made
up for it. He now stands as the world's top-ranked junior _ the
first American to achieve that lofty status since Brian Dunn in '92
_ after a mercurial rise from No. 17 since December.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fighter and he has a very big heart,'' said the
Frenchman Tarik Benhabiles, his coach since August. ``The tougher
it is out there, the more he likes it. He's not afraid to stay out
there three or four hours if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 ranking earned Roddick a wild-card berth in the main
draw of the prestigious two-week Ericsson Open _ formerly the
Lipton Championships _ and he came up with his first professional
victory by defeating Fernando Vicente, 6-4, 6-0, on Friday, earning
a match against Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't his professional debut. That came in late February at
the Citrix Championships in Delray Beach, Fla., where he lost to
Italy's Laurence Tieleman, 7-6 (8-6), 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot,'' Roddick said after a practice at the
Ericsson tournament site. ``When you've got chances, you have to
take them. They're just not going to roll over and die for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Between these two tastes of the professional life, Roddick, a
native of Omaha, Neb., who lives in Boca Raton, Fla., won his last
four juniors tournaments _ the Eddie Herr International, RADO
Orange Bowl International, Australian Open Juniors and Banana Bowl
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Banana Bowl, a clay-court event in Sao Paulo, Brazil, that
attracted the world's top juniors, allowed Roddick to conquer an
unfamiliar surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``He accepted a situation that went against his nature,''
Benhabiles said. ``The balls were heavy and there were many bad
bounces because of the courts, but he adjusted. He showed that
mentally he is very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``With him, it's not like there is only one solution. He can
play different styles and on different surfaces. That's going to
make him a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the next breath, Benhabiles tempers his remarks by
calling the pro circuit a ``jungle, full of good players.'' He's
clearly hoping to make Roddick understand how much quality talent
he will face, without affecting his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Buchholz, tournament chairman of the Ericsson Open and the
only other American besides Roddick to win the Australian Open
Juniors in more than 40 years, saw Roddick lose his composure, then
regain it, in a three-set victory over Germany's Max Abel in the
Orange Bowl International.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at juniors, one of the things you ask yourself
is, `Does he have the guts?''' Buchholz said. ``You can have all
the shots, but if you don't have the mental capacity, you're just
another top junior who never made it on the pro tour. This kid has
the shots and the mental ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Roddick, who has grown an inch since December, is not as
belligerent on the court as, say, Jimmy Connors or John McEnroe.
But no one would call him shy about challenging calls that he feels
are questionable, a stark contrast to his demeanor off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will see me on the court and say, `I can't believe that
was you,''' he said. ``I just tell them: `On the court you have to
go for it. You've got to be mentally tough every second you're out
there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Roddick began going with his parents to the tennis courts at age
4 and started taking private lessons at 6. At 8, according to his
mother, Blanche Roddick, he made an unusual tournament debut: after
pleading with her for a year to play, he teamed with a 70-year-old
woman to finish second in doubles in their category at a country
club event in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all he's done, he still has fond memories of doing
that,'' his mother said, chuckling softly. But mostly young Roddick
drew inspiration from his brother John, who is six years older and
who was then on his way toward becoming a standout at the
University of Georgia. Only last year, Andy beat his brother, who
is now an assistant coach at Florida State University, for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to just follow John to the tennis courts,'' said Jerry
Roddick, their father. ``It was easy for him to pick up a racket
and just start playing.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Andy, who is several months from graduating from the
Boca Raton Preparatory School, often practices on the court in his
parents' back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always played tennis because I enjoy it,'' Roddick said.
``It used to be more of a fun thing with me. But then I really
started to improve. I decided to go for it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
