<HEADLINE>
METS AND CUBS ARE GRATEFUL MCGWIRE SAID NO TO TOKYO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Fresh off their planes Saturday, the Mets and the Cubs
showed strong support for their long haul across the Pacific to
open their regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Players and officials from both teams were asked to respond to
recent remarks by Mark McGwire that the historic trip was based on
``greed'' by baseball. McGwire, who holds the record for most home
runs in a season, 70 in 1998, vetoed the Cardinals' participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Mark McGwire, and I also want to
thank him for saying no because I got to go,'' said Mark Grace, the
first baseman for the Cubs, the team that replaced the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The teams will work out Sunday, play exhibitions against the
Seibu Lions and Yomiuri Giants, powerful Tokyo-area teams, Monday
and Tuesday, and then play each other Wednesday and Thursday. They
expressed enthusiasm, well aware of McGwire's strong comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get that stuff about greed,'' said Bobby Valentine,
the Mets' manager. ``That's a very limited thought. This is much
bigger than that.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had said marketing and merchandising and payments from
Japanese sponsors had spurred the trip. Commissioner Bud Selig
disagreed, saying: ``If this were done for the money, it wouldn't
be worth it. When you see the passion and excitement for baseball
over here, you realize our responsibility goes beyond the United
States and Canada. I believe in social responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig said this competition between the American and Japanese
teams, before the start of their seasons, was a step toward a World
Cup-style tournament. He noted that ``nearly one fourth of all
major-league players come from outside the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had said international competition did not ``turn my
crank,'' but the players at a press conference Saturday seemed
excited. Some other players resent the trip. Rickey Henderson, whom
the Mets may be trying to trade, spoke out against the trip weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The players speaking at the upscale New Otani Hotel were clearly
going along with the program, including Mike Piazza, John Franco,
Robin Ventura and Mike Hampton of the Mets and Grace, Sosa and Jon
Lieber of the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my third time here, and I am glad to be back,'' said
Sammy Sosa, who chased McGwire in epic home-run duels the past two
seasons. ``The people in Japan have a lot of class. I'm glad to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I came over here in 1992 and had a great time,'' Grace said.
``I hit against Hideki Nomo when he pitched for Kintetsu, and I
realize a lot of Japanese and Korean players are talented enough to
play in the majors.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace, who has volunteered to visit an American military base
Sunday, interrupted his remarks to introduce a familiar face
sitting in the front row of the press conference _ Ernie Banks,
long known as Mister Cub, who had flown here to sing ``Take Me Out
to the Ball Game'' during Wednesday's seventh-inning stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started out, you'd think trips to Philadelphia and
Pittsburgh were different,'' Banks said in a private conversation.
``This is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks was seeking out Japanese journalists to get a translation
of his famous slogan ``Let's play two,'' which he had uttered every
day, except when the Cubs were indeed playing a doubleheader, at
which point he lobbied for three games.
</P>
<P>
   Several Japanese-speaking journalists said Mister Cub could be
comfortable saying, ``Ni shiai, yarou'' _ or, very loosely, ``Two
games, let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   On this evening in Tokyo, the Mets and Cubs seemed in agreement.
Mark McGwire was not here, and they were. There are two exhibitions
against Japanese teams looking to prove something. And there are
two National League games that will count, forever. Mister Cub
could have represented this group if he had said, ``Let's play
four.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
