<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GAYS-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      03-25 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY ON GAYS RINGS TRUE TO MANY IN MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)  (jw) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ Although senior Pentagon officials in
Washington expressed surprise at an inspector general's survey that
found widespread harassment of gays in the armed forces, halfway
across the country the results were viewed Saturday as nothing new
by some current and former servicemen living near this city's many
military installations.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of the 71,570 military personnel surveyed in the
Pentagon's report, which was released on Friday, said they had
heard derogatory remarks made about gays and 37 percent said they
had witnessed or experienced an incident of harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it `barracks justice,''' said Dennis Dunn, 40, who
retired as a staff sergeant from the Army last fall after 19 years
of service. ``If people found out somebody was gay, they were gone.
If they weren't kicked out for just being gay, then some other
reason would be found to get rid of them. Either way, they were
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Dunn said, the penalty for being identified as
homosexual took an uglier turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone was gay and got left in the unit for a while, there
would be a `blanket party,' '' he said, ``where they'd grab the guy
during the middle of the night, wrap him in a blanket, and pound on
him with socks stuffed with bars of soap.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said there were rules associated with such attacks,
established by platoon or unit leaders who organized them, such as
no hitting in the head, face, or groin. ``But that was mostly so
there wouldn't be any evidence that could be reported,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he joined the service in 1980 until he retired
with a medical discharge, Dunn said, he heard of dozens of such
`blanket parties,' although he would not say whether he had
participated in them.
</P>
<P>
   And, Dunn said, little changed after the Clinton administration
started its ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all just a show for the media,'' he said of the
policy. ``It didn't change anything. It just made the unit
commanders more cautious about how they kicked people out.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of those interviewed on Friday about the Pentagon
report said they thought that attitudes had changed over the years,
not so much because of the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, but
because of a broader acceptance of gays in society.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton just opened up the closet door and let all
the skeletons out,'' said Carlos B. Palos III, 44, who served in
the Army from 1975 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed while having dinner with his son, Carlos Jr., who
recently enlisted in the Air Force, Palos said that during his
military career, homosexuality was rarely discussed but was
punished whenever discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two guys caught in my unit in Germany in 1977 that were
court-martialed and dishonorably discharged, but it was all kept
pretty quiet. These days, they put it on the front page of the
newspaper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palos' 19-year old son said that during his brief four months at
an air base near Del Rio, Texas, he had seen no signs of
discrimination. ``Sure, you know some people are probably gay, but
that's their business as long as they leave you alone. The younger
guys just don't care that much about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's military it's just not that big of a deal. People
are just more used to the idea of gays in the service,'' said Allen
Decker, 24, an information specialist who served on six different
posts before arriving at the air station here.
</P>
<P>
   But, still, Decker said, if someone were openly gay, ``The
commanding officer will always just get rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   A Navy specialist on leave from a 7th Fleet assignment in Japan,
who spoke on the condition of not being identified, said that while
his superiors would tolerate no discrimination or harassment by
fellow servicemen, anyone who was openly gay disappeared from the
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the first line of defense, the tip of the spear, and
discipline out there is pretty tight,'' said the 24-year-old Navy
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   To Dunn, the inspector general's report offered only
confirmation of what most people in the service, he says, already
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to do these things to placate the media and the
higher-ups, the politicians,'' he said, ''But nothing will change.
It's the Army. Nothing ever changes the Army.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
