<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GAMBLE-ADDICTS0326-CO     03-25 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLE-ADDICTS0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New game plan for gambling addicts
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHREVEPORT, La. _ When it comes to gambling, most people can
walk away at any time. Win or lose, it's just another form of
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But there are those who can't heed the call to fold 'em up. They
are hooked, like an alcoholic or a drug addict.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone at Shreveport's Center of Recovery, known as CORE,
gambling is a pathological addiction that requires acute treatment.
Before coming here for a 30-day stay, one north Louisiana man was
so distraught by his compulsion to go to casinos that he played
Russian roulette with a loaded gun. A Franklin, La., man had tried
one last time to pretend to his wife that he'd lost his money in a
robbery. An Abbeville, La., mother of three had cashed $1,500 in
bad checks and lost it in a video poker machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come here in all states of disarray,'' said Reece
Middleton, executive director of CORE.
</P>
<P>
   CORE, which opened last summer, is one of the few inpatient
facilities in the nation specifically designed to treat gambling
addiction. And it is the only one that is state funded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an amazing step _ the Louisiana folks have recognized
that there is real need for a broad spectrum of services for
gambling addicts,'' said Keith Whyte, executive director of the
National Council on Problem Gambling. ``Most states that have
legalized gambling only fund a help line.''
</P>
<P>
   There are between 57,000 and 100,000 so-called pathological
gamblers in Louisiana, according to a study by the University of
New Orleans. That's about 2 percent to 3 percent of the population,
higher than the national average of 1 percent to 2 percent. Among
Southern states that have conducted similar studies, Louisiana and
Mississippi, which both have riverboat casinos, have higher rates
of gambling addicts than Georgia or Texas, which have no casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state made a decision to have a lottery and other forms
of gambling, and I think it's to the state's credit that the
legislature recognized there would be an increase of people with a
problem,'' said Alton Hadley, who heads the state's Office for
Addictive Disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana spends $1.5 million annually in prevention and
treatment of problem gambling. It funds a 24-hour hotline and
outpatient treatment programs in 10 regions around the state.
Almost a third of that goes to CORE, which has 18 beds that are
free for Louisiana residents. The money for the center comes from
taxes on riverboats, the lottery and video poker machines. The
state receives $580 million annually in taxes from gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling foe C.B. Forgotston objects to public dollars being
spent to treat a problem introduced by the state when gambling was
legalized a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem that did not exist, and now it's a burden on
taxpayers,'' he said. ``When people decide to gamble, they should
be responsible for the damage they do. Now, the taxpayer _ me _ is
asked to pick up the pieces. They should require the casinos to pay
for this, over and above the taxes they pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the funding comes at a time of budget cuts within the
Department of Health and Hospitals, the umbrella agency for the
Office for Addictive Disorders. Hadley's budget was cut by $1
million, forcing him to cancel plans for a new methadone clinic for
heroin addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Whyte said gambling addiction is undertreated nationwide and
exists even in the three states that have no form of legalized
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   This center is cheaper than not treating these people,'' he
said. ``It's cheaper than having them bottom out, go on welfare or
become homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   The residents of CORE see the program, which uses the 12-step
method developed by Gamblers Anonymous, as a lifesaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think you should be able to stop on your own,'' said a
53-year-old woman from Breaux Bridge, La., who requested anonymity.
She started gambling in casinos in 1994 and would lose hundreds or
even thousands in a night. She would hide the mounting debt from
her husband, stalking the mailman so she could get the credit card
bills. ``People say, 'Why don't you just stop?' I hate that.
Wouldn't I stop if I could? This is a godsend. It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
