<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DORISMOND-FUNERAL-ART     03-25 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORISMOND-FUNERAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY MOURNERS CLASH WITH POLICE AT SLAIN MAN'S FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: This is a late add to the front page.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a day of solemnity and outrage that degenerated
into violence, Patrick Dorismond, the unarmed son of Haitian
immigrants who was shot to death in a confrontation with the police
last week, was carried across Brooklyn, eulogized as a martyr and
laid to rest Saturday by 15,000 anguished mourners and angry
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after the funeral, there were brief clashes between
protesters and police. At least four officers were injured and two
people were arrested. Witnesses described scenes of tense
confrontation and tumult: bottles smashing on the street, American
flags burned and a rain of curses falling on police and an absent
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   As a hearse carrying the body of the slain 26-year-old security
guard led a procession of cars and a predominantly Haitian crowd of
3,000 marchers on a three-mile procession from a funeral home in
Marine Park to a church in Flatbush, the sobs of grief mingled with
screams of hostility against the police and shrieked demands for
justice and the resignation of Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   But the noisy procession up Flatbush Avenue was nonviolent until
it neared Holy Cross Church on Church Avenue, where the funeral was
to be held, shortly before noon. Thousands more people stood on
sidewalks, penned behind metal police barricades. Then, it
appeared, the pent-up feelings of the day, and of more than a week
of anger over the shooting and the characterization of the victim
by the mayor, came surging out.
</P>
<P>
   Police barricades were shoved down all along the block. At least
two officers fell under the metal stanchions and were injured, one
with a broken nose, the other with a broken leg. The crowds surged
into the avenue. A thin line of police officers, clearly panicked,
retreated toward the church, where reinforcements were posted on a
side street, Veronica Place.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd took over the avenue outside the church and a tense
standoff with the police began, the hearse drew up and pallbearers
carried the polished wooden coffin of Dorismond inside. For the
next hour, as anger seethed outside, the interior of the church was
an island of grief as Monsignor Rollin J. Darbouze, the pastor,
eulogized the slain man.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Patrick Dorismond were to address young people today,'' he
declared, ``he would say, `Because you are young and because you
are black, avoid being on street corners too long because you could
be confused for drug dealers and be killed. Spare your own life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, the son of one of Haiti's best known singers, Andre
Dorismond, was shot to death outside a bar on the West Side of
Manhattan on March 16 in a struggle with an undercover police
officer. He was the fourth unarmed black man to be killed by police
in the last 13 months _ a series of deaths that has raised
questions about the aggressiveness of the police.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor came under fire from critics for releasing information
about Dorismond's police record, including sealed juvenile records,
for not visiting or even expressing regrets to Dorismond's family
and for defending the police actions in the case, as he had in
previous shootings.
</P>
<P>
   He was not at the funeral. ``In situations where the person
involved may have been involved in a crime, the mayor does not
attend the funeral,'' the mayor's spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel, said
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Among those at the funeral were a number of Democratic state
legislators, City Council members and other politicians, including
the City Comptroller Alan Hevesi. All of them harshly critical of
the mayor, who was not present. Others who attended were relatives
of Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant sodomized by police officers
in a Brooklyn police station in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Standing above a coffin draped in Haitian and American flags,
Darbouze said: ``Let us pray that Patrick's death and the suffering
of his family will not be in vain. May they find solace and
consolation and may they see steps taken so that Patrick will be a
lesson for all of us to work together for a better quality of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the hourlong funeral, the crowd outside was hostile
but relatively peaceful, confining its anger to shouts of derision
against the mayor and police, who had mustered reinforcements and
now numbered about 300 officers in helmets and other riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   But as the funeral ended and the hearse and its procession
pulled away, scuffling broke out between protesters and police.
People on fire escapes and near windows along Church Avenue waved
Haitian and Jamaican flags, and some of them began hurling bottles
down on the street, some of them missing officers by inches.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd in front of the church screamed ``No way! No way!''
Several American flags were burned.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the crowds surged again, more bottles were thrown and
there were reports of more police officers down and injured.
</P>
<P>
   The day's events had begun at midmorning at the Andrew
Torregrossa and Sons Funeral Home in Marine Park, where a wake for
Dorismond had been held Friday night. Dorismond's mother, Marie,
wept uncontrollably as she was escorted to a limousine and her
son's coffin, draped in flags, was brought out to a hearse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
