<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-DEBTS-975(2T     03-25 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DEBTS-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE FAULTED IN FORGIVING HUGE DEBTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Calif.)   (Exclusive)  
(lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration improperly forgave
hundreds of millions of dollars of debts owed to the government by
health-care providers for Medicare overpayments and allowed them to
continue billing Medicare for some of the questionable expenses,
federal investigators have found.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, from the General Accounting Office, said
Medicare officials had ignored their own rules and procedures in
negotiating secret deals to settle the debts _ the three largest
Medicare overpayment cases of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the deals involved health-care organizations in New York,
and the other was with the county health department in Los Angeles.
Medicare said it had overpaid the providers by $332 million. It
settled the cases for a total of $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they had agreed to the
settlements as a way to help hospitals that serve large numbers of
poor people. In each case, the government and the health-care
provider agreed that the settlement would be kept secret. The
government said it wanted to avoid setting precedents that could be
invoked by Medicare providers in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements will be the subject of a hearing on Tuesday
before the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations, headed
by Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, an investigative arm of Congress,
said the New York City Health and Hospitals Corp. received the
largest financial benefits in the deals. The corporation runs
public hospitals and clinics that treat 1.5 million New Yorkers a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their size and significance, investigators said, the
settlements were not reviewed or approved by any lawyer in the
federal government. Medicare rules require such reviews, the
accounting office said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report describing the deals, the General Accounting Office
said Medicare officials ``knew that the settlements were not in the
best interest of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials accepted payments of $25 million of the $155
million owed by the Health and Hospitals Corp.; $67 million of the
$98 million owed by the Visiting Nurse Service of New York, and $28
million of the $79.4 million owed by the Los Angeles County
Department of Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government settled these cases for 36 cents on the
dollar even though it could have collected much more, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare spends over $200 billion a year to provide health care
to people who are elderly or disabled. Health-care providers have
many disputes with the government over Medicare payments, and they
often negotiate settlements or take their claims to an
administrative tribunal at the Department of Health and Human
Services. But these three cases were far bigger than any others,
and the settlement agreements were the only ones not shown to
health department lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   A Medicare official who worked on the cases said he feared that
the ``deals would go up in smoke'' if he sought approval from
lawyers at the Justice Department or the Department of Health and
Human Services, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office said the health-care providers had
used their ``political influence'' to short-circuit the normal
procedures for resolving disputes over Medicare reimbursement. It
said that top Medicare officials, including Bruce C. Vladeck, who
was head of the Health Care Financing Administration from 1993 to
1997, put pressure on subordinates to settle politically sensitive
cases after being contacted directly by health-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office did not accuse the providers of
wrongdoing. It did criticize Medicare officials, saying they had
``acted improperly'' in accepting the settlements without proper
scrutiny. Federal officials generally need Justice Department
approval to settle or compromise any claim exceeding $100,000, the
GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Collins said: ``Lower-level Medicare
employees tried to sound the alarm. They protested the special
treatment given to these three providers. But their concerns were
ignored or suppressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Luis R. Marcos, president of Health and Hospitals Corp.,
denied that it had received special treatment. He said the New York
hospitals were entitled to a much more generous settlement than
they received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider this a sweetheart deal by any stretch of the
imagination,'' Marcos said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Anello, a lawyer for Vladeck, also defended the
settlements, saying that Vladeck had tried to make Medicare more
responsive to health-care providers and beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prompt resolution of these disputes ensured continued
health care for millions of poor people,'' Anello said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official, speaking on the
condition of anonymity, said: ``There was nothing wrong with the
settlements on the merits. There was something wrong with the
process _ how the settlements were reached.''
</P>
<P>
   But the General Accounting Office said the settlements were
``apparently unjustified'' and would not have been approved if
Medicare officials had followed the statutory criteria for
compromising government claims.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the accounting office said, the agreements should
have been reviewed by government lawyers, because Medicare
officials were ``relinquishing the government's right to recover
tens of millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlements not only wiped out the health-care providers'
debts to the government but allowed them to be paid in the future
for some costs that would not otherwise be covered by Medicare, the
accounting office said. The disputed hospital charges included
bills left unpaid by patients.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare discovered the disputed charges in audits that covered
several years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Charles Booth, director of financial services for Medicare, who
has worked for the program since it started in 1966, told
investigators that the agreement with Health and Hospitals Corp.
``allowed past poor practices to be carried into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Booth told investigators that Vladeck, a former member of the
board of Health and Hospitals Corp., had urged him to ``move
faster'' in arranging a settlement. Booth said he replied that
speeding up the settlement process could cost the government $8
million to $10 million, but he said Vladeck told him that ``time
was more important than money.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Booth said, he did not consult any lawyers, because
they would have delayed the settlement, and such delays would have
displeased administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Ohl, a federal Medicare official in California, expressed
``major concerns'' about the settlement with Los Angeles County,
saying it appeared to be ``a political action'' to circumvent
Medicare requirements. In an e-mail message to Medicare officials
in Washington, Ohl said, ``We believe this agreement is not in
Medicare's best interest,'' because it does not protect the
Medicare trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Visiting Nurse Service had, on the average,
billed Medicare for three times as much as the government allowed
for home-health-aide visits, and it justified such claims by saying
that patients tended to be sicker there. But federal investigators
said the nurse service never provided evidence or data to support
that contention.
</P>
<P>
   In carrying out its review, the General Accounting Office
examined 96 settlement agreements that Medicare officials
negotiated with health-care providers over the last decade. In each
case, Medicare asserted that the providers had been overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   In 93 of the cases, the General Accounting Office found nothing
illegal or improper. But it said the Health Care Financing
Administration had acted improperly in the three largest cases,
which accounted for two-thirds of the money at issue.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hash, deputy administrator of the Health Care Financing
Administration, said the agency had formed a ``work group'' to
analyze its debt-collection procedures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
