u i BC-PAKISTAN-MUSHARAFF-NY     03-25 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-MUSHARAFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANI RULER INSISTS HIS MEETING WITH CLINTON WENT WELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistan's military ruler, Gen. Pervez
Musharraf, on Saturday night recapped his meeting earlier in the
day with President Clinton, and to hear him tell it, he and the
U.S. president became fast friends and agreed on almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got on pretty well together,'' the general said
with a broad smile, adding that the two leaders discussed their
golf game over an amiable lunch. ``He told me he is a 12 handicap,
and I told him that I would like to challenge him on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Their mutual affection for golf was equaled by their shared
detestation of terrorism. ``I would say there was no difference of
opinion on this issue,'' Musharraf said at a news conference. ``He
did raise concerns, and I totally agreed with him. We ourselves are
victims of terrorism, and we denounce terrorism in all its forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are those in the U.S. government who believe
that Pakistan arms and commands militants who cross into
Indian-controlled Kashmir and throw bombs and conduct
assassinations. India, too, has made the charge. India and Pakistan
have been fighting over Kashmir since 1947, when both nations were
carved from the British Empire.
</P>
<P>
   The general was asked what assurances he had given Clinton that
such infiltration would stop. ``There were no assurances because
there was no question,'' he said. ``We are not involved in sending
any kind of people across the Line of Control,'' which has been a
de facto border between the Indian and Pakistani parts of Kashmir
for nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all a people's dynamic,'' Musharraf said of the
guerrilla campaign in Kashmir. ``It is not government sponsored.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, the Line of Control is a long, mountainous
stretch, and if India, with 700,000 troops stationed in the area,
cannot stop the guerrillas from entering Kashmir, what could
Pakistan do?
</P>
<P>
   He did allow, however, that there might be some terrorists
operating out of Afghanistan, Pakistan's ally and neighbor
next-door _ and said that he had promised Clinton that he would
personally look into the matter. ``I would certainly like to
address this to the satisfaction of the world community,'' the
general said helpfully.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than five months since Musharraf took power in
a bloodless coup. He has given himself the title of chief
executive. Saturday, dressed in a long white coat called a
sherwani, he seemed quite at ease.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours earlier, Clinton had given a televised speech to the
nation, adamantly refusing to serve as a mediator in the Kashmir
dispute, something Pakistan wants and India disdains. The general
sounded unperturbed, as if confronted by a minor technicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indians are quite allergic to the word mediation, so the word
mediation should be avoided,'' he said. ``But a facilitation of a
dialogue between India and Pakistan is possible. Certainly, the
United States has a role to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times, the general said, given the stakes with India and
Pakistan both possessing nuclear weapons, he would give
``unconditional acceptance of a dialogue at any time, in any place,
at any level.''
</P>
<P>
   A questioner suggested that the general could always pick up the
phone and call India's prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, but
this sounded to the chief executive like ``an impulsive action''
and not the anywhere, anytime he had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could ring me up and I would certainly respond,'' the
general said by way of a counterproposal. ``I don't know if he
would respond if I rang him up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
