<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EMAN-MILITARY0326-COX     03-25 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAN-MILITARY0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Army testing `computerized' soldiers
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At military exercises this summer in Louisiana, troops
will find themselves engaged in fake battle against a rifle platoon
of ``cyborgs'' from the 82nd Airborne Division, headquartered at
Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   Through eyepieces mounted on their helmets, the 'borgs will be
able to view the battlefield through telescopic vision, infrared
vision or nighttime vision. Eyepieces connected by cable to a video
camera mounted on their M-16 rifles will allow them to accurately
aim and fire their weapons around the corner of a building.
</P>
<P>
   If they spot a tank or other target out of their range, they'll
be able to tag it with a laser beam that pinpoints the target's
exact coordinates. The cyborg's ``on-board computer'' will then
ship those coordinates back to headquarters, which will order up an
artillery or air strike on the target.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also be able to view computerized maps of the
battlefield through their eyepiece, with their own positions and
the positions of their fellow cyborgs already plotted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want them shooting their buddies,'' explains Mike
Tryon, deputy manager for the U.S. Army's Training and Doctrine
Command, which is helping to develop the Land Warrior wearable
computing system. Friendly fire accounted for almost a quarter of
the U.S. servicemen killed in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to speech recognition software, platoon members will
be able to perform those chores by voice command alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fighting system, so I want my soldier to keep his
hands on his weapon while he's performing all these other
functions,'' says Tryon, a civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Like many complicated defense programs, the Land Warrior system
has a troubled history. Originally conceived in 1996, it was
supposed to be fully deployed by 2000, with as many as 34,000 units
put in the field. Instead it's still in the early phases of
testing, with 2004 as the earliest possible deployment date. In
December, a report to Congress by the General Accounting Office
outlined problems in the program, the most serious involving
weight.
</P>
<P>
   That's always been a touchy issue. Tryon declined to discuss the
system's total weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would give the wrong impression that we were really
burdening these guys down,'' he says. ``The truth is, in some cases
we're actually lightening the soldier's load over what it would be
if they had these functions individually, with a radio and other
equipment. For example, we've taken about 2.5 pounds off the squad
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report was more candid, putting the weight of the Land
Warrior system at a prohibitive 90 pounds, which includes body
armor and two radio systems. However, the GAO also noted that after
its report was drafted, the Army had begun to redesign the system.
A total weight for the new version could not be obtained. The GAO
also criticized the life span of batteries used in the system, but
again it noted significant progress was being made in overcoming
that obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tryon, the United States is far from alone in
developing such systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next summer we'll have the British, the Germans and us all
demonstrating our systems to NATO,'' he says. ``The Australians are
building a system, too, and the Canadians are sitting back, waiting
to see what kind of technology the rest of us go with.''
</P>
<P>
   After the summer war exercises in Louisiana, the platoon of 82nd
Airborne ``cyborgs'' will train with the Land Warrior system for a
year to test its survivability and functionality.
</P>
<P>
   Later versions of the system may incorporate technologies that
are still under development, such as a type of handheld radar
system that would allow troops to detect objects such as tanks or
even human beings on the other side of a solid wall. Even more in
the future, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, or
DARPA, is funding research into what it calls ``Exoskeletons for
Human Augmentation,'' basically a high-tech form of computerized
armor that will boost a soldier's physical capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mechanically augmenting the speed, strength and endurance of
the ground soldier will lead to enhanced survivability and new
mission capabilities,'' DARPA documents claim.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
