<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WHITNEY-REVIEW0326-CO     03-25 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-REVIEW0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Technology, international character at center of Whitney
Biennial
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 2000 Whitney Biennial gets the new century off to
a good start. The work of the 97 artists is serious, thoughtful,
inventive and carefully crafted. If this graciously installed
exhibition lacks the boisterousness of past biennials, a sense of
maturity is not a bad trade. And most welcome of all, it doesn't
stick its finger or its rear end in your face, which goes to show
you that art _ and the biennial _ can be provocative without being
shrill and confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   (Hans Haacke's critique of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
response to the Brooklyn Museum of Art's ``Sensation'' exhibition
is the exception, and it looks so ``last century.'')
</P>
<P>
   The biennial aims to survey what is being made in America. Its
observation: everything, from abstract painting to installation to
Internet art (included for the first time.) Still, this is
definitely the year of technology. In addition to Net art, there is
an abundance of video, digital and computer presentations. One of
the most intriguing, even though the point isn't quite clear, is
Cambridge, Mass.-based Krzysztof Wodi-czko's ``Aegis: Equipment for
a City of Strangers.'' The contraption is a pair of winglike LCD
monitors worn on the shoulders. They show images of the wearer that
talk to each other.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the year of the figure. That's inevitable, what
with the preponderance of photography and video. But even most of
the nonrepresentational objects have figurative references as
opposed to being an investigation of form and color. In the case of
Chakaia Booker's wall relief ``Homage to Thy Mother (Landscape),''
one of the most strikingly beautiful pieces in the show, the
material _ car tires cut and shredded into a variety of shapes _ is
highly symbolic. The New York artist sees many references to
African-Americans in the tires, from their color to their
resilience. In one of many interesting juxtapositions, Booker's
piece is installed across the room from works by Alabama artist
Thornton Dial, who takes a similar approach to materials.
</P>
<P>
   The biennial abounds with inventive treatment of both au courant
themes and venerable genres. Ghada Amer, an Egyptian native living
in New York, makes elegant ``paintings'' by stitching patterns on
canvas that comment on the place of women in Islamic culture.
Atlantan Chris Verene comments on women in this culture in his
photos of men in camera clubs who take soft-porn pictures of
misguided women.
</P>
<P>
   (Both he and fellow Atlantan Kojo Griffin more than hold their
own here. Unfortunately, many of the videos and films, including
those of Atlantans Robin Bernat and Ruth Leitman, weren't
reviewable during press previews.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the demographics are broader _ both in geography and
generation _ than in the past, don't expect a regional flavor. Most
of the work selected by the six-person curatorial team comes out of
either a more interior source or a larger art world consciousness.
In fact, with 21 artists born outside of the United States, the
biennial exudes an international character. Iranian-born New Yorker
Shirin Neshat has contributed a riveting two-screen video about
Islam and individualism, with a touch of romance. Art may be the
melting pot that America never quite was.
</P>
<P>
   Not every piece is a gem, of course. In some cases, the object
can't carry off the conceptual burden imposed upon it.
Nevertheless, this biennial makes a persuasive and surprisingly
coherent case that contemporary art of all description is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-DEVELOPMENT-N     03-25 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-DEVELOPMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK CITY'S NEW DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   The headlines nowadays are filled with ambitious proposals to
transform New York City's landscape. One day, planners unveil a
scheme to stage the Olympics in the city, with a new stadium on the
West Side and apartment houses for athletes on the Queens
waterfront. Another day, Albany debates plans to connect the Long
Island Rail Road to Grand Central Terminal or build a new Second
Avenue subway. Clearly boom times are producing dreams for big
projects, opening a potential new chapter in the city's
self-renewal. But dreams also entail tough decisions. It is far
from obvious how best to use limited resources for urban growth.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, continuing pressure for New York City to
use its regular capital budget to repair schools, bridges and the
infrastructure. But the city's history also illustrates the
importance of grand projects that spur economic growth and enhance
New York's reputation as a cultural and business mecca. The need
for planned expansion of existing public and private facilities is
illustrated daily by crowded subways, high-priced apartments and
squeezed commercial space. It is equally evident that there is room
for quality development around rail yards, in old manufacturing
areas and in underused waterfront districts. The problem for
elected officials is how to sort through competing plans and find
the best way to continue the tradition that has produced past
successes from Rockefeller Center to Lincoln Center and Battery
Park City.
</P>
<P>
   Four overarching goals are already evident. The city government
should try to open up Manhattan's West Side to development. It
should also revise the city's residential zoning to protect the
character of existing neighborhoods. The other two goals are the
upgrading of transit links and development of the waterfront and
other vacant areas. Shaping projects around these goals will
involve complicated choices about the mix of public and private
funds and the feasibility of various stadium proposals. Those
choices, in turn, will be influenced by the outcome of the effort
to recruit the Olympics. Here is a rundown on the major issues:
</P>
<P>
   _ The West Side. The biggest opportunity for apartments and
offices is in Manhattan, west of Eighth Avenue and south of 42nd
Street, an area developers have eyed for years. The main impediment
is a lack of transit access. The committee that proposes to bring
the 2012 Olympics to New York has some imaginative suggestions. One
proposal is to build a stadium over the rail yards near the
waterfront, and link the site with the No. 7 subway line, the Long
Island Rail Road, Metro North and the Amtrak trains to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic bid is supported by Gov. George Pataki and Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who also wants a West Side stadium for the Jets
and the Javits Convention Center. Madison Square Garden is also
said to be interested in moving west. A valuable new neighborhood
could rise one day from what is now largely parking lots,
warehouses and wasted space. The stadium proposals deserve serious
study. But any new facility should have multiple uses, and no
potential user _ whether the Olympics or a sports franchise _
should be handed a blank check.
</P>
<P>
   The West Side is also being looked at by a team of business
leaders put together by Sen. Charles Schumer and former Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin. They want to find room for high-tech and
other business expansion in other parts of the city as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Olympics. The Olympics do not always produce the economic
activity that sponsors promise. But the Olympics group has laid out
an intriguing scheme in which a stadium just might work. Its
projections show that a public investment in a train stop and
platform over the railroad tracks _ with or without a stadium _
could be paid for by tax revenues from new office, hotel and
residential buildings. Over all, projected revenue from the
Olympics would pay for more than $1 billion in new athletic
facilities throughout the city. The Olympics proposal also calls
for an athletes village to be built on the Queens waterfront and
later converted to apartments. The entire proposal foresees
improvements in housing, public facilities and transportation that
would outlast the Games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Transit. In New York City, of course, grand schemes often
spark big squabbling. The state budget is now being held up by a
fight over Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver's demand that more money
be spent for a Second Avenue subway line. There is no question that
the Second Avenue subway is a priority, but financing that line
should not preclude bringing the Long Island Rail Road to Grand
Central or extending the No. 7 subway line to new West Side
development.
</P>
<P>
   _ Residential preservation. All these ideas for growth reinforce
the city's responsibility to protect its neighborhoods. One
initiative to accommodate construction of new apartments without
destroying existing places is being put forward by the New York
City Planning Commission under its chairman, Joseph Rose. It would
revise the residential zoning code to encourage buildings on the
scale of existing neighborhoods, and discourage blasting down
existing street blocks for empty plazas and big towers like the one
Donald Trump is constructing near the United Nations. This
commendable proposal is going through a review with the city's
community boards and should be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   All these activities reflect New York's optimistic new spirit.
Even in these affluent times, however, the public must spend its
resources wisely. Recent proposals for Columbus Circle and a new
Penn Station have proved that there still is a role for the
government to facilitate and, in some cases, subsidize exciting new
projects. The same attitude can create still more possibilities for
the future. We intend to address the specifics of all these
proposals in coming weeks. For now it is important to salute the
promise of ideas for a new chapter in the constant journey of a
city reinventing itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1629EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-2     03-25 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A HOMECOMING ACROSS THE PACIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (Adds photo note.) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Bobby Valentine greeting fans in Tokyo is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For one epic year, Bobby Valentine embraced Japanese
baseball, thinking he was importing his American ways. He wound up
realizing there are other ways to play this game.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the New York Mets has now returned to his other
baseball home, with all the exuberance of a child waking up on a
birthday. This week, Valentine is proudly leading his team on a
road trip that may be the next step toward a stronger bond between
the baseball continents. Saturday night at a news conference here,
Valentine, speaking in Japanese, said he was glad to be back.
</P>
<P>
   Monday and Tuesday, the Mets and the Chicago Cubs will play
alternate exhibitions against the Seibu Lions and the Yomiuri
Giants, and on Wednesday and Thursday, the Mets and the Cubs will
play regular-season games against each other. This will be the
first time a so-called major league game has ever been played
outside the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The trip will be an ordeal for the players, some of whom are not
amused. Mark McGwire was so opposed to it that he blocked the
Cardinals from taking part, and has criticized the venture as being
driven by money. Valentine concedes that the Pacific Ocean will be
a major block to interleague play, but he said, ``Eventually
they'll have medicine to deal with jet lag.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the Americas are already linked in the fertile mind of
Valentine, the first American manager ever imported to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   His tenure lasted one year, 1995, but his love for Japan was
just beginning. He mingled. He questioned. He won. He lost. And he
brought things home with him.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent spring training in Florida, Valentine held what he
called ``shag-free practices,'' meaning his pitchers do not loll
around the outfield, shagging flies during batting practice. This
is a direct benefit of Valentine's year as the manager of the Lotte
Marines in the Chiba prefecture of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we get into the weight room or the video room,'' he said.
``We try to use the time more beneficially.''
</P>
<P>
   The cliche from Americans is that the Japanese place too much
stock in the 1,000-grounder workout that leaves players bowed and
bloody.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, people prepare as a group,'' Valentine said. ``Their
practices are very long, almost to the point of monotonous. I think
they do it to excess, but we were not practicing enough.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to Japan as a celebrity, having managed six years for
the Texas Rangers and one year with the Mets' Norfolk farm club. He
was a new link between the two continents in a sporting
relationship that began in 1867, when American merchants and
sailors brought the game here. In the second half of the 20th
century, the Japanese began hiring American players.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Yonamine, born in Hawaii of Japanese descent, played 13
years in Japan, spoke the language fluently, and managed the
Chunichi Dragons to a pennant in 1974. Joe Lutz, who had once
coached in Cleveland, managed the Hiroshima Carp briefly in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Don Blasingame, the veteran second baseman from the United
States, played three years with the Nankai Hawks of Osaka, stayed
to coach and manage them for over a decade, and in 1979-80 managed
the Hanshin Tigers. The popular Blazer tried to buck the system by
not overworking his pitchers and playing what he felt was a
consistent lineup, but he resigned after little more than a season.
</P>
<P>
   Never had Japan recruited a manager directly from the United
States until Valentine was courted by the management of Lotte, a
department-store empire with roots in Korea. The general manager
was Tatsuro Hirooka, a former star shortstop and championship
manager _ ``one of the first players to move into management, a
very proud man, impeccable dresser, from the old school,''
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine argued with umpires until he realized he was getting
nowhere, since he did not speak Japanese and also because a temper
is decidedly counterproductive in that country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to fit in in Japan,'' Valentine once said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOKYO: once said. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He studied the language via a computer program, with the side
result of becoming hooked on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He also noticed the way Japanese bunters do not waste motion by
squaring and pivoting but rather tap the ball from the more natural
batting stance. He has found resistance in teaching that technique
to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was fascinated by the rituals _ the organized
cheerleading sections, often organized by the corporations that own
the teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear 10,000 strong, waving flags, doing the wave, blowing
trumpets, it's disconcerting at first,'' Valentine said. ``But it
is part of the game, it's part of the culture. They love sumo
wrestling, and now they have soccer, but for a long time baseball
was their only team sport, so they took parts of all our team
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Lotte, they Americanized their game,'' Valentine
added. ``They got rid of the big, heavy drum. They would sing `Take
Me Out to the Ball Game' in the seventh inning, which was neat.
They had songs for the individual players. They made great puns on
the two languages. There was a guy named Iya Omura, so they would
sing `Old MacDonald Had a Farm' and they would chant `Iya-Iya-O.'
It was kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also had fun trying to personalize the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was riding the trains with the fans, talking to kids, all my
idle time out in public,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He smiles when he recalls the numerical approach, how in pregame
meetings his coaches would predict the score, saying it felt like a
6-1 game. To the American ear, that sounded impossible, given the
inconsistencies of pitching, but the coaches were serious.
</P>
<P>
   In Lotte, Valentine had a three-year contract to transform Chiba
Lotte from ``second-class citizens,'' but while the Marines
finished second behind Seibu in his first season, he and Hirooka
were already at odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hired me, he fired me, we had a falling out at the end,
regretfully,'' Valentine said the other day. ``It's the only
blemish on my experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese baseball has stayed with him. He has gone back on
scouting and good-will missions and has been welcomed by Shigeo
Nagashima, the great third baseman who now manages the Yomiuri
Giants, the Yankees of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine questions the traditional view that the Japanese are
too small to hit for power. Also, competition has narrowed the
baseball gap between nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, if you were behind Nagashima with the Giants,
you stayed in the system forever,'' Valentine said of the Japanese
farm system. ``Now it's loosened up. As some Japanese players come
to the U.S., that develops more exceptional young players.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine praised unrelated players named Matsui: Kazuo, a
shortstop with Seibu ``who rivals Rey Ordonez in the field,'' and
Hideki, an outfielder with the Giants ``who hits for power and
average, the kind of player any manager would love.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we only had three non-Americans, the way they do, I believe
the Japanese league would be stronger than ours,'' Valentine said,
acknowledging the impact of Latin American stars like Sammy Sosa,
who will be a star attraction this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' manager does not foresee ``a true World Series'' in
the short run, but adds, ``What we are doing is the closest thing
to it _ two American teams playing two Japanese teams just before
the season, not just all-star teams. The real thing. I'm going to
play these games like World Series games.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, he plans to go out and mingle. Many players may
regard this expedition as a pain in their sleep cycle, but for
Bobby Valentine, this is a homecoming, deeply anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll sleep on the plane home,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
