<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARD LEADS LATE RALLY AS LOUISIANA STATE BEATS YOUNG DUKE TEAM BY
13
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ On the Louisiana State sideline, the wizened
coach, Sue Gunter, was stomping her black patent-leather heels. Her
cheeks were reflecting the color of her cotton-candy pink blouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana State Tigers were not rebounding the ball,
standing like tourists around the basket and allowing Duke, last
year's national runners-up, to take a 47-42 lead with 12 minutes 56
seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Then guard Marie Ferdinand, a Louisiana State junior, got bored.
She needed a change of scenery, so she took her game inside and as
a result, took her team to the next round.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand, like lightning from a bottle, jumped out to make a
steal with 12:19 remaining, going down the floor for a quick layup
that ignited an 18-4 run. DeTrina White, a sophomore, finished with
19 points and 11 rebounds for the game's only double-double, and
the core of starters who had been together for 61 games outlasted a
young Duke team down the stretch for a 79-66 victory to advance to
the East Regional final Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All throughout the season, my team has fed off me,'' said
Ferdinand, who finished with a game-high 22 points, 11 in the final
12 minutes. ``I got the team a lift and I was able to get the run
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand also anchored a stingy LSU defense that stifled Duke's
outside shooting all day. The second-seeded Blue Devils, usually 37
percent shooters beyond the arc, went 5 for 22 (24 percent) from
3-point range. Third-seeded Louisiana State shot 56 percent for the
game, the percentage helped by a strong presence in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Though both teams played a frantic motion offense that kept the
score close in the first half _ Duke led 31-30 going into the
locker room _ LSU changed from a 1-3-1 zone defense to a one-on-one
that eventually overwhelmed the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``LSU played the game we wanted to play, they always made the
extra pass,'' said Duke's Lauren Rice, who led her team in scoring
with 17 points. ``We tried to trap them but then Ferdinand ended up
with easy layups in the lane.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that coach Gail Goestenkors of Duke kept Rice and
Georgia Schweitzer, the Atlantic Coast Conference player of the
year, on the bench to rest them. That gave Ferdinand some room and
the Tigers began their run, listening to their coach's favorite
expression: ``Whatever it takes to win!''
</P>
<P>
   LSU (25-6) is making its first trip to the regional finals in 14
years. Duke (28-6), which lost four starters from last year's team,
finished the season looking ahead to next year when it has perhaps
the best recruits in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for us to make it to the Elite Eight,'' said
LSU's only senior, Katrina Hibbert. ``That was one of our goals in
the season. We wanted to make history, and of course, do it for
coach Gunter.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunter, 58, has 613 victories overall, fourth on the women's
basketball coaches' list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how many years she has left in her,'' Hibbert
said, ``so we definitely want to get to the Final Four since she's
never been there before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
