<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS FACE ABORTION BATTLE  
 CHANGES LIKELY AT DNC  
 ISSUES VOTERS CARE ABOUT  
 POLITICIANS TALKING GAS  
 CANDIDATES' MONIKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Neb., Conn.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaders of the abortion rights movement in the Republican Party
say they will risk precipitating a noisy, divisive fight at this
summer's Republican National Convention if the party insists on
keeping an anti-abortion plank in its platform.
</P>
<P>
   They have begun a mass mailing to convince top party officials
that a platform that even so much as mentions the abortion issue is
a platform that invites disaster on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive Republican nominee, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, favors an anti-abortion plank. He has shown no inclination
to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 platform carried such a plank, and efforts by the
Republican Pro-Choice Coalition and other groups to have it thrown
out were soundly rebuffed. But in an effort to mute differences
over this touchy issue, the platform writers agreed to include a
mention of some of the positions advocated by Republicans who favor
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Come the 2000 convention, abortion rights leaders plan to say
the plank must go _ or, they warn, there will be a big fight,
nationally televised, and Gov. Bush will enter the fall campaign
with a badly divided party, deprived of the support of thousands of
voters, especially women, who are already more inclined to vote
Democratic than Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party must understand,'' said Susan R. Cullman, a
co-chairwoman of the Republican Pro-Choice Coalition, ``that the
road to a unified Republican Party is filled with deep potholes.
The party will surely tumble into one of them if we don't take
abortion out of the platform.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its campaign to remove the anti-abortion plank, the
coalition is mailing its members and allies 40,000 ``Pothole
Ahead!'' packets that contain postcards to be forwarded to
convention officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pave the road for ALL!'' the cards urge. ``Take abortion OUT
of politics and OUT of the Republican Party platform!''
</P>
<P>
   At the DNC, Upheaval as Usual
</P>
<P>
   Late last summer, when President Clinton picked Edward G.
Rendell to be the general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, the expectation was that the party's campaign war chest
would soon be overflowing. Rendell, then serving his final months
as mayor of Philadelphia, had a reputation as a first-class manager
and a prodigious fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there is never enough management or money in any campaign
to keep everyone happy. So there has been some sotto voce
don't-quote-me grumbling that perhaps Rendell is not such a great
manager or prodigious money man after all.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But this much is clear:
</P>
<P>
   With Vice President Al Gore now the man to see when it comes to
running the Democratic Party _ a perk that goes with being the
presumptive presidential nominee _ some job upheaval is inevitable
at the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   So?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Rendell is doing a fantastic job,'' Gore declared on
Thursday night at a fund-raiser in Detroit, seeming to cast a vote
of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be surprised, some Gore aides later confided, if some
new faces start showing up in jobs just below Rendell's.
</P>
<P>
   Poll Suggests Bush Has the Right Issues
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent much of last week promoting himself as the
``education candidate.'' But that's not to say he has abandoned or
is playing down his earlier pitch about Gore's ``credibility
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He still hammers the vice president on that at just about every
stop, reminding voters about Gore's appearance at a fund-raiser
held at a Buddhist temple and recalling the Gore boast about
``inventing'' the Internet. And he still always manages to mention
Bill Clinton, Al Gore and ``character'' in the same breath.
</P>
<P>
   It is a guess whether this education/credibility attack line is
working. But a new Battleground Poll, by Ed Goeas, a Republican,
and Celinda Lake, a Democrat, indicates that Bush has latched onto
the two issues foremost in voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   When the pollsters asked 1,000 likely voters in mid-March to
list the ``most important'' issue in the presidential election, 18
percent said ``restoring moral values'' and 13 percent said
``improving education.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which had a margin of sampling error of 3.1 percentage
points, found the third-most important issue to be strengthening
Social Security and Medicare (11 percent) and the fourth to be
improving health care (10 percent). After that, in order, came gun
control, crime, taxes, government spending, the environment, the
economy and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Gas Prices the Talk of State Campaigns
</P>
<P>
   The steep rise in gas prices has mainly provided political
fodder for Republicans going after Gore, who likes to boast that
the country has never enjoyed better economic times. But more and
more the gas issue is filtering down into congressional and state
races.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, former Gov. George F. Allen, a Republican trying to
oust Sen. Charles S. Robb, a Democrat, says Robb has to go because
he once called for a 50-cents-a-gallon increase in gas taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In Nebraska, George Grogan, a Republican businessman running for
the Senate, is broadcasting advertisements in which he accuses
Clinton of knuckling under to OPEC and urges cuts in the federal
gas tax and more oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the state's Republican Party recently ran
advertisements in which Gov. John G. Rowland called on voters to
press state legislators, particularly reluctant Democrats, to pass
a 7-cents-a-gallon cut in the state's 32-cents-a-gallon gas tax.
Democrats worry that this cut would cost the state treasury too
much.
</P>
<P>
   And in New York City?
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani says the blame for the price spike should
be laid ``completely at the feet'' of Hillary Rodham Clinton's
husband.
</P>
<P>
   What's in a Name? Secret Service Knows
</P>
<P>
   When Secret Service agents talk into their sleeves while
protecting presidential candidates, they almost always refer to
their charges by code names seemingly picked at random _ Dasher for
Jimmy Carter, Rawhide for Ronald Reagan, Eagle for Bill Clinton,
Sundance for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's code name?
</P>
<P>
   Tumbler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
