<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT FEELS LIKE 1996 TO SOARING LEHMAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (jw) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ In 1996, many believed that Tom Lehman
was the world's best player after he won the British Open, the Tour
Championship and led the PGA Tour money list.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Lehman has felt just as good. Winning this weekend would
be another statement that his game is as good as it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   After two excellent rounds on one of the word's most challenging
courses, Lehman began Saturday one stroke off the lead heading into
the third round of the Players Championship. Hal Sutton led at 6
under (138), one stroke ahead of Lehman and Omar Uresti, who were
tied at 5 under. But the leader board was crowded with Fulton Allem
at 4 under, Tiger Woods, Ernie Els, and Len Mattiace at 2 under,
and Lee Janzen and Scott Dunlap at 1 under.
</P>
<P>
   That was serious competition, but that often brings out the best
in Lehman, who is as competitive as anyone on tour. He looked
forward to the weekend challenge at the TPC of Sawgrass. And he
liked his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my chances are as good as anyone's'' said Lehman, who
already has three top 10 finishes this year, including a victory at
the Phoenix Open. ``I expect Tiger Woods to play great. I expect
Tom Lehman to play great. I expect Ernie Els to play great. Anybody
can win.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tournament has already been interesting, because many
players have commented candidly about Woods and his recent
domination of the tour. Woods has already won three times in six
starts this year, and he has two second-place finishes as well.
Commenting on Woods' victory last weekend at the Bay Hill
Invitational, Colin Montgomerie said that after the first round,
many players had already conceded the tournament to Woods in their
minds. Many players have taken exception to Montgomerie's
statement. Count Lehman among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought what Monty said was a little strange,'' said Lehman.
``After one round it's still anybody's ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give credit where credit is due. I was raised to
think there are two cardinal sins in sports. One is under
estimating your opponent, and the other is overestimating your
opponent. I respect very much the other players on tour. Yet, if I
didn't think I was capable of beating them, I wouldn't be out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Allem was even stronger when asked if he would be intimidated by
Woods this weekend. ``Not unless he has a gun,'' said Allem. ``He
hits it 50 yards by me and he can beat me by 15 strokes. But when I
stand on the first tee, I look into his eyes, I am looking to beat
him. I'm not going to go like Davis Love III and all those guys
that say, `Oh, you know he is so tough.' I'm going for the gusto.
Beat me. I'm not going to sit back and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought that other players were intimidated by
Woods, Allem said: ``A lot of them are. Look, the kid is great, he
is the best player bar none. He is beautiful to watch. But you have
to enjoy the opportunity to beat the guy who is the best player.
That's the way I look at it. If I look at his record and look at
mine, ain't no way. But you've got to be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman has been thinking positively ever since he arrived at the
tournament. Although he has never won the tournament, Lehman has
three top 10 finishes at Sawgrass, including a tie for second in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman has managed to keep his ball dry at the difficult island
green par 3 No. 7, making a birdie on Thursday and a par on Friday.
Some players walk to No. 17 with trepidation, but not Lehman. ``It
adds to the course,'' said Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman would like to add to his trophy case, but he will have to
play superb golf, considering the course and the competition. But
Lehman would prefer it that way. And he was happy that he was again
playing well enough to win, especially with the Masters just two
weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to play well, especially in the big ones,''
said Lehman. ``If you are going to pick a tournament to play well
in, you might as well pick a big one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
