<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DAIMLER-DEAL-NYT &LR;      03-25 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER NEARS DEAL TO BUY 33.4 PERCENT OF MITSUBISHI
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ill.)   (jw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another big move toward the global consolidation of the
automobile industry, DaimlerChrysler of Germany is to announce a
deal on Monday to acquire 33.4 percent of Japan's Mitsubishi Motors
for about $1.3 billion, people close to the companies said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would make DaimlerChrysler the world's third-largest
automaker, behind General Motors and Ford. All three will now have
large shares of the three main markets: Western Europe, Japan and
the United States. The other giants of the auto industry,
Volkswagen, Toyota, Honda and the Renault-Nissan alliance, still
are weak in at least one of these markets.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also marks the second time in the past year that a
Japanese carmaker has ceded management control to a foreign
competitor. Renault of France acquired a 36.8 percent stake last
year in Nissan Motors. If the DaimlerChrysler-Mitsubishi deal is
completed, Japan would be left with only two major independent car
companies _ Toyota and Honda _ with the rest partly or entirely
under the control of western manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi has been in financial distress and is saddled with
about $16 billion in debt. And though it has a presence in
Southeast Asia as well as Japan, the company has only 2.3 percent
of the Japanese market. Mitsubishi had been sought a partnership to
shore up its capital position in the face of brutal worldwide
competition in the market for small and medium-sized cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitsubishi stake would give DaimlerChrysler the right to
name several members of Mitsubishi's board and veto power over
major decisions. And because the German-American carmaker would
provide a crucial capital infusion, it expects to have the leverage
to hammer out a strategy to bolster the two companies' presence in
Asia and in the small-car market worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But the move poses plenty of risks for DaimlerChrysler. The
automaker has already seen its stock pushed down in the past year,
partly because of investor fears about the financial drain of
taking command of a small-car producer and concerns about the lower
profit margins of small cars in comparison with DaimlerChrysler's
core businesses _ Mercedes-Benz luxury cars and Chrysler sport
utility vehicles, light trucks and midsized American family cars.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks between the two companies said that
Katsuhiko Kawasoe, president of Mitsubishi, was in Frankfurt
Saturday to sign a letter of intent with Juergen E. Schrempp,
chairman of DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, DaimlerChrysler will take no stake in
Mitsubishi's truck business, of which Volvo of Sweden owns 19
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural differences are often the biggest barrier to
international auto mergers. But DaimlerChrysler and Mitsubishi may
have an advantage because Chrysler and Mitsubishi have worked
together closely for many years. Mitsubishi makes the Dodge Avenger
and Chrysler Sebring coupes for DaimlerChrysler at a factory in
Normal, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   For Schrempp of DaimlerChrysler, the Mitsubushi deal would
appear to finally satisfy a goal he has had since engineering the
takeover of Chrysler two years ago: to gain a major presence in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Asian car market has been in disastrous shape for the
last several years, thanks to the lingering effects of the
financial crises in Southeast Asia and Japan's intractable
recession, industry experts still believe it will be one of the
biggest sources of growth in years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last year, Schrempp was in advanced negotiations to
acquire a stake in Nissan and was competing against overtures by
Renault.
</P>
<P>
   But after Daimler executives scrutinized Nissan's enormous
financial and structural problems, Schrempp bowed out of the talks
and Renault ultimately struck a deal with Nissan instead.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Daimler said Saturday that Mitsubishi brought
with it some good technology, including the direct-fuel injection
diesel engines.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi also owns a stake in Proton, the Malaysian automobile
company, and that stake in turn could give DaimlerChrysler improved
access to the Southeast Asian market.
</P>
</TEXT>
