<P>
   FBN-NFL-CRIME _ The NFL's p.r. machine has long juked the
growing number of criminal acts by many of its players, but two now
face murder charges and there's no dodging the questions about
off-the-field problems. Domestic violence. Bar fights. Drug abuse
and trafficking. The league cites statistics proportional to
society, but that argument doesn't wash when players already facing
or convicted of crime are allowed to enter and stay in the league.
What's being done, if anything, on a leaguewide scale and with
individual teams? NOW and M.A.D.D. have stepped up pressure in some
situations. Do players believe they're invincibile when it comes to
their actions? Will background checks intensify or be ignored? Will
the league become a Big Brother to players like Baltimore's Ray
Lewis, who was allegedly involved in a double homicide only days
before the Ravens planned to talk to him about his choice of
``friends.'' We speak to players, management, league officials, law
enforcement officials, sociologists, etc. (Woods, Palm Beach Post).
60
</P>
