<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PRICE-REAL-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBAN HOME PRICES SOARING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With 1999 standing as the fourth straight
record-setting year for home prices throughout the nation and the
New York metropolitan region, and with older baby boomers ensconced
in their homes of choice while younger ones seek a place to finally
fit their families, it has come to this:
</P>
<P>
   One day last month in Westchester County, N.Y., a desperate
young woman knelt on the porch of a four-bedroom home in
Hastings-on-Hudson and slipped photographs of her children under
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted the house so badly,'' said Robin Friedman, the
manager of the Houlihan/Lawrence brokerage office in nearby
Irvington. ``They obviously were hoping to pull at the seller's
heartstrings. Unfortunately, they did not make the highest offer
and did not get the house.''
</P>
<P>
   The home, which Friedman described as a ``nice split-level,''
sold for $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   All across the region, because of a confluence of mostly
propitious economic forces, the squeeze is on _ and what spurts up
are prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburban arc around New York City, according to data
collected by the National Association of Realtors, the median price
for existing single-family homes hit $208,000 in 1999, an 11
percent rise over 1998 _ and nearly triple the nation's 3.9 percent
rate of increase. ``Virtually every area around New York City was
close to double digits in increases,'' said Dr. Fred Flick, the
association's vice president for economic research.
</P>
<P>
   The median price for Nassau and Suffolk Counties, for example,
rose by 9.7 percent in 1999, to $197,000. Westchester County's
average price ascended to $458,981, a 15.1 percent increase. In New
Jersey, the median price for Middlesex, Hunterdon and Somerset
counties, computed together by the National Association of
Realtors, jumped to $221,000, a whopping 23.3 percent increase over
1998 _ nearly six times the national rate of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   And while that New Jersey statistic was certainly the extreme,
it was also the point of the arrow for the region. For the second
straight year, according to another measure of the market, the Case
Shiller Weiss repeat-sales survey, every one of the 576 ZIP code
areas in 14 counties that constitute most of New York City's
suburban ring saw prices appreciate in 1999 _ 396 of them by at
least 8 percent. (Statistics for several areas, including all of
Rockland County, were incomplete.)
</P>
<P>
   That boon _ for sellers _ rides atop a historic boom.
</P>
<P>
   January was the 107th month of the nation's economic expansion,
the longest ever, surpassing the 106-month period from 1961 to
1969. ``So, 31 days into the 365,250-day-long millennium, we break
the record,'' said Dr. James Hughes, the dean of the Rutgers
University School of Planning and Public Policy. ``What a way to
start a millennium!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think 3 percent was the maximum growth rate for the
gross domestic product,'' Dr. Hughes said. ``But we closed out the
millennium, the fourth quarter of 1999, with a GDP growth of 6.9
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And housing certainly went along for the economic ride,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the national median price for existing
single-family homes set a record last year, so, too, did sales
volume. There were 5.19 million resales in 1999, said Dr. Flick of
the National Association of Realtors, breaking the record of 4.97
million sales set in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, national sales of newly built homes also set a
record last year, breaking the 1998 mark. ``In the last four
years,'' said Steve Berman, a statistician in the residential
construction branch of the Census Bureau, ``we have had four of the
best six years ever for sales of new homes since the beginning of
time _ which for us is 1963, when we started the survey.'' There
were 907,000 new homes sold in 1999, topping the record of 886,000
sold in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``So don't be surprised,'' Berman said, ``that given last year's
numbers, when combined with the record for existing-home sales,
that the nation's homeownership rate hit an all-time high.'' The
old record, set in 1998, was 66.3 percent of all households owning
their own homes, he said, ``and it hit 66.9 percent in '99.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, sales activity has been feverish throughout most of
the country; regional records were set in the Midwest and South,
and the West enjoyed its third-best year ever. Less obviously,
sales volume has been somewhat dampened in the Northeast, and in
the metropolitan region in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason, as Rae Rosen, senior regional economist for
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, sees it, is that ``in some
sense, we're landlocked _ in the city, but also in many older
suburban areas.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the view of Patrick O'Keefe, executive vice president of
the New Jersey Builders Association, the dearth of development is
attributable to stringent zoning regulations and open-space
preservation. In New Jersey, for example, O'Keefe said, ``housing
production is down 36 percent, decade to decade,'' from 37,900
units a year during the 1980s to 24,000 in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has acted to push up prices.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying forces of the housing market, Dr. Hughes at
Rutgers said, ``have been job and income growth, the wealth effect
from the stock market and consumer confidence, all reinforcing the
other force _ baby boomers trading up at a furious pace.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the baby-boom generation will range in age from 36 to
54. ``The older boomers are locked into the houses they want, so
they are not selling,'' Dr. Hughes said. ``The younger boomers are
trying to settle into the communities where they can finish raising
their families. So we're short of product.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom has it that rising mortgage rates stifle
demand, and interest costs for the standard 30-year, fixed-rate
mortgage have certainly risen recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, we are at four-year highs for the 30-year fixed
mortgage, hovering near 8.3 percent,'' said Keith Gumbinger, vice
president of HSH Associates, a mortgage statistics company in
Butler, N.J. ``There's been a long, steady climb since October of
1998 when we achieved 31-year lows of 6.68 percent.'' During 1999,
the low mark for a 30-year, fixed-rate mortgage was 6.84 percent on
Jan. 31; the high was 8.31 percent on Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Rising home prices and mortgage costs do, of course, take ``some
of the marginal home buyers out of the market,'' Gumbinger said,
but house-hungry, thick-walleted buyers have, literally, adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steady rise in fixed rates,'' Gumbinger said, ``has given
some resurgence to adjustable-rate mortgages'' _ or ARMs _ a
mortgage product that, at least to begin with, offers a lower-cost
alternative to traditional fixed-rate financing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gumbinger said, about 30 percent of mortgages being
originated ``have some form of adjustable rate, up sharply from the
10 percent in January '99.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the reasons home sales have not cooled too much
despite the climb in interest rates,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
