<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-APARTMENT-SEARCHING-N     03-25 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APARTMENT-SEARCHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING AN APARTMENT ACROSS FROM THE OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One problem with being young, hard-working and
successful in New York is that there is no time to find a place to
live, especially when the best apartments seem to be snapped up
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Suzanne Melbinger, who is 31, was living on West
23rd Street in a two-room suite for $2,500 a month at the Chelsea
Hotel that she had taken after a three-year sublet on a Midtown
studio ran out. She was thinking she would find a more permanent
place when she had a spare moment, but she never did. Her job in
sales for Bliss, a company with spas and spa-related products,
consumed her.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a place found her.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, Bliss had moved from downtown Manhattan to
Dumbo, a gritty waterfront section of Brooklyn that takes its name
from its location, down under the Manhattan Bridge overpass. As
time wore on, Melbinger grew increasingly attracted to the
neighborhood. Only someone who has relished the intensity of
Manhattan would describe Dumbo, with its spider's web of highways
and bridges, as a quiet haven, but that is exactly how she
experienced it.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, her co-workers began checking out a building across
from their office on Washington Street that was being converted
into rentals by the developer David Walentas. They kept urging her
to look at it, she said, but ``I wasn't paying attention.''
Finally, she went over to take a look.
</P>
<P>
   What she found was stunning to someone used to living in small
spaces. For $300 more than she was paying in Manhattan, she found a
loft with almost 1,500 square foot, exposed wood beams, new
oak-strip floors, a bedroom, a large office and an open kitchen
with cherry wood cabinets, stainless-steel appliances and an island
topped with black granite.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later she went back with her longtime boyfriend,
Anthony Ancona, a partner in Fountainhead, a wine store in East
Norwalk, Conn. ``We just fell in love with this building,'' said
Melbinger, who grew up in Locust Valley on Long Island. They moved
into the seven-story brick building Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there was much to move. Both are avowed minimalists,
and neither has lugged around the artifacts that tend to create
clutter. Although they do not always live together _ Ancona has a
small apartment in East Norwalk _ this is the first place they are
really sharing, she said, and they are furnishing it with a few
carefully chosen things.
</P>
<P>
   On the kitchen counter is a perfect cream-colored pitcher. A few
candles sit on a bench in the foyer. A Shaker-style dining room
table on wheels was built from a kit. They bought some stools for
their kitchen counter, and they have ordered some couches.
</P>
<P>
   And that's about it. ``We don't want to overfill the room,'' she
said. ``We want to keep it as spacious as it is.'' For the first
time, they will be able to have big dinner parties. ``We love to
entertain, and we've never had the opportunity to do so,'' she
said. In the studio they had sublet, they tried, she said, but
``two people couldn't be in the kitchen at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially rewarding to someone accustomed to Manhattan are the
closets. The large coat closet in the foyer, three times the size
of a garden-variety urban coat closet, is filled with her coats and
shoes (all black).
</P>
<P>
   Although the neighborhood is hectic during the week, and newly
renovated office spaces are filling up, weekends are still quiet,
and traffic is sparse. ``I like to walk down the middle of the
street,'' Melbinger said, giving a tour of her neighborhood. ``It's
cobblestoney.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Dumbo is perfect. ``What is lacking here, obviously, is
food,'' she said. For a supermarket, she must walk 10 minutes, to
Brooklyn Heights. From her apartment, she can see one of the few
restaurants, the Between the Bridges Pub, framed by the
Brooklyn-Queens Expressway and the Manhattan Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   She chose an apartment with a view of traffic rather than of
Washington Street, she said, because she was adamant about one
thing: Despite her obvious pleasure in her work, and her attachment
to her company, she did not want to actually look at her office
from home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
