<HEADER>
A7953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0326-COX     03-25 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOST TENSE DAY AWAITS POPE AS HIS PILGRIMAGE ENDS
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox Newspaper
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Israel On this, the final day (Sunday) of his
pilgrimage to the Holy Land, Pope John Paul II will likely face the
trickiest political challenges so far as he visits some of the most
important religious sites in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The pope will be in Jerusalem's Old City, a walled district that
has been at the center of religious and political conflict for
centuries. He plans to visit the Western Wall, sacred to Jews, and
the Dome of the Rock, sacred to Muslims. Then, he will deliver a
mass in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, the dim and cavernous
church where Catholics believe Jesus was crucified.
</P>
<P>
   But the grueling itinerary , which has apparently weakened the
already frail pope, will be made even more difficult because of a
controversial statements published Saturday by a Muslim cleric who
is scheduled to meet with the pope today.
</P>
<P>
   Ikrema Sabri, the top Muslim cleric in Jerusalem, is quoted by
an Italian newspaper as saying that Israelis exaggerated the number
of Jews killed in the Nazi Holocaust in order to get political
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, the number was less than 6 million and Israel is
using this issue to get sympathy worldwide,'' said Sabri,
confirming the statements to the Associated Press. Sabri was
appointed Grand Mufti of Jerusalem by the PLO which is headed by
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Sabri's comments were sure to anger Israelis and put pressure on
the pope for a responsejust the kind of political dispute the
pontiff has been struggling to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Just Thursday, the pope made a historic and dramatic statement
at Jerusalem's Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial museum. There, he said
the church was ``deeply saddened'' by Catholic persecution of the
Jews. He also noted the ``millions'' of Holocaust victims and said,
``no one can diminish its scale.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was seen by Jewish leaders as an an important
message, though the figure of 6 million was already
well-documented.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Reuters, Sabri also said there could be
clashes between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in the Old City.
He said Palestinians are angry about strict Israeli security
measures including the closing of shops on the pope's route for the
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Old City is populated by Palestinians who oppose
Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert Saturday night said, ``We will
address anything that comes up and I'm sure we'll be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   This tense final day comes after the pope avoided politics in a
visit Saturday to Nazareth, another site of religious
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The pope delivered a mass in the Basilica of the Annunciation,
the church on the site where Catholics believe an angel told the
Virgin Mary that she would give birth to the son of God.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps feeling the stress of a grueling itinerary, the pope
spoke in an especially hoarse voice. His hands shook more than
usual an apparent symptom of Parkinson's disease (cq. Eds: The
Vatican has never confirmed that he has Parkinsons).
</P>
<P>
   Nazareth, an Arab city of about 70,000, was once mostly
Christian but is now about two-thirds Muslim and the two groups
have been involved in a series of religious skirmishes
</P>
<P>
   The pope, for example, rode his popemobile on a street where
Muslims have made a makeshift mosque. Local Christians argue the
mosque is too close to the basilica where the pope spoke and is
meant only to intimidate Christians. Last Easter nearby
Christian-owned shops on the street were vandalized during a
rampage by Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   But people of both faiths gave the Pope an enthusiastic welcome
Saturday. Inside the basilica, the pope focused his message on the
``mystery'' of the Immaculate Conception and urged followers to
``defend the family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Nazareth, where Jesus began his public ministry, I ask Mary
to help the Church everywhere to preach the 'good news' to the
poor,'' the pope said. ``I ask her to teach us the way to humble
and joyful obedience to the gospel in the service of our brothers
and sisters without preferences and without prejudices.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Christians and Muslims lined the street to the
church to get a glimpse of the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``His visit gives the people of Nazareth a feeling of love,''
said Muslim Fakri Fahoum, 27, who stood on a stack of spare police
barricades to get a view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beneficial, the visit, because it helps people understand
that we are not interested in any fights, we just want to live in
peace,'' said Greek Orthodox Christian Katy Tanus, 23.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
