</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-SAVANNAH-STATE0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savannah State baseball's 37-0 run is new mark
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Can a college baseball team go a full season
without a loss?
</P>
<P>
   Before you automatically say no, consider that Savannah State
University already is 37-0. After a streak like that, 13 more wins
doesn't seem all that impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good enough to win them all,'' leading-hitter Brett
Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this team, nothing would surprise me anymore,'' coach
Jamie Rigdon said. ``Who would have believed that we'd have won
this many in a row? Before the season, I was just hoping for 40
wins. I didn't know they'd come at the start of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers are still three short of that number. But who's
counting? Oh, just about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, no NCAA Division I or Division II team had
won more than 34 consecutive games in a season. Texas did it in
1977, and Florida Atlantic matched the Longhorns last year.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah State broke that record last Sunday, completing a home
sweep of Maryland-Eastern Shore with a 24-2 rout that took the
suspense away early. The Tigers had plenty of time to plan their
postgame Gatorade drenching of Rigdon to celebrate the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 35 wins, they could have come by and punched me,''
Rigdon said.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't find Savannah State in the national rankings, and
the Tigers won't qualify for the postseason, no matter how many
more games they win.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah State is caught in NCAA limbo. The school is leaving
Division II for Division I, but the move won't be finished for two
years. Right now, Georgia's oldest public historically black
college is stuck between the two classifications, not eligible for
the postseason in either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a few players because they thought there wasn't
anything to play for here,'' Higgins said. ``That is their loss,
not ours. They cared about themselves more than the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought in some good players,'' Rigdon said, ``but the
hardest recruiting I had to do was convincing some of the ones
already here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Rigdon, in his fourth season at age 27, is the unlikely coach of
a very unlikely baseball powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The graduate of Lakeside High School outside Augusta came to
Savannah State to play basketball, as one of the Tigers' few white
recruits ever. He had averaged 27 points per game as a high school
senior, and he was burned out on baseball after playing that sport
for two seasons in junior college.
</P>
<P>
   But Rigdon broke his foot and soon found his hoop dream ended.
He asked baseball coach Wesley McGriff for a tryout and found his
love for that sport rekindled _ so much so, that he stayed around
as an assistant coach after playing for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   When McGriff left in 1996 after winning his third Southern
Intercollegiate Athletic Conference title in a 5-year span, Rigdon
was promoted.
</P>
<P>
   Rigdon's second team won 25 games in a row and finished 39-9.
Last year, Savannah State won its fifth consecutive SIAC title and
made the NCAA Division II Tournament for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were 108-38-1 in Rigdon's first three seasons. But
this year's team was missing the entire pitching rotation from
1999, plus star outfielder Brandon Jackson, who signed with the
Anaheim Angels after being drafted in the 16th round.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins, a senior catcher from Cleveland and the Tigers' top
returnee, conceded that he was afraid the team might start slowly.
He shouldn't have worried.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah State swept Edward Waters 15-0 and 12-0 in an opening
doubleheader. The Tigers hit five home runs to back the shutout
pitching of freshman Ricardo Castillo and junior-college transfer
Guy Thigpen.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins is batting .558 with 16 homers and 77 runs batted in.
Castillo, a native of Venezuela who started only two games as a
high school senior in Miami, is 15-0 with a 1.58 earned run average
and three one-hitters. Thigpen is 13-0 with a 1.49 ERA. The team is
averaging 13 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah State's student body of 3,000 is about 90 percent
African-American, but the Tigers' baseball team is more diverse.
The 21-man roster includes six whites and two Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wins have no color,'' Rigdon said. ``I don't think being a
white coach at a black school is any advantage or disadvantage. I'm
just looking for the best ballplayers. Nothing else matters to me
or the players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets along,'' said Thigpen, who grew up in Alabama
and went to junior college in Florida. ``We are all here to win as
a team.''
</P>
<P>
   And to play at Savannah State, which has a limited baseball
budget, means playing without a full athletic scholarship. ``You
pay the price to play here,'' Rigdon said. ``There isn't a lot of
money to spend.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes the Tigers' success even more amazing. Nine of their
wins have come against Division I teams. They have beaten Florida
A&AMP;M twice, rallying to force extra innings and winning 17-16 at
Tallahassee on Derron Street's two-run homer in the 10th. Savannah
State's biggest comeback came against St. Augustine, from a 9-2
deficit to win 12-9.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah State president Carlton Brown, who has seen the
school's other athletic teams struggle, gets carried away when he
talks about the baseball success.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're operating with almost no scholarships, aren't eligible
for any championships or postseason play, had some players leave,
and still they're winning,'' Brown said. ``To set an NCAA record is
a fantastic accomplishment. But to set it in the way that this team
has may be the most phenomenal story ever told.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
