u s BC-GLF-BELLSOUTH0326-COX     03-25 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BELLSOUTH0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top players now switching from BellSouth
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The BellSouth Classic golf tournament is an undeniable
success. It sells out every year. It generates nearly $1 million
dollars a year for charity. It has produced high-profile champs
Tiger Woods, David Duval and John Daly.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a controversial move from Atlanta Country Club in
1997, it has maintained a reputation as a solid PGA Tour event at
the Greg Norman-designed TPC at Sugarloaf.
</P>
<P>
   But what about that can't miss pre-Masters date? Moving the
BellSouth from May to the week before the Masters was expected to
produce some of the top fields on tour. It was advertised as a
perfect tune-up for Augusta with similar playing conditions, and
the pros could play in Duluth on Sunday and eat in Augusta on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't worked out that way. The pre-Masters date, under
contract through 2002, is costing tournament officials big-name
players, including Woods, who uses the week to prepare for Augusta.
Woods chose not to defend his 1998 title last year and has said he
has no plans to change his pre-Masters routine.
</P>
<P>
   And he is not alone. When the BellSouth Classic begins on
Thursday, only seven of the world's top 20 golfers (19 of the top
50) will compete, one week after 49 of the top 50 played in The
Players Championship. Some simply take the week off. Others prepare
for the Masters. And some say that Sugarloaf's hilly terrain is too
physically demanding the week before a major.
</P>
<P>
   Even Davis Love III, a Georgian who has been loyal to the
Atlanta tournament, will not play this year. He does not want to
risk his conditioning or spasm-prone back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be rested and have some energy going into Augusta,''
Love said. ``Give me a golf cart, and I'll play it (Sugarloaf)
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some players who don't play because of the golf
course,'' said Stewart Cink, a Sugarloaf resident and runner-up to
Duval last year. ``It's a tough walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the field includes some interesting players _
course designer Norman; defending champion Duval; Masters champion
Jose Maria Olazabal; Casey Martin, who will use a cart; Gary
Nicklaus, Jack's son; and Nick Faldo, who continues to search for
the ingredients that brought him three Masters and two British
Opens.
</P>
<P>
   The late commitments from Phil Mickelson (No. 12), Jesper
Parnevik (No. 8) and Fred Couples (No. 20) certainly enhanced the
event, but, unfortunately, Woods has become the No. 1 barometer for
field appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people understand,'' tournament director Dave Kaplan
said, ``that as long as we're in this date, unless Tiger changes
his (tack) for the Masters, we're not going to get him. But even if
we were to move (the date), there's no guarantee that we would get
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The BellSouth also has been affected by some uncontrollable and
unfortunate timing. Kaplan thinks more of the top players would
have entered the tournament for the annual last-gasp chance to get
into the Masters. But the Masters' decision not to exempt
tournament winners took care of that.
</P>
<P>
   And while the pre-Masters date provides a natural playing
opportunity for European players, the two biggest draws, Sergio
Garcia of Spain (No. 14) and Scotland's Colin Montgomerie (No. 3),
are not playing this year. Montgomerie played Atlanta last year but
reduced his 2000 schedule. Garcia said he will practice with
Australia's Aaron Baddeley at the Golf Club of Georgia next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to play three tournaments before the Masters,
with the Masters being the fourth,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Some players bypassing Atlanta used to play the week before the
Masters when New Orleans occupied BellSouth's spot. But English
Turn in New Orleans is a flat course, unlike Sugarloaf, which has
more than nine miles of hilly terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy Waldorf, a first-round leader in the '99 BellSouth, played
last year because he did not have an invitation to Augusta. This
year, he will play in Augusta _ and skip the BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the old course (Atlanta Country Club), and I like the
new course,'' said Waldorf, a first-round leader in the 1999
BellSouth. ``But Augusta, to me, can be a draining week. I think
Atlanta's a pretty good preparation (for the Masters), but I'm
looking at it more from energy and being fresh for Augusta.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the BellSouth, not enough players feel the
same as Cink and two-time U.S. Open champ Lee Janzen, who tend to
play better at the end of long stretches. The first seven times
Janzen won on tour, it came on the fourth or fifth consecutive
event on his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always skipped the week before the Masters,'' Janzen
said. ``But Atlanta is so close, and I've played Augusta so many
times now, I figured last year it's better I play the week before,
just so I don't get to Augusta too early.... I think Sugarloaf's an
awesome golf course. It's hard for me not to play because I like it
so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
