u s BC-CAR-FORMULA-ONE-NYT &LR;      03-25 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FORMULA-ONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMULA ONE HOPES RACE AT INDY STIRS U.S. GROWTH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN U. BACON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ Last weekend's Australian Grand Prix
opened the Formula One season to the delight of auto racing fans in
every westernized country except the United States, where Formula
One is still largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   That might change before this season ends because the tour will
make its first trip to the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Sept. 24.
The Speedway has sold more than 200,000 tickets to the event, a
Formula One record.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind Formula One's surging popularity is Bernie
Ecclestone, a Napoleonic figure who effectively took over the
wayward sport two decades ago. He instilled discipline, unity and
aggressive marketing strategies to push auto racing to the
forefront of European sports sections and television stations,
behind only soccer. Ecclestone stands just over 5 feet tall, but he
is one of the most intimidating figures in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his ultimate challenge will be getting a foothold in
America.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Ecclestone officially became the vice president of the
international automobile federation _ and unofficially, the most
powerful man in the sport. According to Russell Hotten, author of
the book ``Formula One,'' Ecclestone oversees everything from site
selection to hotdog-stand location.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, Ecclestone needed all the power he could muster
because the sport was a mess. Cheating was rampant. One creative
team attached a bottle full of water to the chassis to meet the
minimum weight requirement, then punctured it during the race to
make the car lighter. And Formula One had no process to handle
violations It was not uncommon for teams to skip races.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Ecclestone claimed for himself the power to negotiate
Formula One contracts on appearance fees and television rights,
ending the era of every team for itself. Now Formula One has a
consistent schedule of 17 races, all two weeks apart, and all 11
teams have committed to running two cars in every race for the next
10 years, assuring future stability and bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   Ecclestone invested $18 million for in-car cameras to give
viewers a better feel for the sport's speed. Although pit stops are
technically unnecessary, Ecclestone requires one per race because
television viewers like them.
</P>
<P>
   Hotten estimates the operating costs for a Formula One team are
$50 million to $100 million a year, with McLaren and Ferrari
putting up more.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Forbes magazine ranked the driver Michael Schumacher
the world's fourth-richest sportsman, and in London, The Sunday
Times estimated Ecclestone was among the 20 wealthiest Britons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
