<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-FANS0326-COX     03-25 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-FANS0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pros are dealing with a new hazard on the course these days _
unruly fans
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ When golfers step up to the 17th tee
today at The Players Championship, they'll be dealing with more
than the wind, water and sand. Add another natural hazard to the
game and to the famous island hole:
</P>
<P>
   The fans.
</P>
<P>
   No longer do they applaud good shots and quietly shake their
heads at bad ones. Now golf fans boo, jeer, harass, heckle and even
confront players as if this were a World Wrestling Federation card.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the price of success. Thanks in large part to Tiger
Woods' emergence, more fans have been introduced to the sport the
past few years, and these newcomers have brought along a different
code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Mark O'Meara, who got steamed Tuesday after his tee
shot at the 17th landed in the rough inches from the water and a
man in the gallery said, ``Good thing you can putt.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, who has won 16 times on the PGA Tour, stopped and
wheeled around. ``Good thing I can what? Who said that?''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of other fans, O'Meara found the wise guy:
73-year-old Dan Breen. O'Meara motioned Breen onto the tee, then
handed him a 7-iron and a ball. Breen's shot never came close to
the green, landing in the water, much to the approval of the
roaring crowd.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara strode off to the green, then turned and smiled: ``Oh
yeah, good thing you can putt.''
</P>
<P>
   This exchange _ during a practice round _ says plenty about how
things have changed on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're getting fans who have never played the game before or
are just coming out to experience the game, to just come out and
throw a few back with their buddies,'' Woods said. ``Fridays are
the worst days, because a lot of the guys get off early with their
buddies. They come out and have a few (beers) and say a few things
they shouldn't say.''
</P>
<P>
   NO ONE'S SAFE
</P>
<P>
   No longer are their barbs reserved for their popular target,
Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, who has been a favorite target of
American fans in the past because he often speaks his mind. In the
past few years, such marquee players as Woods, Greg Norman, David
Duval and Phil Mickelson have found themselves in ugly
confrontations with the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Abusive fan behavior reached new heights _ or lows _ at recent
Ryder Cups, where patriotism mixed with alcohol has created an
explosive backdrop. But some players, such as Montgomerie, can
expect to hear abuse at any tournament.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's Bay Hill Invitational in Orlando, tournament host
Arnold Palmer was so concerned about the threat of heckling to
Montgomerie that he paired himself with the Scot during the first
two rounds. There were no incidents, but Montgomerie was quick to
point out: ``This isn't September of an odd-numbered year,''
referring to when the Ryder Cup competition between the United
States and Europe is held.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie constantly sparred with fans at last year's Ryder
Cup near Boston. But he has tried a different approach when
problems arise on the course in regular events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You rarely see me saying anything on a golf course now,
compared to what I did five years ago,'' he said. ``I've decided
that my caddie should take the flak, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie has had no major problems during past Players
Championships, but he said the par-3 17th has created difficulties
for players, partly because fans wager on which player will hit the
green or land in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie praised tournament officials this year for planting
a hedge and bushes behind the 17th tee to give players more room
from the gallery. But that won't stop some of the obnoxious fans
from yelling a little louder, and those are the ones PGA Tour
veteran John Cook said should be told to leave.
</P>
<P>
   'I RESPECT YOUR HOUSE'
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our house,'' Cook said. ``We invite you into our
house, you respect what we do. I go to your house, I respect your
house.''
</P>
<P>
   It's common for athletes to be heckled in other sports, but
golfers say the nature of their work makes confrontation hard to
handle. There's no way to get rid of the built-up anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other sports if you have a problem with a fan, your
adrenaline is already pumped up,'' said Lee Janzen, who won the
Players in 1995. ``In golf, if you get pumped up because of an
altercation with a fan, you have pretty much no chance of hitting
your next shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Players point out that fans who cross the line are a small
percentage of the gallery, but it only takes one. Just ask
O'Meara's 17th-hole critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lesson today,'' said Breen. ``When Mark O'Meara
hits a shot, don't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
