<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ORLEANS-REAL-895(     03-25 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ORLEANS-REAL-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: FROM CAN FACTORY TO APARTMENTS IN NEW ORLEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREA NEIGHBOURS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Hoping to attract as tenants young professionals
who have been filling suburban apartment developments, a prominent
local developer is turning the landmarked American Can Factory in
the heart of the city into an upscale residential complex with
supporting retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   The project, with 265 apartments and at least nine retail
establishments planned, speaks to the potential that developers see
in some declining urban neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned for the last 13 years, the federally designated
historic complex and brownfields site reflects the decay affecting
parts of the Mid-City area. In 1989, a fire destroyed all but the
exterior walls of one of its six buildings. Canning operations
dating to 1906 have left lead and asbestos on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Upper-middle-class communities flank the project on the north
and west, with low-income and middle-class neighborhoods on the
east and south.
</P>
<P>
   The American Can Factory ``is a building crying out for what
we're doing and a neighborhood crying out,'' said Pres Kabakoff,
co-chairman of Historic Restoration Inc., the developer. ``It's a
symbol of either the success or the demise of the neighborhood,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kabakoff expects to repeat with American Can the success of
earlier factory renovations like the Cotton Mill Apartments, which
he developed as an anchor for the New Orleans Warehouse District, a
once-blighted neighborhood now thriving with art galleries and
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   American Can's lofts and one-, two- and three-bedroom units will
range from 1,050 to 1,450 square feet. A one-bedroom unit will rent
for $900 a month, with two bedrooms at $1,250 and three bedrooms at
$1,500. A subsidized one-bedroom unit will rent for $450.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 444,000 square feet of space to be renovated sits on
7.1 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The new apartments complement the residential flavor of
Mid-City. American Can is within a mile of the central business
district, New Orleans City Park, the New Orleans Museum of Art and
the Fair Grounds Race Course, where the annual jazz and heritage
festival rocks the city each spring.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-City is experiencing a resurgence in residential interest.
The number of home sales has increased on average by 2.8 percent
annually over the last seven years, according to Historic
Restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Can gives people the opportunity to move back to
town, to live in a building with character in a true diverse
neighborhood without a commute, and you're two minutes from the
Interstate,'' said Conrad Abadie, president of the Faubourg St.
John Neighborhood Association, one of several Mid-City groups.
</P>
<P>
   Abadie's group worked with the city's Historic Districts and
Landmarks Commission to preserve the buildings for residential
development and to block proposals that would have torn down the
buildings to make room for a big-box retailer like Wal-Mart.
Construction of the factory dates from 1906 to 1929, with the
earliest buildings using bricks and a timber frame, and later
additions using a brick-on-concrete technique.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the renovation will be to protect the architectural
integrity of the buildings, said Kelly Nicklas, the project's
architect. ``The buildings themselves will dictate the layout of
the units,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Architects will carve out the units around existing pillars,
trying to incorporate the cement or long-leaf pine pillars as a
visual element in as many apartments as possible.
</P>
<P>
   American Can relied on some 1,200 industrial-strength windows,
many with bays measuring 18 feet long by 10 feet high, to ventilate
the factory, which was not air-conditioned and which at its peak
employed 1,500 people and operated 24 hours a day. Taking advantage
of the views provided by these massive steel windows, the
developers have designed each unit to have at least one window per
room.
</P>
<P>
   All of the buildings maintain the traditional American Can
Factory look: clay red brick, white trim and pilasters, and
historic New Orleans weathered green window frames. Everything
previously painted will be painted again, while everything
unpainted will remain that way. Existing factory signage marking
the walls, including exit indications and load limitations for each
floor, will remain as permanent references to the buildings'
industrial past.
</P>
<P>
   From the front of the building, the Orleans Avenue side, the
complex's low facade will showcase the 19,000-square-foot
commercial component of the project. Historic Restoration's retail
plan calls for one anchor tenant _ a Blockbuster- or Starbucks-type
store that would draw a wide range of customers _ and seven or
eight additional tenants, which could include a neighborhood
restaurant, salon/spa, cleaner, bookshop and gardening operation.
</P>
<P>
   Parking was expanded from the typical 1.2 spaces per unit to 1.8
after pressure from Abadie's group. Ultimately room for 450 cars
was made through interior garage facilities and outside spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Boettner, Kabakoff''s co-chairman at Historic Restoration,
described prospective tenants as young professionals and
empty-nesters. Such tenants, Boettner said, would be willing to pay
approximately 15 percent more in rent than they would at a suburban
complex to get the larger spaces, mid-city convenience and fine
finishes, including granite counter tops, that the complex will
offer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nick Silvy, a New Orleans native, is at the top of a growing
waiting list for the units. Silvy, a former homeowner, was
attracted by the convenient location and design of the apartments,
which he characterized as a blending of old and new. ``It's got the
high ceilings, natural materials, large spaces, wonderful outside
area,'' he said. ``You get the loft idea, but it doesn't feel as if
you're living in a warehouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other builders had tried to develop the American Can
project but failed to come up with the necessary financing.
Kabakoff used public-private partnerships to finance the deal. His
first mortgage consists of $29 million in tax-exempt bonds from the
state of Louisiana's private activity bond cap program. The program
mandates that 20 percent of the housing units be set aside for
low-income renters.
</P>
<P>
   Additional financing includes a $6.5 million second mortgage
from the city of New Orleans, $7.5 million of equity capital
invested by Historic Restoration's investment partner, Housing
Horizons, a subsidiary of Kimberly-Clark Corp., and a $500,000
federal brownfields grant. The brownfields program offers
incentives to find new uses for abandoned industrial sites with
mild environmental contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Zurawel, vice president of Citywide Testing and
Inspections Inc., an environmental consulting company hired to
resolve environmental concerns at the site, said that the American
Can site was cleaner than other sites in the city. ``There's not
much here in the ground or in the soil; what there is is lead or
asbestos,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Working under a new state voluntary clean-up program, Zurawel's
company has undertaken a $2.25 million effort to totally remove the
asbestos and remove or encapsulate all lead-based paints from the
buildings. The environmental remediation is well under way, and the
official ground-breaking date for the renovation is scheduled for
April 5. Historic Restoration plans to have tenants settled in by
fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kabakoff, New Orleans has been losing 10,000
residents a year for the last 25 years, which has shrunk its middle
class and its tax base.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Mark Morial, noting that a wider variety of housing in the
suburbs contributed to this urban exodus, said that the recycling
of the old American Can plant ``gives us the medium-upscale rentals
that young professionals, young couples and artists can afford.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
