<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1ST     03-25 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A HOMECOMING ACROSS THE PACIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS ``Hideki'' to ``Hideo'' in 14th graf of 2nd take.)  
(ART ADV: Photo of Bobby Valentine greeting fans in Tokyo is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For one epic year, Bobby Valentine embraced Japanese
baseball, thinking he was importing his American ways. He wound up
realizing there are other ways to play this game.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the New York Mets has now returned to his other
baseball home, with all the exuberance of a child waking up on a
birthday. This week, Valentine is proudly leading his team on a
road trip that may be the next step toward a stronger bond between
the baseball continents. Saturday night at a news conference here,
Valentine, speaking in Japanese, said he was glad to be back.
</P>
<P>
   Monday and Tuesday, the Mets and the Chicago Cubs will play
alternate exhibitions against the Seibu Lions and the Yomiuri
Giants, and on Wednesday and Thursday, the Mets and the Cubs will
play regular-season games against each other. This will be the
first time a so-called major league game has ever been played
outside the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The trip will be an ordeal for the players, some of whom are not
amused. Mark McGwire was so opposed to it that he blocked the
Cardinals from taking part, and has criticized the venture as being
driven by money. Valentine concedes that the Pacific Ocean will be
a major block to interleague play, but he said, ``Eventually
they'll have medicine to deal with jet lag.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the Americas are already linked in the fertile mind of
Valentine, the first American manager ever imported to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   His tenure lasted one year, 1995, but his love for Japan was
just beginning. He mingled. He questioned. He won. He lost. And he
brought things home with him.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent spring training in Florida, Valentine held what he
called ``shag-free practices,'' meaning his pitchers do not loll
around the outfield, shagging flies during batting practice. This
is a direct benefit of Valentine's year as the manager of the Lotte
Marines in the Chiba prefecture of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we get into the weight room or the video room,'' he said.
``We try to use the time more beneficially.''
</P>
<P>
   The cliche from Americans is that the Japanese place too much
stock in the 1,000-grounder workout that leaves players bowed and
bloody.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, people prepare as a group,'' Valentine said. ``Their
practices are very long, almost to the point of monotonous. I think
they do it to excess, but we were not practicing enough.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to Japan as a celebrity, having managed six years for
the Texas Rangers and one year with the Mets' Norfolk farm club. He
was a new link between the two continents in a sporting
relationship that began in 1867, when American merchants and
sailors brought the game here. In the second half of the 20th
century, the Japanese began hiring American players.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Yonamine, born in Hawaii of Japanese descent, played 13
years in Japan, spoke the language fluently, and managed the
Chunichi Dragons to a pennant in 1974. Joe Lutz, who had once
coached in Cleveland, managed the Hiroshima Carp briefly in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Don Blasingame, the veteran second baseman from the United
States, played three years with the Nankai Hawks of Osaka, stayed
to coach and manage them for over a decade, and in 1979-80 managed
the Hanshin Tigers. The popular Blazer tried to buck the system by
not overworking his pitchers and playing what he felt was a
consistent lineup, but he resigned after little more than a season.
</P>
<P>
   Never had Japan recruited a manager directly from the United
States until Valentine was courted by the management of Lotte, a
department-store empire with roots in Korea. The general manager
was Tatsuro Hirooka, a former star shortstop and championship
manager _ ``one of the first players to move into management, a
very proud man, impeccable dresser, from the old school,''
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine argued with umpires until he realized he was getting
nowhere, since he did not speak Japanese and also because a temper
is decidedly counterproductive in that country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to fit in in Japan,'' Valentine once said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He studied the language via a computer program, with the side
result of becoming hooked on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He also noticed the way Japanese bunters do not waste motion by
squaring and pivoting but rather tap the ball from the more natural
batting stance. He has found resistance in teaching that technique
to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was fascinated by the rituals _ the organized
cheerleading sections, often organized by the corporations that own
the teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear 10,000 strong, waving flags, doing the wave, blowing
trumpets, it's disconcerting at first,'' Valentine said. ``But it
is part of the game, it's part of the culture. They love sumo
wrestling, and now they have soccer, but for a long time baseball
was their only team sport, so they took parts of all our team
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Lotte, they Americanized their game,'' Valentine
added. ``They got rid of the big, heavy drum. They would sing `Take
Me Out to the Ball Game' in the seventh inning, which was neat.
They had songs for the individual players. They made great puns on
the two languages. There was a guy named Iya Omura, so they would
sing `Old MacDonald Had a Farm' and they would chant `Iya-Iya-O.'
It was kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also had fun trying to personalize the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was riding the trains with the fans, talking to kids, all my
idle time out in public,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He smiles when he recalls the numerical approach, how in pregame
meetings his coaches would predict the score, saying it felt like a
6-1 game. To the American ear, that sounded impossible, given the
inconsistencies of pitching, but the coaches were serious.
</P>
<P>
   In Lotte, Valentine had a three-year contract to transform Chiba
Lotte from ``second-class citizens,'' but while the Marines
finished second behind Seibu in his first season, he and Hirooka
were already at odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hired me, he fired me, we had a falling out at the end,
regretfully,'' Valentine said the other day. ``It's the only
blemish on my experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese baseball has stayed with him. He has gone back on
scouting and good-will missions and has been welcomed by Shigeo
Nagashima, the great third baseman who now manages the Yomiuri
Giants, the Yankees of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine questions the traditional view that the Japanese are
too small to hit for power. Also, competition has narrowed the
baseball gap between nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, if you were behind Nagashima with the Giants,
you stayed in the system forever,'' Valentine said of the Japanese
farm system. ``Now it's loosened up. As some Japanese players come
to the U.S., that develops more exceptional young players.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine praised unrelated players named Matsui: Kazuo, a
shortstop with Seibu ``who rivals Rey Ordonez in the field,'' and
Hideo, an outfielder with the Giants ``who hits for power and
average, the kind of player any manager would love.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we only had three non-Americans, the way they do, I believe
the Japanese league would be stronger than ours,'' Valentine said,
acknowledging the impact of Latin American stars like Sammy Sosa,
who will be a star attraction this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' manager does not foresee ``a true World Series'' in
the short run, but adds, ``What we are doing is the closest thing
to it _ two American teams playing two Japanese teams just before
the season, not just all-star teams. The real thing. I'm going to
play these games like World Series games.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, he plans to go out and mingle. Many players may
regard this expedition as a pain in their sleep cycle, but for
Bobby Valentine, this is a homecoming, deeply anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll sleep on the plane home,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 1809EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-NFL-CRIME0326-COX     03-25 2269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-CRIME0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH POST, Fla. _ For the next four days, NFL owners and
head coaches will gather at The Breakers hotel for the league's
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will open the meeting,'' NFL vice president Joe Browne said
proudly last week, ``with the backdrop of the 1999 season.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, for better and worse, quite a backdrop. Attendance
reached an all-time high, and TV ratings were up on three of four
networks. The product kept fans interested from the season's
opening kickoff to the very last play _ a touchdown-saving tackle
at the Georgia Dome to finish off what was instantly dubbed the
best Super Bowl ever.
</P>
<P>
   As Kurt Warner, the supermarket-stockboy-turned-MVP, stood at
midfield amid a shower of glittering confetti, praising God, family
and football, it appeared the NFL would head into the off-season
with a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happened again.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later, the warm-and-fuzzy images of Warner
were pushed aside and replaced with cold-and-bloody reports from
the Cobalt Lounge in suburban Atlanta. Two men had been stabbed to
death. Three men would be arrested and charged with murder. One of
them was Ray Lewis _ a 24-year-old linebacker with the Baltimore
Ravens who led the NFL in tackles in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This is the backdrop that Wayne Huizenga, Jerry Jones and the
rest of the NFL owners will be standing in front of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Never has the NFL looked so good on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Never has it looked so bad off it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, front-page headlines proclaimed that crime
in Florida had hit a 28-year-low. Meanwhile, the sports section
included an update on former Dolphins running back Cecil Collins _
one of more than two dozen NFL players arrested since NFL owners
gathered in Phoenix last March.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't necessarily the numbers that are troubling, though. It
is the kind of crimes NFL players are being charged with. Battering
wives and girlfriends. Sexually assaulting strangers. Even plotting
to kill a pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis became the second active player in three months to be
charged with murder. In November, after police found Rae Carruth
hiding in the trunk of a car, they charged the Carolina Panthers
receiver of plotting the murder of Cherica Adams, his pregnant
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The result is, at the very least, a public relations nightmare.
Turn on talk radio and you hear hosts and fans joking about ``the
National Felony League.''
</P>
<P>
   Trace Armstrong, a Dolphins' defensive end and president of the
NFL Players Association, points to other headlines _ from Columbine
to Oklahoma City _ and says that violence is a problem in all of
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a problem germane to the NFL,'' Armstrong
said. ``I think when you look at the overall conduct of 1,600
players, it's very good. But certainly there are incidents that
have given the league a bit of a black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   OFF-THE-FIELD CONDUCT
</P>
<P>
   For years, NFL officials have reacted to questions about
off-the-field violence with a mix of defensiveness and denial. And
when asked during Super Bowl week about the fact that the rosters
of the two teams included 13 players with rap sheets, NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue said: ``I think our track record is
better than society in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is true depends on whose statistics you use and how
you interpret them. Pros and Cons, a 1998 book about NFL players
and crime, said that 21 percent of the players in the NFL in 1996
and 1997 had been arrested for serious crimes at some time during
their lives. The NFL says that in 1999, only 29 of its nearly 2,000
players were arrested, down from 37 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the programs we have are working,'' said Harold
Henderson, the member of the league's executive management council
who is spearheading talks on off-the-field conduct. ``The numbers
are coming down.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even as Tagliabue and his staff argue that it's not as bad
as it looks, they realize that the league has a problem on its
hands _ one that is perhaps more challenging than drugs, gambling
or any previous issue the league has dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-February, two weeks after Lewis was charged with murder,
Tagliabue called his staff together and discussed the league's
response to off-the-field violence. Earlier this month, he and
Henderson met with players union head Gene Upshaw and several
current and former players in New York. Two weeks ago, the league
issued its first suspensions under a 3-year-old anti-crime policy.
And when the owners and head coaches gather in Palm Beach, one of
the items atop the agenda will be to discuss off-the-field conduct.
</P>
<P>
   For the Wednesday morning meeting, a gathering restricted to
head coaches and primary owners, Tagliabue has asked three coaches
_ Baltimore's Brian Billick, Tampa Bay's Tony Dungy and Seattle's
Mike Holmgren _ to bring three assistant coaches and lead a
discussion about off-the-field conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Christine M. Thrower, president and CEO of Women in Distress of
Broward County, which has the largest and oldest shelter for abused
women in Florida, greets this news with a mix of optimism and
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a start,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCHING FOR ANSWERS
</P>
<P>
   For years, it was commonplace for the league to suspend a player
for doing something to his own body _ whether it was injecting
steroids or smoking marijuana _ yet it was unheard of for it to
punish a player for doing something to someone else's body.
</P>
<P>
   Then, before the 1997 season, the NFL became the first league in
major U.S. sports to institute a policy that allowed for penalties
for off-the-field violence. It calls for mandatory psychological
evaluation for any player accused of a violent crime and fines and
suspensions for players convicted of or admitting to a violent
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, until earlier this month, no player had been suspended
under this policy. Even the eventual suspension of Carruth was done
under a more general policy for conduct the league deems
detrimental to its well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see the NFL talking about domestic violence;
maybe other leagues will take notice,'' Thrower said. ``But if
you're not using the rules, what good are they?''
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials say other cases are under review and more
punishment could be on the way. And although there is a wide
variety of opinions on what should be done once an NFL player is
arrested, all agree that the ideal solution would be to find a way
to prevent it from happening in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, one must first figure out why it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not too hard,'' said Dr. Lauren Langman, a professor of
sociology at Loyola University in Chicago who has written several
papers about football. ``Football is not exactly chess. It's not
meant to be terribly cerebral. Basketball players are less likely
to be arrested for violent crimes. That's not to say it doesn't
happen. But it's less likely. Why? Their athletic prowess is based
on speed and agility.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone buys the violence-begets-violence theory.
Armstrong, the NFLPA president, calls it ``garbage.'' And Richard
Lapchick, director of the Center for the Study of Sports in Society
at Northeastern University, said: ``This is a society-wide problem.
... Violence has become a part of our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   A CULTURE OF VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but it has been a part of the NFL culture for quite a
while. It just was limited to what happened on the field. Or was
it?
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Weinstein has been in the business of keeping tabs of NFL
players' off-the-field activities since 1973. He spent 12 years
doing security work for the league, then was hired by the Dolphins
to be the team's security investigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things went on when I worked for the league back in the '70s
and '80s that never got reported,'' Weinstein said. ``Now it's kind
of hard for that to happen. Consequently, the perception's out
there that things are worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein insists they aren't. He says that, in a strange way,
the increase in headlines about domestic violence is a good sign _
it shows that it is being fought more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the '70s or '80s, if someone hit their significant
other and she called the police, they would sometimes come over,
talk to the people and leave,'' he said. ``What happened was wrong.
It just wasn't considered a crime. It was a private matter. Nobody
got arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   And when they did ...
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late '80s, I went down to get a player out of jail on a
domestic violence charge,'' Weinstein said. ``When I saw the
girlfriend, I was embarrassed to get the guy out. I said, 'You've
got to be kidding me.' And she didn't want to prosecute. So they
ended up dropping it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although even today there is much dispute about statistics and
how they should be interpreted, everyone seems to agree on
something. The problems start long before players get to the NFL.
They often begin in impoverished backgrounds, places where the
game's future players are surrounded by examples of crime and
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dolphins cornerback Troy Vincent, speaking to a group of
schoolchildren several years ago, recalled what it was like in his
Trenton, N.J., neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was part of the community to beat your wife, your
girlfriend,'' he said. ``It was cool. When you'd leave home and go
to school, you'd hear some of the guys say, 'Man, I smacked my
girlfriend three times last night.' Then one of his friends gives
him a high-five. That was the way of life. And it wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent eventually severed ties with the childhood friends whom
he felt were a bad influence. Many other athletes have not _ and
these friendships create a sticky issue for the league.
</P>
<P>
   Can it tell players who they can and can't associate with?
</P>
<P>
   GOOD VIOLENCE, BAD VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   These days the NFL tries to help break the cycle of crime with
education. The league conducts a mandatory three-day symposium for
rookies in June at which, Weinstein said, topics range from
``something as innocent as how to handle yourself on a traffic
stop, to staying away from certain areas and, most importantly,
staying away from certain people.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, once the players hit the field, the NFL, whether
intentional or not, often gives them another message: Violence is
good.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, then Jacksonville defensive coordinator Dick Jauron
praised strong safety Donovin Darius, a first-round pick in 1998,
for bringing ``an element of violence'' to the defense. Darius
responded by saying: ``That's the highest compliment I can think
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, even the violence off the field is given approval.
</P>
<P>
   When the St. Louis Rams drafted Ryan Tucker, one of four Texas
Christian players who nearly beat a 21-year-old man to death
outside a bar, Rams coach Dick Vermeil joked: ``He can finish a
fight; that's a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   This leads to another problem with cutting down crime among NFL
players. The league can talk all it wants about an improved
screening process for identifying ``at-risk'' players before they
get in the league. But will teams steer away from those players? If
the player can run 40 yards fast enough or bench-press 300 pounds
enough times, will they even care if there is the potential for
problems?
</P>
<P>
   ``Really what has changed in the last 10 years is that teams are
taking more chances,'' one veteran NFL player said. ``There are
guys being drafted now that teams wouldn't have drafted in the
past. Look at what Jimmy did.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about former Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson. During
four seasons in Miami, Johnson signed running back Lawrence
Phillips and receiver Lamar Thomas, two players with long histories
of domestic abuse; drafted Collins, a player who was arrested twice
during his brief college career for breaking into women's
apartments; claimed Tony Martin, a receiver who was released by the
Atlanta Falcons after being indicted on federal drug money
laundering charges; and signed Dimitrius Underwood, a defensive end
who had disappeared from the Minnesota Vikings camp.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Johnson gave an identical reason for the signing. ``I
think he can be a player,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Thomas and Martin, who was acquitted after a trial that
featured courthouse appearances by Johnson and Dan Marino, remain
on the team. Phillips was arrested in a Plantation bar and charged
with battery of a woman who wouldn't dance with him. Underwood
attempted suicide during the team's bye week last season. And
Collins was arrested after police say he jumped through a window of
a women's apartment. All three eventually were cut by the team, but
some players believe the off-the-field problems took their toll not
only on the team's image but its performance.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Newman, who played offensive line for the Dolphins for 13
years and is now a criminal judge in Miami-Dade County, agrees with
NFL officials who say that the majority of today's players are
good, law-abiding citizens. But he wants to see the league come
down harder on those who commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to pull out the few bad apples,'' he said. ``The
league has the responsibility to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it? This much is certain: When the owners come to Palm
Beach, they will be aware that others perceive they have a problem.
And at least some of them agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have this type of thing,'' Kansas City Chiefs owner
Lamar Hunt said recently. ``We must find a way to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
