<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TROUT-SEASON-PREVIEW-     03-25 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROUT-SEASON-PREVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PLAYING HOOKY FOR TROUT OPENER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York state's trout season April 1 opener falls on a Saturday
this year, sparing young and not-so-young anglers alike the
awkwardness of having to play hooky from school or jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is always risky to predict opening-day stream conditions, and
this year is particularly challenging. Mild weather during the
first few days of March seemed to presage a truly auspicious early
season, as did the winter of 1999-2000, during which there were
only three weeks of bitter cold in the Northeast. The past three
winters in the United States set records for warmth. But before
mid-March this year, a lot of rain fell in the state, and in the
Catskills, streams were close to overflowing. This was followed by
a stretch of cold weather, more rain and some snow.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, barring a blizzard or torrential rain on April 1,
opening-day devotees are going to sally forth no matter what the
weather or water levels. For them, the ritual is not to be missed.
It is a long-anticipated escape from winter's grim embrace, and
this year there are indications that they will find many waters
quite fishable. One fly-fishing expert, Ed Van Put of Livingston
Manor, N.Y., said recently: ``It looks promising on the Beaverkill
and Willowemoc. The streams are high but clear, and there are only
patches of snow in the headwaters of the Beaverkill.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Put, who is a wildlife technician with the state's
Department of Environmental Conservation, also notes that the mild
winter augurs well for the denizens of the streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beaverkill and Willowemoc froze over only once this past
winter in late January, and iceout was a relatively gentle event,''
Van Put said. There was relatively little scouring of the stream
bottoms by ice jams and uprooted trees. Such scouring destroys
aquatic insect life, a major source of food for trout.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day I talked to him, Van Put had seen anglers
fishing the no-kill section of the Willowemoc and added that
throughout the winter, whenever there was open water, anglers would
often be working that stretch or the two portions of the Beaverkill
that are similarly regulated. Fishing with flies or artificial
lures only is allowed there all year and all trout must be returned
to the water. During the regular season, the creel limit on the
remaining portions of many of those rivers is five trout, nine or
more inches long.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Elliott, fisheries manager for the conservation
department's Region 3 (Westchester, Putnam, Dutchess, Rockland,
Orange, Sullivan and Ulster Counties), says that stream conditions
are about normal for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the streams in his area, Elliott said, are going to get
an increase in the numbers of 2-year-old brown trout being stocked,
up from an annual quota of about 12,000 the last couple of years to
almost 17,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are nice fish,'' he added, ``from about 12 to 15 inches
long.''
</P>
<P>
   During the previous two years, about 1,000 of those fish were
tagged and anglers were asked to report catching tagged fish. This
year's stocked trout will not be tagged, but the reporting proviso
for survivors of the previous years' releases holds.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pierce, a conservation department fisheries biologist who
watches over the branches of the Croton River, as well as the
Amawalk, happily reports that ``the city has completed, or nearly
completed, work on the Amawalk dam.'' A reservoir on the Amawalk
and two others on the aforementioned branches of the Croton are
part of New York City's far-flung water system.
</P>
<P>
   The work included construction of a water fountain below the
Amawalk dam that is intended to correct the oxygen deficiencies as
far as trout are concerned, which occasionally occurred in the
first half-mile of the river downstream from the dam.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past,'' Pierce said, ``in late summer, when dissolved
oxygen levels got low in the reservoir, the water was coming out of
the bottom of the dam nice and cold but was nearly devoid of
dissolved oxygen. The fountain should solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a fountain adds atmospheric oxygen to the water, similar to
what happens when wind-driven waves churn the surface of a lake, or
a river tumbles through precipitous rapids.
</P>
<P>
   A section of the West Branch of the Croton _ between Croton
Falls Reservoir and the stream's confluence with the East Branch of
the Croton _ retains its no-kill status this year, lures or flies
only, and regulations on the section of the East Branch from the
East Branch reservoir to the diverting reservoir, remain unchanged:
flies or lures only, open to fishing year-round, and a daily limit
of one trout, 14 or more inches long.
</P>
<P>
   Long Island has three major trout streams, the Connetquot,
Nissequogue and Carman's River, which are almost always eminently
fishable. On Carman's, within Southaven Park, a section is set
aside for fly-fishing only and catch and release. Elsewhere the
daily limit is three trout, 9 inches long or more; and a daily fee
of $2 is required. The number for information is (516) 854-1414.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nissequogue, in Caleb Smith State Park, there are
four-hour daily sessions. Angling is limited to fly-fishing with
barbless hooks and the limit is two trout, minimum length 9 inches.
The fee is $15. Reservations, which are needed, can be obtained by
calling (516) 265-1054.
</P>
<P>
   Intrepid anglers are already flogging the Connetquot _ taking
advantage of its special no-kill, February to March,
fly-fishing-only season that ends April 1. On April 1, the regular
season, also limited to fly-fishing, begins. There are three daily
four-hour sessions ($15 each) and two trout of any size may be
kept. The number for reservations is (516) 581-1005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
