<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-865&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: KEEPING MOSQUITOES AT BAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Ill., Mass., Ark.)  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While mosquitoes are generally not a high-priority
item at this time of year _ in the New York City area, the insects
do not become active until late spring _ some recent announcements
by the city's Health Department may inspire homeowners to launch a
pre-emptive strike against the pests even before they take their
first flight.
</P>
<P>
   On March 9, the Health Department reported that a study by the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention confirmed that
hibernating mosquitoes collected in Queens had low levels of the
West Nile virus genetic material.
</P>
<P>
   While no live viruses were recovered, officials said, the
discovery raises the possibility of a repeat of last year's
outbreak. The virus can cause encephalitis and meningitis. Seven
people died last year, and 62 others became seriously ill as a
result of being bitten by infected mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Though health officials have developed a surveillance and
control plan to prevent a repeat of last year's outbreak, there are
steps that homeowners can take to keep the number of new mosquitoes
at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be the time of year you expect to see
mosquitoes,'' said John Gadd, a spokesman for the Health
Department. ``But it's not too early for homeowners to start their
mosquito prevention efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Pest control authorities say that the best way to reduce the
number of mosquitoes around a home is to remove any standing water.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Potter, an urban entomologist at the University of
Kentucky in Lexington, said that the kind of mosquito identified by
health officials as the carrier of the West Nile virus _ Culex
pipiens, the common household mosquito _ typically lays its eggs on
the surface of standing water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homeowners often don't realize that there are a whole bunch of
places where water might be accumulating,'' Potter said, adding
that while it is unlikely there are any mosquitoes flying around
now, it is only a short time before egg-bearing females will take
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the conditions are right, they'll start laying
eggs,'' Potter said. ``And any eggs they lay will hatch in a matter
of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the likely _ or perhaps unlikely _ places where eggs will
be laid, Potter said, are buckets, birdbaths, pool covers,
discarded tin cans, old tires, cisterns, recycling bins, inverted
trash-can tops, saucers for flowerpots, water that has collected on
top of pool covers and tarpaulins, and even small pockets on
children's toys. One of the most common breeding areas, he said, is
a leaf-clogged rain gutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mosquitoes develop rapidly,'' Potter said, and they can go
from tiny water-bound wrigglers to flying, biting adults in as
little as one week. ``That means that a single neglected roof
gutter can produce hundreds of new mosquitoes each day,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But what can homeowners do if they have an ornamental pond or a
swampy area that is impossible to drain?
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing to consider might be to stock the pond with mosquito
fish,'' Potter said, referring to fish called predacious minnows,
which are about an inch to an inch and a half long and dine quite
happily on mosquito larvae.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative, he said, is to treat the pond or swampy area
with a ``biorational'' insecticide that will kill mosquito larvae
while leaving pets, plants and people unharmed. Products that will
accomplish this, he said, include Bactimos, Vectobac and Altosid,
all of which can be bought from Clarke Mosquito Control Products in
Roselle, Ill., (800) 323-5727; and Mosquito Dunks, manufactured by
March Biological Control in Sherwood, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all essentially harmless to other aquatic organisms,''
Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Ross, the owner of March Biological Control, said that
Mosquito Dunks are similar in size and shape to small doughnuts and
float on the surface of standing water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each dunk will treat 100 square feet of surface water for 30
days,'' Ross said, adding that the product will remain effective
for that period even if the area in which it has been placed _ a
swampy area, for example, or pools that may form along the banks of
a brook or stream _ dries up and then refloods.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquito Dunks are sold in six-packs for about $8.25 and can be
bought from March Biological's Web site: www.marchbiological.com.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have not been able to eradicate mosquito larvae,
there are various products on the market that can be used on adult
insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the products that can be purchased by consumers are
reasonably safe,'' said Timothy Deschamps, a member of the
executive board of the Northeastern Mosquito Control Association, a
nonprofit organization in Northborough, Mass. ``But be sure to
follow the label directions. More is not necessarily better, and if
you use too much, you could end up killing beneficial insects along
with the mosquitoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Deschamps recommends spraying around the bases of shrubs and
high plants because that is where mosquitoes are likely to rest
during the day. And since most mosquito sprays have little residual
effect, he said, it is typically necessary to find the mosquitoes
and make a frontal assault.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One product that does not work very well with mosquitoes,
Deschamps said, is the electronic bug zapper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that a typical backyard bug zapper might get 1
percent of the mosquito population in a back yard,'' he said.
Instead, they attract harmless or beneficial insects like moths and
ladybugs.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one zapperlike product now being marketed whose
manufacturer claims that its mosquito-killing power is considerably
increased by the use of heat and even carbon dioxide to lure its
prey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our machine actually mimics the body temperatures of humans,
cattle and pets, all the things that mosquitoes like to bite,''
said Alvin Wilbanks, the president of Environmental Products and
Research in Blytheville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   And while the device may look to a human like an aluminum
wastebasket with a hat, Wilbanks said, it looks like a human to a
mosquito.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Chandler, the town treasurer of Pollard, Ark., said, the
town bought five of the gadgets last year and has bought five more
for this summer. ``The machines are being used as an alternative to
using airplanes to spray insecticide in public parks. They've
really done the job for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology is not cheap: The basic Mosquito Killer unit
costs $399. A $120 addition that emits carbon dioxide, mimicking
exhaled breath, increases the kill rate, Wilbanks said.
</P>
<P>
   Additional information about the Mosquito Killer can be found at
www.epar-mosquito.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
