u p BC-BUSH-ROGICH-1STLD-WRI     03-25 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ROGICH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGER BUSH LOOKS TO FATHER'S IMAGE BURNISHER
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 4th graf to change focus from advisers to Republican circles;
DELETES pronunciation from 5th graf; ADDS that advisers insist
there are no plans to hire him in 11th graf; CORRECTS ``advisers''
to ``loyalists'' in 1st graf of 2nd take)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Sig Rogich has such a reputation for buffing _ in
some cases salvaging _ the images of big-name Republicans that
former President Bush summoned him from a post as ambassador to
Iceland to try to rescue his re-election drive in 1992. Four years
earlier, Rogich had conceived the legendary Bush commercial that
featured a helmeted Michael Dukakis riding in a tank.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogich's prowess at crisis management is celebrated far
beyond the political world. Three years ago, Mike Tyson, the former
heavyweight champion, turned to him for public relations tutelage
after Tyson gnawed on Evander Holyfield's ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hired me after he bit the guy,'' Rogich recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the chatter in Republican circles is that Gov. George W.
Bush, the party's presumptive presidential nominee, might turn to
Rogich, an advertising and public relations executive, for a
political reconditioning job. Even in victory, the Texas governor
is trying to add gloss to his image after his battering in the
primaries. In an interview on Friday in his Las Vegas office, with
a panoramic view of the hotels and casinos where he has been a
fixture for years, Rogich heaped praise on Bush. He said the White
House was the governor's to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this master at stage managing politicians was not timid
about reviewing discouraging episodes in the Bush campaign that had
weakened the governor's public persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``In campaigns it's the little things that you've got to pay
attention to if you're going to be successful,'' said Rogich, who
counts the singer Wayne Newton as among his close friends and has
served as state boxing commissioner and once owned a slot machine
company. ``Churchill said, `Little things bring empires down.' I've
always believed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogich prefaced his comments about the Bush operation by saying
repeatedly that he did not want to ``second guess'' the team in
Austin. Still, he suggested that had he been managing Bush's public
presentation, as he did with the elder Bush in the White House,
there would have been fewer lapses, and perhaps a crisper message.
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly distressed by the Bush campaign's decision
early this month to allow the candidate to appear before millions
on David Letterman's show on a satellite hookup from St. Louis.
Bush drew devastating reviews for cracking second-rate jokes,
grinning nervously and looking downright mirthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never let the president go on a satellite,'' Rogich
said. ``It doesn't make sense. First of all, the audience is
clapping when you're standing so you don't respond to it because
you're delayed. When he's laughing because he has said something
funny, the audience is finished with the laugh. It's not smart. You
need to get on there in person, be part of the show, stand up and
do a high-five if that's what it calls for _ and sit down. You
never do the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Rogich is not tapped for a formal role _ Bush aides
insist there are no plans to hire him _ he already carries
significant influence with the Bush family: He checks in with
former President Bush every week or so. He said he got to know Gov.
Bush ``quite well'' during the 1988 campaign. And he does not
hesitate to dispense tips to the candidate directly or in e-mail
notes to the chief strategist, Karl Rove.
</P>
<P>
   Rogich would not reveal what those pointers are. But he said the
Bush campaign needed to be more aggressive at defining the governor
_ and highlighting his most captivating qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The George Bush that I knew was a fun guy to be around,'' he
said. ``He's got a nice sense of humor, a nice way about him and a
deep compassion. Now, they need to get on message. They need to
talk about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogich made clear that he did not have much use for Bush's
``Reformer with Results'' slogan, which the campaign unveiled in
the wake of Sen. John McCain's upset in the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably appropriate at the time,'' he said. ``I'm not
sure it stays in play.'' Picking his words carefully so not to
sound too dismissive, he said, ``Some of the themes we've done in
the past have a little more poetic side to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamenting the absence of the rallying cry of ``compassionate
conservatism'' that for so many months had been the Bush campaign's
signature, Rogich said: ``That's a terrific slogan. The word
compassion is something that is important in people's lives. You
could almost drop `conservative.' That's how good the word is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogich also confessed that he was bewildered by Bush's failure
to be more magnanimous to McCain and his followers in a recent
interview with The New York Times in which the governor allowed
that he had learned no lessons from his vanquished rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to naturally reach out to bring your enemies, or
opponents, into the fold,'' he said. ``The smart candidates reach
out a little more. It's all about winning: At the end of the day,
there's a column that says, `Won' or `Lost.' I just would have
liked to have seen a little more harmony at the end of it. But
you've got to remember that McCain didn't reach out, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its imperfections, Rogich, who is 55, said the Bush
campaign should hardly feel desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a second expansive wave of talent that comes in
to take part,'' he said. ``So I think those problems take care of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was critical that the campaign broaden its inner
circle, explaining: ``This is not a training ground. This is the
big leagues. They've got six months now to put this package
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Might his services be part of that second wave? ``It's not
really something I'm thinking of doing,'' he said. ``But I'm going
to be there to help them in any way I can.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Told that his name seems to keep resurfacing among Bush
loyalists, he said: ``I'm flattered. But they've done pretty well
without Sig.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rogich, hardly out of the picture, is keeping an especially
close eye on Vice President Al Gore. While Gore has provided ample
grist for damaging commercials from the Bush camp, he said there
was nothing as potent as Dukakis in a tank, an advertisement that
ridiculed the former Massachusetts governor and, many believe,
contributed to his defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that they've made gaffes that I've seen per
se,'' Rogich said of the Gore camp. He said of Gore: ``I think he's
articulate. He's very smart. He's sincere. He's a little over the
top on certain issues but he comes at them from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogich said that unlike Bush, the vice president ``comes across
too cold and is tough to warm up to.'' Rogich does give Gore credit
for shedding his blue suits for casual apparel and favoring earth
tones. ``Changing the dress a little bit was a smart thing to do,''
he said. ``It just lightened him up.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the time President Bush was wearing an unsuitable
tie when he was about to address the House about the Persian Gulf
War: ``I said, `Take my tie!'''
</P>
<P>
   That blue tie is now framed at the entrance to Rogich's office.
There is also a note from President Bush about the tie: ``It just
sent the right message to Saddam Hussein. Thanks, Sig.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about doing something about the attire of the younger
Bush, who favors off-the-rack suits? ``Everybody keeps asking me
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the governor is really a product of the East Coast,
Rogich, who favors Italian suits and Hermes ties, added, ``Most
Eastern people do need a little help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
