<P>
   (NYT21) HAVANA, Cuba -- March 25, 2000 -- HAVANA-REVIEW-3-B&AMP;W
--In Havana, everything waits. Forty-one years after Fidel Castro
came down from the hills to claim Cuba's then-vibrant capital, the
island has become, says photographer Stephen Crowley, ``a giant
waiting room.'' Over the last 10 years, Cuba has lost its place in
the superpower confrontation and lost its life-sustaining subsidies
from the Soviet Union. Cubans have made lives out of waiting. Under
the harsh tropical light, only the architecture seems alive. But
the people of Cuba, together, yet alone, wait as if suspended in
time, in the calm before the storm. A couple on a beach in Havana.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
