<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 25, 2000 -- DORISMOND-FUNERAL-5 -- The
funeral of Patrick Dorismond, the unarmed son of Haitian immigrants
who was shot to death in a confrontation with New York City police,
on Saturday fired up both Haitian protest and pride. An angry crowd
burned an American flag draping his coffin and mourners clashed
with police in riot gear after a procession that began with Haiti's
national anthem. Demonstrators break through police barricades,
above, outside the Holy Trinity Church in Flatbush, Brooklyn.
Below, police officers rush to the aid of a fellow officer as
violence erupted. (Ruth Fremson, top, Alan Chin, bottom/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NAZARETH, Israel -- March 25, 2000 -- POPE-2 -- Cheered
by a mixed local crowd of Muslims and Christians, Pope John Paul II
appeared for one moment to have erased the religious rifts in this
ancient city as he came to celebrate Mass in Nazareth on Saturday.
The pope's visit was seen primarily as a gesture toward Israel's
dwindling number of Christians, who once dominated Nazareth and the
Galilee region. Local Christians worry that they have become a
minority within a minority, now barely 10 percent of an otherwise
Islamic Arab population in a state that is five-sixths Jewish.
(Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 25, 2000 -- DORISMOND-FUNERAL-4 -- On
a day of solemnity and outrage that degenerated into violence, the
body of Patrick Dorismond, the unarmed son of Haitian immigrants
who was shot to death in a confrontation with New York City police,
was laid to rest on Saturday. Dorismond's coffin was carried across
Brooklyn and surrounded by some 15,000 anguished mourners and angry
protesters along the funeral route. Before and after the funeral,
several clashes between protesters and police took place. Family
members at the Cypress Hills cemetery in Queens pay their respects
to the son of one of Haiti's most beloved singers, Andre Dorismond.
(Alan Chin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 25, 2000 -- DORISMOND-FUNERAL-3 -- On
a day of solemnity and outrage that degenerated into violence,
Patrick Dorismond, the unarmed son of Haitian immigrants who was
shot to death in a confrontation with New York City police, was
carried across Brooklyn, eulogized as a martyr and laid to rest
Saturday by 15,000 anguished mourners and angry protesters. Before
and after the funeral, there were brief clashes between protesters
and police. A young man wrapped in the Haitian flag watches the
funeral procession, Saturday. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MYSTIC, Conn. -- March 25, 2000 -- AMISTAD-RECONSTRUCT-2
-- The Cuban schooner Amistad, whose cargo of rebellious African
slaves galvanized pre-Civil War abolitionists and made the ship an
enduring symbol of freedom's triumph, has been reconstructed with
painstaking attention to historic detail. The vessel will be used
as a floating classroom, traveling from port to port to teach the
Amistad story. The new Amistad docked in Mystic, Ct., at the
dedication ceremony, Saturday. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) JOELTON, Tenn. -- March 25, 2000 -- CHRISTIAN-HUNTERS-2
-- Trying to build a bridge between Christianity and outdoorsmen,
with the overall theme of hunting and honoring family, the
Christian Sportsmen's Fellowship uses hunting and fishing
illustrations to convey the love of God in terms many men can
relate to. The fellowship, an evangelistic organization based in
Atlanta, has nearly 300 local affiliates in the United States.
Guests at a recent fund-raising dinner at the Joelton First Baptist
Church, which featured such concoctions as elk chili, deer sausage
and barbecued black bear. (Christopher Berkey/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON, D.C. -- March 25, 2000 -- BUSH-ROGICH -- Sig
Rogich, left, an advertising and public relations executive, when
he was working with President George Bush in 1991. In 1988, Rogich
helped Bush with a legendary commercial that featured a helmeted
Michael Dukakis riding in a tank. Chatter among Texas Gov. George
W. Bush's advisers is that the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee might turn to Rogich, for a political reconditioning job.
Even in victory, the Texas governor is trying to add gloss to his
image after his battering in the primaries. (Jose R. Lopez/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MYSTIC, Conn. -- March 25, 2000 -- AMISTAD-RECONSTRUCT
-- The Cuban schooner Amistad, whose cargo of rebellious African
slaves galvanized pre-Civil War abolitionists and made the ship an
enduring symbol of freedom's triumph, has been reconstructed with
painstaking attention to historic detail. The vessel will be used
as a floating classroom, traveling from port to port to teach the
Amistad story. Samuel H. Pieh of Tennessee, a descendent of Sengbe
Pieh, the slave known as Cinque who led the Amistad mutiny, at
Saturday's dedication ceremony of the ship in Mystic, Conn. (James
Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 25, 2000 -- DORISMOND-FUNERAL-2 -- The
coffin bearing the body of Patrick Dorismond, the 26-year-old son
of Haitian immigrants, who was shot to death in a confrontation
with New York City police, in which he was unarmed, arrives at the
Holy Cross R.C. Church in Brooklyn on Saturday. The funeral
procession was surrounded by thousands of mourners who came out to
express both their grief and anger. At least four police officers
were injured and two people were arrested. Witnesses described
scenes of tense confrontation and tumult: bottles smashing on the
street, American flags burned and a rain of curses falling on
police and an absent Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani. (Andrea Mohin/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 25, 2000 -- DORISMOND-FUNERAL-1 -- On a
day of solemnity and outrage that degenerated into violence,
Patrick Dorismond, the unarmed son of Haitian immigrants who was
shot to death in a confrontation with New York City police, was
carried across Brooklyn, eulogized as a martyr and laid to rest
Saturday by 15,000 anguished mourners and angry protesters. Before
and after the funeral, there were brief clashes between protesters
and police. At least four officers were injured and two people were
arrested. Some of the signs carried by Dorismond supporters read,
``You didn't protect him, you killed him!'' and ``Giuliani must
go!''. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 25, 2000 -- USAIRWAYS-ACCORD -- US
Airways and its flight attendants reached an agreement early
Saturday, averting a strike against the nation's sixth-largest
airline. The union held a candlelight vigil early in the morning at
New York's La Guardia Airport. The accord gives the airline's
10,000 flight attendants a substantial raise, which was one of the
main demands of the Association of Flight Attendants, while US
Airways said the deal helped advance its primary goal, to keep its
costs competitive. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAMARA, Russia -- March 25, 2000 -- RUSSIA-VOICES --
Pollsters and analysts claim that Vladimir Putin, the 47-year-old
former KGB agent who took over as acting president of Russia last
New Year's Eve after just four months as prime minister, has
managed to remain remarkably popular precisely because he has
religiously shunned any one ideology. But almost a continent
westward, in the Volga River town of Samara, Boris Fursov, a
retired Soviet army officer who devoted much of his career to the
Cold War, says Putin's muscular submission of Chechnya is reason
enough by itself to deny him the presidency. ``In Soviet times,''
he says, ``maybe one man could impose order. In a democracy, it is
an entire nation's job.'' (Patrick E. Tyler/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NAZARETH, Israel -- March 25, 2000 -- POPE -- Cheered by
a mixed local crowd of Muslims and Christians, Pope John Paul II
appeared for one moment to have erased the religious rifts in this
ancient city as he came to celebrate Mass in Nazareth on Saturday.
The pope's visit was seen primarily as a gesture toward Israel's
dwindling number of Christians, who once dominated Nazareth and the
Galilee region. Local Christians worry that they have become a
minority within a minority, now barely 10 percent of an otherwise
Islamic Arab population in a state that is five-sixths Jewish.
(Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SHORT HILLS, N.J. -- March 25, 2000 -- WOMEN-VOTERS-2 --
Behind much of the political debate in recent weeks, on issues from
gun control to education, is an intensifying struggle for the
hearts of women, particularly suburban mothers. Ann Brunett and
Donna Dees-Thomases fold T-Shirts and promotional material for the
Million Moms March scheduled for May 14 in Washington. (Dith
Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- March 25, 2000 -- WOMEN-VOTERS-1 --
Behind much of the political debate in recent weeks, on issues from
gun control to education, is an intensifying struggle for the votes
of women, particularly suburban mothers. Vice President Al Gore,
top, greets supporters during the New Hampshire Primary in
February. At bottom, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas meeting
supporters after he spoke at the New Hampshire Federation of
Republican Women Lilac Luncheon in Manchester in June, 1999. (Paul
Hosefros, top, Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   4w
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) JOELTON, Tenn. -- March 25, 2000 -- CHRISTIAN-HUNTERS --
Trying to build a bridge between Christianity and outdoorsmen, with
the overall theme of hunting and honoring family, the Christian
Sportsmen's Fellowship uses hunting and fishing illustrations to
convey the love of God in terms many men can relate to. The
fellowship, an evangelistic organization based in Atlanta, has
nearly 300 local affiliates in the United States. Steve Axley and
his 2-year-old son, Austin, were guests at a recent fund-raising
dinner at the Joelton First Baptist Church, which featured such
concoctions as elk chili, deer sausage and barbecued black bear.
(Christopher Berkey/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SHOALWATER BAY INDIAN RESERVATION, Wash.-- March 25, 2000
-- TRIBE-MISCARRIAGES-2 -- Members of the Shoalwater tribe have
been involved in many struggles over time including economic
survival. But the most difficult battle of all is for the women who
live on the Shoalwater Bay Indian Reservation. The women are up
against an unseen foe, a killer that seems to come and go over the
years, though no one can even prove it exists. For some reason, it
is frighteningly difficult to give birth to a living child on the
Shoalwater reservation. Kim Zillyett, who has miscarried twice, is
expecting in May. ``I did everything I thought I could possibly do
to have a healthy baby,'' says Zillyett. ``It's not over till he's
out.'' (Rick Giase/The Seattle Post-Intelligencer)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SHOALWATER BAY INDIAN RESERVATION, Wash. -- March 25,
2000 -- TRIBE-MISCARRIAGES-1 -- Members of the Shoalwater tribe
have been involved in many struggles over time including economic
survival. But the most difficult battle of all is for the women who
live on the Shoalwater Bay Indian Reservation. The women are up
against an unseen foe, a killer that seems to come and go over the
years, though no one can even prove it exists. For some reason, it
is frighteningly difficult to give birth to a living child on the
Shoalwater reservation. ``You look around the village and you start
asking yourself, 'Where are all the children?''' says Lisa Shipman,
who gave birth to daughter Kaylee last year. (Larry Davis/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
