<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE0326-COX     03-25 2894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonfire safety issues overlooked for traditionBy Mike Ward and
Suzanne Gamboa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ For 40 years, Texas A&AMP;M University
officials knew that the Aggie bonfire was a dangerous and
potentially deadly project.
</P>
<P>
   Despite hundreds of injuries and repeated written warnings of
safety threats, A&AMP;M administrators made preserving the bonfire as a
student-run activity paramount. Official action to deal with safety
issues often was short-lived and poorly enforced, sometimes because
of fear that changes to the revered tradition would upset students
and alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last November, the incomplete, four-tier tower of logs
collapsed. Twelve people were killed and 27 were hurt. The tragedy
reverberated through the tight network of Aggies, who consider the
bonfire a powerful symbol of unity.
</P>
<P>
   University officials have insisted they had no reason to believe
that the bonfire would collapse. But many of more than 10,000 pages
of documents _ memos, letters, manuals and committee reports _ show
that chronic safety risks went uncorrected, partly because of
ineffective oversight by university officials. Preventing injuries,
identifying safety risks and eliminating those risks were largely
left to the students in charge of building the stack, the records
show.
</P>
<P>
   University officials have declined to discuss details of the
bonfire project, citing an ongoing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In January, A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen said he would resign if the
investigation determined that poor leadership or oversight by the
university contributed to the Nov. 18 collapse.
</P>
<P>
   A five-member commission appointed by the university to
investigate the collapse is expected to release its report in early
May.
</P>
<P>
   Retired A&AMP;M professor Bill Stout, who co-chaired a 1990
committee that recommended shrinking the size of the bonfire,
already has an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my personal opinion, if they had followed the
recommendations, there's a good chance that 12 people would be
alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen, working through a spokeswoman, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   WARNINGS WENT UNHEEDED
</P>
<P>
   In February 1960, an aide to the then-military school's
commandant wrote what now sounds like a prophetic warning about the
annual precursor to the Texas A&AMP;M-University of Texas football
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most dangerous parts of the operation is the actual
stacking of the logs on the bonfire itself,'' the aide wrote,
recommending that the height and size of the bonfire be limited.
``We in the Administration owe it to the students to do all we can
to help them construct a bonfire they will be proud of ... However,
we must keep control over them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, more warnings followed, but with little
effect:
</P>
<P>
   After the bonfire reached a record height in 1969 _ 109 feet, 10
inches _ university officials ordered future bonfires capped at 70
feet.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, officials again capped the bonfire's height,
this time at 55 feet. They later acknowledged that bonfires
continued to be built too high.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, a recommendation to reduce the height to 45 feet _
mostly to keep flying embers from starting fires in surrounding
neighborhoods _ was dropped amid fears that shrinking the stack
would anger students and alums and damage the campus tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, a committee of students and faculty members recommended
that the bonfire height be reduced to 44 feet to address safety,
academic and environmental concerns. Then-A&AMP;M President William
Mobley endorsed the change, but it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Texas Fire Chiefs Association executive director
tried to persuade A&AMP;M to build a bonfire out of wooden pallets,
saying such a stack would be ``less difficult to construct and more
structurally stable.'' The recommendation was not implemented.
</P>
<P>
   University officials tout a student-written safety manual as a
key to minimizing the risks of injury. They asked students to
review the bonfire-building operation and update the manual
annually to enhance safety.
</P>
<P>
   In two years, the manual instructed students to build a bigger
fire than was allowed. The collapsed bonfire was headed toward 75
feet _ 20 feet higher than the 55-foot limit.
</P>
<P>
   And even though a faculty adviser has overseen the bonfire for
years, there is no evidence that the adviser was held accountable
for ensuring the university rules were enforced.
</P>
<P>
   A HUGE UNDERTAKING
</P>
<P>
   Putting on the bonfire is a giant undertaking for students,
particularly the so-called senior redpots and other student bonfire
leaders. Their responsibilities include raising money _ usually
tens of thousands of dollars _ lining up equipment, finding a
tree-cutting site, coordinating construction schedules and
enforcing safety rules. Most participants say the exercise has
taught them about leadership, teamwork and problem-solving.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Dollins, who was the 1990 student chair of the Bonfire
Advisory Committee, called the work the most important part of his
education at Texas A&AMP;M. At 20, he was in charge of 5,000 people who
worked at a remote location with chainsaws, axes and machetes,
oversaw the use of $1.2 million in equipment and managed a budget
of tens of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most 20-year-olds in the U.S. don't get that kind of business
background,'' Dollins said.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY OF INJURIES
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, hundreds of students, perhaps even thousands,
have been injured building the bonfire, most during the
tree-cutting phase.
</P>
<P>
   So many people were hurt in the early 1950s that officials one
year ordered all bonfire workers to don coveralls with ``Safety
First'' emblazoned across the back.
</P>
<P>
   Although injuries dropped, university officials still worried.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960 report to the commandant, officials recommended
limits on the height and size of the bonfire. A smaller fire, they
reasoned, would mean fewer logs to be cut, and fewer cuts would
mean fewer injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly if the height of the centerpole is regulated and the
outrageously large logs not permitted to be used on the stack this
will, in effect, limit the size of the bonfire so that each class
will not be attempting to better last year's record,'' the report
stated.
</P>
<P>
   The stack reached 101 feet that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accidents during the construction are a problem and serious
injury or death could easily occur,'' another internal A&AMP;M report
warned in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire topped out at a record 109 feet, 10 inches in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   For some, however, safety concerns were overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety in the stacking area is excellent and the danger
would not be lessened by reducing the height of the bonfire,'' a
March 1972 memo quotes J. Malon Southerland as saying during a
meeting on the issue. At the time, Southerland was the bonfire
adviser. He now is A&AMP;M's vice president for student services, and
the bonfire is among his responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1974, amid lingering concerns, A&AMP;M Vice President John
Koldus decreed in a memo: ``The height of bonfire will be
controlled.'' He set the limit at 70 feet, but it proved
short-lived. In two years, the bonfire height was widely reported
to be 75 feet. There's no evidence in the documents that any
university official was held accountable for the lack of
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   EFFORTS TO IMPROVE IMAGE AND MANAGEABILITY
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire's height and safety remained hot issues in the
1980s. A faculty committee reporting to Koldus considered further
height limits because fewer and fewer students were showing up to
help build the bonfire. The ones who did skipped classes and
neglected homework, hurting their grades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, a student who had been drinking died after falling from
a tractor en route to a tree-cutting site, University officials
promised a crackdown on drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, drunken revelry was mentioned in local newspaper
accounts. Advertisements in the campus paper to recruit bonfire
workers for the cutting phase enticed: ``Bring your axe, your lunch
and your friends. Keg party Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   As flames leapt up the bonfire that year, the plywood outhouse
at its peak _ representing a UT fraternity house and symbolic of
the rivalry between the schools _ toppled from the log stack and
landed on a hard-hatted student. Miraculously, he was not seriously
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kibler became the university's bonfire adviser in 1983. He
later said in a memo to a colleague that he was ``shocked over how
`out of control' the program was in many respects'' when he took
over. He blamed a ``prevailing attitude of animosity, mistrust, and
belligerence'' between bonfire leadership and the university
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1984 memo, Kibler, now A&AMP;M's associate vice president for
student affairs, said that despite changes _ ``part of the overall
effort to improve the image and manageability of Bonfire'' _
problems lingered, including drunken revelry among the student
construction crews. As an example, he cited ``pot passing,'' the
annual ritual where the construction chiefs, known as senior
redpots, designate their successors by passing their hardhats,
called ``pots,'' to junior redpots, who have less experience than
senior redpots.
</P>
<P>
   Kibler described the tradition as ``a raucous nighttime event
involving excessive drinking, unsafe activity on the stack and
axe-handle beatings by the senior and junior redpots. This usually
took place before a crowd and so represents one of Bonfire's most
difficult image problems. ... It is imperative this year that this
activity be brought completely under control so that no violations
of university regulations take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his warning, drinking and horseplay on and around the
stack would continue to plague the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, neighbors and College Station officials were
lobbying the university to find a new home for the bonfire. At the
time, the bonfire was built on Duncan Field, an open space at the
south edge of the A&AMP;M campus that is within shouting distance of a
residential neighborhood and several university dorms and
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Eaton, a vice president for academic affairs and a
resident of the affected neighborhood, warned of the fire danger in
1986: ``As meaningful as this event is to our students, it is
really a tragedy that is poised and waiting to happen,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One report that year noted a ``perception by citizens and the
fire department that the university (students and administration)
does not care about the problems created by Bonfire.'' But another
warned of ``a backlash from students/former students'' if the site
were moved.
</P>
<P>
   In response to university president Frank Vandiver's request to
study relocating the bonfire, two vice presidents said in a
February 1986 memo that the bonfire adviser would enforce the
height limit and ``appropriate safety measures, both during the
cutting and stacking phases of construction.'' Although the pleas
to relocate the bonfire seemed compelling _ a dorm roof had caught
fire from the embers in 1972 _ tradition won out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Aggie Bonfire is one of the most important
traditions at Texas A&AMP;M University,'' began the memo announcing the
decision not to move the bonfire 1986. It would be another decade
before university officials would move the bonfire to the Polo
Ground, a larger field at the northeast edge of the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the very few tangible events that embodies the
Aggie Spirit, while emphasizing the importance of teamwork and
camaraderie,'' said Charles Cargill and John Koldus, the A&AMP;M vice
presidents. ``It should be retained as a viable tradition as long
as it is properly managed and controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert H. Stiteler Jr., a university health and safety officer,
tried in the fall of 1986 to ``minimize accident potential''
related to the the bonfire and asked university officials to reduce
the height of the stack to 45 feet. But Kibler, now associate
director of student affairs, rejected the proposal. As Kibler
explained in a subsequent memo: ``The main objective of the
university is to minimize accident potential by making a reasonable
effort to control the hazards associated with Bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC OUTCRY
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, criticism had reached fever pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, including clergy, were clamoring for the university
to bring the raucous behavior under control. Students, including a
group that called itself Aggies against Bonfire, also were up in
arms about the cutting and burning of thousands of trees.
</P>
<P>
   In response, two committees _ a faculty-student committee and a
Texas A&AMP;M regents' committee _ studied changes in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   None focused on the structural soundness of the log tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally and completely foreign to us that something
like this could happen,'' said Dollins, then the senior redpot
leader who served on the faculty-student committee.
</P>
<P>
   The faculty-student committee came closest to addressing the
structural issue, recommending yet further limits on the size of
the stack.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion was quickly endorsed by Koldus, then vice
president for student services; Kibler, by then associate director
of student affairs; and William Mobley, A&AMP;M's president at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   But the change would never come to pass. Within months, students
objected to the height reduction, and officials dropped the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Kibler declined comment. Koldus and Mobley could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The regents' committee, including Raul Fernandez, who now serves
on the Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board, former House
Speaker Billy Clayton and Houston attorney Ross Margraves, set as
its goal to assure that the bonfire ``will continue to be a safe,
sane, sober and orderly activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee had never met.
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY MANUALS
</P>
<P>
   The annual safety manual, which was to identify, evaluate and
control ``all hazards associated with the Aggie Bonfire ...
according to accepted safety engineering practice,'' focused mainly
on the safe use of chainsaws, axes and tractors. In the 1984
manual, the earliest one still in university files, the hazards
inherent with building the log pile are mentioned in one paragraph
_ without specifics on how to build the stack.
</P>
<P>
   Another section rated the risks associated with the stack
construction as relatively high. To minimize the risks, the manual
recommended allowing only experienced workers on the higher reaches
of the stack and having redpots continuously supervise every step.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1999 tragedy would later confirm, that was not followed.
Freshmen and sophomores were working on some of the highest tiers
of the stack when it fell.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire adviser was responsible for reviewing the safety
manual annually, but in a 1985 deposition, Kibler said he could not
``claim that I look at every letter and every word.''
</P>
<P>
   In some years, it contained incorrect information. For example,
since 1986, the circumference of the bonfire was supposed to have
been limited to 145 feet. But manuals in years since have listed
the limit as 150 and 195 feet.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1988 memo, Kibler said he was enforcing the limits: ``I now
personally measure the height and diameter of the stack during its
construction.''
</P>
<P>
   When the log pile collapsed in November, it was 59 feet high and
headed to 75 feet. Its circumference was about 120 feet. Soon after
the collapse, bonfire adviser Rusty Thompson said he thought the
stack was 55 feet high. He has not elaborated.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   During the '90s, the university began offering a construction
sciences class to teach the student bonfire builders how to oversee
such a large construction project. An improved safety manual was
developed.
</P>
<P>
   Though a professor has said he helped draft diagrams and
specific plans to make the bonfire more structurally sound,
university officials say they have been unable to find any of them.
They have not said whether the plans were used in building the 1999
bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Even in those design changes, tradition was considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we tried to remember was design features were
incorporated without infringing on the spirit and tradition of
bonfire construction,'' former A&AMP;M professor Larry Grosse, who
helped develop the manual recalled in an e-mail to Kibler after
last November's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the changes, problems continued.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the log stack buckled as it was under construction.
Because it did not fall suddenly, no one was hurt, and the bonfire
was torn down and rebuilt within a few days. Some credit the design
changes with keeping the log pile from falling. Others say the
near-collapse was another signal that was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, there are indications that many of design changes
were not adhered to in subsequent years. Scribbled in a diary kept
by one of the 1999 student bonfire leaders is this notation:
``Bonfire is never built the same way twice.'' Bill Stout, the
retired professor who co-chaired the student-faculty committee,
believes the recommendations from 1990 remain a worthy goal: save
the positive aspects of the bonfire, reduce the negatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Bonfire needs to be stopped, ``said Stout, who
taught at A&AMP;M 18 years and donates regularly to A&AMP;M. ``It certainly
needs to be made smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
