<HEADER>
A8000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-BOS &LR;      03-25 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMA, IF NOT OUTCOME, IN RUSSIA VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KLYUCH ZHIZNI, Russia _ Barring a spectacular upset, Russian
voters Sunday will choose as their president a man they barely
know, one whose views on running the world's largest country remain
a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The acting president, Vladimir Putin, is the hands-down
favorite; his election has become a foregone conclusion. The event
is a huge milestone in Russia's 1,000-year history, the first
change in Kremlin leadership to take place by popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   But if the outcome of the presidential election is clear, that
does not mean there is no drama.
</P>
<P>
   The suspense is about how this steely former KGB agent plans to
deal with the world's other nuclear superpower _ and with his own
people _ once he is armed with the popular mandate that a majority
vote would give him.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders, and undoubtedly some Russians, will be watching
for clues on whether Putin might steer Russia toward integration
with the rest of Europe or whether he might turn to Soviet-style
rule _ authoritarian and isolationist.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of other Russians _ teachers and mushroom vendors,
television salesmen and lion-tamers _ will also be watching. But
most will be thinking little about Putin's KGB past, his foreign
policy ideas, or his relative commitment to democratic freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   In the heartland south of Moscow, voters from all walks of life
said last week that they long for a leader whom they can trust,
someone who can help drag their lives out of the circle of poverty,
corruption, and chaos that has characterized post-Soviet Russia.
</P>
<P>
   To assume that Putin is the answer to their problems is a leap
of faith, especially when his own connections to the ``oligarchs''
_ the business tycoons whom Russians blame for most of their
problems _ have hardly been dispelled.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters seem to realize that. These are people who have been
badly treated, time and again, by their leaders. Dozens of
interviews found that many of the Russians on Putin's bandwagon
appear to be reluctant riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not fooled,'' said Anna Lazareva, 72, who was selling
marinated mushrooms for the equivalent of a dollar a jar on a
roadside near Klyuch Zhizny, a farming settlement 250 miles south
of Moscow with a name _ it means ``Spring of Life'' _ that belies
the village's decrepit appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Putin is the favorite because he is the one we
see most often,'' Lazareva said.
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to the way Putin has capitalized on the
popularity of his military campaign against rebels in Chechnya with
a blitzkrieg of tough-guy promotional stunts and straight-talking
promises, which are displayed nightly on three news networks.
</P>
<P>
   Polls put Putin's support at about 50 percent, more than double
that of the nearest of his 10 competitors, the Communist leader
Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   The only questions Sunday are whether the required 50 percent of
Russia's 108 million registered voters will turn out to make the
election valid, and whether Putin will get his victory right away
by gaining 50 percent of the vote, or whether he will get it in a
lopsided runoff contest with Zyuganov on April 16.
</P>
<P>
   Whizzing around in jet fighters, promising to crack down on
corruption and make life better, Putin has captured the imagination
of Russians disenchanted by the last four years of the Yeltsin
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   They are people like Boris Biryukov, one of Russia's most
renowned lion tamers. Biryukov nearly died the last time he was in
the cage five years ago, when one of his eight lions, realizing
that the aging trainer had lost a step, took a swipe at him. He
managed to fight the 350-pound beast to a standstill, and escaped
only slightly mauled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin reminds me of the way I was with my lions,'' said
Biryukov, now the director of the circus in the regional capital of
Voronezh, 300 miles south of Moscow. ``When you go into that cage,
you have to show them who is boss or else they'll rip you apart.
Putin is like that. He knows how to turn the screws, and he'll help
us straighten out this mess. He's not afraid of lions.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a young lion snaked his paw out of his cage and made
a nasty slash in the jeans of a photographer standing too close.
Taking it in stride, Biryukov was marveling about how difficult it
must have been for Putin to fly in a spartan military jet,
something he has done twice in impromptu visits to military units
in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The flights have made at least as much of an impression on
voters as Putin's visit March 18 to Voronezh. People seemed to draw
conclusions about how Putin would run Russia from the way he has
overseen the Chechen campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What impressed me about Putin was his trip to Chechnya on New
Year's eve, when the rest of the country was getting drunk,'' said
Vera Avdeyeva, a geography teacher in the town of Khokol, 25 miles
west of Voronezh. ``He looks like someone who will be active, who
will make people care.''
</P>
<P>
   Khokol, like so many rural Russian towns, is a tangle of
rambling wooden huts, crumbling cinderblock apartments, and piles
of junk lying around rusting. Most of its food-processing factories
are unable to make payroll and probably should be bankrupt. (Only
one factory, Khokhol Sugar, has been declared officially
insolvent.) Like most of Russia, the town rarely finds the money to
pay its teachers their $35 a month salaries on time.
</P>
<P>
   Avdeyeva became a celebrity of sorts last year, after a Russian
television station did a story about how she had to donate blood to
get cash for a couple of hot dogs and margarine for her New Year's
meal. A Danish TV station picked up the story, and soon after,
Avdeyeva received a wire transfer of 150 Danish crowns (about $25
at the time) from a well-meaning Danish couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was very suspicious,'' Avdeyeva said as she shivered
last week in the unheated geography lab of Khokol's High School No.
1. ``The bank wanted to know why I was getting money from abroad.
It took them two days to sort out whether they could actually
release the money, even though there's nothing in the law that says
I can't have friends in Denmark.''
</P>
<P>
   Avdeyeva is counting on Putin to make laws in Russia work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might even help that he was in the KGB, from the point of
view of discipline and thoroughness,'' she said. ``I'm hoping he
turns out to be a decent man. Otherwise, there's no hope.'' But she
is not counting on things getting much better soon.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that impoverished people in Russia voted for the
Communists, but that is no longer necessarily the case. Perhaps
because Voronezh has a Communist governor, or perhaps because they
have been voting for Communists in parliamentary elections since
1993, people here see Zyuganov as a representative of the status
quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``People voted for him, but he sits around in Moscow in
Parliament and nothing changes,'' said Sergei Lavrov, who was
selling television sets in Yelets, a small industrial city in the
heart of Russia's fertile Black Earth region, 200 miles south of
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The television sets are made by a local factory that, like many
Russian enterprises, pays its workers in kind. Other employees in
Russia get paid in toilet seats, sex toys, and crystal vases, among
other things. Motorists occasionally stop to buy the televisions,
which are fitted to work in cars. Lavrov, a former factory worker,
makes 5 percent on each set he sells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this is not a market economy, this is something
primitive and fundamentally wrong,'' he said as he gazed at the
rusted metal garages, ripped military tents, and rickety lean-tos
where a dozen other television vendors sold the same sets. ``But I
don't know if anyone here thinks Putin will get around to fixing
our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   It was getting late at Klyuch Zhizny, and Anna Lazareva was
gathering her jars of mushrooms to take inside the one-story house
she shares with her son's family of seven and their dog, Mukhtar.
Her son, Anatoly, a farmer who gets paid in flour and feed from
what is left of the local collective farm, was explaining the
tragic story of the town's oddly beautiful name.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that a wealthy 19th-century merchant built a pond
for his sick wife and called it ``Spring of Life,'' because
spending time there miraculously made her feel better. In fact,
local historians say that the merchant was a cruel man who refused
to accept his son's marriage, driving the son and his wife to
commit suicide. The merchant then refused to take in his
grandchildren, and instead built an orphanage for them. To comfort
his wife, he built the pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, Putin is a bit like that merchant,'' Anatoly
said. ``But we don't know if we're getting the one from the fairy
tale or the one from real life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
