<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' BRYANT BLOSSOMING INTO STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is 21, and the world already is his stage as he blithely
dances through it with a gladness peculiar to his modest age.
</P>
<P>
   The aging process hasn't even begun to work its cruelties on
him, and he dashes around basketball courts throughout America in a
frenzied ballet of soaring leaps and acrobatic moves that excite
the multitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just love basketball,'' he says. ``Want to be the best at it.
Will be the best at it. Only a matter of time. I'm learning all the
time. Getting better. But still got a lot to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant smiles, and it's the contented, confident, knowing
smile of a youngster who is worth millions of dollars and who is on
the best team in the NBA and who is rapidly emerging as one of the
top performers in his industry.
</P>
<P>
   He is standing in front of his dressing cubicle in the Staples
Center locker room of the Los Angeles Lakers on a recent evening,
and I ask him what he does for enjoyment when he isn't playing
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that during the season basketball is my
total life,'' he says. ``I don't get away from it very often. Oh, I
do go see a movie once in a while. I usually go in after it starts,
and sit in the back. Don't want to cause any commotion. Just me
sitting in the back alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant is as eligible a bachelor as there is in Southern
California, but he doesn't go clubbing, doesn't pursue women and
doesn't engage in the temptations that are available in the garish
nights to athletes with such wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in L.A., I mostly stay home with my family and when
I'm on the road I mostly stay in my room,'' he says. ``I like
reading. I watch some TV. But my main priority now is basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has become uncommonly proficient at it in the past few
weeks as he has played with an unselfishness that was noticeably
missing in his game in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all been a maturing process,'' says Bryant. ``I'm seeing
things now that I didn't in the past. Remember, when I was in high
school, I was called upon to do everything. And then, suddenly, I'm
in the pros, but I still have that same mentality. That's the only
way I ever knew how to play. I felt I had to do everything. It took
me time to learn that I don't have to do that here.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 21, and he and Shaquille O'Neal have become the most
overwhelming force in basketball, The Combo, as O'Neal has dubbed
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's energy is unbelievable,'' says Jerry West. ``He's just
all over the floor when he's playing. There's a chance he can make
the all-defensive team this season. Not bad for a kid 21.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing well together,'' says O'Neal. ``I'm proud the
way Kobe has matured.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an almost overnight metamorphosis.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, Kobe Bryant still was taking too many
wayward shots that did nothing but anger his coach, Phil Jackson,
and his teammates, still was dribbling too often into traffic,
still was committing too many turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   He even was bawled out for his undisciplined antics by O'Neal
after a home game on Jan. 19 against the Cleveland Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   He constantly was being railed from the sidelines by Jackson,
and even was yanked out of several games as punishment by Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But no more.
</P>
<P>
   He suddenly has turned into the Lakers' top passer, and even has
been the beneficiary of some extraordinary passes himself,
especially from O'Neal, since teammates have detected the dramatic
change in his style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there was some frustration by teammates,'' says
Bryant. ``Listen, I was frustrated, too. I just want to win. I want
to do everything I can to help us to win. And, if it means me
passing more, I will. I don't mind that a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among the sporting pundits is that Kobe Bryant
could be duplicating the well-publicized accomplishments of
Toronto's Vince Carter if he weren't on a team that featured
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather be a one-man show like Vince Carter, or would
you rather play in the shadow of O'Neal?'' I ask Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' he says. ``I like it just the way it is. I'd much
rather be on a team that can win the NBA title. Winning is fun.
I'll have my time in the sun. Remember, I'm only 21. One day,
Shaquille O'Neal will be gone, and I'll still be here. And I'll
still be pretty young.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though Kobe Bryant is being ignored.
</P>
<P>
   You're not ignored in the NBA when you're averaging more than 22
points and making dazzling shots and passes that elicit applause
from the patrons and hand-slaps from teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time's on my side,'' he says. ``My goal still is to be the
best basketball player in the world, and I work to reaching that
goal every day. I'm learning more all the time. And I'm having a
lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 21, and it's all going his way, including time, his most
blessed ally. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
