<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN PAKISTAN, TALKS OF INDIA PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD _ Ending his six-day visit to the South Asian region
that he recently dubbed ``the most dangerous place in the world,''
President Clinton stopped here briefly Saturday to speak frankly
with its new military leader and directly to its citizens, urging
an end to violence and a return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do not,'' Clinton warned, ``there is a danger that
Pakistan will be even more isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has shown concern over the heightened
conflict between Pakistan and India over the disputed territory of
Kashmir, and about the possibility that the dispute could escalate
to involve nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of his remarks, from a 10-minute nationally televised
address to about 100 minutes of meetings with the military leader,
General Pervez Musharraf, was in striking contrast to his speeches
in India since Tuesday, all of which have emphasized the potential
of the Indian-US relationship. The statements on Pakistan seemed to
carry a threat of diminished or severed ties if Islamabad does not
do what the United States wants.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton will arrive in Geneva to meet President Hafez
al-Assad of Syria. Clinton has been a prominent force trying to
promote peace in the Middle East and Northern Ireland, and seemed
eager to add Kashmir, the disputed territory occupied by both India
and Pakistan that has been at the center of two of three
Indian-Pakistani wars since 1947, when the two countries were
created out of British colonial India.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who slipped into Pakistan quietly, switching from Air
Force One to a small, unmarked jet to counter possible terrorists,
concluded his South Asian tour without visible progress on defusing
tensions between Pakistan and India, both of which have nuclear
weapons. He also was unable to win from Musharraf a timetable for a
restoration of democracy or a pledge to curb Pakistan's nuclear
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after Clinton left, Musharraf said he could
not agree to talks on Kashmir unless India took a series of
``reciprocal'' steps to ease the tensions. He also made it clear
that he had given no ground on the other issues of concern to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf appeared to place on Clinton the onus of preventing
the frictions over Kashmir from exploding into a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told you of my openness to meet anybody, anywhere and
at any time. And now it is up to him how he uses his influence to
initiate this process of dialogue,'' Musharraf said of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, said he empathized with Pakistanis'
frustrations over corruption and bad governance by Pakistan's two
previous, democratically elected governments. Warning that there is
little excuse to overthrow a bad but democratically elected
government, as Musharraf had done in a bloodless coup in October,
Clinton added: ``The answer to flawed democracy is not to end
democracy, but to improve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also highlighted the faltering alliance between
Islamabad and Washington, a relationship that served US interests
well during the Cold War, when Pakistan was a buffer to communism
in the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the partnership should be ``a force for tolerance
and understanding throughout the world.'' But, he said, the
military coup that suspended Pakistan's democracy last October
threatened to undermine that friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the absence of democracy makes it harder, not easier,
for people to move ahead,'' Clinton said. ``We share your
disappointment that previous democratic governments in Pakistan did
not do better for its citizens. But democracy cannot develop if it
is constantly uprooted before it has a chance to take hold.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the goals of Clinton's visit was to press Musharraf to
set a timetable for national and provincial elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Musharraf, who calls himself Pakistan's chief executive,
reiterated that it would take time to create conditions for those
elections and noted that he had announced earlier in the week that
local council balloting would be held on a nonparty basis beginning
in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
