<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-BOS &LR;      03-25 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GET-OUT-THE-VOTE CAMPAIGN, MOSCOW STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Corrects spelling in slug)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With one last little trick in a campaign full of them,
the Kremlin on Saturday tackled the one thing that can stop
Vladimir V. Putin from winning Sunday's presidential vote outright:
apathy.
</P>
<P>
   The question is not whether Putin will win a four-year term in
the Kremlin, but when he'll win it. Polls put Putin's support at
about 50 percent. He needs to exceed that figure in Sunday's first
round to avoid a runoff election next month with the runner-up, who
is most likely to be the Communist, Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   A low turnout Sunday could hurt Putin's chances of an instant
victory, and even invalidate the ballot if it falls below 50
percent of Russia's 108 million voters.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, state-run Russian public television subtly urged
people to vote while appearing to remind them to set their clocks
ahead one hour Saturday night, thus skirting campaign rules about
politicking on the eve of the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget,'' intoned a voice in the ad. ``On March 26 a new
time will begin in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only the latest thinly veiled effort to support Putin in
a race where just about everyone _ including some of the
contestants _ seems to be trying to maximize his chances for a
first-round victory.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has dominated Russian politics since he took power after
President Boris N. Yeltsin resigned on New Year's Eve, so much so
that he has eschewed campaign advertisements and avoided televised
debates with his rivals. Instead, his ``working trips'' have
brought him daily, favorable coverage from the state-run national
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Most other media have joined the Putin bandwagon, making it easy
for the front-runner to stay above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, none of Putin's rivals appear to be trying hard to defeat
him. Neither Zyuganov, who is running second in most polls with
about 20 percent, or the liberal, Grigory Yavlinsky, who is in
third place with 7 percent, has tried to stir up support with
rallies or noisy public appearances. Zyuganov has avoided attacking
Putin altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns of other contenders have raised suspicions that
they are running as part of a Kremlin ploy to weaken Zyuganov's and
Yavlinsky's chances. In fact, Aman Tuleyev, the Communist governor
of the Kemorovo province in Siberia, has endorsed Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Ella Pamfilova, a former Cabinet minister, contributed to
suspicions that her campaign had been conceived to take votes from
Yavlinsky when she launched a personal attack against him last
week. Among other things, Pamfilova asserted that Yavlinsky had
undergone plastic surgery, and questioned whether Russia needed
``Michael Jackson as its president.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamfilova's outburst was part of a televised news broadcast that
contained several blatant attacks on Yavlinsky that played on the
anti-Semitism, xenophobia and homophobia still present in parts of
Russian society.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks came as Kremlin officials realized that Putin's
chances of a first-round victory might be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Putin, perhaps uneasy about his first-round
prospects, appealed for people to get out the vote. At the same
time, a poster from an ostensibly nonpartisan Committee for Honest
Elections went up in provincial cities, with a message to vote.
Because of a pun on Putin's name, any Russian might read the poster
as an appeal to support the acting president.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Putin must win convincingly Sunday to decrease his
dependence on politically connected business moguls, who for years
have profited from their influence on government. Putin has
promised to crack down on these oligarchs, whom Russians blame for
many of the country's economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most prominent oligarchs, Boris Berezovsky, who
holds a controlling stake in ORT television, hinted that Putin's
promise, like the campaign itself, was for show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the oligarchs must be distanced from the authorities.
That is normal, absolutely correct. But it is impossible to
achieve,'' Berezovsky told the Russian newspaper Vedomosti. ``But
the words are right for the voters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
