<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-MIDEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONTIFF VISITS TOWN OF JESUS' BIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II retreated from the politics and
pageantry of his pilgrimage Saturday, seeking to turn his attention
to the personal side of his spiritual journey.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff began the day with quiet prayer and then a Mass in
Nazareth where the New Testament says an angel announced to Mary
that she would give birth to the Christ child.
</P>
<P>
   Looking weary on the sixth day of his Holy Land tour, the
79-year-old pontiff ended the day with a twilight vigil in a garden
here on the Mount of Olives where Jesus is believed to have
agonized before his crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the pope prayed in silence at the stone in the Garden of
Gethsemane where Jesus contemplated his impending death, a new
controversy began festering.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a scheduled meeting with the pope, Jerusalem's
leading Muslim cleric told the Italian newspaper La Repubblica that
Israel had exaggerated the death toll of the Holocaust to garner
international sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six million? It was a lot less,'' said Ikrima Sabri, the grand
mufti of the Al Aqsa mosque, one of Islam's holiest shrines. ``It's
not my fault if Hitler hated the Jews. Anyway, they hate them just
about everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The minimizing of the Jewish deaths, which flies in the face of
historians' consensus, was later repeated in interviews with The
Associated Press and provoked bitter responses in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy will probably cast a shadow over Sunday's plans
to end John Paul's trip with a strong interfaith message as he
visits Jerusalem's Old City and shrines sacred to Judaism,
Christianity, and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   On his journey here the pope delivered a powerful and emotional
reflection on the evils of the Holocaust. More than any pope before
him, John Paul has devoted part of his 22-year papacy to fostering
better Catholic-Jewish relations and renouncing anti-Semitism of
church followers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican spokesman declined to comment and said no decision had
been reached as to whether the pope would cancel his meeting with
Sabri, who was appointed a senior cleric by Yasser Arafat's
Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Cabinet minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said, ``I would
recommend Muslim spokesmen not engage in this garbage of historical
writing or interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope has, at least so far, managed to avoid the pitfalls of
this politically and religiously charged region.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled to a Palestinian refugee camp and spoke of the
suffering of the 3.5 million Palestinian refugees, but he avoided
the thorny issue of whether they have the right to return to homes
and villages in what is today Israel. He has also seemingly won the
hearts of many Israelis by confronting the tragedy of the Holocaust
while skirting the emotional issue of the status of Jerusalem,
which both Israelis and Palestinians claim as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the pope stood and waved through the bulletproof glass
of the ``popemobile'' as it weaved through the narrow streets of
Nazareth, the town where Jesus grew up. The visit coincided with
the Roman Catholic Feast of the Annunciation, celebrating the
occasion when the angel Gabriel announced to Mary that she would
give birth to Jesus. The pope's sermon explored the Christian
belief in the ``great mystery'' of the virgin birth and the story's
message of faith and submission to God's will.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, the pope's motorcade wound its way to a vacant
piece of land that has torn this town apart. Muslims want to build
a mosque there to honor a martyr of the Crusades. The Christian
mayor and much of the Catholic hierarchy insist it be a public
plaza for tourists visiting the massive Basilica of the
Annunciation, a central shrine of Christendom.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed construction of the mosque, which Israel has
approved, sparked Muslim-Christian rioting last Easter. The pope's
visit seemed to be an occasion for Nazareth's Muslims and
Christians to come together.
</P>
<P>
   Nisreen Shomar, 23, a Christian, standing in the crowd to catch
a glimpse of the pope as he passed by, said, ``The pope's message
here is very important for Christians who have felt under siege
here. But it is also important for the whole community, a way to
bring us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Barkarni, 26, a Muslim, came to the lot where some 800
Muslims held daily prayers, but craned his neck to see the pope as
he passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All people of Nazareth, Muslim and Christian, believe the pope
is a welcome guest,'' he said. ``He is a man of God, so we are
honored to have him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
