<HEADLINE>
US AIRWAYS   RETURNS TO NORMAL SCHEDULE AFTER TENTATIVE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US Airways flew a normal schedule Saturday, after a tentative
labor agreement reached in the wee hours of the morning averted a
strike at the nation's sixth-largest airline and the busiest on the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   There were no long lines or delays at Boston's Logan
International Airport, and US Airways officials said travel was
smooth throughout its system.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials, however, declined to comment on the proposed
settlement with the flight attendants' union, reached more than
three hours after a 12:01 a.m. deadline had passed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the auspices of the National Mediation Board, the two
sides had been trying to reach an agreement that would give the
airline's 10,000 flight attendants raises, while making the
company, which has the highest costs in the industry, competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The mediation board chairman, Ernest DuBester, had requested
that the two sides continue talking, and the airline team, headed
by chief executive Rakesh Gangwal, and the Association of Flight
Attendants team, led by US Airways AFA president Lynn Lenosky,
agreed on a proposal that calls for a signing bonus, pay raises
over the life of the five-year contract, and increased job
security.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the company got changes in work rules that will
make the airline more competitive. Among the work rules the company
sought to change were how flight attendants are scheduled and how
much paid sick leave they can take.
</P>
<P>
   A breakthrough came when the airline stated Thursday that there
might be alternative ways to achieve its goal of having US Airways
employees at parity with workers of United, American, Delta, and
Northwest Airlines, plus 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the settlement, neither the flight attendants nor
the airline mentioned parity. ``Parity is their concept and you
should ask the airline,'' said Cynthia Kain, spokeswoman for the
flight attendants' association. ``But there are all kinds of way to
find cost savings.'' A US Airways news release, in the only comment
made by the airline, stated, ``The AFA leadership and the company's
management worked extremely hard to put in place an agreement that
works for our flight attendants and allows the company to compete
in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   About 11 percent of the stock of US Airways Group Inc., the
holding company for the airline, is owned by Tiger Management, a
hedge fund, which has seen the stock price plummet in the last two
years. Tiger Management has said it is working with the US Airways
Group board to increase shareholder value by merging the airline or
selling part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Kain said increased job security was very important for flight
attendants in the event of a merger or partial sale, such as its
low-cost brand MetroJet. The new contract has stronger job
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   The contract must be reviewed by the AFA US Airways Master
Executive Council. The council will then recommend to the rank and
file how to vote on the contract. Ratification is expected to take
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Airports, airlines, Amtrak, and passengers along the East Coast
had braced for a shutdown. Management had said it would ground all
planes rather than let its passengers face the uncertainty of
wildcat walkouts promised by the flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways is the No. 1 or No. 2 carrier at more than 40
airports along the East Coast and operates the
Boston-LaGuardia-Washington shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   At the Massachusetts Port Authority, which owns and operates
Logan, officials were relieved by the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good news for the traveling public and it is always a
good day when you don't have to use your contingency plans,'' said
Massport spokesman Jose Juves.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was even more upbeat at Charlotte, N.C., Philadelphia,
and other cities, most notably Pittsburgh, where US Airways
operates hubs and dominates travel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
