<HEADLINE>
HOW ABOUT AN NBA MINOR LEAGUE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An NBA team is on the gurney, rolling to the emergency room, and
you have been hired as its vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   You scrub.
</P>
<P>
   You need a power forward donor, or point guard transplant
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   You deploy the cell phone and dial a familiar, multi-digit
number preceded by zero. An operator picks up on the first ring and
you say, ``Collect call from the Los Angeles Clippers.''
</P>
<P>
   The operator asks about your family, then waits for a response
on the other end of the line. After three more rings, you hear a
click followed by the voice of the general manager for the South
Lake Tahoe Snake Eyes, your Triple-A farm team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're callin' up Rascalitisovich,'' you say, referring to last
year's third-round pick. Nice shooter, good feel for the game, this
kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``You flyin' him down on Southwest?'' the Eyes' GM asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. It also happens to be 2002 (the year 4 AJ; After
Jordan) and Lamar Odom still hasn't been convinced to use his right
hand on those kamikaze streaks to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so that's already a major problem.
</P>
<P>
   But today's topic is strictly minor league.
</P>
<P>
   As those of you who haven't developed or borrowed a life may
know, the basketball future includes the threat of a real minor
league (lose the panic; we're not referring to the Big West). No,
this will be a professional league comprised of teams directly
linked with NBA franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a portent for the future of college basketball? Well, it
could mean March Madness will be downgraded to March Testiness
(some critics believe it already has been).
</P>
<P>
   However, the anticipated jailbreak by college and high school
players may not be as inclusive as doomsday prophets would have us
believe.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Television. The college game has network TV and ESPNs 1 &AMP; 2;
minor league basketball might be displayed on TBS4 or something.
Many young players are savvy enough to realize Dick Vitale and
Billy Packer are two of the best agents they'll ever have.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the college game will take an even greater hit, but it
figures to survive.
</P>
<P>
   When a minor league does erupt, what would it mean for the NBA's
future?
</P>
<P>
   It could mean you'll need a jacket in hell and commissioner
David Stern has reached some sort of compromise with CBA owner
Isiah Thomas. You may be aware that Thomas is attempting to
purchase another minor league or two, merge these properties into
one big stew and serve it up as an officially licensed NBA minor
league.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds fine. With existing minor league franchises in place, NBA
owners wouldn't have to cough up the scoots required to create
their own farm teams.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to NBA yard dogs, Stern's not exactly turning
cartwheels over the notion of having his institutional control
challenged by Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   What to do: cede some of his power to Zeke or blow him off and
have the NBA and its owners go into pocket to produce a minor
league?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if, for the next year or two, the NBA
continues to lean on its current minor league:
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA. &QL; 
Rivers on a roll
</P>
<P>
   First-year Orlando Magic coach Doc Rivers bought even more
respect from his players last week.
</P>
<P>
   The sticker price was $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   The cash will go to the NBA, which fined Rivers for ripping the
officials after the Magic shot only 13 free throws in a loss to
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with the fine,'' he said. ``I just
thought my players needed someone to stand up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The amens you now hear are being produced in the dressing room
of the Clippers, who typically receive as many calls as the
Elephant Man on the eve of prom night. &QL; 
Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   The Nike Hoop Summit game to be contested by a team of U.S. high
school hotshots and a squad of their foreign peers will include the
participation of Yao Ming. Ming is an intriguing 19-year-old,
7-foot-5 prospect who currently is posting 12 points, 7 rebounds
and 4 blocks per game for a pro team in China. Ming may be
available for the 2001 NBA Draft and could join three American high
school phenoms (including Tyson Chandler of Dominguez High) in the
top steps of the lottery. ... Before annihilating the UCLA defense,
Iowa State point guard Jamaal Tinsley was unable to lead Mt. San
Jacinto College past Cerritos in the 1999 California state juco
championship game. Tinsley, by the way, was being tracked on NBA
radar screens long before the NCAA Tournament began. ... If, as
expected, Bill Laimbeer is named head coach of the Detroit Pistons,
don't be shocked if he hires Bruise Brother Rick Mahorn to ride
shotgun. Mahorn now coaches the Rockford Lightning of the CBA. ...
</P>
<P>
   Ex-76ers center and Lovetron ambassador Darryl Dawkins has been
named head coach for the Tampa Bay franchise in the new ABA 2000.
... According to many scouts who really like Florida's Mike Miller,
the Southeastern Conference sophomore small forward with the best
NBA future is Vincent Yarbrough of Tennessee. ... Many of the same
big thinkers who say the UCLA squad is poorly coached now believe
Jerome Moiso would be better prepared for an NBA career by spending
another year with the Bruin staff. ... Clipper Troy Hudson arrived
for Friday's practice with his hair unbraided, but insisted the
condition of his 'do was unrelated to the breeze created when
Houston's Steve Francis blew past him Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
