<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-ROUND3-0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sutton makes splash; Woods 1 back
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Guess who's the intimidator at The
Players Championship? OK, here's a clue: It's not Hal Sutton or
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the most famous holes in golf. It's a piece of land
so terror-filled, you'd think the Bates Motel was located there.
</P>
<P>
   It's the TPC at Sawgrass' nerve-racking, 145-yard island green
17th, which Saturday became the unmerciful undoing of leader Sutton
and helped make today's final round a certain TV ratings bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton came to the 17th at 12-under-par, leading Woods by four.
When the 41-year-old Sutton left, it was with a triple-bogey 6
after hitting his 9-iron tee shot into the water, then
three-putting with his reload from up against the high back fringe,
60 feet from the hole.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's Sutton and Woods battling today for ``the fifth major''
and a first prize of $1,080,000. Sutton, who first won the event in
1983 and seeks a wire-to-wire victory, finished with his third
straight 69 and is at 9-under-par 207.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is one stroke back at 8-under 208 after a solid 66, his
first round in the 60s in 15 rounds at The Players Championship.
Woods, who made six birdies, an eagle and two bogeys, is trying for
his 11th victory in his last 17 PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton indicated early in the week that he was not intimidated
by Woods and reiterated it Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played really good golf today,'' Sutton said sternly. ``That
69 could have been a 64 or 65 pretty easily and was one swing away
from being a 66. I hope I can do the same thing tomorrow. If I do,
he'll have to play his tail off.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the intimidation factor that Woods commands with the
way Woods seems to intimidate most players, Sutton said, ``I think
it's a bigger deal to y'all than it is to me. I'm not looking at it
that way. He's just another guy who's going to put his left leg in
his pants and then his right leg in his pants, just like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman is third after a double-bogey at the 18th for a 72
and a total of 5-under 211.
</P>
<P>
   Friday challengers Fulton Allem and Omar Uresti obliterated
themselves Saturday. Both one stroke off the lead after 36 holes,
they shot 82 and 80, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sluman shot a 66 for fourth place at 4-under 212. Craig
Parry of Australia (69) and two-time U.S. Open champion Lee Janzen
(70) are tied for fifth at 3-under 213.
</P>
<P>
   Alpharetta resident Scott Dunlap is the best among Georgians,
tied for seventh at 2-under after a 71.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's 9-iron at the 17th traveled about 5 yards too far,
nearly striking the back fringe on the fly, then bouncing into the
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it when it was in the air,'' Sutton said. ``I'll just
have to accept the consequences.... It was one of those situations
where I was hollering 'uncle' all the time and I just couldn't get
away from the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
