<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PRESTON-KING0326-COX     03-25 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESTON-KING0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patriarch's legacy of self-reliance and hard work leaves an
indelible mark on next generations
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, Ga. _ Preston King's recent return home to Albany was
chronicled by local, national and international media as an
extraordinary journey. After all, the 63-year-old college professor
had to wait 39 years to make the trip from England, all because of
his long-ago insistence on being treated with respect.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for the Kings of Albany, Preston King's homecoming was the
latest in a long line of journeys _ both literal and metaphorical _
in search of dignity for themselves and others. These travels are a
theme of a rich family history. They have taken generations of
Kings along country roads, across the continent, over oceans and
beyond racial barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The first steps were taken when Clennon Washington King, who
would become the patriarch of a remarkable family, set off on foot
from a Florida Panhandle hamlet called Two Egg, determined to reach
Tuskegee, Ala., 180 miles to the north.
</P>
<P>
   C.W. King was a farmer's son who didn't want to spend his life
farming. He wanted the better life an education could give him, and
he knew he could work his way through college at Booker T.
Washington's famous Tuskegee Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon reaching Tuskegee, he told Booker T. that he wanted to
get that education,'' says Carol King, widow of C.B. King, one of
C.W. King's seven sons. Having worked with horses back home, he was
hired as Washington's coachman, driving him in a carriage to and
from the train station.
</P>
<P>
   King's close encounter with Tuskegee's founder and the school's
philosophy of black uplift through hard work and self-reliance were
lifelong influences. ``Whatever I am,'' he was fond of saying,
``and whatever I hope to be, I owe to Booker T.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also at Tuskegee that he met and fell in love with a
fellow student named Margaret (Maggie) Slater from Milledgeville,
Ga. She graduated a year ahead of him in 1915. After he served in
World War I, they married and, in 1919, moved to Albany, where C.W.
King's father, Allen James King, had moved from North Florida.
Allen James King worked as a drayman for the railroad, hauling dirt
for rail beds.
</P>
<P>
   Clennon Leslie King, C.W. King's grandson, says family legend
holds that the move followed Allen James King's defiance of white
authority. ``My great-grandfather was a man who had very little
tolerance for white people showing him disrespect,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Allen James King and his wife journeyed 100
miles up the Flint River to Albany, and his son followed. C.W. King
secured a job as a letter carrier. But he also started a business:
the Little Wonder Cafe. It was Albany's first black-owned
restaurant, though some whites who saw the very light-skinned
Maggie King behind the counter thought the place belonged to a
Greek family.
</P>
<P>
   The Little Wonder was the first in a string of businesses owned
by C.W. King: a women's clothing store called the Swank Shop
(opened in the late 1940s and still operating today), a bus
service, a newspaper and two neighborhood grocery stores, the Busy
Spot and the Super Spot. He also bought property tracts around
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   He showed a knack for making money. But, according to one of his
sons, C.W. King was most interested in serving as an example for
the rest of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``By opening several businesses,'' Paul King said, ``my father
was trying to inspire other black people to start businesses. He
was more interested in inspiring than in making a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The businesses also gave King a degree of independence that was
unusual for a black man in the South at the time. And he passed
along the advantage to his seven sons. (The Kings also had a
daughter, Muriel, who died when she was 14 months old.)
</P>
<P>
   The businesses ``provided employment for the sons,'' says Carol
King. ``It provided employment so that those sons were not required
to go elsewhere to get jobs, which meant that they weren't
subjected to the abuse and exploitation of many employers. It was
built in to avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the sons of C.W. King spread their wings and left the
cocoon their father had created for them, they led lives of
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Clennon W. King Jr., the eldest, became an educator, minister
and civil rights activist. At one time while living in Albany, he
simultaneously held jobs as a high school principal, a pastor and a
radio disc jockey. He studied Egyptology at the University of
Chicago and could read and write hieroglyphics. He was a professor
at several U.S. universities and founded colleges in Ethiopia and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, Clennon King attempted to become the first black person
to enroll in the University of Mississippi. He was promptly
committed to a state insane asylum. That incarceration clearly was
politically motivated, but Clennon, as the King family iconoclast,
often did things that embroiled him in controversy and brought
trouble on himself. He was imprisoned in California after being
convicted of abandoning his family. In 1976, he mounted a one-man
campaign to integrate the congregation of the small baptist church
President Carter attended in Plains. But his crusade only resulted
in national attention for Clennon King _ much of it criticizing him
as a grandstander _ and a painful rift in the local community.
</P>
<P>
   Slater King was a graduate of Tuskegee and did his graduate
study at Oberlin College in Ohio. He returned to Albany and opened
insurance and real estate businesses in offices he built on
property his father owned. He served as president of the Albany
Movement, which brought the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. _ who was
not related to the Kings of Albany _ to town to help protest
segregation and racial discrimination. In 1963, he became the first
black candidate to run for mayor of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Slater King also worked to bring low-income housing to Albany
and to improve services to senior citizens. A city street has been
named in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin King became a building contractor after graduating from
Tuskegee. Among the buildings he constructed in Albany are the
present location of the Swank Shop and the offices of the local
NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Chevene Bowers King graduated from Fisk University in Nashville
and attended law school at Case Western University in Cleveland,
Ohio. He was the first _ and for many years the only _
African-American attorney in Albany. C.B. King represented Martin
Luther King Jr. when he was arrested during the Albany
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   C.B. King also represented blacks in civil rights cases and
other court cases around Georgia. In Albany, he filed suit to end
segregation in the public schools. In 1970, he became the first
black person to run for governor of Georgia since the
Reconstruction era. Both of Georgia's U.S. senators advocate naming
the new federal courthouse being built in Albany in honor of C.B.
King.
</P>
<P>
   Paul King attended Howard University in Washington and the
University of Madrid in Spain. He eventually earned a Ph.D. in
Mexico and became a professor of foreign languages at Albany State
University. According to Carol King, her brother-in-law showed a
knack for languages early on. As a high schooler, he learned
Spanish during trips to Miami. After that, he earned money serving
as an interpreter for wealthy Miami families who took vacations in
Cuba. At one point, Carol King says, Paul King could read and
understand 12 languages.
</P>
<P>
   Allen King graduated from Atlanta's Morris Brown College and
moved to Washington to be a schoolteacher. When Slater King was
killed in a car accident in 1969, Allen King came back to Albany to
continue the real estate and insurance businesses. He also bought
and operated a drug store.
</P>
<P>
   Preston King was admitted to Atlanta University's early entrance
program as an 11th-grader. The following year he enrolled at Fisk
University. After graduating in 1956, he went to the London School
of Economics, where he earned a master's degree and then his Ph.D.
The draft deferments Preston King received for his college studies
were the genesis of the 39-year exile that ended last month when he
returned home from the funeral of his oldest brother, Clennon.
</P>
<P>
   Paperwork for his first deferment was sent from Fisk.
Correspondence from the Albany draft board concerning his status
was addressed to ``Mr. Preston King.'' But King went home between
his graduation from Fisk and the start of his classes in London. He
dropped by the draft board offices and, for the first time,
officials saw that he was black. It is evidence of the racial
divide in Albany at the time that those whites in positions of
power didn't connect the Preston King at Fisk _ one of the nation's
best known historically black colleges _ to the city's most
prominent black family. At any rate, once they knew who and what he
was, things changed.
</P>
<P>
   Envelopes from the draft board were addressed to ``Preston
King.'' The board's letters simply addressed him as ``Preston.''
King informed draft board members he would no longer respond until
they addressed him with the courtesy title ``Mr.'' When the board
ended his deferment and ordered him home for induction into the
Army, he returned but refused to be inducted until he was addressed
as ``Mr. King.'' After he was tried and convicted of draft evasion,
King did not report to serve his 18-month prison sentence. Instead,
he fled back to England, where he eventually became a distinguished
professor of political science at the London School of Economics.
He wrote books and lectured around the world, but he never returned
to American soil until President Clinton issued the pardon that
allowed him to attend Clennon King's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
