<HEADLINE>
POPE GIVEN A REMINDER OF THE DIVISIONS AMONG THE HOLY LAND'S
CHRISTIANS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ John Paul II has sought to use his time in Israel
and the West Bank to foster reconciliation among Jews, Muslims and
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday night, he attended an ecumenical meeting given by
Diodoros I, the Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem, that for all
its warmth also underlined the deep divisions among Christians in
the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   The most vivid trace of the schism between Catholicism and
Orthodoxy that dates back more than 1,000 years took place after
the pope and the patriarch had delivered their remarks. The papal
nuncio in Jerusalem, Pietro Sambi, took the microphone and asked
that all church leaders present recite together the Lord's Prayer,
each in their own language. It was an unscripted suggestion, and it
turned out to be more of a breach of ecumenical etiquette than a
rousing inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   On the right, in the elegant reception room, where Roman
Catholics, Melchites, Maronite Christians, Armenian Catholics and
Chaldeans (and the head of the Church of Scotland, in green tartan
trousers and a frock coat) were seated, all rose and recited the
prayer, mostly in Latin. The left side, which included Greek
Orthodox, Armenian Orthodox, Syrian Ethiopian Coptics, and others,
also rose, but almost all remained silent. So did Patriarch
Diodoros I.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not used to saying the Lord's Prayer in these
circumstances,'' Father Aleksandr, a Russian-born priest who works
for the Greek Orthodox Patriarchy and was at the meeting, said
afterward. ``You cannot just jump over history.''
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox doctrine bans prayers with Roman Catholics and while it
has happened _ most notably, when John Paul II made his
breakthrough visit to the Patriarch of Romania and the two leaders
attended each other's Masses _ some branches of the Orthodox Church
are stricter than others. The Greek Orthodox Church, which withdrew
from all efforts at dialogue with the Vatican in 1989 and has
denounced the Roman church as ``cunning'' and ``heretical,'' is one
of the most conservative.
</P>
<P>
   That was one reason John Paul II, who has made Christian unity
one of the goals of his papacy, was so eager to meet 77-year-old
Diodoros I, whom he kissed on both cheeks. The Greek Orthodox
church is the largest Christian denomination in Israel, and its
hierarchy controls many holy sites. Others are jealously divided,
including the Holy Sepulcher, the church built over the site where
tradition says Christ was crucified, in which the pope will say
Mass on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Holy Land, where Christians live side by side with the
followers of Judaism and Islam, where there are almost daily
tensions and conflicts, it is essential to overcome the scandalous
impression given by our disagreements and arguments,'' the pope
said in his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The patriarch praised the pope for his ``tireless and continuous
contribution'' to promoting Christian ideals, but also reminded him
of his grievances against Rome, including, he said, the efforts
some Churches make to increase the numbers of their faithful ``by
exploiting unemployment, education, and other social needs in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear that the Roman Catholic church is using its resources
and clout to convert Orthodox believers is acute in Israel, where
tensions between the Greek hierarchy and their ethnic Arab
followers has tempted many to join the Catholic church, whose
hierarchy is mainly ethnic Arab, and which has many schools and
hospitals. But there are also signs that the local churches are
beginning to cooperate, notably in Nazareth, where all Christian
churches closed for two days to protest the construction of a
mosque next to the Church of the Annunciation, where the pope said
Mass Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's encounter, where the two leaders exchanged
gifts and crosses and toasted each other with champagne, was not a
breakthrough, but it signaled a significant step forward in the
pope's campaign to mend the rift.
</P>
<P>
   The rift, however, is far more important to leaders than most
Christians, who are a small, uneasy minority in Israel and the
Palestinian-controlled territories. ``The important thing is for
the pope to help settle the question of Palestine,'' said Nicholas
Shbeita a Greek Orthodox Christian who runs a gift shop near the
Holy Sepulcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
