<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET'S SILENCE SPEAKS VOLUMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Stephane Fiset's ``no comment'' after Saturday's 4-4
Los Angeles Kings tie with the Boston Bruins rang out like shot off
the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset wasn't merely pulled by the Kings after two periods, he
was betrayed. After beating mighty Philadelphia on Thursday, he was
forced to face the Bruins without any intensity from his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want everyone to know that I wasn't disappointed in Stephane
Fiset,'' said Kings coach Andy Murray, who watched the Kings rally
from a three-goal deficit after Fiset left. ``He played his heart
out for us on Thursday and this is how we thanked him. It was
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins outshot the Kings 17-4 in the first period. In the
second, Boston scored twice after turnovers in the Kings' end. The
Bruins scored four consecutive goals, including three in the
second. The last one came from Brian Rolston on an impossible
angle. His shot struck Fiset's right leg and trickled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a guy like (Fiset) coming back from an injury and
play the way he did against Philly, you'd think we'd be building
some momentum. Instead we left him out there to dry. We got a point
tonight with the tie, but it doesn't feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Fiset's second game since missing 10 days with a
strained right groin. The Kings did not want to rush him back.
Earlier this season, Fiset was forced to return ahead of schedule
from a hand injury when Jamie Storr suffered a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Chartrand returns: With all the jumbled lines since Ziggy Palffy
was injured six games ago, it wasn't hard to miss rookie Brad
Chartrand, who has been back after missing two months with a broken
jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Chartrand played almost eight minutes against Boston. More
amazing is that he is playing at all. After undergoing surgery to
insert two pins and a plate in his jaw, Chartrand was back playing
at minor-league Lowell, Mass., in 2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come back as soon as I could,'' Chartrand said.
``I didn't want the Kings to forget about me. But even I was
surprised how quickly my jaw responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: Fourth-line strongman Steve McKenna played his
40th game for the Kings, qualifying him for protection in this
summer's expansion draft. He responded with an assist on Bob
Corkum's third-period goal.... Jozef Stumpel had assists on both of
Glen Murray's third-period goals. Stumpel, who had two goals
Thursday, has 14 goals and 33 points in his last 26 games.... After
going nine games without a goal, Luc Robitaille has two in his past
two games. He has 35 this year and 552 for his career, four behind
former Boston great Johnny Bucyk for 15th all-time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
