<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: GOP abortion battle brewing
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaders of the abortion rights movement in the Republican Party
say they will risk precipitating a noisy, divisive fight at this
summer's Republican National Convention if the party insists on
keeping an anti-abortion plank in its platform. Abortion rights
advocates have begun a mass mailing warning party officials not to
mention abortion issues in the GOP platform at the 2000 convention
in Philadelphia in August, or face a battle. Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the likely GOP presidential nominee, favors an anti-abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party must understand,'' said Susan R. Cullman, a
co-chairwoman of the Republican Pro-Choice Coalition, ``that the
road to a unified Republican Party is filled with deep potholes.
The party will surely tumble into one of them if we don't take
abortion out of the platform.''
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY STILL STRONG LEADERS SAY
</P>
<P>
   Pat Choate, chairman of the national Reform Party, said that
infighting among party members won't cripple the party or
overshadow its mission. ``These are issues that had to get
resolved, and it's well that they be resolved here, in March,''
Choate said Saturday at a meeting of the Virginia Reform Party in
Richmond. On Monday, U.S. District Judge Norman K. Moon is to rule
in Lynchburg, Va., whether Choate's faction or one headed by former
chairman Jack Gargan controls the party and almost $15 million in
campaign funds. Choate deposed Gargan last month at a rowdy meeting
in Nashville, Tenn. Pat Buchanan is considered likely to win the
party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   GORE BACKS CAMPAIGN MANAGER
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said Friday that his campaign chairman, Tony Coelho, is
doing a ``terrific job'' and suggested Coelho would remain with his
presidential campaign despite a criminal investigation into past
financial dealings. Asked if he was concerned about the possibility
of criminal wrongdoing, Gore refused to elaborate on his statement,
saying, ``He's doing a great job and he will keep on doing so.''
When asked about Gore's problems regarding Coelho and an
investigation of White House e-mail, George W. Bush said Friday:
``The best way to make sure we get rid of all these investigations
is to change administrations.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE IN BUSH COUNTRY TO RAISE CASH
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was in Houston attending a reception and dinner Friday
in hopes of raising more than $600,000 for the Democratic National
Committee. The event capped a week of fund-raising in Washington,
D.C., Cincinnati and Detroit. Gore, who has called for an overhaul
of campaign finance laws and challenged George W. Bush, the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee, to mutually halt the
raising of large, unregulated donations of ``soft money,'' has
shown no signs of letting up his own prodigious fund raising.
Gore's goal is to help the party rase $35 million in soft money
during the next few months to finance anti-GOP TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S IN A NAME?
</P>
<P>
   When Secret Service agents talk into their sleeves while
protecting presidential candidates, they almost always refer to
their charges by code names seemingly picked at random _ Dasher for
Jimmy Carter, Rawhide for Ronald Reagan, Eagle for Bill Clinton,
Sundance for Al Gore. George W. Bush's code name? Tumbler.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
