<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME IS WHERE THE WINS ARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ As if they required a gentle reminder of the need
for home-court advantage in the playoffs, the Los Angeles Lakers
play today in one of the most daunting settings in the NBA. Against
their potential first-round opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Kings' 27-6 record at Arco Arena is tied for
second best in the Western Conference (behind the Lakers' 31-4 at
Staples Center), and third overall in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Kings fans are rabid, close to the action and packed in tight in
one of the more intimate - and deafening - arenas in the league.
The Lakers have lost two of their last three games here.
</P>
<P>
   But if these teams meet in the first round of the playoffs, the
Lakers will have home-court advantage in the five-game series. If
the Lakers win at least eight of their final 12 games, they'll lock
up home-court advantage throughout the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``(That's) always great to have,'' coach Phil Jackson said,
``but regular season and playoffs are like two different seasons.
Nothing counts. You throw everything out the window and start over
again. The thing that's fortunate is if you do have home court, you
can rest in your own beds, that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Lakers are also the NBA's best road team this
season, with a 27-8 record away from Staples Center. And the home
court doesn't always translate to an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to win all your home games (in a series), and if you
hold serve the entire time then you win it all,'' Brian Shaw said.
``But that's all that it really means. A few years ago when we were
in Orlando, we had the best record, had home court all the way
through and ended up being swept in the Finals. You realize that
you can't put too much on it, because each night you have to go out
and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jackson, who had derided Staples for being ``cavernous,''
among other things, won't yet proclaim his home court an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. Our fans are really animated, though. They do
the wave about the third quarter every night. It's enjoyable to
watch them do it,'' Jackson said. ``We still have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Can the Lakers boast an intimidating home-court edge, the way
the Kings, Utah Jazz and Portland Trail Blazers do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we can say that yet,'' Shaw said. ``It's a new
building for us, too. And now we're not even coming in and having
(a) shootaround here on game days. So hopefully it's turning into
that. It seems like the fans are starting to get a little bit more
into it, and it's starting to become more intimate out there.
Hopefully, by the time we get to where we need to be going, we'll
have it all working for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead: The Kings have again moved up to the No. 7 slot
in the West, and the battle for No. 8 - and a first-round matchup
with the Lakers - could go down to the last game. Jockeying among
seeds four through eight are Phoenix, San Antonio, Minnesota,
Seattle and the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will see all of those teams at least once more, but
``we're still a ways away'' from scouting a first-round opponent,
Jackson said. ``We'll probably track their last five games, however
it boils down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Assistant coach Tex Winter and rookie Devean George
are both suffering from the flu and did not make the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 2043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
