<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13-YEAR-OLD PRODIGY OVERSHADOWED BY WEBB  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN STREGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. _ Only the magnitude of her domination
here this past week has kept Karrie Webb from joining the rest of
the LPGA in turning over one of its pre-eminent stages, the Nabisco
Championship, to a 13-year-old wunderkind from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Aree Wongluekiet, an amateur playing here on a sponsor's
exemption, shot Saturday's second-best round, a four-under-par 68,
which left her tied for third place heading into the final round on
the Dinah Shore Course.
</P>
<P>
   The best round of the day was delivered by Webb, who shot a
five-under-par 67. It was a demonstration of the No. 1 player in
the world at the peak of her game, emphatically reiterating that a
close second does not exist, at large or in this particular
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Webb concluded 54 holes in 12-under-par 204, leaving her eight
strokes ahead of the defending champion, Dottie Pepper, and
virtually assuring her fifth victory in six starts this year and
the second major championship of her career.
</P>
<P>
   She will be paired in the final round with Wongluekiet, who
along with her twin sister, Naree, have been leaving notes in
Webb's locker, expressing a desire to play together someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's played her way into playing with me,'' Webb said. `I'm
excited to play with Aree. I can't image what's going through her
mind right now, 13 years old and playing in the last group in a
major.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely it also taxes the imagination to know what Webb is going
through with her dominating play right now. Perhaps only Tiger
Woods can relate. Indeed, parallels often are drawn between the
two, and another surfaced here. When Woods won the Masters in 1997,
he carried a nine-stroke lead into the final round and won by 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Nabisco Championship is the women's equivalent of the
Masters, and the notion that Webb's lead is not insurmountable
seems as far-fetched as anyone suggesting Woods had not already won
the green jacket at a similar stage at Augusta in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never say, whatever the lead, that I've won,'' said Webb,
25. ``I don't give myself that luxury. I've got 18 holes ahead of
me, four or five hours of work ahead of me. I still have to play
some good golf.''
</P>
<P>
   What Webb accomplished Saturday even seemed to surprise her.
</P>
<P>
   ``From tee to green, I hit the ball extremely well, maybe the
best I've ever hit it,'' she said. ``I only missed two greens. I
probably missed four or five putts inside 12 feet. I'm not
complaining, but I probably could have made a few more putts.''
</P>
<P>
   The only complaints that warrant consideration at this point of
the 2000 season would have to come from the others on the LPGA.
Webb has not been unbeatable, though she has been close. She has
won three of the four LPGA tournaments she entered, and finished
second in the other, losing to Charlotta Sorenstam at the Standard
Register Ping last week. She also won the Australian Women's Open,
which is not an official LPGA event.
</P>
<P>
   She began play Saturday with a three-stroke lead over Pepper,
who experienced back pain on the practice tee and struggled through
a round of 72. Webb made only one bogey, at the fourth hole, and
birdied three consecutive holes on the back nine to open a
nine-stroke lead at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to play my game,'' she said, ``and not pay
attention to what anyone else was doing. When I saw that Dottie and
Lorie weren't making a move, it made it easier to fire at pins.`
</P>
<P>
   The most notable move was made by Wongluekiet (pronounced
wahn-gloo-KEE-it), who might have erased doubts anyone had about
the wisdom of inviting 13-year-old twins to compete in a major
championship. Naree missed the cut, but her sister has carried the
Wongluekiet banner impressively enough to remind everyone that Webb
is not the only golfer in the tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
