<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TECH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSH FOR DIGITAL TECHNOLOGY STRAINS RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN HOLLYWOOD,
THEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As movie stars collect their Academy Awards
tonight, a behind-the-screens crisis is shaking the relationship
between those who make movies and those who show them.
</P>
<P>
   Financial fallout from a glut of movie screens in the United
States already has the exhibition industry on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hollywood wants theater owners to upgrade for digital
projection technology at a cost of $100,000 per screen.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, neither side seems willing _ or perhaps able _ to pay
for the upgrade. In the end, some industry observers say,
moviegoers may pay higher ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   While exhibition firms have been adding movie screens at a
steady pace in the last decade, a multibillion-dollar building
binge began in earnest in 1994 when Kansas City-based AMC
Entertainment Inc. broke ground on the nation's first megaplex _
the Grand 24 in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of losing customers, AMC's competition began their own
building frenzy, sometimes opening megaplexes within blocks of
similar ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade the number of movie screens has increased by
66 percent to almost 37,000. In the same period, the number of
tickets sold increased by 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result the length of movie runs has decreased, meaning
Hollywood receives a greater share of the box-office revenue at the
expense of exhibitors. Traditionally moviemakers receive a large
percentage of box-office receipts early in a movie's run, with the
percentage declining over the run. Thus, a long run helped
exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ego seems to be driving market share aspirations ... and now,
we're collectively drowning in red ink,'' said Robert E. Goodrich,
head of Goodrich Quality Theaters in Michigan, which recently
closed the South Quality 12 in Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the request from Hollywood to upgrade to digital.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does an industry that's drowning in red ink ... undertake
a major technological retooling of its presentation?'' Goodrich
asked.
</P>
<P>
   That, says John Fithian, president of the National Association
of Theatre Owners, is the $3.7 billion question, the theoretical
cost to convert 37,000 screens at $100,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that $800 million, a cost mostly borne by the
studios, is spent each year making and distributing film prints to
the more than 7,500 movie houses and complexes in the United
States. Digital delivery _ by satellite, a disc or perhaps cable _
would drastically lower their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Who pays for digital conversion was the topic at last month's
ShoWest in Las Vegas, an annual exhibition extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Fithian shocked _ and delighted _ some in attendance when he
said distributors should pay for the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I said stands _ we're not looking to assume more
financial obligations at this point based on what we've just gone
through,'' Fithian said. ``We would look to them, if they want it,
to finance it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Hollywood insiders say the exhibitors' woes are of their
own making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street got involved in putting a lot of money in a lot of
(exhibition) companies because they saw a cash cow,'' said Tom
Sherak, chairman of 20th (Century Fox) Domestic Film Group.
``People see cash coming in, they think it's a good business, add
Hollywood to it, and they think it's a great business _ but it
isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Successful exhibition operators, Sherak said, control costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's never changed about exhibition over the
years: It's a Ma and Pa business,'' Sherak said. ``It's nickels and
dimes _ and the ones who've succeeded are the ones watching
those.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, said Sherak and others, Hollywood has its own financial
woes.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, which represents the major studios, said eight of 10 films
in domestic theatrical release never recover the cost of making the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   And, Valenti said, even when all other revenue streams, from
video to overseas exhibition, are tapped, only four of 10 movies
make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making movies is a lousy business,'' Valenti said. ``It is not
an attractive, congenial marketplace to make money just in
theatrical exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherak said profit margins had been squeezed from 10 percent to
12 percent a decade ago to the current level of 2 percent to 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while the exhibition industry is swimming in red ink, the
stocks of many studios' parents have soared. MGM and Sony, for
example, in the last year have seen their share prices increase 139
percent and 158 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the average cost to make and market a movie dropped
2.5 percent, to $76 million. And those that are financially
successful often rely on making money from all venues.
</P>
<P>
   For instance ``The Beach,'' which starred Leonardo DiCaprio and
cost $50 million to make (including more than $20 million for
DiCaprio), as of Monday had pulled in $38.8 million in its six-week
domestic run.
</P>
<P>
   But that figure already has been surpassed by runs in a few
European countries, including France and Britain. Its distributor,
20th Century Fox, expects to make money on the movie.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. exhibitors concede that few movies make money in their
domestic runs alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Fithian said, ``if the movie doesn't make it on the
American cinema, it's not going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the half-dozen exhibition companies contacted for this
report, Goodrich was the only one that would speak on the record.
Others, including AMC, declined to talk about the issue or did not
return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Poessiger, a local movie insider who produces the radio
show ``Jack Goes to the Movies'' and who attended ShoWest, was not
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The love/hate relationship is alive and well. ... And this
whole digital conversion issue isn't helping,'' Poessiger said.
``It's strictly a one-sided deal as far as I can see in terms of
helping distribution and not exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   But exhibitors have too much at stake to complain on the record
about their treatment from Hollywood. And while Hollywood and
exhibitors thrive or perish together, Hollywood seems to have the
upper hand now because of the glut of screens, which gives it an
edge in rental negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Film rentals between studios and exhibitors are negotiated in
various ways, including declining percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Under such a deal, in the first two weeks of a run the studio
may get 70 percent of ticket sales, 60 percent of the second two
weeks, 50 percent the next two weeks and so on.
</P>
<P>
   That system and others usually were satisfactory. But now that
movie runs are shorter because movies are being shown on so many
screens, such agreements are no longer satisfactory to exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, splits are supposed to even out at 50/50. But in
the last several years exhibitors have been paying 56 percent or 57
percent of the box office to studios.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel O'Neill, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston, said
exhibitors would like to use digital conversion as leverage to get
Hollywood to change the way film terms were set.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, would address exhibitors' woes until enough
older, outdated and unprofitable theaters are closed to put
exhibition on more even footing with Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood's inclination to help exhibitors is almost
nonexistent, O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich, for one, is not expecting handouts from Hollywood. He
says he thinks Fithian and National Association of Theatre Owners
are unrealistic if they think they are going to change a
relationship that has been the same for 30 or 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he says he thinks the solution is for exhibitors to
raise ticket prices. Last year Americans paid an average of $5.08
per ticket, compared with $4.23 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the 14-year-old who's willing to pay $18 for a T-shirt
and $16 for a CD would be willing to pay significantly more for a
movie ticket,'' Goodrich said. ``Why are we theater owners so
unable to do what so many others are able to do and raise prices?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
