<HEADLINE>
BORING A HOLE IN OUR SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ I tried, folks, I really tried. I spent three
weeks in two shifts at spring training with the Red Sox and did my
best to find color, controversy, tension, and pizzazz.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. It is truly hopeless. Dan Duquette has accomplished the
ultimate in his Dukedom: He has assembled a team in his own boring
image. No more Foxy Lady for these guys. Now it's more like the Fox
Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Sox camp has been Tranquillity Base throughout the spring. I
think the biggest controversy was Pedro Martinez arriving a
half-hour late because he had to blow out the candles on his dad's
birthday cake in the Dominican Republic. I mean, how long would it
be before anybody noticed if Troy O'Leary stopped talking to the
media?
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Sox are a Boston sportswriter's worst nightmare _ nice
guys who stay out of trouble and say nothing inflammatory about one
another or the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm boring, I know,'' said manager Jimy Williams, a man given
to answering the most harmless question with, ``We're just playing
the schedule, trying to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Honest, I think when the checkout kid at the supermarket asks
Jimy, ``Paper or plastic?'' Jimy smiles and says, ``Just playing
the schedule, son. Trying to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   They won 94 games last year, then took a thrilling Division
Series from the Indians. They are Sports Illustrated cover boys,
picked to win the World Series. They have two of the premier stars
in baseball, and they own the Boston sports market. They just
aren't very funny anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we had a team meeting and said, `Let's be as boring as
possible,' '' said catcher Jason Varitek. ``Seriously, it starts
with our best people. Look at Bret Saberhagen. He's not even on the
team right now, but he's here every day, doing his work. Nomar is
one of the top five players in baseball, but he doesn't pop off.
Petey (Pedro Martinez) is a different story, but he'd never do
anything to hurt the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. Team players. Careful with their words and actions off the
field. It makes me long for the good/bad old days when Oil Can
Boyd, Wade Boggs, Mike Greenwell, Roger Clemens, Jose Canseco, and
Mo Vaughn patrolled the premises. It was always something with
those guys. Wade would get run over by his wife in the family
four-wheeler and announce, ``I'm the white Irving Fryar.'' Roger
would thumb his nose and show up a week late. The Can would get a
summons from the Florida police. Greenie would get into fistfights
with teammates. Mo would flip his SUV then rip Duquette and John
Harrington as ``the joint chiefs of staff.''
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin is just about the only active Sox player who
remembers the good/bad old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was young at that time,'' said Valentin. ``Wade and
Greenwell couldn't keep their mouths shut, stuff like that. But the
game has changed. These younger players now are more serious. They
take vitamins and drink healthy shakes. It's a different mentality.
There's a lot less activity off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure. Gone are the days when the Sox were fodder for Barbara
Walters and Geraldo Rivera. It's highly unlikely Williams is going
to get a Fed-Ex package from a cocaine-dealer friend. As far as we
know, the front office hasn't hired private detectives to follow
any Boston ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Saberhagen, Stanley, and Garciaparra invest in
collections of fine wines. That's a far cry from the days when
Boggs and Tim Lollar had their names stitched on barstools at the
Howard Johnson's lounge in Winter Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said, ``I've got to be the most boring interview. It's
the personality of this team. It's also Jimy and the way he treats
people. It doesn't allow for grumbling. But I don't think we're
boring by design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our superstars are as quiet as you're gonna get. On a lot of
teams, that's where you get your controversy. The biggest names are
the most vocal. But our shortstop is the exact opposite. Mo used to
be the go-to guy for the media. Now there's no one. I'm too boring.
Nomar's too nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was a teenager during the Delta House days of Sox
spring training. Baseball's Rain Man has little use for off-field
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're boring,'' he said. ``There shouldn't be
controversy and most of it is made up anyway. It's been like this
since I've been here. I don't know if other stuff would be
tolerated. When someone comes to this team, he knows what it's
going to be like. There's a certain demeanor and mentality. You
guys just make up the other stuff anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, Nomie. In the old days, it took no creativity to make
the Red Sox colorful. Who could invent Velvet Elvis, Roger running
in headphones with Daddy Butch Hobson, the Can's film festival
(Boyd got a summons for overdue X-rated videos), or Lou Gorman
reacting to a Clemens walkout with, ``The sun will rise, the sun
will set, and I'll have lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody says stuff like that anymore. Not around Camp
Tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters is what's on the field, not what you guys write
about,'' said Valentin. ``Now you have to work harder, and you
don't want that. You want the easy stuff. We're boring but
efficient on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Boring but efficient. The Duke Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
