<SLUG> BC-HKO-MINOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUES' BREAKTHROUGH WELL-PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAGUE NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two weeks from Sunday, the St. Louis Blues will most
likely lay claim to the Presidents Trophy, awarded to the NHL's
most successful team during the 82-game preliminaries to the
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The honor is based on fact (the best regular-season record)
rather than opinion, but no one is more worthy than the Blues.
Their mastery of every aspect of the game _ goaltending, defense,
penalty killing, offensive balance, coaching _ made them the first
NHL team this season to record 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   High on the list of reasons for St. Louis's success is the
contribution of its minor leaguers. No other NHL organization has
relied upon, or benefited as much from, the American and
International Hockey Leagues as the Blues. More than half of St.
Louis's players were developed in its farm systems; even its front
office and coaching staff were groomed in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   An entire line came through Worcester (the Blues' AHL
affiliate), and their resident pest and an impact rookie also spent
plenty of time at the Centrum. Both goaltenders and a key
defenseman also paid their dues in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``From day one, we've been developing NHL players in a
competitive, successful environment,'' said John Ferguson Jr., who
is Worcester's general manager and the assistant GM in St. Louis.
``Our philosophy is to prime the pump. It's worked even quicker
than we thought it might.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk of development and minor league pipelines would have
been heresy under former GM/coach Mike Keenan. When he departed St.
Louis in 1997 after 2 1/2 seasons, he left a team weighted down
with aging free agent acquisitions under long-term contracts and a
demoralized AHL affiliate plagued by constant, seemingly impulsive
recalls and demotions.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan would summon players to participate in a morning skate,
then fly them back to Worcester afterward. Those days are long
gone. Instead, the Blues utilize an unofficial ``three-year plan,''
roughly the amount of time a prospect is granted to show whether he
has NHL potential.
</P>
<P>
   After Keenan was fired, Larry Pleau was named GM, and he hired
Joel Quenneville as coach. Both had prepped for NHL jobs in the
minors, Pleau with the Rangers' and Whalers' systems and
Quenneville as coach in Springfield (AHL) in 1993-94. The Blues
then began to retool, placing an emphasis on development rather
than free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is not to have someone play for two or three
years, but to play for 10 years for the St. Louis Blues,'' Ferguson
said. ``We started to develop our players by giving them important
minutes and high expectations. Our whole outlook is to work to
produce players.''
</P>
<P>
   It's paid off better than the Blues could have imagined. The
dynamic ``Slovak Pak'' line of Pavol Demitra, Michal Handzus, and
Lubos Bartecko all skated in Worcester, though Demitra's background
is a bit more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Originally property of Ottawa, Demitra broke his hand early in
his professional career while with the Senators' Prince Edward
Island AHL team. But Ferguson, a scout with the Senators when
Demitra was drafted in 1993, was aware of his potential. The Blues
traded for Demitra three years later, and he has proven Ferguson's
acumen. With 28 goals and 46 assists, Demitra is St. Louis's
leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   If Demitra is Exhibit A of how minor league seasoning can pay
off, then center Marty Reasoner is Exhibit B. A star on Boston
College's 1998 NCAA final team, Reasoner received a 22-game NHL
baptism last year. The Blues' No. 1 draft pick in 1996 was
Worcester's top scorer when he was recalled for the second time
this season last month and has nine goals in 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Bergevin experienced a career resurrection in the early
1990s when he played on two Calder Cup teams in Springfield under
Jim Roberts. Now one of St. Louis's steadiest defensemen, he gets
his marching orders from Roberts, a Quenneville assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Jamie McLennan, the backup to Roman Turek (himself
plucked from Dallas's system after last season), resuscitated his
career in Worcester in 1996-97; the summer before, he nearly died
of meningitis before completing a year with the IceCats. He's in
his third season with St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Tyson Nash, the Blues' chief agitator, spent last
season in Worcester. Center Johan Hecht, defenseman Ricard Persson,
and right wing Jamal Mayers also there played at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rule A in minor league hockey: When the parent club calls, the
farm team answers as quickly as possible. But the result often
isn't positive for the minor league affiliate. Such is the case in
Providence, which has run through 54 players while providing some
of its leading names to the injury-riddled parent club in Boston.
So severe was the personnel shortage that only 14 skaters dressed
for a recent game, and the Baby B's have been scouring for players
everywhere from the IHL to the East Coast Hockey League to the
United Hockey League. Typical of the Baby B's situation: Just when
it appeared they had an offensive linchpin in New Hampshire's Jason
Krog, the Islanders recalled the reigning Hobey Baker winner
Thursday. Krog had been loaned to Providence earlier in the month
from Lowell and earned last week's AHL Player of the Week honors
with six goals and five assists in four games. Still, the defending
Calder Cup champs clinched a playoff berth Wednesday . . . Many
comings and goings from Tsongas Arena, including a trade involving
Lowell and the IHL. Former BC standout Dave Hymovitz was dealt to
Chicago and ex-UMass-Lowell center Jeff Daw headed to the Lock
Monsters from Houston. In late February, center Craig Charron was
traded back to Lowell, his college town, from St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The annual late-season signing period has begun, as players
whose collegiate seasons are finished try their hand at the pros.
Among the first to hook on are two former Northeastern Huskies,
center Roger Holeczy and right wing Billy Newson, both of whom
joined New Orleans (ECHL) . . . Gordie Howe as a Detroit Red Wing?
Of course. Howe as a Hartford Whaler? Sure. As a member of the
Syracuse Crunch? Not really, but that's the answer to a question in
the latest edition of Trivial Pursuit. The board game asks: ``Whose
cameo appearance with the AHL's Syracuse Crunch made him the only
puckster to skate actively in six decades?'' Howe is given as the
answer, but his plan to play in Syracuse in 1997 never materialized
and he wound up taking one shift with the IHL's Detroit Vipers
during the 1997-98 season. But it's absolutely no problem with the
Crunch. ``I think it's great that we're getting all this mileage
out of it,'' said general manager Vance Lederman . . . Logo of the
Week: Augusta, Ga., is a pretty august place, what with the
Masters. So when the ECHL's Raleigh IceCaps relocated to the city
two seasons ago, their new nickname reflected a dual meaning. The
link of the Lynx to the genteel sport of golf is obvious, and the
feline connection is honored by a live lynx which resides in a cage
in the Richmond County Civic Center during home games. One
question: Should Tiger Woods be informed of this?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
