<HEADLINE>
KASPER NOT EAGER TO REVISIT GHOSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Steve Kasper is an agent now, likes his life of
representing players, and doesn't long for the days of being behind
an NHL bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given that a thought,'' Kasper said last week,
reflecting on the business only some 24 hours after Robbie Ftorek,
his Devils in first place in the Eastern Conference, was given the
gate in New Jersey. ``I mean, the idea of being successful, and
then having to pick up every two or three years, that's not really
appealing to me at this point in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   For those in Bruins Country who need reminding, Kasper was
behind the bench here in the Hub when the Bruins last finished out
of the playoffs. Only three years later, the Black and Gold club
coached by Pat Burns is about to meet a similar fate, unless there
is another version of the Massachusetts Miracle staged on Causeway
Street in the last two weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond how they'll be compared in their futility, there really
isn't much in common between Kasper's 1996-97 Bruins and today's
lackluster lot under Burns. For two seasons, Kasper and assistant
Cap Raeder were in charge of an aging squad with some key stars _
Ray Bourque, Adam Oates, and Cam Neely _ that desperately needed an
infusion of young support players. When the old guys fell apart,
Mssrs. Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell decided it was time to cut
with the past and ditched the likes of Oates, Rick Tocchet, and
Bill Ranford, all of whom were dispatched to D.C. in the swap for
Jason Allison, Anson Carter, and Jim Carey.
</P>
<P>
   The employment equation changed drastically not only on the
roster, but behind the bench, too. When the smoke cleared, and
everyone was talking about moving ahead with youth (the club Burns
inherited), Kasper and Raeder were left looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Sinden sincerely believes Kasper did a good
job behind the bench. Sinden said last week it was the public
outcry over how Kasper handled one incident _ the benching of Neely
and Kevin Stevens in a game at Toronto _ that ultimately left him
with no choice but to make the change in coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt his public persona,'' said Sinden, referring to the
Neely benching that riled vox populi. ``But I thought he was a
damned good coach. I likened him to Terry O'Reilly _ maybe not
quite right there yet, but on his way to being a damned good coach.
It's just that the public perception was so strong against him,
after benching Neely and the fact that we finished last. Everyone
was focusing on that. We couldn't move beyond it. I had no
rebuttal. If you recall, I was in his corner over the benching
thing. Between that, though, and finishing last . . . for the
organization's sake, I really had to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, in a wide-ranging interview with the Globe,
team owner Jeremy Jacobs identified Kasper and the much-beloved Don
Cherry as two of the club's worst coaches in his quarter-century of
ownership. Neither Sinden nor Kasper chose to comment directly
about Jacobs's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he felt that way,'' said Sinden. ``Overall, I'd
liken Steve's situation to changes you sometimes see in government.
You'll see situations where the government is good, but the leaders
get tossed because economics are down. Other times, you see bad
leaders keep jobs simply because economics are good. Steve Kasper
got caught in that political situation with Cam and there was just
no getting beyond it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasper remains ever the loyalist, even while suffering the
slings and arrows from the owner's office in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole season, right to the last game, we played hard,''
he said. ``We were just a team short on talent. I'll just say that
I know what we had and I think we got a lot out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How are the Bruins going to go about rebuilding the franchise?
Well, they haven't dared to spend with the big boys since the
summer of '95 when they swapped for Stevens and Shawn McEachern,
and they did that then because they knew they had seats to fill
with the opening of the new and bigger FleetCenter. After this
season's flop, and Bourque's departure, empty seats loom again. But
will management spend again? At the moment, it appears they have no
choice. If so, two names to keep in mind: 1. Brendan Shanahan and
2. Keith Tkachuk. Shanahan is an unrestricted free agent as of July
1 and will be looking for at least $6 million-plus a year.
Tkachuk's deal in Phoenix increases to $8.3 million next season,
which has made him virtually an untradeable commodity (remember
Hurricanes owner Peter Karmanos calling Tkachuk's deal ``a stupid
contract''?). But with last summer's drastic drop in free agent
prices _ everywhere except Manhattan _ the likes of Shanahan and,
eventually, Tkachuk, ultimately might have to look at smaller
paydays. At a price around $5 million or $6 million, the Bruins
could be enticed by Shanahan or Tkachuk _ more so Shanahan, because
they wouldn't have to give up bodies in the acquisition . . . There
isn't a single NHLer who would take the ice without putting on a
protective cup and pulling on elbow pads and shinguards. But the
vast majority choose to play without eye protection. Go figure. In
light of Bryan Berard's tragic accident a couple of weeks ago, the
matter is just now getting proper attention. Kudos to Toronto boss
Ken Dryden, who stated the obvious last week, noting that sooner or
later everyone will wear eye protection. ``And why not sooner than
later?'' asked Dryden. Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Ftorek was skilled. He is also a skilled X's and
O's guy. What he needs, obviously, is a crash course in people
skills. No doubt he'll get another chance, but it will take a
cooling off period, similar to the waiting game Mike Keenan has had
to play since getting turfed in Vancouver, his fifth club. Bedside
manner isn't addressed in the Coach's Manual, but eventually every
good coach has to develop it, or at least figure out the facade . .
. Now that Eric Lindros has burned the bridge in Philadelphia even
before he departs, what do the Flyers do? L'Enfant Terrible
unloaded on club management and medical staff last week after
learning, via second opinion, that he suffered a Grade 2 concussion
when hit recently by Boston defenseman Hal Gill. The Flyers'
medical staff had told him his problem was migraine headaches. It's
obvious the two sides can't live with one another, but where are
the Flyers going to find a suitor for Lindros, his $8.5 million
salary, and his dicey medical history, including last year's
collapsed lung and numerous concussions? The only potential landing
spot could be the Rangers, who would be only too happy to unload
their No. 1 headache, Theo Fleury. Another out for the Flyers could
be to hope that Lindros gets a Group 2 (free agent) offer sheet
over the summer and they pick up five first-round picks as
compensation . . . Ken London, former producer/director of Channel
38's Bruins broadcasts, figures Bourque has played the equivalent
of more than a full season shorthanded. The rough math: Bourque
will have played some 1,525 games by season's end and,
conservatively, he was on the ice at least four minutes per game
while the Bruins/Avalanche killed penalties _ a total of 6,100
minutes, or approximately 100 games. It proves two things: 1.
Bourque could use a breather; 2. London has a little too much spare
time on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pronger has emerged as a viable (leading?) candidate for
the Hart Trophy, awarded to the league's Most Valuable Player. The
last defenseman to win it was Bobby Orr, who rattled off three
(1970-72). Another great Bruins blue liner, Eddie Shore, won it
four times in the '30s . . . Ex-BU forward Mike Grier will be out
of the Edmonton lineup at least three weeks, following surgery to
repair a torn left triceps and tendon near the elbow . . . For
better or worse, Mike Vernon will be Florida's No. 1 goalie for the
playoffs. He's not the best answer, but he's better than Trevor
Kidd . . . As of Saturday, the brothers Bure (Pavel and Valeri)
were within one goal of tying the brothers Hull (Bobby and Dennis)
for most NHL goals by brothers in a season. Bobby scored 58 and
Dennis 30 for the record of 88, set in '68-69. As of Friday
morning, Pavel had 52 for the Panthers and Valeri 35 for the
Flames. ``It doesn't matter if he scores 88 and I score 1,'' said
Valeri. ``It will be our record. If we do it, it will be something
special.'' . . . Sergei Zubov's new deal in Dallas will bring him
$25 million over five years. Is he that good? Probably not. But it
underscores, once more, the value of a legitimate quarterback to
work the point during power plays . . . Detroit coach Scotty Bowman
didn't win friends in NHL headquarters with his skewering of
referees Dave Jackson and Rob Shick following the Wings' 4-3 win
over Colorado. He added to the insult when he fingered Bryan Lewis,
director of officiating, for not assigning one or two of the top
refs _ Bill McCreary, Kerry Fraser, Don Koharski, or Dan Marouelli,
by Bowman's account _ to such a key game. Bowman wound up with a
$7,500 fine for his tirade . . . As with the Marty McSorley
incident, there is no defending Scott Niedermayer for chopping
Florida tough guy Peter Worrell over the head with his stick
(Niedermayer was suspended 10 games). But Worrell goes over the top
sometimes. Witness: his throat-slashing gestures, which the league
promptly outlawed . . . Ron Tugnutt, recently dealt from Ottawa to
Pittsburgh for Tom Barrasso, would be a logical candidate to move
to Tampa Bay as a free agent in the offseason. Remember, Bolts boss
Rick Dudley was Senators GM when Tugnutt was north of the border,
and Tampa Bay needs a veteran hand to bring along Dan Cloutier . .
. Only two clubs have fired coaches in the second half of the
season and gone on to win the Cup. The Leafs ditched Art Duncan for
Dick Irvin and won in '32. The Habs dumped Claude Ruel and won with
Al MacNeil calling the shots in '71 _ and with Dryden stopping
everything in net . . . Kelly Buchberger, when asked if he had any
say when it came to his being dealt from Atlanta to Los Angeles:
``I'm not Ray Bourque _ I don't have that luxury.'' In the end, not
even Bourque had that luxury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
