<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX NOT LETTING SEASON TURN TO ASHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last week, after helping Phoenix defeat the Celtics,
Penny Hardaway took a moment to reflect on how his new team does
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, they have great management,'' said Hardaway. ``They have
a great staff overall. They make sure everything is up to par.
Before we leave the building, if there's anything we need, they get
it right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, there was something the Suns needed. And they
went after it right away, before Hardaway &AMP; Co. left America West
Arena after dispatching the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Just before halftime of the Kings game, Suns sparkplug Jason
Kidd went down with a broken ankle. Before the game was over, Suns
executives Bryan Colangelo and Cotton Fitzsimmons were tossing
around names. Colangelo put the initials ``KJ'' at the bottom of
his list and circled them. Fitzsimmons liked what he saw and picked
up the phone, making an SOS call to Kevin Johnson, who retired
after the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' said Suns CEO Jerry Colangelo, ``things move
quickly around here.''
</P>
<P>
   And KJ, who said he spurned other offers last year because it
wouldn't have felt right wearing a uniform other than Phoenix's, is
scheduled to be back in a Phoenix uniform Sunday night against the
Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   No one could replace Kidd, who will be a first-team All-NBA
selection (or should be) and one of the top five MVP candidates.
But KJ is as good a fallback as one could envision. He just turned
34, and while he hasn't played in two years, he claims to be in
excellent shape _ somehow we can't imagine otherwise _ and will get
a full month to get back into the flow. Even more important, he'll
be eligible for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought this day would come,'' Johnson said upon
arriving back in the Valley of the Sun. ``I don't think anybody can
anticipate something like this. But it's the life we live and the
twists that come our way. I never thought I'd say this, but it's
good to see you (media) guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns proved again that, as the late, great Ron Grinker liked
to say, they play chess while the others play checkers. They have
had an incredible string of misfortune this season, ranging from
Tom Gugliotta's near-fatal seizure, to Penny's foot problems (22
games missed), to Shawn Marion's knee woes, to Gugliotta's
season-ending knee injury, to Rex Chapman's appendectomy. There
also was Danny Ainge's abrupt resignation. Somehow, they have risen
above it all and, entering the weekend, had the fifth-best record
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who had tired of Orlando (and vice versa), is
continually amazed at how the Suns operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once (Orlando) management kind of turned against me, I knew I
couldn't win the battle; once they gave up on me, it was time to
go,'' he said. ``Here, they come in and tell you what's on their
minds. That's the biggest thing. If they have a problem, they tell
you. That's the way it has to be. It'd save a lot of relationships
if you could just be straightforward instead of trying to go behind
players' backs and affecting their games.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Kidd is a devastating loss both individually to
Hardaway and to the Suns. KJ will help. But Kidd is a magnet for
others because he gets them the ball. The first words out of
Hardaway's mouth Monday when he was asked what he liked most about
Phoenix were ``Jason Kidd.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes that they're letting him just be Penny. He may not
be an All-Star Game regular anymore (last appearance, 1998) or an
annual All-NBA selection (last appearance, 1997) but he is happy to
blend in. He's been the big fish in the little pond, and it didn't
go well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where I had to be Superman in
Orlando,'' he said. ``Once I got hurt, no one wanted to accept that
I wasn't the same player at that time. I had knee surgery. I
couldn't come back and play like they wanted me to play. I was a
wimp. Chuck (Daly) came in and wanted instant success. The year
before, I had 40-plus points, back-to-back, in the playoffs against
Miami. That's the player he wanted. But I still had knee problems.
I had to have a second surgery. And he gave up on me. I couldn't
reach his expectations with a 10-foot pole. If I couldn't get
there, it wasn't accepted. He had high standards and I couldn't
produce for him the way he wanted. He gave up on me. That's just
the way it went.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston will be crawling with NBA executives and scouts over the
next few days. The reason: the annual McDonald's High School
All-Star Game is Wednesday night at the FleetCenter. Scouts and
general managers are likely to be more interested in watching the
practices (Sunday, Monday, and Tuesday) and the scrimmage (Tuesday)
than the actual game, which has turned into a glorified
dunk-o-rama. ``The games have been disappointing ever since the
high school exodus started,'' said Celtics GM Chris Wallace.
``They've disintegrated into these rock-and-jock contests where
there's no defense and everything is `can you top this?' The
practices can be more revealing. And it's also better to either see
these guys with their own high school team or at a summer event.''
There are six kids thought to be considering a direct jump to the
NBA. The best of the lot, 6-foot-9-inch Eddie Griffin from Roman
Catholic in Philadelphia, is believed to be thinking about honoring
his commitment to Seton Hall. How's that for a concept? But 6-9
Darius Miles of East St. Louis, Ill., who has committed to St.
John's, and 6-7 Gerald Wallace, of Childersburg, Ala., who has
committed to Alabama, are thought to be closer to taking the
plunge. (The Blue Ribbon Yearbook said last fall that Wallace and
Griffin were further along than Al Harrington, Tracy McGrady, and
Jonathan Bender were at this point.) Another, Jerome ``Buddy''
Harper, who hails from Columbia, S.C., is thought to be coming out
as well. He's a 6-6 shooting guard who has bounced from school to
school and may have eligibility concerns. Two others thought to be
considering: DeShawn Stevenson, a 6-5 guard from Fresno, Calif.,
and Alton Ford, a 6-9 Karl Malone-in-the-making from Houston.
Wallace said he doesn't understand what all the fuss is about when
the topic turns to high schoolers turning pro. ``I think it's been
overblown,'' he said. ``First of all, you're talking about a
handful of kids. It's not like we're getting 30 guys every year.
Yes, a few shouldn't have done it. But how can you legislate away
the freedom of a Kevin Garnett or a Kobe Bryant to protect a Red
McDavid? And the teams that drafted these guys would do so again.
Rashard Lewis (a second-rounder in 1998) would probably be a top 15
pick if that draft were redone. Where I think it does hurt the
league is on the promotional end. You don't see these guys in
college and it takes a while for them to get the recognition they
would have had had they gone to a Final Four or two.'' The Celtics
have several McDonald's alums, from Pervis Ellison to Paul Pierce.
Asked about the game, Pierce said, ``It was something special for
me because I had a chance to showcase my skills against the top
players. It gave me a lot of confidence going into college.'' That
year, the game also featured Garnett, Vince Carter, Stephon
Marbury, and Shareef Abdur-Rahim. But Pierce also says he found his
college experience invaluable. ``It was important to me,'' he said.
``I don't think I was ready or mature enough to make that jump.
College days are some of the best days of your life. It's the last
chance you have to still be a kid and have a lot of fun, because
once you get to the NBA, it's all work. Some of the things you
experience in college, you don't get a chance to do. I'm glad I had
a chance to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame has advanced to the semifinals of the National
Invitation Tournament in New York, and there's one man watching the
Irish with a certain degree of smugness: John MacLeod. He spent
eight seasons in South Bend and now is back in the NBA as the
treasured ``veteran assistant'' on Scott Skiles's Phoenix staff.
MacLeod has bittersweet memories of his years at Notre Dame. He
never got the Irish into any postseason tournaments, and there was
a ``Forever .500'' feel about them during his years. But he's proud
that he helped get them into a conference. (The school was an
independent until 1995-96.) ``I campaigned like heck to get Notre
Dame into a conference,'' said MacLeod. ``When we joined the Big
East, it was a lot tougher than it is now. And it was the right
move for Notre Dame basketball.'' A sore spot: He feels his
reputation as a recruiter was belittled, even though he got Troy
Murphy and Matt Carroll to come to South Bend. ``We recruited one
heck of a group of kids,'' he said. ``Both of those guys are going
to be NBA players. And, against a lot of odds, we did an excellent
job of recruiting. We didn't have a lot of support in that area.
When your ability to recruit is questioned publicly, in the papers,
while you are in the middle of the recruiting process, that's what
I refer to as not getting the support you need. It's tough enough
to recruit as it is without having your ability as a recruiter
questioned in the middle of the recruiting process. That's what was
taking place.'' . . . Another ringing endorsement of the Clipper
Way, courtesy of Rodney Rogers: ``They don't try to do anything.
They just try to stay the same and they don't care that players
want to leave or get traded. The owner doesn't care. The front
office doesn't care. You end up showing up and collecting the
check. It's no fun out there at all.'' . . . One of the great
late-season stories is the somewhat startling success of the
Pistons. Detroit had lost 11 straight on the road. But when the
Pistons headed out West under interim coach George Irvine, who is
doing what he wants because he's not interested in the job, what
happens? Detroit beats Vancouver, Seattle, and Portland to start
the trip, improving to 7-2 under Irvine. Against the Sonics and
Blazers, Grant Hill, nursing a sore ankle, scored 28 fourth-quarter
points on 14-of-19 shooting. ``George has been smart,'' Hill said
after the Portland game. ``He doesn't run me dog-tired. In the
past, I'd get tired down the stretch. Not to make excuses, but when
I'm fresh down the stretch, I play better.'' . . . Speaking of the
Blazers, they will use Jermaine O'Neal a lot more now that Arvydas
Sabonis is out indefinitely with a sprained right foot. Old friend
Joe Kleine also could be exhumed for real playing time. That's why
he's there . . . Indiana's 21-point loss to Milwaukee Thursday
night was the Pacers' worst home setback since a 24-pointer to
Sacramento in November 1995. The Pacers were booed as they left the
court at halftime. Imagine that . . . Those frolicking Bulls are on
track to become the lowest-scoring team over a full season since
1954-55. Of course, the Bulls took scoring to a new low last year,
when they (a) averaged 81.9 points a game and (b) erupted for 49 in
a game against Miami. They are about 3 points below the 1954-55
Milwaukee Hawks, which, given their personnel, can hardly be termed
a shocker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
