<SLUG> BC-BKW-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN'S DEPTH STOPS OKLAHOMA; LSU IS NEXT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ The Connecticut women's basketball team, ranked
first in the nation all season, is a caravan of steamrollers
hurtling down the highway at breakneck speed.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: the Round of 8.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams are fortunate to field five good players; Connecticut
boasts a continuous wave of all-world and all-American talent,
undeniable and interchangeable.
</P>
<P>
   When Oklahoma players peeled themselves off the court,
Connecticut's substitutes hovered over them Saturday, eclipsing the
Sooners' sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you feel kind of smothered, you can't breathe,''
Oklahoma Coach Sherri Coale said after the game. ``It was like each
basket gave us oxygen just to get us through to the next one, and
there it comes again.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the top-seeded Huskies flattened the fifth-seeded
Sooners, 102-80, in the East Regional of the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament to advance to the Round of 8 for
the sixth time in seven years. Eleven Connecticut players scored,
five in double figures. Asjha Jones and Tamika Williams _ the
sophomore forwards who come off the bench _ led their team with 16
points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut will play third-seeded Louisiana State on Monday for
a berth in the Final Four in Philadelphia. LSU defeated Duke,
79-66, in the earlier regional semifinal Saturday at Alltel
Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some pretty talented players on our team; it could be
any two or three people any night,'' said Shea Ralph, the UConn
starting guard who scored 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have starting post players that wear out their starting
post players and then we put two more in. We don't miss a beat. A
lot of time, they're even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Every player Connecticut Coach Geno Auriemma recruited was an
all-American in high school. Ralph and Williams, were national
players of the year. So was Kelly Schumacher, in Canada, and
Svetlana Abrosimova, in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   There is remarkable depth on the UConn team, which crushed
opponents by an average margin of 31.7 points this season. With
five players who average double figures, the balance always seems
to be in the Huskies' favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the Microsoft of women's basketball,'' Auriemma
said. ``Somebody can sue us when we have a monopoly on the game.
But we don't have a monopoly on the game. Tennessee does with all
their championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has one national title to Tennessee's six. The two
could meet in this year's championship game, three contests away.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Huskies were seeded No. 1 in the East Regional
was in 1995, when they were undefeated and won their only title.
This season the Huskies are winning just as convincingly as that
team.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two rounds of this tournament, the Huskies beat
their opponents by an average of 54.5 points, holding them to an
average of 45 points. Although the Sooners scored 42 points by
halftime, the Huskies had already established their defensive tone.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma actually took a 9-6 lead with 16 minutes 34 seconds
remaining in the first half. Connecticut responded by unleashing an
18-0 run in a frantic three minutes, which included six steals.
UConn caused 33 turnovers in the game.Twenty-one of them came on
steals.
</P>
<P>
   As Oklahoma pulled within 57-42 at the half, the Sooners
celebrated each shot as if it were a moral victory. Within the
first five minutes of the second half, though, Connecticut raced to
a 67-46 lead. Jones scored 12 of her 16 points in the second half
to keep the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to score as many points as we can,'' Abrosimova said.
``Our defense is really aggressive. We don't look at the scoreboard
and say, `We're up by 20, we can stop playing.' We just keep
pressing. We keep pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Phylesha Whaley, the only senior for Oklahoma, which was making
its first appearance in the Round of 16, said the Sooners had no
answer for Connecticut's depth. ``You can't tell when one comes
in,'' she said. ``They don't drop off.''
</P>
<P>
   With 36.8 seconds left, 6-6 forward Christine Rigby, who plays
just four minutes per game, sunk a perfect left-handed hook shot
that broke the 100-point mark. She finished the play by converting
the foul shot, an exclamation point to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma said: ``They better not be satisfied. We're not done
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State (25-6) was trailing Duke, last year's national
runner-up, by 5 points with 12:56 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Then the LSU junior guard Marie Ferdinand leapt to make a steal,
scored a quick layup and ignited an 18-4 run that sent the Tigers
to the Round of 8 for the first time in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore DeTrina White gave her team a boost on the boards
in the second half, finishing with 11 rebounds and 19 points. She
led four starters who had been together for 61 games past a young
Duke team down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``All throughout the season my team has fed off me,'' said
Ferdinand, who finished with a game-high 22 points, 11 in the final
12 minutes. ``I got the team a lift and I was able to get the run
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State held the Blue Devils, usually 37 percent
shooters beyond the arc, to just 5 for 22 from 3-point range.
Louisiana State, meanwhile, shot 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``LSU played the game we wanted to play; they always made the
extra pass,'' said Duke's Lauren Rice, who led her team in scoring
with 17 points. ``We tried to trap them, but then Ferdinand ended
up with easy layups in the lane.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
