<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-BRUINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SETTLE FOR TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Maybe you don't have to play all 60 minutes like the
coach keeps insisting. Maybe the Los Angeles Kings found a few
shamrocks left over from St. Patty's Day, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Andy Murray knows there are no maybes when the playoffs
begin in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He knows Saturday afternoon's 4-4 tie with the Boston Bruins in
front of 17,565 at the Fleet Center will not be a tie against the
Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Murray took no solace in watching his team overcome a three-goal
deficit in the final period to force overtime against the
disappointing Bruins. The Kings had dug such a hole that Murray
unleashed a stick-throwing tirade before the third period that
still had him shaken after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have to realize that in the National Hockey League
you just can't turn it on and off,'' Murray said. ``It was
disgusting the way we played the first 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after playing probably their most inspired game of
the season last Thursday in Philadelphia. The Kings tied that game
with 2:15 left in regulation and won it 3-2 in overtime, both on
goals by Jozef Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they broke down after Luc Robitaille gave them a
1-0lead midway through the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins scored the next four goals, including two by Scott
Heinze. Brian Rolston made it 4-1 with less than two minutes left
in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kings (35-30-10, 84 points) remain fifth in the
Western Conference with seven games to play, Murray knows it is
just as easy to get bounced from there in the first round as it is
from the eighth and final spot.
</P>
<P>
   So Murray pulled goaltender Stephane Fiset after two periods,
not out of disgust but out of respect for the game played in
Philadelphia and concern for the way his teammates let him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fiset) did not deserve what we did to him,'' said Glen
Murray, who scored twice in the second period, including the second
with 21 seconds remaining in regulation. ``I don't know what it
was, whether it was the afternoon game or a letdown after
Philadelphia or whatever. It never should have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the goal that gave the Bruins a 2-1 lead. Shawn Bates stole
the puck away from Bryan Smolinski along the boards. Bates tried a
backhander against Fiset, but the puck rebounded to the slot where
Heinze fired it for the goal.
</P>
<P>
   And not on the next goal when Stumpel turned it over and Heinze
wound up with his second and a 3-1 Boston lead with 13:40 in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   But there were other signs of the breakdown. The Kings were
outshot 17-4 in the first period. Kelly Buchberger and Aki Berg
were called for penalties in the Boston end during the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played so bad, it could have been 5-0 after one,'' said Ian
Laperriere. ``Not a lot of people know how intense the coach can
be. He let us have it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Murray stopped yelling, the Kings took off. They even
could have won it when a high-sticking penalty by Kyle McLaren gave
them 1:54 on the power play in OT.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings caught their first break just 28 seconds into the
third period when Dave Van Impe was called for holding. Seventeen
seconds later, Glen Murray took a pass from Stumpel in the corner
and one-timed it past Bruins goaltender John Grahame.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd started to buzz. The Bruins, considered a playoff
contender before the season, has faltered badly. On Thursday, they
took a two-goal lead into the third and lost 4-3 to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started playing too tight,'' Heinze said. ``We played not
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings made it a one-goal game at 8:07 when Bob Corkum skated
from behind the net and fired the puck past Grahame.
</P>
<P>
   Boston continued to fade and the Kings kept on the pressure.
With a minute to go, the Kings pulled Jamie Storr, who replaced
Fiset. Stumpel, one of two centers on the ice, took the puck out of
the corner and fed Murray in front.
</P>
<P>
   With 21 seconds left, Murray scored his 26th of the year, one
behind injured Ziggy Palffy for second on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good that we came back, but bad that we had to,'' Garry
Galley said. ``This is why St. Louis has the best record in the
league. Every night they are consistent. That's where we need to
get. In a hurry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
