r s BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     03-25 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S COMMENTS TOWARD CARTER ARE, ER, DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Toronto forward Vince Carter has grown tired of
the increasing comparisons to Michael Jordan this season, but they
must be gaining some validity.
</P>
<P>
   Because this week, the hyper-competitive Jordan went out of his
way to take a shot at ``Air Canada,'' just as he is blossoming into
the NBA's best marketing tool for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   That's a role Jordan owned in the '90s, and even though he's
retired, don't expect him to be gracious toward anyone who might be
considered a worthy successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince doesn't play defense,'' Jordan said. ``Kobe (Bryant) can
play both ends. Right now, (Bryant) is the better player.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had a simple response to Jordan's comments: ``So what?''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan continued by paying a backhanded compliment to Carter's
offensive skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince Carter is probably the worst thing for (Bryant) because
Vince can dunk and do all the incredible things and that makes Kobe
want to do them, too, for the notoriety.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter wasn't amused. ``I don't care what anybody says about (my
defense),'' he said. ``People (make critical comments) for a
reason. Everybody has an opinion on everybody else. It's no
different than hearing it from anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The stunning aspect of Jordan's criticism is that he slammed a
fellow North Carolina alumnus, which is supposed to be one of the
tightest and most loyal cliques in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do (stick together),'' Carter said. ``But (Jordan) is a
popular guy. We don't see him much.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was asked if he had any sort of relationship with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't surprise many of Jordan's Bulls teammates, who
would have a similar answer to that question.
</P>
<P>
   The self-serving comments continued for Jordan this week, when
he announced he would no longer make endorsements once his current
contracts expire. It's a little late for Jordan to find religion on
this topic, after shamelessly hawking himself for the past 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Music buff: Nets coach Don Casey was introduced to a member of
the pop group 'N Sync this week. ``Is that one of those bands that
hums?'' Casey asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sundown in Phoenix: No team has experienced worse injury
problems than the Suns, and that was before Jason Kidd broke his
ankle Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Kidd's injury, the Suns temporarily lost Tom Gugliotta
after he suffered a seizure, and then for the rest of the season
after his knee injury. Penny Hardaway missed 21 games with a torn
foot muscle, and Rex Chapman underwent emergency surgery for an
appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't enough, center Oliver Miller got into an
altercation this week with assistant coach Phil Weber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather not talk about it,'' Miller said, although he
did apologize to Suns president Bryan Colangelo. No word if he
apologized to Weber.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kidd, he is expected to return for the Olympics in
September, but his return for the playoffs is doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   No Nike fan: Sonics small forward Ruben Patterson has been out
with a swelled Achilles' tendon, and he swears the injury is the
result of his Nikes, after a MRI proved negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to wear Nikes anymore,'' Patterson said. ``Gary
(Payton) went through it. Vin (Baker) went through it. I think it's
just how Nikes are made.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time a player has blamed his shoes for an
injury. Earlier this year, the Suns' Hardaway blamed his Nikes for
contributing to his foot problems.
</P>
<P>
   Easy on Rider: Miami coach Pat Riley was intrigued by the
possibility of adding released/troubled Hawks guard Isaiah Rider,
but since Rider would be ineligible for the playoffs, Riley will
wait until the offseason to make a run at the enigmatic shooting
guard.
</P>
<P>
   New league: The NBA is close to announcing formation of a new
minor league in the fall of 2001, with eight to 12 teams in non-NBA
cities playing in arenas of around 10,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The league is concerned about the growing number of young
players trying to make the jump to the NBA. There was one redshirt
freshman, four true freshman and two high school players in last
year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would always prefer that (a player) goes to college,'' NBA
deputy commissioner Russ Granik said. ``Legally, we can't require
it. So, if he has made the decision not to (go to college), but
he's not quite ready to play in the NBA, we think having some other
league where we could closely monitor him would be better for the
player and ultimately better for the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the NBA can make a little money on the side ... so much
the better.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious downfall is that too many marginal players will
forgo college, preferring to play in the developmental league.
</P>
<P>
   A 10 spot: The Mavericks have added former Lakers coach Del
Harris and former Wizards coach Gar Heard, bringing to 10 the
number of assistants on the staff.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Peter Vecsey of the New York Post to write: ``The
Mavericks team plane now has three classes ... first, coach and
assistant coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mavs owner Mark Cuban didn't appreciate Vecsey's criticism
regarding Cuban's hiring practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can quote me on this; Peter Vecsey is an idiot,'' Cuban
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
