u s BC-OLY-TURIN-BOS &LR;      03-25 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TURIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURIN OUT TO CHANGE ITS IMAGE WITH '06 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TURIN, Italy _ Their calling cards still say ``candidate city''
and from time to time the organizers will catch themselves
reverting to bidding mode. ``Bid? Basta! (Enough!),'' says
committee chief executive Evelina Christillin with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Turin, the old industrial city on the banks of the Po, will be
hosting the 2006 Olympic Winter (si, Winter) Games. The Lords of
the Rings decreed it last June in Seoul when they chose this city
of a million people over the Swiss hamlet of Sion in a startling
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the victory, there were very few people who thought we
could win,'' says Marco San Pietro, the committee's international
relations director.
</P>
<P>
   And now, nine months later, it's finally sinking in that the
world is coming and the clock is ticking. Though the Games are
still six years away, everything must be up and running by the
autumn of 2004. But until the government turns over the $600
million needed to build everything from the ice rinks to the bob
run, nothing can begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have time,'' says Christillin. ``But we have no time
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Turinese, who had never before bid for the Games, hardly
expected to get them. Their bid, which wasn't launched until May
1998, was primarily a marketing tool to show that the Piedmontese
capital was more than automobiles and soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiat and Juventus are great resources,'' says mayor Valentino
Castellani, who doubles as committee president. ``But Turin is much
more. The industrial image we have is from the century that is just
past. But before, our city was one of the great capitals of Europe,
part of the Grand Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Turin, founded two millennia ago by the Romans (who called it
Taurinorum, the city of bulls), was the first capital of the
kingdom of Italy in the 1860s. It was the showplace of the House of
Savoy, a baroque jewel at the foot of the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Henry James, the American writer, called Turin ``a city of
arcades, of pink and yellow stucco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every object is a reminder, every reminder a thrill,'' he
wrote nine decades ago in ``Italian Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as its residents readily admit, is that there are
too many reminders here of what was. The city's history, and curse,
is for things to begin here and move elsewhere. Over time, Turin
was eclipsed by Rome, by Milan, by Florence, by Venice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in Australia two years ago, we had to point out
Turin on a map,'' says Christillin.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic bid was a way to make the city stand out in bold
baroque type on the eve of its third millennium. Nobody denied that
it was a long shot. Italy hadn't hosted the Winter Games since
Cortina d'Ampezzo in 1956, when Americans still watched them on
movie newsreels.
</P>
<P>
   Sion had bid before, had wined and dined and lobbied
International Olympic Committee members by the dozen. The town was
a short train ride along the lake from Lausanne, headquarters of
the IOC and many international sports federations.
</P>
<P>
   When Swiss journalists ventured here for a look, they brought
back tales of an industrial sinkhole with no snow and no chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Swiss were so sure,'' says Christillin. ``They had no
doubts, not for one moment. It was like a one-man race.''
</P>
<P>
   When the IOC abruptly banned visits to bid cities last winter in
the wake of the Salt Lake City payoff scandal, the Turinese figured
they were doomed. How could they convince the Lords that this was a
winter city, that the mountains were barely an hour's drive to the
west?
</P>
<P>
   They had been counting on the visits to give the voters their
own Grand Tour, to show them the arcades and piazzas and castles
and museums, and ply them with agnolotti and Barbera d'Asti and
their fabled chocolates and ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can send them a book, but it is not the same thing,'' San
Pietro said with a shrug back then. ``They cannot taste our wine or
our food.''
</P>
<P>
   So Turin was left to practice the ancient Italian art of
arrangiarsi, of making impromptu arrangements. Its approach was
subtle, both by necessity and by design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turin is not a city that leaps with enthusiasm,'' says
Castellani, an engineer who did his graduate work at MIT and calls
Boston ``my second home.'' ``It is a city of understatement. That
is the usual mood, and you can't change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rome had boasted and swaggered two years earlier and lost the
2004 Summer Games to Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good lesson for us about what to do and what not to
do,'' says Christillin. ``The Romans had said their candidacy was
by far the best. We decided not to shout too much, to be cool and
calm and not pretend that we were the favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Turin's low profile played perfectly against Sion's brass-band
clamor. And the Italians got an undeniable boost from the ``Hodler
backlash'' _ voters who resented Marc Hodler, the Swiss member
whose whistle-blowing on his hands-out colleagues broke open the
Salt Lake scandal and turned the IOC inside-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we made our calculations, we thought maybe we could win
by eight or nine votes, no more,'' San Pietro says. Instead, Turin
won by a stunning 17 out of 89 cast. Castellani and his cool, calm
coterie sprayed champagne on each other in the hotel lobby and
returned home amazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back, I am still wondering how we could do it,''
acknowledges Christillin, who makes her living as a university
professor. ``We began with no telephone, no fax, no nothing. We had
not the faintest idea what to do. It was `La Cage Aux Folles.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The organizing committee, which works out of the old Fiat plant
at Lingotto on the edge of downtown, still numbers only 10 people.
``The Korean War refugees,'' Christillin calls them.
</P>
<P>
   The new committee wasn't put together until last month and the
general manager, businessman Paolo Rota (of Diadora sportswear),
won't be named formally until Tuesday. But once the agency
coordinating the government and the organizers is put in place and
the money starts coming in, things will move double-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two opportunities here,'' says Castellani, who will
stay on as committee president after his second mayoral term ends
next year. ``We can change a little bit the image of our city,
which has been obscured by our history as an industrial site. And
we can accelerate our development.''
</P>
<P>
   For too long, Turin has been Detroit with castles, stuck in
neutral and fading from view, wanting to evolve but needing a
jump-start.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be a lab test of what we are capable of doing in the
future,'' says Castellani.
</P>
<P>
   The model is Barcelona, another old industrial city that used
the Games (1992 Summer) as a steam engine to remake itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many similarities,'' says Christillin. ``Barcelona is
our flashlight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Games will force the Turinese to transform a bunch of
overdue projects (a subway, a fast train to Milan, better roads,
more hotels, new housing, renovated factories) from dreams to
realities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be under observation by all the world,'' Castellani
realizes. ``We cannot make mistakes. So it is a nice resource to
have a deadline that is so straight, so imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Turinese are worried. They may be understated (it's
the old House of Savoy influence, they say), but once an object is
in their hands, they are precise. They are eager to show the world
that the home of Fiat and Juventus (whose black-and-white striped
jerseys are soccer's Yankee pinstripes) can also host a winter
carnival.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stay for two weeks on television, everyone in the
world knows where you are,'' Castellani says. ``I did not know
before where Lillehammer was located. Now I know.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was leaving Seoul last June, Castellani picked up a
Korean newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not read what was written, but there was a chart of
Europe,'' he says. ``Next to it was a chart of Italy, with Turin
put there. Now, everybody knows where we are. Having been selected
_ that is already an important result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
