<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND PLAYING MONOPOLY 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ News from the International Skiing Federation meeting
has a most curious headline. Too many injuries, rising costs, and
the dominance of the Austrians are the problems that the FIS is
hashing through in its annual year-end meeting.
</P>
<P>
   There's always been a strong connection between sailing and
skiing, but listen to what FIS officials say about their situation:
``The domination of the sport by the Austrians has become an
increasing concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest problem is that, as Austria dominates skiing with
800-pound gorillas such as Hermann Maier (four of five World Cup
titles) and Renate Goetschl, fans in others countries are losing
interest.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it is idle speculation, but might we be looking
at a similar situation in the America's Cup?
</P>
<P>
   According to ESPN, once Prada sqeaked past AmericaOne to win the
Louis Vuitton Cup and face New Zealand in the America's Cup final,
television viewership fell like a rock.
</P>
<P>
   It was not helped by the three days of abandoned light-air races
interspersed with inflexible laydays, three of which fell right
after postponements.
</P>
<P>
   And with the near-certainty after a couple of races that Prada
was not in contention, the air was out of the Cup balloon for good.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't seem to be an end in sight to the domination of
the Austrian ski team, which won an unheard-of 39 races this
season. Symbolically, the male team made its statement at the
season-ending 2000 Snow Festival, where the 27-year-old Maier and
lots of younger teammates swept the podium in the downhill,
Super-G, and giant slalom.
</P>
<P>
   The women showed only slightly less dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that the skiers fighting for Austrian positions
could score well on any other World Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for spots on the Austrian team is intense.
Talented youngsters who pour out of the country's academy system
have one thing in mind _ to knock off the competitor just ahead on
the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   A 23-year-old star such as gate specialist Benjamin Raich is a
glimpse into the depth and youth of the Austrian team. So who's
going to knock off the juggernaut?
</P>
<P>
   Almost anything that can be said of the Austrian ski team can be
said of the New Zealand America's Cup team, many of whose members
will compete in the next Volvo around-the-world race (formerly
Whitbread).
</P>
<P>
   Once it was clear that the many assumptions were wrong regarding
the value of the Challengers' Olympic-style competition, it was
also true that New Zealand was an indomitable force in not just
building boats but racing them as well.
</P>
<P>
   The sailors who dominated in Auckland earlier this month are
hardly youthful, but there are young sailors who, they say, can
step into any position and sail the A boat just as well as the B
boat.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Coutts's final-day gesture of turning over the wheel to
26-year-old Dean Barker sends no message other than that. And
Barker took that message a step further by sailing a stronger start
than the four Coutts sailed before him.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gary Jobson, a former Cup racer and longtime observer:
``There's not one single sailor on the Kiwi team that I would
replace with one from the Challengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the team was so good in every department, the
speculation is still strong that the Kiwis probably could have
beaten Prada if the two sides switched boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our boat had a little edge in some winds,'' said Alan Sefton,
a Team New Zealand syndicate chieftain, ``but not anywhere near as
much as they're making it seem out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Crunch the numbers on the legs of each race, and it is clear
that Prada was much closer in boat speed than the results indicate
_ sort of like a tennis player losing a match, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was in the start, then getting lucky with the
windshifts,'' said New Zealand tactician Brad Butterworth. ``They
couldn't win a start from Russell, and they couldn't win a race
without winning a start.''
</P>
<P>
   So the questions remain, fascinating ones to hold us through the
three offseasons until the next Cup:
</P>
<P>
   --Had Paul Cayard sailed against New Zealand, could he have won
at least the right-entry starts from Coutts? And could AmericaOne
then have held a lead to the finish?
</P>
<P>
   --Even with Patrizio Bertelli in possession of Young America's
boats, which even the Kiwis believe were the fastest of the
Challengers, can they reach beyond the level that Team New Zealand
enjoyed this month?
</P>
<P>
   --In Peter Gilmour's logical view, it will do no good in 2003 to
be as fast as New Zealand was in 2000. And since only New Zealand
has its own benchmark, how do Challengers now find a way to get
beyond them?
</P>
<P>
   And the ultimate question is, again, are the Kiwis so dominant
that they effect a kind of paralysis on Challengers, who must raise
funds, field teams, and build boats?
</P>
<P>
   And start today, if they haven't already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
