<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL MAKING AN EFFORT TO LIFT THE SHADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ David Duval concedes that he has
sought professional advice to help deal with the media after some
rocky times in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to change my nature,'' said Duval. ``I want to
sit here and if I am asked a question, I want to answer the
question. I want to understand sometimes where the questions are
coming from and try to relay my point better than I have in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   It's admirable to make the initiative, and even more so for
Duval to talk openly about it. For two years he received nothing
but positive press, but last year many of the stories turned
negative. Some of it was his fault, he said, but much of it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for instance, all that nonsense coming out of the
British Open, when reporters over there lambasted him as an ugly
American. Supposedly, Duval ripped the tournament, criticized the
Carnoustie layout, and behaved poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that disappointed me the most,'' he said, ``was that
they made it sound like I didn't like playing there. That is
completely 180 degrees from the truth because I love playing over
there. Always have.''
</P>
<P>
   Check the transcripts of his interviews, Duval has said time and
time again, and read his comments about Carnoustie; Duval was no
more critical than the other 149 competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman had terrible things to say about the course. So,
too, did Colin Montgomerie. And Tiger Woods was another.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Duval got ripped.
</P>
<P>
   Next was the Ryder Cup money issue, a situation that never
should have gotten as far as it did. The fact that it boiled over
at the PGA Championship at Medinah was the fault of the PGA of
America, which should have heeded Tom Kite's suggestion and
straightened out the mess following the grumblings at Valderrama in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a whole lot I can change about that week at the
PGA,'' said Duval, who found himself in the middle of a controversy
after an interview in Golf Digest in which he talked honestly about
the right to direct money from the Ryder Cup toward a charity of
his choice. People thought Duval wanted to be paid for playing in
the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you ask my opinion of things, I give it to you,'' Duval
said. ``I don't have a problem with people who differ with my
opinion _ that is what it is all about. But to be lambasted for
having a different opinion . . . well, I find it strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval is trying to convey a better image of himself to golf
fans. To that end, he did a series of commercials for Footjoy,
Charles Schwab, and AT&AMP;T that cast him a favorable light. That's
good for him and good for the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference last week, a reporter started to ask,
``Everybody talks about the whole Tiger rivalry . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Duval politely interrupted and said, ``Not much of a rivalry
right now, is there?''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed, and so did everyone else in the room. Then, when the
press conference ended, Duval put on the sunglasses and retreated.
Not to the solitude of the driving range, but to the madness of the
first tee at TPC Sawgrass, where he helped conduct a junior clinic
for hundreds of kids.
</P>
<P>
   He had them laughing, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour's lucrative TV contract is up next year, and
negotiations probably will start this summer. One idea bandied
about is moving The Players Championship to May, which could take
it away from NBC because of a conflict with the NBA playoffs. Some
officials like the idea of having a marquee event each month _
Andersen Consulting Match Play in March, Masters in April, TPC in
May, US Open in June, British Open in July, PGA in August, American
Express in September, Tour Championship in October _ but there
could be resistance from players. They like TPC's present spot as a
serious springboard to Augusta, but don't be surprised to see it
moved to May. . . . According to PGA Tour officials, major network
ratings for weekend golf coverage are up 11 percent from a year
ago, and ESPN's weekend ratings are up 26 percent. There's probably
a chance those figures will be mentioned during the negotiations .
. . The European Tour breaks new ground this week _ in South
America. The Brazil Rio de Janeiro 500 Years Open marks the Tour's
first visit to that continent, and there will be a second event in
Sao Paulo next week. The European Tour also visits Asia and
Australia . . . When the European Tour actually gets back to
Europe, one of its better events will be the Deutsche Bank SAP Open
in Germany, thanks to the entry of defending champion Woods. It
means missing the MasterCard Colonial, but Woods will have serious
challengers, most notably Nick Price, Jesper Parnevik, Darren
Clarke, Lee Westwood, and Bernhard Langer. Woods's victory at the
Deutsche Bank last May ignited his winning roll . . . Speaking of
Langer, it was a busy week for him. Last Sunday, he finished tied
for 18th at the Bay Hill Invitational. The next day, his wife
delivered the couple's fourth child, and two days later Langer
drove to TPC Sawgrass to squeeze in six practice holes before the
start of The Players Championship. . . . Woods made a cut for the
46th straight time, to tie Vijay Singh for fourth-best in Tour
history. Now Woods can set his sights on 53 (Kite), 86 (Hale
Irwin), and 105 (Jack Nicklaus) . . . President Clinton is the
honorary captain of the 2000 Presidents Cup. Perhaps that means
players will get to hit two or three drives at each tee, select
their best, and have Secret Service agents toss back errant shots
at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twin sisters Aree and Naree Song Wongluekiet were given
sponsor's exemptions into this week's Nabisco Championship. Aree is
in third and in the final pairing, but it's still a major mistake
at a major tournament. Forget all the junior championships they
have won. Forget the immense talent. Remember this: They are just
13 years old. Perhaps they can compete physically with many of the
LPGA Tour players, but so what? Intellectual maturity should be
considered. The sponsor did not do the LPGA Tour any favors by
shoving the sisters into the spotlight, at the expense of gifted
players such as Karrie Webb, Annika Sorenstam, Laura Davies, Juli
Inkster, Dottie Pepper, Janice Moodie, and Lorie Kane. The girls
cannot play regularly on the LPGA Tour until they are 18, but they
have plans for some Monday qualifiers this year. ``They are good
players at this age, but there's a lot of things to avoid, like
burnout, overexposure, injury,'' said Jonathan Yarwood, who coaches
the girls at the David Leadbetter Academy in Florida. ``But
hopefully, if they keep going on the course that they're on,
they're going to be pretty good.'' What's the hurry? . . . Last
year, Sorenstam expressed objections to two days of pro-am play at
the Nabisco, a situation that is still testy. She participated this
year, though a pairing with Celine Dion certainly enticed her . . .
Though she has earned enough points for the LPGA Hall of Fame,
Sorenstam cannot be officially inducted until she completes the
10-year ``waiting period.'' That will take another three years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The youthful innocence seems to be wearing off Sergio Garcia,
who has not played well in the early months as a card-carrying
member of the US PGA Tour. In his round of 82 Thursday at TPC,
Garcia looked (take your pick) mystified, bored, frustrated, and
befuddled. Conditions were brutal, and had he been more
experienced, perhaps he would have done what Duval and Montgomerie
did later in the day in much tougher conditions _ hang in there and
shoot 75. Instead, Garcia played carelessly and with very little
patience. His swing is long and loose and gets him in trouble quite
often. Fortunately, he has a marvelous short game and can get
himself out of many dire situations. Unfortunately, a marvelous
short game alone will not cut it on the PGA Tour week in and week
out. The undisciplined mechanics could prove costly to Garcia,
something that Price alluded to last summer. Garcia also seems less
at ease with the media, which is understandable. Then again, he
jumped into this madness with full force, and trying to play in the
US and Europe this year, at the tender age of 20, could be a
mistake. TPC is his fourth event (three medal play), and in 12
rounds he has broken 70 just once. He has missed the cut twice.
When he talked following Thursday's debacle, Garcia seemed far
removed from the bubbly personality who captivated the golf world
last year. ``It looks like it is taking its time,'' he said. ``We
will keep waiting and let's see what we can do.'' . . . If he
continues to struggle, how attractive will that Garcia-Woods
made-for-TV event be? . . . Duval showed that he has a good grasp
of the situation when asked about winning last year's TPC. He
didn't want to argue the merits of it being a fifth major, but he
does know this: Winners of the TPC since 1991 have one thing in
common _ a major championship on their resumes. The TPC winners who
have won majors: Steve Elkington, TPC winner in 1991 and '97 (PGA
Championship was his major); Davis Love, 1992 (PGA); Price, 1993
(two PGAs, one British Open); Norman, 1994 (two British); Lee
Janzen, 1995 (two US Opens); Fred Couples, 1996 (Masters); Justin
Leonard, 1998 (British Open).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
