<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ COOKING WITH GAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ Pedro Martinez insists he's not much of a
spring training pitcher, which is not to be confused with what he
does in spring once the games count.
</P>
<P>
   Fast starts have been a staple of Martinez's first two seasons
with the Red Sox. Last season, he was 10-1 with a 2.01 ERA through
the end of May, his only loss coming April 15 in his first Fenway
Park appearance of 1999, when he was beaten, 4-0, by John Snyder
and the Chicago White Sox. In '98, he was 6-1 by Memorial Day, and
in his career he's 37-10 with a 2.45 ERA for the season's first two
months.
</P>
<P>
   He has given no indication this spring will be any different.
Ten days away from his Opening Day start in Seattle, Martinez threw
76 pitches in 4 2/3 innings Saturday, allowing six hits (five
singles and a double by Doug Glanville) and a couple of runs while
striking out six in a 10-4 loss to the Philadelphia Phillies in
Jack Russell Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I feel, I'm pretty much ready to do it,'' Martinez said.
``I could go seven or eight innings (in the opener), if I happen to
be in command of all my pitches and don't go too deep in my counts.
My body feels that way, that I could throw seven innings and 100
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, in Boston's 5-3 Opening Day win over the Royals in
Kansas City, Martinez threw 121 pitches in six innings, striking
out nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a couple of mistakes, one to Glanville, when he kept
the curveball up,'' said Red Sox catcher Tim Spehr, ``but I thought
he threw better here than in the minor league game he threw, when
he got away with some pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some fine tuning he needs to do, but a guy like
that, even on his worst days, is still incredible. You can see his
intensity pick up. He's ready for the season. All his pitches are
sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last Monday, Spehr hadn't caught Martinez since 1996, when
both were with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him afterward, `You've improved so much,' '' Spehr
said. ``Like, his curveball is so much better than it was in
Montreal. In Montreal, he was more of a thrower. He's a pitcher
now. He knows how to use his stuff, his mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a dominating pitcher. Every time he goes to the
mound he can throw a no-hitter or a shutout. He has the best
fastball in the game, the best changeup in the game, and one of the
top three curveballs in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a pinch, Martinez might even swing the bat a little bit.
His high chopper to short off Phillies starter Andy Ashby in the
second inning scored Donnie Sadler from the third. It was
Martinez's first RBI in a Red Sox uniform in any game, spring or
regulation. In the fifth inning, third baseman Scott Rolen took a
hit away from Martinez with a diving stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the only one he robs,'' he said of Rolen, who was the
National League Rookie of the Year in 1997, when Nomar Garciaparra
won the AL award. ``He robs everybody. He's awesome. Maybe I need
to get Rolen to autograph the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolen, who went down swinging at high heat from Martinez in the
second inning, when the Sox ace struck out the side, was told of
Martinez's compliment. ``If he does that, then maybe I need to send
over six balls for him to sign,'' Rolen said.
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez played in the NL, which requires its pitchers to
bat, he boasted with a smile that he'd driven in plenty of runs. He
amended that when told a check of the records showed he had 11
RBIs. Martinez takes an .098 average (25 for 255) into this season,
having struck out 117 times. But he did hit a bases-loaded triple
once, in Pittsburgh six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was off Denny Neagle,'' he said, reciting details of his
at-bat like any other big-leaguer. ``I hit a fastball. What else am
going to look for in a bases-loaded situation?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest thing that ever happened to me as a
hitter. I hit it to right-center. If you hit it in the right place,
you can get bases. And I can run. That's something I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams will be happy if he sticks with his other
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good,'' Martinez said. ``My arm is in great
shape. It's just a matter of pitching now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
