<HEADLINE>
YANKEES FEEL THEY HAVE RED SOX COVERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The news that the Red Sox have been ordained World
Series champions by Sports Illustrated barely caused a ripple in
the New York Yankees' clubhouse when the Sox visited here the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Bernie Williams sat in front of his cubicle with his
electric guitar, jamming with pitcher Jason Grimsley. Coach Mickey
Rivers visited with his old Angels teammate, Sox broadcaster Jerry
Remy. Derek Jeter posed with Nomar Garciaparra for a promotional
photo. Roger Clemens paused long enough from his off-day workout
regimen to smirk and say, ``Great, new century,'' when apprised of
the SI cover. Tino Martinez, who later in the day would have the
option on his contract picked up, chuckled. Jim Leyritz, the King,
laughed at the idea that the Sox were now doubly cursed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, somebody has to pick somebody,'' Leyritz said.
``We feel pretty good about defending our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   This had the makings of a disquieting week in Yankeeland. George
Steinbrenner, perturbed at the club's 5-18 spring record, had
called a late-night summit meeting, during which general manager
Brian Cashman tried to assure him that the two-time defending World
Series champions did not require any undue tinkering. By the end of
the week, the Boss had to be feeling better, as the Bombers blanked
the Sox, 2-0 (with Ramiro Mendoza making a strong bid to win the
No. 5 starting slot), and the next day crushed the Marlins, 19-0.
</P>
<P>
   Let the season begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can put any team on the cover right now until the
season starts,'' outfielder Paul O'Neill said. ``Depends how you
want to look at it. A lot of people think it's time for the breaks
to start going against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But our pitching staff gives us a chance to win it, day in and
day out.''
</P>
<P>
   There's some thought out there that the Yankees are starting to
show age. Clemens and David Cone are 37. So is O'Neill, while third
baseman Scott Brosius is 34, which is about the age most people
have El Duque, Orlando Hernandez, pegged at.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens isn't buying it: ``People said David Cone's shoulder was
about to fall off last year, and he pitches a perfect game.''
O'Neill isn't, either: ``I don't see where a year makes that much
difference. We swept through the playoffs and the World Series last
fall, with the best baseball we played all year, and that was what,
four months ago? I don't think things change that much.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the Yankees and their challengers,
O'Neill said, is that other clubs need players to have career
seasons in order to contend. ``We're lucky,'' he said, ``in the
sense that we're a good enough team that if everybody has a pretty
good year, we have a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell me that if Pedro wins only 10 games this
season, Boston will win,'' said O'Neill, who left unspoken the fact
that Clemens won just 14 in 1999 and the Yankees still went all the
way. ``That's a lot of weight on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best pitcher in baseball, so he can probably handle
it, but our main concern is that people stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so rare, O'Neill noted, that the Yankees have been able to
keep their core players together, a function of the Boss's deep
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun part of this, other than the rings, is that it has
been the same people,'' O'Neill said. ``That's the way sports ought
to be. People go to a Yankees game, they know who's going to be out
there, year in and year out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston has a good team. I respect them a lot, that team.
They've got some great players, and it starts with Jimy Williams,
the same way it starts with Joe (Torre) here. It's the same way.
Jimy knows how to get people to win.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was told how Sox catcher Jason Varitek, among others,
said the Yankees played perfect baseball against the Sox in the
ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect? No, we weren't perfect,'' O'Neill said. ``But we
played sound baseball. We don't have guys who hit 40 or 50 home
runs, but we have guys who put together good at-bats. We give
ourselves a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And no magazine cover is going to change that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's an absolute lock that the brothers Martinez will be paid
more than any pair of pitching siblings in the history of the game.
Pedro the Younger has a base salary of $11 million this season. If
he wins his second consecutive Cy Young Award, the club will owe
him an additional $250,000. That's the only performance clause he
has in his contract. Ramon the Elder, meanwhile, is guaranteed
$5.25 million, a hefty increase over his $750,000 base salary last
season. His contract is loaded with incentives and performance
clauses. If he wins the Comeback Player of the Year award, he will
be paid $250,000. There are $50,000 bonuses if he is an All-Star or
the MVP of the League Championship Series, $100,000 if he is World
Series MVP. If he wins the Cy Young Award, he will be paid $150,000
(he gets $75,000 if he finishes second, $50,000 if he is third).
The performance clauses include $100,000 for 175 innings pitched
and $200,000 for 200 innings. Sixteen starts, he earns $100,000.
Twenty-six starts, he gets $175,000, and there is an additional
$200,000 for every start over 30. Ramon hasn't pitched 200 innings
since he was with the Dodgers in 1995, which also was the last time
he made 30 starts. The last time he made as many as 20 starts was
in 1997, when he took the ball 22 times. Next season, if the Sox
exercise the option on Ramon's contract, the brothers would crack
the $20 million mark. Ramon would be guaranteed $8.5 million,
unless the club were to exercise a $750,000 buyout. Pedro,
meanwhile, will have a base salary of $12.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baseball America takes a dim view of Dan Duquette's vaunted
minor league system, ranking the Sox organization 21st in terms of
premium prospects and depth. Baseball America's comment: ``The Red
Sox have become increasingly dependent on their foreign scouting
efforts to both the Far East and Dominican Republic to stock their
talent base. One advantage of signing Asian talent is the
experience level of the pitchers. Boston can start pitchers like
Sun Woo Kim, Sang Hoon Lee, or Tomokazu Ohka at advanced levels and
move them to the big leagues in one or two years. Trades and a
couple of marginally productive drafts have left the system thinner
than in recent years, especially with athletic players.'' . . . Sox
outfielder Carl Everett, who expressed his dislike for the Yankees
his first day in camp (``I never liked pinstripes''), had little to
say last week when the Sox visited the Yanks in Tampa about the
team that made him its No. 1 draft pick in 1990. ``I've talked
about it too much already,'' he said. ``I said what I have to say.
It's not something I want to keep on. I said it. That's how I felt.
A lot of people think I'm bitter. That's not true. I jumped for joy
when I went to Florida.'' Everett played three seasons in the
Yankees organization before the Marlins took him in the second
round of the 1992 expansion draft. He had advanced as far as the
Single A Florida State League with the Yankees in '92, when he was
chosen the league's best defensive outfielder in a poll of managers
and coaches. Everett, who grew up in Tampa, said he was surprised
when the Yankees drafted him. ``I never heard from the Yankees,''
he said. ``It was mainly Seattle and Pittsburgh and the White
Sox.'' . . . Both New York teams have been mentioned as
possibilities for Tigers outfielder Bobby Higginson, who averaged
25 home runs for three seasons before falling off to a dozen last
year. Boss Steinbrenner dispatched aide Gene Michael to follow
Higginson over the weekend, while the Mets, with Rickey Henderson
once again asking to be traded, are said to be considering
Higginson, too, perhaps in exchange for a lefthanded reliever or
Henderson . . . The Phillies were thinking about bringing back
second baseman Mickey Morandini from the Expos in exchange for
outfielder Rob Ducey, who would fill Montreal's need for a
lefthanded-hitting outfield reserve. Another second base
possibility that has been mentioned for the Phillies is San Diego's
David Newhan, whose father, Ross, is the national baseball writer
for the Los Angeles Times . . . The Mariners, still in the market
for a lefthanded-hitting outfielder and thwarted in their attempts
to acquire Jim Edmonds, apparently are mulling over a list that
includes Matt Lawton of the Twins, Todd Hollandsworth of the
Dodgers, and Travis Lee of the D-Backs . . . With Eli Marrero and
Mike Matheny hitting below the Mendoza Line and Rick Wilkins just
above it, the Cardinals may be in the market for catching help
(Scott Hatteberg?). They thought about San Diego's Carlos
Hernandez, who is coming back from a ruptured Achilles' tendon, but
passed for now . . . Mixed signals still are flying around about
Brad Radke, though the best guess now is the righthander will open
the season with the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Expos apparently have decided that Peter Bergeron, a
throw-in to the Carlos Perez/Mark Grudzielanek deal with the
Dodgers, has better game than Milton Bradley, his competition for
the Expos' center field job. Bergeron apparently will start in
center and bat leadoff. He's been working with base stealing guru
Maury Wills, whose only knock on Bergeron is that he's too nice.
``No matter how many times they throw over to the base, you say,
`I'm going anyway,' '' Wills said. ``You're not popular with the
other team, but your own teammates love you. The visiting fans boo
you, and that's a great compliment. Bergeron's a mild-mannered guy.
He's not cut out to be that kind of person. I'm trying to make him
mad _ dirty him up a little in his thinking.'' . . . Frank Thomas
says he's healthy and happy again in White Sox camp, but 1 home run
in his first 37 at-bats has some people wondering whether the
private hitting lessons he's getting from Walt Hriniak are robbing
him of power. The Big Hurt laughs at that notion. Like Mo Vaughn,
he said his power comes later in spring . . . Heather Nabozny, who
is in charge of the care and nurturing of Detroit's new Comerica
Park field, is the first woman to be hired as a head groundskeeper
in the big leagues . . . Canton's Bobby Witt, who was mentioned as
a possibility for the Red Sox when they were casting about for a
starter this winter, is close to nailing down a spot as the
Indians' No. 5 starter or a long man out of the pen . . . With
regular broadcaster Dave O'Brien planning to miss the Marlins'
opener against the Giants in order to do an ESPN game, Boston
College grad Jon ``Boog'' Sciambi is scheduled to do six innings on
WQAM, the team's flagship radio station in Miami. Sciambi, whose
love of the game is such that he once left a comfortable studio job
in Miami to spend a summer broadcasting minor league baseball in
Boise, Idaho, has done the occasional inning for WQAM while
handling pregame and postgame duties . . . Meanwhile, former
Harvard baseball captain and shortstop David Forst has been hired
by GM Billy Beane to work in Oakland's front office . . . Former
Sox pitcher Stan Belinda, who has waged a successful fight to keep
his career alive despite multiple sclerosis, has beaten out former
A's closer Billy Taylor for a job in the Rockies' bullpen . . . It
may be the end of the road for ex-Sox catcher John Marzano, who
refused a minor league assignment from the Devil Rays, opted to
take his release instead, and went home to Arizona . . . Grand
exit: After playing an exhibition against the Twins in Fort Myers,
Texas catcher Pudge Rodriguez boarded a helicopter that landed
beyond the center-field fence and flew off for a personal
appearance in Miami . . . Former Sox replacement player and
reliever Ron Mahay is now the clear front-runner to be the A's No.
5 starter. The lefthander came into the weekend with a 2-0 record
and 2.50 ERA in 18 spring innings . . . Jim Leyland, who is
spending a month in Cardinals camp as a special assistant to GM
Walt Jocketty, is a huge Everett fan. ``I love him,'' Leyland said.
``Power, speed, intensity. He made himself a hell of a player.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the Edmonds deal came together so quickly, four days
after Angels GM Bill Stoneman said his center fielder wasn't going
anywhere. When the Angels originally talked to the Cardinals, they
asked about young pitchers Rick Ankiel and Chad Hutchinson, neither
of whom is available. Thursday was the first time Stoneman asked
for Kent Bottenfield, and Jocketty quickly took the deal. The Cards
think that with the development of Garrett Stephenson, the
impending arrival of phenom Ankiel, and the possible June return of
Matt Morris (who missed all of last season with elbow surgery),
they can offset the loss of Bottenfield. Meanwhile, with Eric Davis
slow to come back from rotator cuff surgery on his left
(non-throwing) shoulder, St. Louis manager Tony La Russa can move
J.D. Drew from center to right and let Davis take his time. And
when he's healthy? No one's saying so, but a trade isn't out of the
question . . . Give credit to agent Scott Boras, who didn't win
free agency for underaged Dodger signee Adrian Beltre but cut him a
fat three-year, $5.5 million deal that could be worth considerably
more if Beltre triggers an escape clause. If the third baseman has
400 plate appearances this season or 800 in the next two, he can
void the last year of the deal. The contract includes a $1.5
million signing bonus and calls for a $500,000 salary this season,
$750,000 next year, and $2.3 million in 2002. If Beltre voids the
last year, he'll be arbitration-eligible. Escape clauses are not
unknown for free agents but are believed to be unprecedented for an
arbitration-eligible player . . . Mike Hampton said he lost
interest in signing with the Astros last winter because they traded
catcher Brad Ausmus and Everett, leading him to question whether
owner Drayton McLane was committed to winning. But Hampton, who was
traded to the Mets but has yet to sign a long-term deal with New
York, said he isn't ruling out a return to Houston after the season
. . . The Cubs originally voted against the trip to Japan but OK'd
it after Major League Baseball offered guaranteed payments to
players, coaches, and clubhouse personnel of $10,000-$25,000.
``Their original offer was $10,000 and we knocked it up,'' said
Cubs player rep Mark Grace. ``We wanted them to grease our palms a
little more. That's the American way.'' No, this wasn't another
case of greedy ballplayers. Grace said he was looking for a maximum
payday for the support personnel and minimum-wage guys . . . Six
teams _ the Dodgers, Rangers, Astros, Indians, Royals, and Orioles
_ will meet Tuesday in Las Vegas with city officials and MLB
representatives about moving spring operations there. The Dodgers,
the only West Coast team still training in Florida, hold the key to
the deal. If they go, the others are likely to follow . . . The
Indians took a day off last week, their first in seven springs
here. GM John Hart had vowed not to schedule another one after the
tragic events of March 22, 1993, when pitchers Tim Crews and Steve
Olin were killed and Bob Ojeda seriously injured in a boating
accident on Little Lake Nellie near Orlando. But time, said Hart,
has healed the wounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
