<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIPPETT'S VENTURE STUFF OF DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ronnie Lippett is returning to football. Not to pro
football, mind you, but to pure football.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of football the former Patriots cornerback feels
is missing these days from the hearts of too many players in the
NFL. They play now for money, for fame, for a shoe contract, for
everything but what got them started. What they don't play for much
anymore, it seems, is precisely what Lippett is hoping to find in
the tiny football outpost of Warren, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   It is there that he will join former teammates Steve Grogan and
Mosi Tatupu to run a football team on which the only money changing
hands will be with the uniform suppliers. It is a team to be known
as the East Bay 1776 Minutemen, the latest arrival in the New
England Football League. It is here _ in minor league football _
that Lippett believes men can be free to dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Houston (NFL expansion) franchise wasn't available to us,
so I went for this,'' joked Lippett, who bought the NEFL team along
with Grogan and Tatupu after being approached by longtime Boston
sports figure Jack McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack was a great friend of Billy Sullivan's, and he called and
asked if I'd help start a team in Warren, R.I. I had just gotten
back from a USO trip to Bosnia, and I had seen how dreams can be
destroyed so easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the dreamers will be Lippett, although his dream is
different. When he came to the Patriots as an eighth-round draft
choice in 1983, little was expected of him. Supposedly, he was too
slow to play corner in the NFL and not physical enough to play
safety. That is what the scouts said, but the scouts don't dream.
</P>
<P>
   After a rough start, his grit and ability made him an NFL
starter on a Super Bowl team and a fixture for years at cornerback.
Lippett has no illusions about, or interest in, playing football
again, although he'd probably be a star even today in the NEFL. His
dream is different from that of his players, but it is a football
dream all the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance for me to live out my dream to be a head
coach,'' said Lippett, who will continue to serve as an assistant
at Curry College under another former teammate, Steve Nelson. ``I'm
looking forward to having players who play for the love of the
game. That's missing nowadays. It seems to me so many guys are
playing only for the money. The essence of the game is lost for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Grogan will serve as the club president, Tatupu as offensive
coordinator, and Lippett as the on-the-field boss. It is a position
he had long dreamed of landing somewhere, but it is only a
part-time dream, because Lippett has bigger dreams than just
winning a few more football games.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, he has run the Ronnie Lippett Mentoring
Program, a youth organization in Taunton in which high school
juniors and seniors serve as mentors to elementary and secondary
school kids, many of whom are struggling with the same kinds of
problems Lippett grew up with. Just as he has not forgotten the
love of football, Lippett hasn't forgotten the importance of love
in all things, especially the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to work in a program where kids are getting what
you're saying,'' said Lippett, whose program received a big
financial boost from NFL Charities. ``They're learning who their
real role models are: their parents and grandparents.''
</P>
<P>
   Lippett also has worked with Family Service of Greater Boston
for seven years, talking with kids who are growing up in much the
same circumstances he had to overcome growing up in Sebring, Fla.
What he tells them is what he will tell his NEFL players: Dream and
know what's important in your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep kids stabilized in the home,'' Lippett
said. ``When I was 8, I was taken out of my mother's home. My
stepfather was beating me pretty good, so eventually they put me
with my grandmother. My mother and my grandmother made sure to put
people in my life who were good role models: a minister, a teacher
I really liked, eventually my coach. They molded me into a person
who wants to give back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lippett does that in schools in Taunton and Boston and anywhere
else someone asks him to go. He does it at Curry, where he coaches
young men who play for fun, not fame. And now he'll be doing it in
Warren, R.I., with a group of men who play football for only one
reason: love of the game.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they'll be coached by a guy who feels the same way .
. . about football and about life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the owners meetings begin in earnest Tuesday in Palm Beach,
Fla., one of the few hotly debated issues will be instant replay.
Again. After much debate last year, replay returned for the first
time since 1991. It was generally successful, but opponents still
exist. Among the most outspoken is Bengals owner Mike Brown, who
cast the lone vote against the system being continued. ``We're
trying to perfect the imperfectable,'' Brown said last week. He
claims replay was used fewer than a dozen times on plays that
actually affected a game, yet games were stopped 195 times (out of
more than 38,000 plays) for a review. He called the system ``a
hoax'' on the game and the fans. Oddly, of the six ``yes'' votes,
one came from Cardinals general manager Bob Ferguson, whose boss,
owner Bill Bidwill, has never voted for replay. ``It's always a
close call,'' said NFL senior vice president for communications Joe
Browne. ``Some clubs spoke up against it during the season. The
calm of the offseason may have calmed them down.'' . . . Replay has
prompted one change in the rules. During last year's playoffs, a
key reception by Buccaneers receiver Bert Emanuel was ruled
incomplete upon review because the tip of ball touched the ground _
even though Emanuel was in full possession. This ruling _ on a play
that has come to be known in Tampa as ``the Immaculate Deception''
_ has led to a rule change allowing such a catch. The new rule will
save the elbows of many receivers, who scrape them on artificial
turf making sure their hands are beneath the ball on low throws.
Detroit's Herman Moore claims to need surgery after slamming his
elbows into the turf so often over the years . . . One innovative
plan the NFL is considering will be discussed by the owners at
length: a flexible December schedule in which the nationally
televised games on Sunday and Monday nights would not be announced
until 3-5 weeks in advance. The idea is to play the top games in
front of a national audience. One argument for this is to avoid
what happened last year, when neither the Rams nor Colts got much
national exposure until the playoffs because so little had been
expected of them before the season. If such a plan were approved,
it would not be implemented next season . . . Denver coach Mike
Shanahan believes in creative tension. He's providing it this
spring by saying the Broncos' quarterback job may belong to Brian
Griese on the first day of training camp but not necessarily on the
last if Gus Frerotte plays better. Considering what Shanahan did to
Bubby Brister a year ago _ taking the job of John Elway's
replacement away from the veteran in the preseason and handing it
to the untested Griese _ he must like to keep his quarterbacks on
their toes . . . Here's how young players end up broke. In a
deposition given several weeks ago in a case brought against
embattled agent Tank Black by the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Jaguars star running back Fred Taylor said he lost his
entire $3 million signing bonus in bad investments Black put him in
. . . Old friend Ben Coates is a realist. While visiting the
Tennessee Titans last week, Coates conceded that he will not earn
anywhere near the $2.7 million he was scheduled to be paid by the
Patriots in 2000 before being cut for salary cap reasons. ``The
price is definitely down,'' Coates said. The price may be down more
than a little. It may be cut in half, with either Coates or Troy
Drayton likely offered not much more than a $1 million package on a
one-year contract . . . By the way, Coates's opinion on how he was
misused last season hasn't changed. He finished with 32 receptions,
his lowest total since his second NFL season, 1992, when he was
still a spot player. He still believes it was not a result of a
dropoff in his ability. ``It's not my fault,'' Coates said. ``I'm
still the same player I was two, three years ago.'' . . . The
Titans allowed free agent safety Anthony Dorsett to sign with
Oakland because Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher did not believe Dorsett
could be a full-time starter, even though he filled in for injured
Marcus Robinson in the Super Bowl. He is a top special teams player
who was a Pro Bowl alternate last year, but is hoping to win a
starting safety job with the Raiders . . . Four-time Pro Bowl guard
Ruben Brown is learning the harsh realities of free agency: Get
your money early or you may not get it at all. When the free agency
period opened, the Bills' guard was demanding a $5 million-$6
million package, but when Detroit and Miami passed, Brown was in
limbo. His demands have decreased to around $3.5 million-$4
million, but even that is not likely in the price range of Buffalo,
which has cap problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins coach Dave Wannstedt called a staff meeting Tuesday to
outline how he believes Miami has improved this offseason despite
the retirement of Hall of Fame quarterback Dan Marino and the
departure of probable Hall of Fame coach Jimmy Johnson. Wannstedt
talked for 20 minutes, insisting the Dolphins had not lost a single
free agent he felt was key to their chances. He also predicted that
ex-Patriot part-time starter Heath Irwin could start at right guard
for the Dolphins in September . . . Jacksonville Jaguars defensive
end Tony Brackens has decided not to attend the team's voluntary
workout program until he has a new contract despite having the
team's franchise label slapped on him. Brackens must play for the
average of the top five defensive end salaries, a figure that
should be around $4.2 million. Brackens is seeking a long-term
contract averaging $7 million-$8 million after leading the team
with 12 sacks in 1999 . . . Nine weeks ago, Jacksonville All-Pro
tackle Tony Boselli tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his
right knee, keeping him out of the playoffs. The normal recovery
time is eight months to a year, but Boselli believes he will start
the season in September _ barely the minimum recovery time . . .
Seattle quarterback Jon Kitna recently signed a one-year deal with
the Seahawks worth $1.3 million, far more than he'd hoped for when
his pro career began. ``When I got into this, all I wanted to do
was pay off some bills,'' Kitna said. ``Now I've done that.'' I'll
bet . . . If you want to get the skinny on what Doug Flutie was
really feeling the week he was benched by the Bills in the
playoffs, get the new issue of NFL Insider magazine. Senior writer
Vic Carucci details Flutie's long week of turmoil before the AFC
wild-card game with Tennessee. One cute story Flutie told is how
his daughter, Alexa, told him her middle school had started a
petition to ask the Bills to reconsider starting Rob Johnson.
``That was her way of trying to make me feel better,'' Flutie said.
``Isn't that what it's all about?'' . . . Quietly the Dolphins
brought in Tom Donahoe as a consultant to work with Wannstedt in
preparing for the college draft. The move is still seen by many as
the precursor to Donahoe ending up with Wannstedt full-time . . .
Here's one assessment of Raymont Harris, the onetime 1,000-yard
rusher the Patriots signed to help ease their running back
problems. He has lasted a full season only once, in 1994 as a Bears
rookie. Three years later, he rushed for 1,033 hard yards but took
a battering and has never been the same. He started only three
games in Green Bay the next year and didn't play at all last year.
Harris runs hard up the gut, but the belief around the league is
that his body can't hold up to a steady pounding and he lacks the
elusiveness to play any other way. The point being, the Patriots
still need a running back . . . The Raiders intend to expand their
use of defensive back Charles Woodson, both offensively and
defensively. Head coach Jon Gruden says he is working on ways to
utilize Woodson not only as a receiver and return threat but also
as more than just a cover corner. The Raiders plan to use Woodson's
speed to blitz in certain situations. With ex-Patriot coach Ron
Lynn handling Oakland's defensive backfield, you can expect more
aggression from Woodson. Woodson was an explosive receiver at
Michigan and believes he can outdo the 36 receptions two-way man
Deion Sanders had for Dallas four years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
