<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-WEST-NYT &LR;      03-25 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN DEFENSE DOES IT AGAINST PURDUE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ As the buzzer sounded, they ran toward each
other in disbelief, sharing a similar feeling with college
basketball fans across the country. The Wisconsin Badgers, the
sixth-place team from the Big Ten Conference, stunned even
themselves Saturday as they advanced to the school's first Final
Four in 59 years.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's improbable ride in the National Collegiate Athletic
Association men's basketball tournament continued with a &QC; 64-60
victory over Purdue in the West Regional final. It lifted the
Badgers into the national semifinals, a place Jon Bryant once
thought existed only in his dreams. Two years ago, Bryant
transferred from Division II St. Cloud State in hopes of earning a
spot on Wisconsin's roster. After knocking down five of nine
3-pointers and scoring 18 points Saturday, the senior guard
celebrated as the regional's most outstanding player and a symbol
of the Badgers' unlikely success.
</P>
<P>
   Next Saturday in Indianapolis, Wisconsin (22-13) will play
Michigan State (30-7), a 75-64 winner over Iowa State Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous. Just look at us,'' Bryant said, motioning
around Wisconsin's locker room. ``We never thought we'd be here. It
just goes to show what confidence does. That, and good
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-seeded Badgers became the lowest-seeded team to reach
the Final Four since 11th-seeded Louisiana State in 1986. They are
the first No.8 to advance this far in the NCAA tournament since
Villanova in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The last time they qualified for the Final Four, in 1941, the
Badgers won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just expected to make the tournament, and once we got in,
we thought maybe we could do a little damage,'' said guard Roy
Boone, who came off the bench to score 12 points. ``Not this much
damage. But after a couple of wins, we started thinking we could
beat anybody in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin beat the Boilermakers (24-10) for the third time in
four meetings this season, doing it again with a scrapping defense
that held them without a field goal for two long stretches. Purdue,
which shot 39.6 percent, did not make a field goal for seven
minutes in the first half (from 9 minutes 1 second to 2:01) and
almost six minutes in the second half (from 6:55 to 0:57 seconds).
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kowske added 14 points and 8 rebounds for the Badgers. Led
by Bryant, they made 43.8 percent of their 3-point attempts (7 of
16). Purdue had more balanced scoring, but hurt itself on 3-point
shots, making only 7 of 23. Brian Cardinal and Carson Cunningham
had 13 points each. Mike Robinson scored 12 and Greg McQuay added
10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their team defense and Bryant's 3-pointers really cut our
throats,'' Purdue Coach Gene Keady said. ``It was one of those
things where they just played a little bit better and we could
never get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   In a personal contest of senior guards, Jaraan Cornell, the
Boilermakers' streaky shooting guard, rarely escaped the shadow of
Mike Kelley. Cornell made only one shot, a 3-pointer, in nine
attempts. Kelley finished with 5 points and 5 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kept chasing him and fighting through screens and
telling myself not to relax,'' Kelley said. ``I was working real
hard to get his shots. They just weren't falling for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell said, ``In the last four minutes they stepped it up a
notch on defense, and we couldn't execute our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   With the scored tied at 52-52, the Badgers slowly and painfully
ended the Boilermakers' hopes of taking Keady to his first Final
Four in 20 seasons at Purdue. Kowske scored on a drive across the
lane, Boone hit a jump shot, Mark Vershaw made two free throws and
Boone added two free throws for a 60-53 lead with one minute left.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Purdue was forced to foul, and came within 61-57
with 19.5 seconds to go on a tip-in by Greg McQuay. Cunningham sank
a 3-pointer to make it 63-60 with 11.5 seconds left, but the
Badgers responded with four of seven free throws down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They easily could have won,'' Wisconsin Coach Dick Bennett
said of the Boilermakers. ``The key was our ability to take better
care of the basketball in the second half. In the first, we just
had too many turnovers and were rushing a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal, who scored all of his 13 points in the second half,
kept the Boilermakers close as the Badgers threatened to pull away,
sparking a rally for a 50-49 lead with 6:50 to play. He scored 9
points in an 11-4 run, hitting back-to-back 3-pointers, a short
jumper and a free throw after being fouled by Kowske, Wisconsin's
leading rebounder. It was Kowske's fourth foul and put him on the
bench for almost five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He returned after Cardinal tied the score at 52-52 on two free
throws with 5:23 left.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team led by more than 7 points as the Badgers held on
for a 31-28 halftime lead despite a jump shot at the buzzer by
Purdue's John Allison. Bryant sparked the Badgers with 10 points,
making 3 of 4 of his 3-point attempts, and Boone scored their last
5 points. Wisconsin shot 57 percent to Purdue's 47 percent in the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue got 7 points apiece from Robinson, Cunningham and Maynard
Lewis. The Boilermakers forced more Wisconsin turnovers (10) in one
half than the Badgers had against Louisiana State (9) in their
semifinal victory Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The first half developed into a series of mini-runs as both
teams tried to gain momentum. The Badgers held it with four minutes
left with seven unanswered points on a 3-pointer from Maurice
Linton, a running one-hander by Kelley and a short jumper by Kowske
for a 25-19 lead. Kelley's basket was important because his drive
down the lane resulted in the second foul on Cardinal, who spent
the rest of the half on the bench.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
