<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE NEEDS LATE RUN TO ENSURE PLACE IN FINAL FOUR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Three of the players are a proud and
unperishable export of an industrial town that has seen better
days: Flint, Mich. And Saturday night, when Michigan State needed
to fire the Spartans' steel to overcome a tournament by bouncing
Iowa State, Mateen Cleaves, Morris Peterson and Charlie Bell pulled
their welders' masks down and went to work.
</P>
<P>
   The three combined for 14 clutch and often spectacular points in
the final four minutes of the Midwest Regional final of the
National Collegiate Athletic Association men's basketball
tournament to turn a 6-point deficit into a 75-64 victory and a
return trip to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-0 run erupted with a 21-foot bomb from the lefty Peterson
and was fanned by free throws, followed by a 15-foot runner from
Bell. But what finally torched the Cyclones, broke what had been a
willful effort and left them in tears after the game, was Cleaves'
alley-oop pass from the top of the key to a body soaring above the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   It was Peterson who, with 2 minutes 4 seconds left, seemed to
slam the ball below him and through the rim for Michigan State's
64-61 lead as a sold-out and loudly partisan Michigan State crowd
of 21,214 began calling for Indianapolis and a semifinal matchup
with Big Ten rival Wisconsin. They were the sort of acrobatics
Michigan State's A.J. Granger has seen plenty of from his teammates
of four years, but they continue to amaze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drew that up in a timeout because we wanted to make sure we
got a sure thing,'' said Granger, who along with Peterson led the
Spartans with 18 points. ``That is about as sure as you get. I did
my usual thing _ turned around with my mouth open and watched Pete
go flying through the air. It got the crowd, the momentum, and I
knew where we were going from there.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, it was as if the Cyclones, who had contained
Michigan State to that point with vicious jersey-to-jersey defense,
had been paralyzed by a high-flying ghost. Up to that point, the
showdown between the No.1- and No.2-seeded teams _ the only region
to play to form _ was being punched out in Iowa State's favor.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones outrebounded Michigan State _ which had led the
nation in that category _ by 38-27. They held the Spartans to 40
percent shooting and had Cleaves in foul trouble with four
personals with seven minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cyclones scored only once more _ a 3-pointer by Michael
Nurse _ and Iowa State Coach Larry Eustachy beat his team to the
locker room by getting two technical fouls and being tossed from
the game with 13 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Behind by 69-64 and still seething about a double foul called
minutes earlier _ when one official disagreed with another on
whether Bell had blocked a drive by Iowa State's Paul Shirley _
Eustachy lost his composure when the all-American Marcus Fizer was
called for his fifth foul.
</P>
<P>
   He followed Referee Lonnie Dixon to midcourt and unleashed a
nose-to-nose tirade that Dixon tolerated briefly before calling two
quick technical fouls and waving Eustachy out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Eustachy went to the Michigan State bench and shook hands with
Spartans Coach Tom Izzo and then stalked off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disappoint way to the end the game and I apologized
to my team for it,'' said Eustachy, who was still shaken after the
game. ``But we went down fighting and I'm not going to apologize
for my actions either. They played better quality basketball in the
last five minutes and thus they're moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cleaves was able to skip off the floor, waving his arms to
gather in the noise from the crowd, he acknowledged the Spartans
had been fortunate victors in a mostly well played war and gave all
the credit to another teammate not from Flint: the junior Andre
Hutson, who had 17 points, 11 rebounds and wore Fizer out inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was huge for us _ taking on a guy like Fizer, said Cleaves,
who had 10 points. ``Everyone was talking about Marcus, but Andre
took the challenge. If it wasn't for him, we wouldn't be sitting
here right now and talking about next week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclone players, on the other hand, could barely talk at
all. Michael Nurse conceded that with a 6-point lead and a habit of
not making mistakes in the game's final minutes, he and his
teammates were counting on the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team thought we could win it,'' said Nurse, who had
18 points. ``We needed three stops. You got to credit them. They
didn't stop playing.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked what their emotions were in the locker room, both
Nurse and Fizer bowed their heads and tried to talk through the
tears. Eustachy reached for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know this is our last game,'' said Fizer, who had
18 points. ``That this is the end of a great season. A lot of
people didn't expect for us to get this far. But it's over now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
