<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-LABOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONS MAY DISRUPT L.A. DURING CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Flexing its new power, Los Angeles labor unions
with more than 250,000 members have banded together to fight for
lucrative contracts in the public and private sectors, threatening
to embarrass or even disrupt the city during this summer's
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   From blue-collar workers to actors and writers, from sheriff's
deputies to janitors and graduation students, the coalition of
local unions hopes to see them work together if they don't win
large pay raises or other concessions in contract talks that kick
off this month.
</P>
<P>
   Among the targets of joint protests _ and, as a last resort,
strikes _ are the Los Angeles Unified School District, county
government, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, city of Long
Beach, the Gas Co. and Kaiser Permanente.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles city workers are not members of the coalition but
police and firefighters are up for a new contract, and those talks
will add to the labor tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a convergence of this kind with the
opening of collective bargaining,'' said Miguel Contreras,
executive secretary-treasurer of the federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also don't think we've ever been at a point where so
many workers have contracts coming up in the same period. We just
realized what we will be facing last year and it sent up a red flag
for us to try to create a common message around the county.''
</P>
<P>
   As a way to kick off the campaign, some 2,000 members of the
different unions have scheduled a rally and march Tuesday in the
downtown area, beginning at LAUSD headquarters and picking up
marchers at the county Hall of Administration, Ronald Reagan State
Building and other locations, ending up at Pershing Square.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras said each union will be negotiating on its own, but
will look to the others for support in the event of any
demonstrations or work actions.
</P>
<P>
   And while he voiced hope the negotiations would be concluded
before the Democratic National Convention in mid-August, he
acknowledged it could be a factor in some talks and that local
officials do not want to see the city embarrassed during the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, the county wants to hold off on some talks until
after the convention,'' Contreras said. ``We think we should be at
the table now.''
</P>
<P>
   Convention planners are monitoring the situation and voice hope
there will be no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that any labor issue will be resolved before
the convention begins,'' said Ben Austin, spokesman for the Los
Angeles Host Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But others privately admit to having some concerns if there is
not a resolution on most of the contracts by June.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get to June and there are still a number of outstanding
contracts, it would be a real concern,'' said one official, asking
not to be identified. ``If it gets to July, then it's a red-hot
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides of Mayor Richard Riordan said he is monitoring the
situation and believes the unions will have successfully completed
most of their contracts by the time of the convention. The
convention is scheduled Aug. 14-17 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The first test could some soon, with the janitors who are
members of SEIU Local 1877 preparing for a strike starting April1.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of janitors and their supporters demonstrated Friday
along Ventura Boulevard in Encino, temporarily stopping traffic,
while similar protests were held in Pasadena and Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are working to do is get the message out that it is
unions who represent workers and will get the best deal for them,''
Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   The federation had its most successful year ever last year,
signing up 91,000 workers for unions, mostly home-care workers. It
has continued its aggressive recruitment drive this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Economic Development Corp.
of Los Angeles, said forming the coalition was a logical next step
for the unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is strong and they want to get their fair share,''
Kyser said. ``But there are some who worry that while the economy
is good now, it might cool off and they don't want to get into high
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Contreras said workers particularly those in the government
sector are due for large raises since many took pay cuts or saw
their salaries frozen during the bad economic times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the workers who took the cuts and when the economy is
strong, we should benefit as well,'' Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the contract talks involve more issues than
salary and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Sacharow, a spokesman for the federation, said teachers
will be dealing with issues such as the breakup of the school
district and pressure to accept merit pay rules. Workers in the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority are concerned about efforts
to create a San Fernando Valley Transit Zone that would take over
operation of dozens of MTA bus lines.
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges facing the unions is getting members to
work together and support one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what we're doing is education and let someone who
works for the Gas Co. know that an unemployed actor or writer from
the Screen Actors Guild has the same problems he does,'' Contreras
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 2347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
