<DOCNO> NYT20000325.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8275 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LIBERTY-FIGHT-LADN     03-25 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTER GOING ON TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For more than a year, an unfinished, 12-story
mural of the Statue of Liberty has gazed down on the National
Cemetery from a nearby building in Westwood, a tear in her eye
reflecting a battle over free speech and city rules for public art.
</P>
<P>
   Artist Mike McNeilly intended the mural as a tribute to fallen
veterans. But now it symbolizes his fight with City Hall over rules
that required him to win Councilman Mike Feuer's approval before he
can even apply for permission to paint the privately owned
building.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, more than a year after police and building inspectors
forced him to stop the mural on the Westwood Medical building,
McNeilly goes on trial for painting ``Liberty'' without a permit.
He faces six months in jail and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called the chilling effect when a politician can put a
chilling effect on your right of free speech,'' McNeilly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a picture of the top half of the Statue of Liberty
in the United States of America. I can't think of anything more
fitting than the symbol of freedom within one block of the National
Cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeilly said that just as police moved in to stop him from
finishing the painting, he improvised a tear drop to reflect his
frustration and anger.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer refused to comment on the matter, citing the pending
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a city renowned for larger-than-life murals and billboards,
the controversy pits the artistic community against critics
fighting what they see as visual clutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's being unjustly persecuted as an artist for doing
his work,'' said Al Boime, an art history professor at University
of California, Los Angeles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feuer argued in a letter to the Cultural Affairs Commission last
year that murals such as this ``detract from the scenic aspects of
the Wilshire Corridor.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that his office ``continues to get numerous complaints
about this illegally installed sign,'' and said McNeilly should not
be allowed to finish what he started without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   McNeilly admits he never applied for a permit because he
believes the city's permit system was arbitrary and
unconstitutional. It allowed a single council member in this case
Feuer to block the project before McNeilly could even submit his
permit application to the Cultural Affairs Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Since McNeilly voiced his criticisms, the restriction has been
removed, but the city continues to prosecute him
</P>
<P>
   and the building's owner for painting without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time Feuer has stood in the way of
McNeilly's efforts to paint the building. The councilman blocked
him from painting a Disney-commissioned mermaid in 1997, so
McNeilly assumed Feuer wouldn't approve Lady Liberty and decided to
ignore the rules as a form of protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try it once and they slam you down. You either go back and
fight it your own way, or you just don't do it, which means you've
given up your basic right of free speech,'' McNeilly said.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 21, 1999, he fought it his own way. After obtaining
permission from the building owner, he and his assistants began
work on the mural. They had finished the top half of her face when,
according to McNeilly, at least eight police officers, along with
building inspectors and other city officials, descended on the
building and forced him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   McNeilly was allowed to go back up briefly to secure his
equipment, and managed to paint a subtle teardrop.
</P>
<P>
   McNeilly then tried to legally apply for a permit, only to be
quickly rejected by Feuer and the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Gloria Dabbs-Mann said the fairness of the
permit process is not the issue, since McNeilly didn't file for a
permit first. If he had, and was rejected, he could have appealed
that rejection and then argued the process was unfair, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is being prosecuted for painting the mural without a
permit or a contractor's license and then refusing to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that Mr. McNeilly needs to take down that sign
because it wasn't permitted,'' Dabbs-Mann said. ``If you allow him
to have a sign up, everyone can put a sign up on a building without
a permit.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that even under the old process, the Cultural Affairs
Department's staff would sometimes make exceptions and allow
permits to go forward without a councilman's letter of support.
</P>
<P>
   McNeilly and his attorney, Gary Mobley of Irvine, counter that
he did not have to apply for a permit to challenge the
constitutionality of the law, citing Supreme Court decisions that
date to the civil rights protests of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Boime, the art history professor, said that public murals are an
important part of Greater Los Angeles' culture and history, from
the Chicano protest murals of East L.A. to the enormous commercial
``tall-walls'' of West Hollywood's Sunset Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think L.A. culture, you think murals. First as a form
of protest, then also as a way of enhancing the buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the appearance of the neighborhood would be
improved, not hurt, by this particular mural.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least this gives it some color and appeal. And it does have
a symbolic importance in overlooking the veterans' cemetery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
