<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8278 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HOLLYWOOD-REVIVAL-3Ta     03-25 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-REVIVAL-3Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLITZ RETURNING IN FILM CAPITAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(``Tonight's'' in story refers to Sunday, March 26.) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Shreiber, unheralded author of an anti-IRS
tract and full-time street hawker of old magazines, looks at the
scene along Hollywood Boulevard and sees ``a sleazy, scuzzy place''
full of ``lunatics and vagrants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood reminds me of a suburb of Tijuana,'' he says flatly,
unimpressed by the touches of glitter that have begun to dot this
legendary street of grand illusions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the film industry gathers for tonight's 72nd Oscars
ceremony, skeptical voices like Shreiber's are being drowned out by
the roar of construction equipment and the buzz of speculators.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of decline, new restaurants, stores, coffeehouses
and nightclubs are poking up through Hollywood's grimy sidewalks.
At the northwest corner of Hollywood Boulevard and Highland Avenue,
the massive $430 million retail-entertainment complex that will
permanently host the Academy Awards rises at a feverish pace, next
to the new subway station that is supposed to bring tourists in
record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to say to people is if you haven't come to
Hollywood lately, you haven't seen it,'' says Jackie Goldberg, the
powerful Los Angeles City Council member whose district encompasses
much of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But along with Hollywood's long-delayed, oft-proclaimed revival
has come great uncertainty _ and sticky questions about the shape
of its future.
</P>
<P>
   Will wary suburbanites who haven't set foot in Hollywood in
years be lured by its growing lineup of tourist-friendly
attractions?
</P>
<P>
   Can the area's eccentric and colorful street life, represented
by people like Michael Shreiber, co-exist with the sleek ``new
economy'' culture of dot-coms colonizing the area?
</P>
<P>
   Will whatever still remains of Old Hollywood's raffish charm _
its vintage 1920s office buildings and musty antique bars be
eclipsed by the towering new retail developments?
</P>
<P>
   In short, will the new Hollywood offer a dynamic and complex
urban environment, or a sanitized simulacrum a la Universal
Citywalk?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that anyone even remotely could say that
development is not going to be good for Hollywood,'' says Margaret
Crawford, a professor at Southern California Institute of
Architecture. ``But good in the long run? Good in the short run?
Good for who?''
</P>
<P>
   Such questions may sound almost heretical in a town that has
been awaiting its economic savior for nearly 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the 1920s and'30s, the major film studios began
uprooting from Hollywood and taking their act to Century City and
the San Fernando Valley. Only one, Paramount, still survives there
intact.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Hollywood never got over the exodus. By 1954
producer David O. Selznick was grumbling that ``Hollywood is like
Egypt, full of crumbled pyramids. It'll never come back.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, the last of Hollywood's once-glamorous
storefronts were morphing into porn shops and wig emporiums, and
its star-embossed sidewalks were serving as makeshift beds for
junkies and teen-age runaways.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, earthquakes, riots and Southern
California's swooning economy took a further toll. Just one year
ago, City Council President John Ferraro described Hollywood as ``a
cesspool'' where visitors ``come from all over the world,
regurgitate and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   But today that jaundiced viewpoint contrasts sharply with the
hopeful forecasts of planners and politicians: Hollywood's worst
days may indeed be behind it.
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Since 1993, violent crime in the district is down more than 75
percent and property crime down 55 percent. Office rents in that
period have doubled to an average of $2 per square foot, still a
bargain by Westside standards.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the new commercial activity has centered on
Hollywood Boulevard between Vine and La Brea, investment has begun
moving south toward Santa Monica Boulevard, which is part of a
business improvement area called the Hollywood Media District.
Among its new tenants are IFILM, a digital film company that's
relocating its 150 employees to Hollywood from San Francisco, and
Kozmo.com, a New York-based firm that delivers products ranging
from groceries to DVDs via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area of Hollywood has been a hub for production and
post-production, but it has never really touted itself the way the
media district in, say, Burbank has,'' says Julie Kleinick,
director of acquisitions and leasing for Albert Sweet Development.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ryan, IFILM's chief financial officer, says that five
years ago, ``I wouldn't have set foot in this area.'' Now, he
believes Los Angeles is ``the next big boomtown in the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Residential home sales also are up throughout Hollywood,
Realtors report.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the area's most prominent signs of renewal can be
found along Hollywood Boulevard between La Brea and Highland, the
stretch most frequented by tourists. In the past, the majority of
these visitors came, saw, and left central Hollywood in less than
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Today, construction cranes loom over Hollywood Boulevard, where
Toronto-based TrizecHahn Development Corp. is raising a
640,000-square-foot retail complex, due to open in September 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Straddling two full blocks and subsidized with $98 million in
city bonds, the project will include a 640-room hotel, a spa, a
ballroom and architecture mimicking the faux-Babylonian sets from
D.W. Griffith's ``Intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Its centerpiece will be the 3,000-seat Premiere Theatre for
concerts and other live performances between annual Oscar
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Among its future neighbors will be the $20 million Hollywood
Orangeland project, next to Mann's Chinese Theatre, which will
house retail stores and a Frederick's of Hollywood museum.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, TV Guide announced plans for a West Coast
headquarters in a 12-story building across from the Chinese and the
TrizecHahn project.
</P>
<P>
   Alberta Davidson, senior vice president of corporate marketing
for TrizecHahn Development, predicts that a redeveloped Hollywood
could draw 20 million visitors annually up from its current
9million and nearly double the 11 million people who attend the
theater annually in New York City's Times Square district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception was always much worse than the reality,'' says
Leron Gubler, president and CEO of the Hollywood Chamber of
Commerce. ``That's what we've had to battle in bringing Hollywood
back. It was the reputation ... as this place with hookers and
pimps on every corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hollywood's new development is not without critics. Some say
the TrizecHahn project is a suburban-style mall of the kind that
saps the vitality of surrounding streets
</P>
<P>
   the antithesis of Pasadena's One Colorado, in the heart of Old
Town, or Santa Monica's popular Third Street Promenade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really are based on the urban block and the idea of the
city, and this (TrizecHahn) is more of a shopping mall, inwardly
focused,'' says Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   (3RD TAKE FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-00 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
