<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-25 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HOLLYWOOD-REVIVAL-3rd     03-25 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-REVIVAL-3rdtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: focused,'' says Crawford    
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She personally welcomes such recent additions to the
neighborhood as a new Starbucks, but believes that the rush to
entice middle-class shoppers and diners will sacrifice the area's
eclectic quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we need to be romantic about tattoo parlors and hustlers?''
Crawford asks. ``No. But at the same time there are legitimate
concerns about that kind of homogenizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Hollywood VOTE, a group lobbying for Hollywood to
secede from the city of Los Angeles and become its own
municipality, maintain that Hollywood's spruce-up has simply
arrived too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there has been a lot of money dumped here lately,'' says
Hollywood VOTE attorney Mitchell Green. ``But I think a lot of that
has to do with Hollywood being so ridiculously run-down that it
attracted the money. There was a vacuum here. I don't think that's
something the city can take credit for. It happened through
neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that neglect is still highly visible. On Hollywood
Boulevard, boarded-up buildings sit side-by-side with Disney's
brilliantly restored El Capitan movie house. East of Highland
Avenue the foot traffic drops off, especially after dark, and most
storefronts are shuttered well before 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood today remains, at best, a patchy work in progress, a
bazaar of contradictory impulses that change from building to
building.
</P>
<P>
   But where some see neglect, others sense opportunity, like New
York City's 42nd Street/Times Square area, which in recent years
has evolved from a tawdry strip of peep shows and porn theaters
into a booming entertainment mecca.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore that parallel, in October the Walt Disney
Co. will open its hit Broadway musical ``The Lion King'' at the art
deco-style Pantages Theatre at Hollywood and Vine, which is
undergoing extensive renovations for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Just 2 years ago, Disney's opening of ``The Lion King'' at New
York's New Amsterdam Theatre, an ornate 1903 vaudeville house
painstakingly restored by Disney Imagineers, signaled 42nd Street's
revival.
</P>
<P>
   Now Disney _ which spurred corporate interest in Hollywood three
years ago when it bought and restored the El Capitan movie house _
is hoping that ``The Lion King'' can further reclaim Hollywood's
lost luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Hollywood is all about,'' says Peter Schneider,
president of Walt Disney Theatrical Productions. ``It's always been
about the entrepreneur, the excitement of the movies, the
excitement of what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jed Bernstein, president of the League of American Theatres and
Producers Inc., the national trade organization for the commercial
theater industry, thinks Hollywood faces many obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to feel safe, you have to feel comfortable, and you
have to feel that it's not going to take you an hour to drive from
Brentwood to Hollywood and Vine,'' Bernstein says.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will all of Hollywood's new cultural attractions be of the
PG-13 variety.
</P>
<P>
   The Knitting Factory, the renowned New York City music club and
paragon of digital-age hipness, will launch a Hollywood satellite
this summer in the Hollywood Galaxy building, near Mann's Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was drawn to the Hollywood area not only because
of the new corporate investment, but because its edgy ambience
evokes a funkier, pre-gentrified New York, says Guy Compton,
KnitMedia director of marketing and media relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area now sort of walks the line,'' Compton says. ``It's
got almost like the old 42nd Street feel to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
